<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRINGTON'S RED SOX PRIORITIES DUBIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Suddenly, John Harrington has an image
problem. For a quarter-century, he was Mr. Squeaky Clean _ a
humble, friendly, and charming accountant who went to daily Mass
and was trusted by all.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as he has become more withdrawn and more
powerful, Harrington's motives as CEO of the Red Sox have come
under question. And Saturday he released an in-house memo (to be
sent to Sox partners and employees) aimed at convincing folks that
he's not just another Kevin Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald is the state representative (D-Mission Hill) who
befriended a bag lady who turned out to be a wealthy bag lady. When
Mary Guzelian died, Fitzgerald and a top aide inherited her
$400,000. The will was later invalidated and Fitzgerald and his
aide were ordered to return the money to Guzelian's 76-year-old
sister.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have Harrington, the keeper of the Yawkey Trust, getting
to play with the big league owners even though he doesn't have big
league money. Harrington worked for, and befriended, Thomas and
Jean Yawkey back in the early 1970s and has been the man in charge
of the Yawkey Trust (trustee of the majority general partner of the
ball club) since Jean Yawkey died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Sox are owned by the Ozlike Corporation, a
faceless file cabinet filled with stock certificates and the Yawkey
wills. Harrington has been left in charge of how the money is
spent. Prospective buyers are rebuffed. Harrington gets to play
owner, and a Herald report last week charged that he ``has
personally reaped millions of dollars from Jean Yawkey's estate and
the charitable foundations of her and her husband Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   The in-house memo _ only slightly shorter than ``Tuesdays With
Morrie'' (six pages, single spaced) _ goes to great lengths to
refute many of the charges in the Herald report. On Page 4 of the
memo, Harrington states, ``At no time have I committed to a
specific schedule to sell the Yawkey interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The polygraph would explode if Harrington uttered that whopper.
On May 20, 1992, Harrington told the Globe's Will McDonough,
``These are the facts. The team will be sold in the next two to
five years.'' In 1993, Harrington and former Sox partner Haywood
Sullivan told the Globe's Curtis Wilkie that Yawkey's will decreed
that the team be sold as quickly as was practical.
</P>
<P>
   It has now been seven years since Jean Yawkey died, and
Harrington shows no signs of putting the club up for sale.
Harrington believes the club will be worth more once a new park is
built, and that he can better serve the Yawkey Trust if he waits
until Fenway Park is replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington's in-house memo concludes with, ``I take my fiduciary
responsibility as trustee very seriously and have always acted in
what I believe are the best interests of the Yawkey Trust and
Foundations and the wishes of the Yawkeys. These foundations have
helped thousands of people throughout Massachusetts and the U.S.
and are the legacy of Tom and Jean Yawkey that the trustees always
hold in trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington's closing remark might make his employees and
partners feel better, but it's not likely to soothe the restless
natives who follow the Red Sox. Boston baseball fans would rather
have an owner who puts winning championships ahead of his fiduciary
responsibility to a trust.
</P>
<P>
   Sox fans want to know why the club wouldn't pay the going rate
to keep Mo Vaughn. They want to know why Dan Duquette has been
anointed GM-for-Life. They want to know why the club keeps raising
ticket prices while falling farther behind the Yankees. And they
don't get these answers from a CEO who is beholden to a trust.
</P>
<P>
   There's no accountability in the owner's box on Yawkey Way.
Harrington had no comment after the settlement of a nasty lawsuit
involving former employee Thomas Sneed _ litigation that had
threatened to uncover some nasty in-house allegations. Before the
release of Saturday's memo (no doubt a counterstrike to keep
Harrington in good graces with the politicos he'll need to get a
new ballpark), the last time Harrington made a public statement was
when he stood on the Fenway sidewalk on Christmas Eve and
complained about ``50 or 60 years of unfair criticism'' directed at
the Red Sox. He made that remark in the wake of public outcry after
the Sox had bounced peanut and hot dog vendors from the streets
around Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington's new profile is that of a paranoid, indecisive
accountant who charmed his way into enormous power and now is
unwilling to yield the throne. He should sell the team, or get some
investors and buy it. Fans simply don't trust the trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
