</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE REASON FOR HUSKIES TO HOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They've done nothing to impress and just enough to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   They were blessed with a bracket of yapping canines _ Texas-San
Antonio, New Mexico, Iowa and Gonzaga _ and barely got the monkey
off the team bus.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut prevailed on Saturday, slipping by a No. 10 seed,
liberating their coach from an invisible noose, taking an important
step in the evolution of their program.
</P>
<P>
   But they have proven nothing, other than put a pop-gun to four
teams that would make up a wonderful Alaskan Invitational. &UR; And
while the fog of failure has been lifted, they'll arrive in St.
Petersburg, Fla., with the same nagging question:
</P>
<P>
   Can they beat a great team when it matters?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I'd probably have to go through purgatory to get to
heaven,'' Huskies Coach Jim Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice, of course, that Calhoun's career will no longer be
defined by previous roadblocks. No man of his status should have to
explain how he can win more than 300 games at a faceless oasis, a
rural school somewhere between Boston and New York, and go 0-3 in
regional finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to go to the Hall of Fame the right way,'' guard
Khalid El-Amin said. ``Not as the best coach never to reach the
Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and it's touching that El-Amin heard the buzzer, jumped
over the scorer's table and ran 15 rows into the stands to hug
members of his family. Impressive that Richard Hamilton was able to
keep his team in the game during the first half by scoring over a
gimmick defense spearheaded by a 5-foot-8 point guard.
</P>
<P>
   But if Connecticut thinks the battle for respect is over, well,
sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the game until the last seconds,'' Gonzaga guard
Matt Santangelo said. ``It's not like we lost the game by 25.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. And this just in: The combined seeding of UConn's
conquests is 40. Not exactly a riveting run to glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``True, we haven't played our `A' game yet,'' Huskies guard
Ricky Moore said. ``But when we get everyone playing their special
game on the same night, we're unbeatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a week to practice,'' El-Amin said. ``We can tune up
our game.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, after shaking off Iowa in the closing
minutes, the Huskies were bursting with confidence. Later that
night, El-Amin scoffed about the perception of playing in a 63-team
field with one pre-ordained champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world's hyping up Duke as much as possible, and they
haven't even played us yet,'' El-Amin said. ``I'll leave it at
that.''
</P>
<P>
   So Duke is beatable?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the UConn message had softened considerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message we send to ourselves is we're happy to go to
Florida,'' Calhoun said. ``If anyone's talking, I guarantee Duke
isn't listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Gonzaga wasn't too impressed. Had a lid not formed on
the basket, had they not lost their edge on the boards, had
Santangelo not lost his game, had either one of two Gonzaga players
recognized an open teammate outside the three-point arc in the
closing seconds . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, we had an opportunity to win down the stretch,''
Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't tee it up like we did in the last couple of
games,'' center Jeremy Eaton said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, sorry all you Gonzag-nuts. Your team deserves mad praise
for supplying some entertainment value to a staggering tournament.
For openly disdaining all the gleeful cliches and glass slippers.
For proving they belong. But for the competitive balance of the
Final Four, it's best that UConn advances.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it would be nice to see one of the few anointed
heavyweights play up to their marquee value. Nice to know that if
UConn can survive Ohio State, a team that lost to Illinois two
weeks ago, the Huskies can make a championship game worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, they cut down the nets and soaked in the victory,
but the swagger was missing. And when asked about the Blue Devils,
the cockiness was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we come to that bridge, we'll cross it,'' El-Amin said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is really all the Huskies accomplished on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, can they handle the other side? &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0005EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
