<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8401 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARR     03-21 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA SEEKS SECOND OPINION 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ There can no longer be any hiding behind
half-answers, shrugged shoulders, or, as was the case Saturday when
Nomar Garciaparra left camp with no comment, silence.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox shortstop is sufficiently concerned about the
condition of his right arm _ more specifically, his right elbow _
that he plans to fly Sunday to Los Angeles for a magnetic resonance
imaging and a consultation with Dr. Tony Daly, who was medical
director for the 1984 Olympics and is the team doctor for the NBA's
LA Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who has not played shortstop since March 11 _ a
span of nine games, including Saturday's 2-1 win over the
Pittsburgh Pirates _ met Saturday afternoon with team doctor Arthur
Pappas.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas, who had left camp more than a week ago and had not seen
Garciaparra since the injury, said the shortstop had
``sensitivity'' in his right biceps, but stated for the first time
that the primary area of concern was a strained flexor muscle,
located on the inside of the elbow. The MRI, Pappas said, will
determine whether there is any ligament damage. Saturday, Pappas
said Garciaparra had a ``mild'' strained ligament.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the ligament, we have to see what's going on,'' he said.
``I think he's going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Pappas, asked if he thought Garciaparra would be playing again
at the end of the week, said, ``Probably.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra took some ground balls at shortstop Saturday
morning, lobbing them back into the home plate area or flipping
them to second without making any throws to first. He also hit in
the batting tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's feeling better each day,'' Pappas said. ``He's doing his
ground balls, hitting and fielding OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, despite denials, apparently had decided to seek a
second opinion even before meeting with Pappas. Normally, Pappas
said, the Red Sox would have sent the player to the UMass Medical
Center in Worcester for the MRI, but with Garciaparra's plans to
see Daly, it was decided that it was best for the exam to take
place in LA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have recommended an (MRI) at this point,'' said
Pappas, adding that he was in full agreement with Garciaparra's
desire to seek a second opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas has asked Garciaparra to also see noted orthopedist Dr.
Lewis Yocum, one of the foremost elbow specialists in baseball.
Yocum is team doctor for the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an excellent idea,'' Pappas said of Garciaparra's
wish for a second opinion. ``First of all, it's (his) right.
Secondly, it's important for me to have information from people
with knowledge of baseball biomechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Pappas said he believes Garciaparra has some history with Daly
but didn't know the circumstances under which Garciaparra may have
seen Daly in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, club officials, including manager Jimy Williams,
described Garciaparra's condition as biceps tendinitis, a muscle
problem that in the case of infielders usually requires only two or
three days of treatment. Pappas said Saturday that diagnosis did
not come from him. Garciaparra was given anti-inflammatory
medication, and Pappas said Saturday he was responding well to the
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, Garciaparra told reporters he had felt a ``sharp
pain'' in his arm, though he didn't mention that his elbow was
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra watched Saturday's exhibition from the bench,
dressed quickly and left. When reporters sought to speak with him
in the waiting area reserved for family and friends, Garciaparra
told club publicist Kevin Shea repeatedly he did not wish to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that it was suggested to him that Garciaparra
injured his arm while making a relay throw March 11 in an
exhibition against Toronto. It was in Toronto in June 1997 that Tim
Naehring sustained a career-ending elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas said there is no correlation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's didn't show improvement,'' Pappas said. ``Nomar has
shown improvement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
