<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-GAMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL FOUR EMOTIONAL TRIP FOR CALHOUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - After Kevin Freeman heaved the ball nearly to the
rafters and Ricky Moore got off one last celebratory shot, after
the mobbing and the hugging and the net-cutting, Connecticut's
players gave their coach, Jim Calhoun, an ice water shower right
there at midcourt at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   At last, the frustrations were washed away, the smoldering
embers of past NCAA Tournament failures doused. UConn and Calhoun
are going to the Final Four. Finally.
</P>
<P>
   The spirited Huskies beat spirited Gonzaga, 67-62, advancing to
St. Petersburg, Fla., next week and ascending to Calhoun's view of
``heaven'' for the first time in school history. UConn will play
South Region champion Ohio State on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a soaked Calhoun again downplayed the significance
for himself and spoke of the program he has built over the past 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feared that people would put so much undue pressure om Jim
Calhoun going to the Final Four,'' he said. ``I'm tagging along as
the coach. Connecticut's going to the Final Four. I didn't want
that pressure put on the kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to do everything humanly possible, including
yelling an awful lot, about just (focusing on) basketball. That's
all we talked about today. Another road game to earn a trip to
Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Right, another road game that moved Calhoun to the brink of
tears, that moved his wife, Pat, past that point when he summoned
her from the stands for a warm embrace. Another road game that
prompted his son, Jim Jr., to also choke up and whisper, ``I'm
proud of you, Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Just another road game that has an entire state figuring out how
to hitch itself to a trailer and head down Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, top-seeded in the West and the strong favorite, had
to literally snatch the game from the 10th-seeded Bulldogs and the
non-UConn portion of the 18,053 fans who embraced the underdog Zags
and tried to scream them into a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   It almost worked, but the Huskies are tougher than that. They
hit the backboards with a ferocity that produced 21 offensive
rebounds and 10 points off second and third chances in the last 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Forced into a zone because of their inability to deal one-on-one
with All-America forward Richard Hamilton, the Bulldogs paid the
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just piranhas on the boards,'' Gonzaga Coach Dan
Monson said of the Huskies after Freeman, a junior forward, had 15
rebounds, 10 off the offensive glass. Both were career highs.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman said, ``It was a matter of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of down-and-dirty work was needed to offset an
0-for-12 shooting performance by sophomore point guard Khalid
El-Amin. El-Amin also got into early foul trouble, and UConn never
got into an offensive flow, shooting 36.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But El-Amin predicted Friday that defense would determine the
outcome, and he was right. The Huskies locked on Gonzaga's
three-point shooters, who had riddled Minnesota, Stanford and
Florida to advance farther in the tournament than most presumed
possible.
</P>
<P>
   After making 32 of 63 three-pointers in their three West Region
victories, the Bulldogs were 5 for 21 against the Huskies. Richie
Frahm, who made five three-pointers in Thursday's win over Florida,
was 1 for 7. Matt Santangelo, the team's No. 2 scorer behind Frahm,
was 0 for 4 from long range and 1 for 9 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who was named the regional's outstanding player, had
the primary defensive duty on Frahm. But he couldn't explain what
he did, except to say, ``I wasn't worried about scoring baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   He did anyway, ending up with 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a senior guard whom Calhoun labels the best defender he
has coached, was chiefly responsible for Santangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about as good as it gets,'' Monson said of Moore's
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get up into him when he caught the ball on
the perimeter because I knew he was a terrific shooter,'' Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite their failures from three-point range, the Zags did
enough from other parts of the court to lead by one at halftime and
by four with 16:28 to go before a 14-4 run gave UConn a 51-45 lead
with 8:28 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (32-2) wouldn't trail again. But Gonzaga (28-7)
repeatedly stayed within a breath, the last time with 36.6 seconds
left when Quentin Hall launched a three-pointer from his shoulder
to cut the UConn lead to 63-62.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin came back with a pair of free throws to put the Huskies
up by three, and Santangelo opted for a two-point attempt on the
next possession. But his runner in the lane was altered by UConn
center Jake Voskuhl. Freeman hit a pair of free throws and then
stole the inbound pass, heaving it into the air as time was
expiring. Moore grabbed it, shot and missed, but the celebration
already had begun.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga huddled up and walked off, heads held high. After that,
Santangelo talked of friendship and love of each other and of
competition. He said the most important thing he wanted to get
across was ``people to understand that we deserve to be here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8403 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-EL-AMIN-AZR &LR;      03-21 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-EL-AMIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL-AMIN HAPPY WITH END RESULT  
 GUARD SURVIVES SUBPAR OUTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - After it was over, Khalid El-Amin had plenty to smile
about.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he spent all but four minutes of the first half
on the bench in foul trouble. Or missed all 12 field-goal attempts.
Or committed what could have been a costly turnover when he took
his eye off a teammate's pass with less than two minutes left. Or
was outplayed by Gonzaga's 5-foot-8 Quentin Hall.
</P>
<P>
   UConn won, 67-62, in Saturday's West Region final at America
West Arena, so everything was fine in El-Amin's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a few good looks, and I missed,'' he said, shrugging off
his performance. ``I decided I was going to try and do a few more
little things. I had a couple assists and also a couple of big
rebounds. We got the `W,' and that's what I was very pleased
about.''
</P>
<P>
   It could have easily turned disastrous for El-Amin. With
Connecticut clinging to a two-point lead, he let a pass slip
through his hands out of bounds, giving Gonzaga the ball with 1:47
left. Fourteen seconds later, Gonzaga guard Matt Santangelo was at
the free-throw line for a one-and-one that could have tied the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo missed the first shot, and the Huskies held off the
Bulldogs the rest of the way, thanks in part to two key free throws
by El-Amin that gave UConn a three-point lead with 34.4 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-10 and 203 pounds, the only sharp edges to El-Amin are
in his game. His tough mentality is his biggest asset. Yet
Saturday, it was his mental mistakes that did him in, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first couple of possessions, I wasn't paying attention
to detail very well,'' he said. ``I was running at him (Hall), he
went around me, and I bumped him twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun considered bringing El-Amin back in the first half, but
the Bulldogs never threatened to pull away.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we stayed within three or four points, I felt we
could roll the dice,'' Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin struggled when he returned, missing all 10 of his
second-half shots. And his turnover late in the game would have
been costly had Gonzaga converted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had so many thoughts going through my mind at one time, I
just forgot about catching the ball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, meanwhile, caused the Huskies problems all afternoon. He
finished with 18 points and was the best point guard on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out with every intention of outplaying him (El-Amin),
but I do that every game, no matter who I play against,'' Hall
said. ``I tell you what, if I had a choice, I'd take his game and
take the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall and El-Amin held an animated conversation in the final
minute, but after the game neither wanted to go into detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some friendly greetings-type things,'' is how El-Amin
described the conversation. ``He was trying to get into our heads.
We won the game, so that's my talking.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hall was confident, he didn't expect El-Amin to play as
poorly as he did Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him on TV,'' Hall said. ``I know he's got more than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of UConn's biggest strengths is its depth. When El-Amin
went out, senior Ricky Moore took over at the point and finished
with 12 points, three assists and one turnover. He also was
suffocating defensively, limiting Santangelo to 1-of-9 shooting
from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was the Huskies starting point guard until El-Amin
arrived, so he felt comfortable in the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew somebody had to step up because Khalid was out,'' Moore
said. ``We were not making the shots in the first half, and I knew
someone had to do it. I thought this could be my last game, and
that kind of scared me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
