<HEADER>
A8404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-BRAND-BOS &LR;      03-21 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-BRAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN'T BRAND HIM A SOFTIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ How do you describe the play of Duke
sophomore power forward Elton Brand? You know that space on the
front and sides of the basket, the area folks call the paint? That
belongs to him. It's his. Others in college basketball play well in
the area. Some would lead you to believe they control the paint,
that they own it. They don't. Elton Brand does.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-8-inch, 260-pound widebody owns it because if a loose
ball lands in that area and he is among five players who go after
it, he is the one who comes up with it. Attack him with a shot and
watch him swat it out of the paint. He's territorial.
</P>
<P>
   Double- or triple-team him in the area while trying to score,
and watch him score. Whack him in the process and watch him step to
the line to complete the 3-point play. He's strong, tenacious.
</P>
<P>
   Leave a driving lane along the baseline that only an underweight
gnat could get through, and he'll find a way through. He's agile,
nimble. Try to beat him to the baseline and you'll settle for
second. He's quick, fluid.
</P>
<P>
   The national player of the year candidate is the primary reason
top-ranked, top-seeded Duke (35-1) is one of the most dominant
teams in recent college basketball history, why it enters Sunday's
East Regional final against sixth-seeded Temple (game time is 2:40
p.m.) the odds-on favorite to capture its third national
championship this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how big he is, but man he plays basketball as
well as I've ever seen a strong forward,'' said Temple coach John
Chaney. ``Watch him play with those long arms, and to watch him
play like a pro at this level is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand leads the team in scoring (17.7 ppg) and rebounds (9.6
rpg) and is coming off a most impressive showing in Duke's 78-61
victory over 12th-seeded Southwest Missouri State in the regional
semifinal. He finished with 14 points, 8 rebounds (including 5
offensive), 5 blocks, and 4 steals. Battling 6-11 center Danny
Moore and being double-teamed throughout, Brand controlled the
paint as if, well, as if he owned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can muscle you. He can bounce off people,'' said Chaney.
``He can throw his body into you and make you play to the basket.
I've neer seen a player his size play that well underneath. I
remember Larry Johnson, from Las Vegas, but he's even better than
that kid.''
</P>
<P>
   And he does it with an intense demeanor that spreads to his
teammates. ``He brings a lot, from his personality to his
expressions on the court,'' said Duke guard William Avery. ``When
he scores and shakes his head at a guy, like he's saying, `It's no
way you can guard me,' we really feed off of that. We get energy
and we just play harder.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that a player could be this dominant in
college basketball. But someone from Peekskill, N.Y., a small,
bucolic town more than 30 minutes north of New York City?
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember taking a bus trip upstate to play an AAU game,''
said Brand, ``and the guys on my team were looking at different
media guides. They said, `Throw out a school. Where would you like
to go?' And I said, `Duke, Georgetown, North Carolina.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a freshman at the time, and they were like, `Be
realistic.' They thought I should have gone to a place like the
University of Buffalo. That was where they were looking at. I had
big dreams, and they kept saying, `Be realistic.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a few growth spurts following his freshman year in
high school. Brand grew to 6-4, 200 pounds as a 13-year-old. And,
when he realized kids his age were too small to contend with him,
he took his game to outdoor courts, to play against men two or
three years out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   They were multi-talented players who didn't make it to college
but still were living out their basketball fantasies. He was
someone trying to make his unfold. ``They were signed-up hackers,''
said Brand. ``That's all they did. They would just hack you and
wouldn't let you call the foul, so I was used to being physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Peekskill High School coach Lou Panzanaro gave Brand's
dream a major push in 10th grade, working with him on low-post
moves, jump hooks, drop steps and his work ethic so much that it
almost backfired when Brand contemplated quitting basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would say things like, `All right, we're not leaving until
Elton makes 20 jump hooks,' '' said Brand,in a tone that reveals
he's still a little bothered by his coach's approach. ``It was
extra pressure on me, but he wanted me to improve and I give him a
lot of credit for my success and work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   By his junior season, the kid from Peekskill had begun excelling
at AAU tournaments against some of the nation's stars and became
one of the most sought-after players before choosing Duke over
Kentucky, Villanova, and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Since his arrival at Duke, Brand has been one of the most
dominant players in college basketball. Last season he was named an
honorable mention All-American, averaging 13.4 points and 7.4
rebounds. ``Being able to play against some of the top players like
Antawn Jamison and Robert Traylor last year,'' he said, ``that's
what gave me the confidence (to think) I can play at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he suffered a broken left foot in practice last season that
forced him to miss 15 games. Brand returned to help guide Duke to
last year's NCAA South Regional final, but the Blue Devils lost to
eventual champion Kentucky after leading by as many as 18 points in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up a lot, and I remember saying with 12 minutes to go
that we were on our way to the Final Four,'' said Brand. ``And then
the buzzer sounded and we were down by 2. That was somewhat of a
daze.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand scored just 4 points in that game. He wasn't as dominant a
player as before the injury and said he sought to prove the setback
had left no lasting effects. Many said he began doing that when he
led the US squad to a gold medal in last summer's Goodwill Games,
where he averaged 17 points, 7.6 boards, and shot 65 percent from
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was a New York summer league matchup against New York
resident Anthony Mason, now with the NBA Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to make it more of a matchup and all the fans
there were trying to make him go at me,'' said Brand. ``He pretty
much went at me. But I held my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his prowess this season, Brand was benched for Duke's
games against Michigan (Dec. 12) and North Carolina A&AMP;T (Dec. 20).
The remainder of the season, he was arguably the most dominant
player in college ball, posting double figures in 13 of Duke's
remaining 24 games. That included a 16-point, 12-board, 7-block
effort vs. St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just not playing hard enough,'' Brand said, ``and I
think the coach wanted to send a message to the team that nothing's
given, especially on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the NCAA Tournament, Brand has fielded questions
regarding his future. He denied reports that he will definitely
turn pro, going so far as to say that he is leaning toward
returning to Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you can let down the temptation (of going to the
NBA) is knowing it will be there and enjoying yourself right now,''
said Brand. ``I think I'm leaning more towards staying because I
love school and this is all I know. I don't know how to be rich,
how to have money yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
