<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-HAMILTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHY ON FANCY BUT IT COUNTS  
 FOR UCONN'S HAM ILTON, REGION TITLE STILL A KEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It wasn't the prettiest of victories, but All-America
forward Richard Hamilton said the videotape of Connecticut's 67-62
win over Gonzaga on Saturday goes right to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Shots weren't falling. The Huskies made just 36.9 percent of
them. Point guard Khalid El-Amin was 0 for 12 and was reduced to
being a spectator for most of the first half because of two fouls.
</P>
<P>
   But the statistic the Huskies can cherish all the way to St.
Petersburg, Fla. _ site of the Final Four _ is the rebounds,
particularly on the offensive end.
</P>
<P>
   UConn had 47 boards. Twenty-one were on the offensive end, 13 in
the second half. Gonzaga, which had three fewer rebounds in the
first half, when it led by a point, finished with 33 boards, 13 on
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``To not be on your `A' game, but to still will yourself to win,
shows how much heart we had today,'' said center Jake Voskuhl, who
had nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga used a 1-2-2 zone for much of the second half. Its game
plan was to turn the quicker Huskies into jump shooters. Given
UConn's shooting struggles, including 0 for 9 from three-point
range, it seemed a sound strategy. But when the shots were clanking
off the rim, Kevin Freeman was usually there. So was Voskuhl. So
was reserve forward Edmund Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with trying to get them to shoot outside, when
you're in a zone, they're piranhas on the boards,'' Bulldogs Coach
Dan Monson said. ``We paid the price. Twenty-one offensive
rebounds. We cut that in half and we're probably second at this
podium'' _ referring to the post-game news conference in which the
losing team meets the media first.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman rated his offensive performance a one (he made 4 of 14
shots), but the way he hit the offensive boards, especially in the
second half, received ovations from his coach and teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He had 10 of his 15 rebounds on the offensive end, including a
tip off his own miss with 7:42 to play to give the Huskies a 53-47
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin has had more artistic games,'' Coach Jim Calhoun said.
``But coming down the stretch, he had that look you occasionally
see with him that he will not be denied. I think, down the stretch,
his rebounding was one of the most phenomenal things I've seen a
guy do.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman said he noticed how Gonzaga beat Florida on a late tip
in Thursday's semifinals. He said there was no way the Huskies were
going to let this game get away by being soft on the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gonzaga) got after it early, and it kind of told us, `Hey, we
have to make this lane ours and keep them out,' '' Freeman said.
``We had to fight for every score. It was a tough situation. But
this team isn't going to quit after the shot goes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun also liked his team's defensive effort. Hamilton limited
Richie Frahm, Gonzaga's leading scorer, to seven points on 2-of-11
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over here is the first time I had respect for my defense,''
Hamilton said. ``I told everybody, but nobody wanted to listen. I'm
trying to be a complete player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton did his part on offense, too. With El-Amin on the
bench, Hamilton put the Huskies on his back and scored 11 of his 21
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look up in the dictionary for NBA player and you've got
Hamilton,'' Monson said. ``He does everything you want from a
player.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
