<HEADER>
A8406 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-GONZAGA-AZR &LR;      03-21 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-GONZAGA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTANGELO TAKES LOSS PERSONALLY  
 GONZAGA GUARD BLAMES OWN PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If Gonzaga guard Matt Santangelo has endured a more
miserable game, he can't remember it.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 2-for-12 shooting performance against Idaho. But
that came in a 39-point non-conference victory.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 1-for-9 effort couldn't have come at a worse time _
the biggest game in school history and a chance for the Bulldogs to
continue their fairy-tale season.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo blamed himself for Gonzaga's 67-62 loss to
Connecticut in the NCAA West Regional final at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I let down my teammates with my performance,''
said Santangelo, Gonzaga's floor leader and its first honorable
mention All-American since John Stockton in 1984. ``It's a real
personal thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with Santangelo's dismal shooting, the Bulldogs still
had a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Quentin Hall's off-balance three-pointer with 36
seconds left pulled Gonzaga to within one point. Then, after
Connecticut's Khalid El-Amin hit two free throws with 34 seconds
remaining, Santangelo had another chance to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   He drove through the lane with eight seconds left and could have
dished the ball to either wing for a game-tying three pointer.
Instead, he shot and missed, and the Bulldogs were forced to foul
with 6.2 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should have kicked it out,'' Santangelo said.
``Then again, we could have gotten a quick score (two-pointer), and
there still would have been plenty of time left. We could have
fouled and then had another possession. I may have made a bad
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Up until Saturday, Santangelo had made many good decisions in
orchestrating Gonzaga's marvelous ride through the NCAA Tournament
from the No. 10 seed to the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I don't feel I did the things I did all year,'' said
Santangelo, who finished with a season-low two points. ``I fought
through it. But I still feel real disappointed in myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to win a game like this, you have to have all the
strengths going at once. The (shooting) guards never held up their
end of the bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo and Richie Frahm combined to shoot 3 of 20 from the
field, 1 of 11 from three-point range. As a team, the Bulldogs were
5 of 21 beyond the arc. In their first three tournament games, the
Bulldogs made 32 of 63 three-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo's teammates were quick to come to his defense. Hall,
who kept the Bulldogs in the game with a team-high 18 points and
eight rebounds, said he thought Santangelo was being too hard on
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Casey Calvary concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt's got so much on his shoulders,'' Calvary said. ``The
other team focuses on him so much, and he does so many other
things, bringing the ball up, rebounding, defense. He still had a
good game, even if the shots weren't falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Frahm's shots weren't falling, either. He was 2 of 11 from the
field, 1 of 7 from three-point range while being guarded by
Connecticut All-America forward Richard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the life of a shooter,'' Frahm said. ``You live and die
with the shot. I just couldn't hit the open shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Monson said the offensive difficulties were somewhat
understandable, given the magnitude of the game and the caliber of
the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team isn't just a three-point-shooting freak show,''
Monson said. ``We've had games where the shots didn't go in. It
didn't surprise me we were struggling offensively. This was a game
to go to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was up to the task. He completely outplayed El-Amin,
holding him without a field goal on 12 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was indescribable,'' Santangelo said of Hall. ``He did
everything he needed to do for us to win. I feel sorry we didn't
give him any help.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the loss, the 10th-seeded Bulldogs know they put
Gonzaga's program on the map.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to understand we belonged and we deserved to be
here,'' Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Said center Jeremy Eaton, ``This was not the way we wanted it to
end, but in a couple of days, we will realize where we were. We
were among the top eight teams in college basketball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
