<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-PING-3RD-RD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBB VAULTS TO THE FRONT  
 BUT LEADER RESPECTS FOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Perhaps it is too early to hand Karrie Webb a check
for $127,500, the lion's share of the purse for the Standard
Register PING.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Lorie Kane is a fine player who is only 2 strokes
back entering today's final round at Moon Valley Country Club. And
former Arizona State University star Wendy Ward and Scottsdale's
Tina Barrett also are in shouting distance, 4 off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Kristi Albers has an outside chance, too. She is 5 strokes back
after posting the best score of Saturday's wind-blown third round,
a 6-under 66.
</P>
<P>
   Although Webb is 48 under through her last 11 rounds, the
Australian knows better than to get ahead of herself.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it's her tournament to win or lose, Webb said, ``No,
there's a lot of good players in this field, and I have a lot of
respect for the girls that are up there on the leader board. I
could still shoot 2 or 3 under and lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But the way the cool and confident Webb is striking her driver,
launching her irons and holing putts, she looks unsinkable. In the
19 rounds she has played this season, she has been under par in 15.
Only twice has she been over par, and those were just barely, a 73
and a 74.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll play the same sort of golf I have been and see what
happens,'' said Webb, who already has two victories in 1999,
including a record-setting 26-under effort in the recent Australian
Ladies Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``(A 2-shot lead) can be turned around in one hole, and this
course can reach up and grab you.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Webb has her game on cruise control. Her latest
effort included four birdies and a bogey as her 69 got her to 11
under.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions were pretty tough out there,'' noted Webb, who
entered the day 1 shot behind second-round leader Tracy Hanson, who
felt the wrath of the wind on her way to a devastating 81.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a little windy, and the course is drying up,''
Hanson said. ``The new greens (Nos. 14, 15 and 18) are like bricks.
(The wind) affected club selection, especially the last few holes,
because it was crossing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson actually lost the lead on the first hole, where she
bogeyed and Webb birdied. From that point on, everyone was in
pursuit of Webb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karrie drove it fabulous,'' said Kane, who was in the same
threesome. ``My consistency comes from driving the ball, and I let
the wind move me around out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kane still managed to hang on with a birdie on the final
hole that got her to 71 and 9 under.
</P>
<P>
   Kane said she's just glad ``we've got one more round of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest, I wasn't trying to chase Karrie, just stay as
close as possible,'' said the Canadian, who has yet to win on the
LPGA in three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. Kane knows what she is up against.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got a golf swing, a game and an attitude like
Karrie, you're going to win,'' Kane said. ``She really sets the
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who carded a 68, and Barrett, who shot 70, have both won
before. Of the two, Ward has perhaps the best vibes, having
finished in third place here as an amateur in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Ward said she does not feel intimidated while chasing the
hottest player in women's golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karrie and I have played a lot of golf together,'' said Ward,
who at one point had it to 8 under through her first eight holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '95, I (was paired in the final round of the Standard
Register PING) with the best two golfers in the world at that time,
Beth (Daniel) and Laura (Davies), and came close to catching
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Albers, who made seven birdies and a bogey to get to 6 under,
will have to go at least that low again _ and hope Webb has a
hiccup or two.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, it's probably long-shot city, as three other
pre-tournament favorites _ Davies (72), Annika Sorenstam (71) and
Helen Alfredsson (74) _ are all 7 strokes back.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's biggest fear, if there is such a thing, might be that the
forecast calls for stiffer breezes today.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what the weather will do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kane hopes the wind blows and blows and blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up on an island,'' said Kane, who hails from Prince
Edward Island. ``I'll be happy if it does.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
