<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLES IN ONE JUST PAR FOR THE LPGA COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Annika Sorenstam was steamed. Standing outside the
scorer's tent, she shook her head. Downcast, arms crossed, she
muttered to herself and her caddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But ``Annika'','' I wanted to say, and it was all I could do
to keep from grabbing her by the shoulders and shaking her
violently, ``you got a HOLE IN ONE!!!''
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish-born golfer aced the par 3 second hole Saturday at
Moon Valley Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Her 8-iron shot traveled 140 yards. Dropping out of the bright
blue sky, the little white ball landed softly on the green,
bounced, rolled about 15 feet and disappeared like a bunny rabbit
down a hole. Startled witnesses erupted in wild cheers.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the miracle, Sorenstam requested a few moments
alone while she composed herself. Sorenstam, who shot 71, couldn't
shake her disappointment after bogeying the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   And the hole in one?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good shot,'' Sorenstam said later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good''?
</P>
<P>
   Perfect, if you asked me.
</P>
<P>
   But what do I know?
</P>
<P>
   Like most human beings, I've never made a hole in one, and I've
been trying since before Annika was born.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam's muted reaction to a feat that duffers dream of
experiencing just once before going to that big par 3 course in the
clouds is typical of professional shotmakers. To them a hole in one
isn't such a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Hollis Stacy hasn't made a hole in one during the LPGA Standard
Register PING tournament, but she has bagged her share. How many,
Hollis?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about eight,'' she said casually.
</P>
<P>
   ``About'' eight?
</P>
<P>
   ``In competition, only three or four.'' Hollis said, smiling.
``I can't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   How does one not remember something as remarkable as a hole in
one? To me, it's like asking a mother how many times she has given
birth, and she says `Oh, three, maybe four. . .'' The exact number
had slipped her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy said she got her first hole in one when she was 12 or 13.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to strangle her.
</P>
<P>
   Groucho Marx once was asked what he thought was the toughest
shot in golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it,'' Marx replied, his eyebrows doing pushups, ``to be
the hole in one.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the degree of difficulty is overrated. Jackie
Gallagher-Smith knocked the ball into the 15th hole on Friday, 172
yards, using a five iron. LPGA players have recorded five holes in
one in eight tournaments this year.
</P>
<P>
   These women totaled 25 aces in tournament competition last year,
and a record 29 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Whitworth, an LPGA pioneer, had 11 during her career. Jan
Stephenson has more aces (8) than ex-husbands. Tracy Kerdyk had
three holes in one in one ``year''.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Ward, the former ASU All-American, scored her first ace in
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still three behind my mother,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I hate them. Both of them.
</P>
<P>
   If life were fair, each person who played golf would be allotted
one hole in one.
</P>
<P>
   But life isn't fair, as evidenced by a Texas man who claims he
has recorded more than 40. Mancil Davis reportedly once sliced his
tee shot into a pine tree. The ball ricocheted toward the green,
bounced off a sprinkler head and hopped into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Even more remarkable is the frequency of holes in one scored on
the LPGA Tour. TV announcer Ben Wright once actually said that
women golfers were handicapped because they ``have boobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this anatomical ``disadvantage,'' women keep knocking
the ball into the hole with one swing. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
