<HEADLINE>
BARKLEY, ROCKETS KNOCK OFF SUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Charles Barkley was embarrassed the last time the
Houston Rockets lost a game. It was in Phoenix, where Barkley says
the Suns have a team that won't even reach the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Barkley made amends against his old ballclub,
scoring a season-high 35 points, including the first six on three
unanswered baskets in overtime, and grabbed 18 rebounds as the
Rockets beat the Suns, 103-93, at the Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley and the Rockets sent the Suns home with their third loss
on a four-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Suns Coach Danny Ainge, after wearing Barkley down with Joe
Kleine defending him in Phoenix, tried the same ploy in the
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked for them once, so they tried it again,'' Barkley
said. ``Only this time we weren't playing the second game
back-to-back.''
</P>
<P>
   And he made Kleine a profit. The Suns' reserve center had said,
after limiting Barkley to two fourth-quarter baskets in Phoenix,
that if Barkley is hitting his mid-range jump shots, ``you're at
his mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   They were, and he was merciless, scoring inside and outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he's one of the top 50 players of all time,''
Kleine said.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge agreed. ``It's pick your poisin in the overtime,'' he
said. ``Do we play him man-to-man and hope he can't post us up, or
do we double-team and let them shoot threes?'' he said. ``It's a
helpless feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took all Barkley had to keep the Suns from stealing
another from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns had an opportunity to win in regulation, but Scottie
Pippen forced Phoenix guard Rex Chapman into a turnover with 5.1
seconds remaining, ma king up for his own turnover with 14 seconds
to go that opened the door for the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a miscommunication,'' Chapman said. ``I take
responsibility because I'm a guard out on the court. I don't think
everybody knew what we were doing. We were trying to get me a shot
off a screen, and the play broke do wn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played hard, but there's no excuse for the mental
breakdowns. You can live with the physical mistakes, but we lost
this game because of mental mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Suns had played with the same exuberance they had in
Houston in their fourth game in five nights on the road earlier in
the trip, they would have gotten out of Charlotte or Atlanta with a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   They hit the boards, scrambled for loose balls. Luc Longley even
drove past Hakeem Olajuwon for a slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was that guy?'' Suns Coach Danny Ainge asked.
</P>
<P>
   With Tom Gugliotta pouring in 12 of his team-high 22 points in
the first quarter, the Suns mounted a 27-22 lead. Still, they had
to weather an 18-0 second-quarter Houston run to stay in the game.
And the Rockets mounted it with center Hakeem Olajuwon and Pippen
on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   It started after Danny Manning's 17-foot shot put the Suns up
29-22 less than a minute into the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley's postup move in the lane started it with 10:50
to go in the second and Barkley's fade-away jumper, then a power
move in the paint capped it with 6:04 to go in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Manning finally ended it with a driving layup, and that started
a surprising 11-1 Phoenix counterpunch that trimmed a 40-29 deficit
to two points.
</P>
<P>
   And the Suns actually regained the lead briefly when Gugliotta
pushed the ball up the floor, kicked it to Kidd, who fed Robinson's
for the finish and a 46-45 lead. But Pippen hit his first shot of
the half, a three-pointer, with 19.9 seconds to go and Othella
Harrington's free throw with less than a second remaining sent the
Rockets to the locker room with a 49-46 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Suns responded, this time with one of their best
third-quarter performances of the season. The third quarter is
often their Achilles heel. It was 24 hours earlier in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But the starting five rallied to a 60-60 tie, then the reserves
came in and kept it going. Rex Chapman's three-point shot with half
a second to go in the quarter gave the Suns their biggest lead of
the game to that point, 77-68.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets rallied behind Barkley. He scored their first five
points in a 10-0 Houston run to start the final period. His
offensive rebound and putback basket with 6:16 to play started
another spurt, this one 8-2 that gave the Rockets an 86-84 lead
with 4:03 to go in the game. And Barkley's fastbreak lay up with
1:31 to go gave Houston a three-point advantage.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for the Suns last-gasp effort. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
