<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TRADE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES TRADE FOR ISLANDERS' LEADING SCORER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - General Manager Bobby Smith fired the 100 mph slap
shot everyone has been waiting for. And he scored Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the woeful New York Islanders decided to continue
gutting their team, Smith swooped in and plucked away their leading
scorer, 27-year-old center Robert Reichel, in exchange for young
winger Brad Isbister, 21, who is on the injured list with a pulled
groin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Coyotes swapped third-round picks in the
upcoming June NHL entry draft _ potentially moving up 18 spots that
round by virtue of the Isles' disastrous season _ and also acquired
a fourth-round pick from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased we were able to make this trade,'' Smith
said, shortly before the deal became official early Saturday night.
``Obviously, there's an age difference and a salary difference, but
you can tell by the compensatory picks involved that we value our
youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been extremely impressed with Brad Isbister. He's
a terrific young player and a terrific young man, who's going to
have a great career. I did not want to trade him, but to get a
player as accomplished as Robert Reichel, who's so talented and so
good on the power play . . . (Jeremy) Roenick's the only guy we've
got who's scored more points than him.''
</P>
<P>
   Listed at 5-foot-10 and 186 pounds, Reichel, a two-time 40-goal
scorer from the Czech Republic, will center the Coyotes' No. 2 line
between veterans Greg Adams and Rick Tocchet. The eight-year pro,
who helped the Czechs win the gold medal last year at the Nagano
Olympics, should be in the Phoenix lineup tonight at 6 when the
Coyotes meet the Los Angeles Kings at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   After 70 games, he was leading the Islanders in goals (19),
assists (37) and points (56) _ eight fewer than Roenick. A
fifth-round find by Calgary in 1989, Reichel, who scored the
Czech's lone goal in their semifinal Olympic win over Canada, hit
the 40-goal mark with the Flames in 1992-93 and 1993-94. That last
season, when he added 53 assists for 93 points, was his NHL best.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel earns $1.7 million, $500,000 of which reportedly is paid
by the Flames following his trade to New York two years ago. He
will become a restricted free agent this summer and had threatened
to return to the Czech Republic for good if the Islanders didn't
extend his contract this season. Reportedly, he wants a multiyear
deal worth $3 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, however, isn't worried about losing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to have him here for several years and we'll deal
with that after the season,'' Smith said. ``I'm optimistic he's
going to like Phoenix, like our team and that's he's going to be
able to come to agreement with us on a new deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Isbister, who expects to play within a week to 10 days, said he
was shocked to learn he was going to the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard rumors I was going to Montreal for (Vincent)
Damphousse, so yeah, I was kind of caught off guard,'' Isbister
said. ``When Bobby called me, I thought that's what he was going to
say. But this is a good opportunity for me, too. I should get the
chance to play a lot and show them what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   A fourth-round pick in '95, Isbister had four goals and four
assists for the Coyotes during an up-and-down, injury-riddled
season. He has missed 29 of the team's past 33 games because of the
nagging groin injury, which weeks ago developed into a hernia,
requiring surgery. He recently returned from that injury only to be
sidelined again after three games on the active list. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
