r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-SPORT-ANALYSIS-AZ     03-21 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-SPORT-ANALYSIS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING STENCH GROWS FROM GARBAGE INSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   News item: Muhammad Ali knocks out Sonny Liston on May 25, 1965,
at Lewiston, Maine, with a phantom punch. It wasn't seen at
ringside, and it has never been detected in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Boxing is condemned.
</P>
<P>
   News item: Mike Tyson bites Evander Holyfield's ears on June 28,
1997, at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: Loud condemnations.
</P>
<P>
   News item: Lennox Lewis scores heavily and repeatedly against
Holyfield, yet the judges declare a draw on March 13, 1999, at New
York's Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction: The chorus continues.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Will it ever end?
</P>
<P>
   The controversial beat of a sport, contentious by definition,
has been going on since the day somebody discovered that fists are
pretty handy as weapons. There's no dispute about the world's
oldest profession. Nonetheless, boxing runs a very close second,
both in time and practice.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing always has resisted regulation. Defiance is admired
inside of the ropes and practiced outside of them. The public
complains. Yet it always seems to return. Many of 1.4 million
pay-per-view television customers for Tyson's dinner date with
Holyfield's ears screamed that they would never watch the sport
again. But, nearly two years later, there were about 1.2 million
customers for Lewis-Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like a great fight,'' said Don Harris, a
longtime boxing judge and the Maricopa County Attorney in 1976. ``A
great fight is like a work of art.''
</P>
<P>
   But the old art form is beginning to look like graffiti. It
still has its moments. Oscar De La Hoya's stirring decision over
Ike Quartey on Feb. 13 has been debated and reviewed as though it
were a masterpiece worth another look. But Lewis-Holyfield has
taken on a powerful stench. It's been called garbage by fans,
media, politicians and seemingly everybody but promoter Don King,
who is better at selling controversy than any tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis-Holyfield has begun to attract attention that not even
King can deflect, or perhaps elude. Above all, there's the
government, which has begun to look at the bout as though it were a
problem for waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least three investigations. Two have been launched
by the state of New York. A third has been ongoing. The federal
district of Manhattan has had a grand jury looking into boxing's
business practices for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is Arizona Senator John McCain, who has authored the
framework for some federal legislation and is pushing for more.
McCain was at ringside for Lewis-Holyfield. He said he a got phone
call last week from Muhammad Ali's wife, Lonnie, who relayed her
husband's disgust at the result. In a letter Wednesday to New York
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, McCain wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``The best outcome of the Holyfield-Lewis bout would be a
complete overhaul of boxing industry abuses in America. . . . An
inquiry into the Holyfield-Lewis controversy presents an
opportunity to reform this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   There are allegations that Holyfield-Lewis is the tip of a
titanic iceberg full of kickbacks to promoters, bribes for world
ratings and manipulation of judges. The ruling bodies _ World
Boxing Council, World Boxing Association and International Boxing
Federation _ take percentages of purses as sanctioning fees for
titles that are designed to give televised bouts some credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing always has been run by questionable, unethical practices.
In the late 1940s and 1950s, there was a U.S. Senate hearing on
involvement by organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were better off when the mob ran it,'' said Steve Eisner, a
longtime Valley promoter who has managed fighters since the 1950s.
``At least then, you knew who and what you were dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the three organizations each want 2.5 to 5 percent of the
purses for sanctioning fees. The federal grand jury reportedly is
asking questions about whether those same organizations rig the
ratings. Can a top-10 ranking be bought?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called outstretched palms in T-room meetings, the T
standing for Treasury bills,'' said Eisner, who said in the 1940s
and '50s there was only one body _ the mob _ to pay, unlike today's
many-sided collection agency.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate task is to root out the influence that ruling
bodies and promoters have over the selection of judges, according
to Harris, McCain and Eisner. At Lewis-Holyfield, each of the
heavyweight titles _ WBA, IBF and WBC _ was represented by a judge
selected by the respective organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has to change,'' said John Montano, executive director of
the Arizona State Boxing Commission and vice president of the
national Association of Commissions, which was created by McCain's
legislation. ``We need to create a pool of recognized, reputable
judges. Then, the national association would make assignments for
the big title fights. As states, we have to exercise more control
over who judges and referees.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, there are too many conflicts of
interest. For instance, the IBF judge is less likely to score
against that organization's champ. Example: Jean Williams was the
IBF judge at Lewis-Holyfield. Holyfield holds the IBF title.
Williams scored the fight for Holyfield. If there's a rematch,
there's another sanctioning fee for the IBF, which figures to look
kindly on Williams when it assigns judges for another major bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it is now, if the judge doesn't see it the way the
organizations or the promoter sees it, that judge might not get
another assignment,'' Montano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody, of course, wants to lose power they've had for a long
time. In trying to take away that power from the ruling bodies,
we'll undoubtedly have a huge fight on our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as it doesn't end in a draw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
