<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8413 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MEETINGS-ANALYSIS     03-21 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEETINGS-ANALYSIS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL: INTO 21ST CENTURY AT 55 MPH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's viewed as a ``Good Old Boys'' club, a bunch of
rich curmudgeons who aren't crazy about change.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, change the NFL did during the spring meetings at the
Arizona Biltmore last week _ even if some of the team owners had to
be dragged kicking and screaming into the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
   They took steps to catch up with high technology, foremost being
their approval of the return of instant replay on a one-year trial.
</P>
<P>
   There were other issues discussed that could impact the league
significantly, but the manner with which the owners dealt with
those indicates that they're still generally driving 55 mph in a 75
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to several high-profile officiating snafus, an instant
replay video has become as hot an item as a Lauryn Hill video, and
even the geriatric crowd in the owners' room seemed to appreciate
that.
</P>
<P>
   Three systems, shown to teams at the scouting combine in
February, are under consideration to become the means by which
instant replay will be administered during its trial run. All are
quick and sharp to view, addressing the biggest concern among many
replay opponents: pace of the game. The strongest sentiment seemed
to be for a hand-held digital camera.
</P>
<P>
   When the coach wants to make a replay challenge, he will beep
the referee, much like a restaurant pages patrons who have waited
an hour and 45 minutes for a table, or like the employee in the
third hour of a lunch break who is being sought frantically by the
boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I like the old bean bag that you tossed out
there,'' said Mike Holmgren, new coach of the Seattle Seahawks.
``But it ``is'' the high-tech age. It might be kind of fun to zap
these guys once in a while, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It might also lead to the hiring of a computer-geek assistant
coach to monitor network television feeds of games to determine
whether a challenge is likely to be won, according to Tony Dungy,
coach of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. Coaches don't want to waste a
timeout on a lost challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we're all going to have to take a look at
now,'' Dungy said. ``It's possible that we'll have to have a replay
coach who would have the same access to the TV feed as the replay
assistant working with the officiating crew.''
</P>
<P>
   Even stately Wellington Mara, the owner of the New York Giants
who epitomizes the league's old guard, changed his vote this time,
after voting against replay nine straight times. ``Duke,'' as he is
known, is approaching his 83rd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are new stunts they are going to try, and new
equipment,'' Mara said. ``They have all this new technology.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is a by-committee version of instant replay, with
narrow parameters governing what can be challenged. Supporters
conceded they just wanted to get it on the books while the issue is
hot, try out the new technology, and hope that it works so well
that it will be expanded and extended when the owners re-evaluate
it next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't get it passed this time,'' Holmgren said, ``we
never would have.''
</P>
<P>
   Instant replay will give officials the ability to reverse many
of the obviously blown calls. But not all of them. The one that
most sticks in the craw of Cardinals fans was the obvious pass
interference against Rob Moore by Kevin Smith of the Dallas Cowboys
on the final play at Sun Devil Stadium in November. Had it been
called, the Cardinals would have had one play from the 1-yard line
to score, tie the game, and force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would have been no effect on that play with this system,
it's not viewable,'' said Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin. Pass
interference is not covered in the trial replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never included judgment calls,'' said Holmgren,
co-chairman of the league's competition committee. ``What we'd like
to do is develop consistency in the way officials call pass
interference. That is a tough call, but you can't have judgment
part of instant replay.''
</P>
<P>
   On some matters, the owners ought to make faster judgment calls
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   While the owners are enjoying unprecedented wealth in their
revenue sharing plan thanks to huge television rights and expansion
fees, they could rake in even more. The nation's second-largest
television market, Los Angeles, has been allowed to remain out of
the league for four seasons. That's more than enough time to have
put together an ownership group and arrange for construction of a
stadium, or significant modifications of an existing facility such
as the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The owners awarded a 32nd team to Los Angeles, conditionally.
The two competing groups have six months to come up with stadium
and financial plans suitable to the owners, or they'll pull the
plug on LA and award the expansion franchise to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   When _ if _ the NFL returns to LA, Al Davis wants to be
compensated for it. He doesn't necessarily want to move his Raiders
back down the coast from Oakland, where he's hoping the city lives
up to promises it made when he returned in 1995. He just wants to
be paid for the ``Los Angeles opportunity'' he believes he owns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to stop them from anything,'' Davis said. ``I
just want to uphold the rights for the territory I have.''
</P>
<P>
   If the league doesn't settle with Davis it could be looking at
legal action that might further delay the return of the game to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The owners were more moved by noise of a different sort, piped
in artificial noise, acknowledging that technology has gone too far
when canned music and cheers drown out civil conversations on the
sideline. The Cardinals were among those that complained about it
during their second-round playoff game against the Vikings at the
Metrodome in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The owners approved a rule that limits the number of speakers on
the field to four. They must be placed between the 20-yard-line and
the goal line, and they may not face toward the bench or the
playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the issue of the Milsteins, Edward and Howard, and
their business partner, Daniel Snyder. They are trying to buy the
Washington Redskins for a whopping $800 million, or about 150
percent of the expansion fee charged to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   In classic NFL style, the owners tabled for 60 days action on
approval of the purchase of the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed what the owners want is to keep the team in the
hands of John Kent Cooke, son of Jack Kent Cooke, another longtime
old-school NFL crony who died two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There also is some concern that the Milsteins would prove to be
flamboyant rogue owners, in the style of Davis or Jerry Jones of
the Cowboys. The old boys don't want their territory shaken up any
more.
</P>
<P>
   While the bow tie was smart in its time, maybe a kick in the
pants is what some of them need.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
