r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZ     03-21 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MVP RACE IS WIDE OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The season's halfway point has arrived, so it's time for the
lockout-abbreviated, 25-game midseason awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The envelopes please: &QL; 
Most Valuable Player &QL; 
With  &UR; Michael Jordan out of the league, this is suddenly a race.
And there's no clear-cut favorite.
</P>
<P>
   If the Suns could just win some games, point guard  &UR; Jason Kidd
might be a runaway choice for this right now. He has five
triple-doubles and has come within one rebound of three others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on your definition of Most Valuable Player,'' Suns
Coach
 &UR; Danny Ainge said. ``I know there's no player in the league more
valuable to his team.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the Suns are foundering. Still, Kidd will get some
votes if he continues on his current pace.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Allen Iverson of the Philadelphia 76ers is leading the league
in scoring and has blossomed since moving from the point to
shooting guard. His team also might not be good enough to get him
the award.
</P>
<P>
   And Iverson is getting some heat for missing a practice without
being excused, the latest in a series of transgressions that has
marred his young career. Unless the 76ers come on stronger, it will
cost Iverson enough votes to exclude him from winning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Karl Malone of the Jazz will get a lot of votes if Utah
finishes with the best record, although he's not playing at quite
the same high level he did two years ago when he upset Jordan for
the award.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's  &UR; Alonzo Mourning figures to carry a lot of votes in the
East, and they're deserved. His club has the second-best record
right now, and he has been a force.
</P>
<P>
   But the midseason winner here is Lakers center  &UR; Shaquille
O'Neal, who is second in scoring (27.0 points a game), first in
field goal percentage (.575) and fourth in rebounding (11.2). He's
the league's most dominant player, and although his team has
underachieved, O'Neal has been the one constant in a tumultuous
year. His coach was fired, the club made a major trade and  &UR; Dennis
Rodman has been at the same time a godsend and disruption. It's a
reluctant vote, but it goes to O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the Year &QL; 
It's a two-man race _ Miami's  &UR; Pat Riley in the Eastern Conference
and &UR; Jerry Sloan of Utah in the Western Conference. Riley has done a
fabulous job keeping a team that has been damaged by injuries to
two starters,  &UR; Voshon Leonard and  &UR; Jamal Mashburn, on track to
finish with the best record in the East.
</P>
<P>
   But our vote goes to Sloan, who never has gotten enough credit
for Utah's consistent success. Make no mistake, he'd much rather
win the Larry O'Brien Trophy that goes to the league's champion. He
might get both this year. &QL; 
Rookie of the Year &QL; 
Part of the problem with this lockout-shortened season is that many
of the voters for these awards won't even get to see all the
players under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly troublesome in voting for rookies. Boston's
 &UR; Paul
 &UR; Pierce has a checklist of teams he plans to embarrass for not
drafting him, and he's doing a pretty good job of it. He's
averaging 16.1 points a game, shooting 42.5 percent from
three-point range and is among the league's leaders in steals.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's  &UR; Vince Carter has evoked comparisons with  &UR; Dominique
Wilkins for his ``human highlight'' aerial maneuvers and leads all
rookies with 16.6 points a game average.
</P>
<P>
   But the best rookie we've seen, in person at least, is
Sacramento's
 &UR; Jason Williams, dubbed ``White Chocolate'' by his teammates. Sure,
Williams plays out of control at times, but he's fearless and a
blast to watch. And how many players can that be said about this
season? Plus, he has had an impact. Pierce and Carter may have
improved their clubs, but Williams has lifted his. &QL; 
Defensive Player of the Year &QL; 
Phoenix forward  &UR; Clifford Robinson should get consideration for
this award. He has guarded somebody at every position this season.
In fact, when someone suggested to Ainge that maybe he should let
Robinson do it all in one game just for kicks, Ainge said he
already has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee that's happened,'' he said. ``He guards a three,
four and five (small forward, power forward and center) in every
game. He's guarded (point guard)  &UR; Gary Payton. And we switch on
twos and threes (shooting guards and small forwards) defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he may not have them as a primary assignment, but he's
guarded them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson will be a long shot, though, because he doesn't have
big shot blocking or steal statistics. The likely winner is
Mourning, who is the interior anchor of the league's best defensive
team.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning gets the vote by a narrow margin. &QL; 
Sixth Man Award &QL; 
But we haven't forgotten Robinson. He has been the league's best
reserve, and based on the criteria, he qualifies despite moving
into the starting lineup. The award only requires that a player
come off the bench in the majority of his games. Robinson may not
be eligible when the season ends, but he has more bench games than
starts at the midpoint. Robinson won the award in 1991, and if
Ainge moves him back to the bench, he'll probably win it again _ if
the Suns make the playoffs. &QL; 
Most Improved Player &QL; 
This award typically goes to a player who hasn't necessarily
improved but has taken advantage of more playing time. This year,
the two leading candidates in our opinion don't fit that bill.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's  &UR; Joe Smith was considered such a bust that the
former overall No. 1 draft pick could only get a one-year, $1.75
million salary cap exception as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been terrific for the Timberwolves. Question is, did
Smith improve or did his situation just get better? He's surrounded
by better players than he had been in either Golden State, where he
started his career only three years ago, or Philadelphia, which
didn't re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   The other contender, believe it or not, is Iverson. He was
already an explosive player, but since moving off the ball, he has
taken his game up a notch. He leads the league in scoring with an
average of 29.2 points a game and is third in steals.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing he hasn't improved is his practice attendance
habits.
</P>
<P>
   So this ballot goes to Smith. &QL; 
All-NBA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, Phoenix, point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson, Philadelphia, shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, LA Lakers, center.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kevin Garnett, Minnesota, small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, Utah, power forward. &QL; 
Bob Young can be reached at 602-444-8271 or at bob.young(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
