<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYERS SEARCH FOR ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The winless streak has reached 12 games and counting for the
Philadelphia Flyers. It has swollen to 0-8-4 entering their big
showdown today against the Detroit Red Wings and because of it, the
Flyers have fallen all the way to the No. 6 spot in the Eastern
Conference where, egads, they'd have to open the playoffs on the
road at Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening to Philly isn't shocking,'' Hurricanes Coach
 &UR; Paul
 &UR; Maurice said. ``It's all part of the tightrope that teams are
walking in the Eastern Conference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers have already plunged to their demise. Or have they?
Carolina General Manager  &UR; Jim Rutherford isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is they're going to win a game here pretty soon and
then rattle off seven to 10 in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers hope that's true. But even if they don't, Coach
 &UR; Roger
 &UR; Nielson's job is safe, according to General Manager  &UR; Bobby Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no thought to replacing Roger,'' Clarke said.
``We're not going to do that. A couple of months ago, this team was
25-1 under him and people were talking about him as Coach of the
Year. So now he's going to get fired?''
</P>
<P>
   Something's got to happen, though. But please, not a last-minute
flurry of trades. Clarke's made enough moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have a good club,'' captain  &UR; Eric Lindros said.
``It's just that the people in the dressing room aren't doing the
job on the ice . . . I don't know why it's this way. We're
snake-bitten at times. The snowball keeps getting larger. We've
gotta hope for some warm weather around here to melt it down.'' &QL; 
JR wants to stay &QL; 
Responding to an ESPN report that he won't be back in a Coyotes'
uniform after this season,  &UR; Jeremy &UR; Roenick said he doesn't want to
go anywhere and he wants his fans to know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real ticked when I heard the rumor. I'm very
disappointed,'' he said. ``I'm extremely happy to be playing in
Phoenix. I love the team I play for. I love the organization. And I
really enjoy playing for the fans in Phoenix. I'm thoroughly happy
in the position I'm in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the house I've always wanted (in Paradise Valley). My
family's happy and secure there. And I've just made a couple of
purchases in the Arizona area, which should prove to everybody that
I want to stick around here for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that. The rumor was based more on the assumption
that the Coyotes may try to further trim their payroll this summer
and that Roenick, who has two years remaining on a contract that
pays him an average of $4 million a season, could be the biggest
cost-cutting casualty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if that's the case, that's the owner's decision, the
owner's and management's decision,'' Roenick said. ``If they want
to move me somewhere else because of my salary, that's their right.
But my points are up there with the same guys making the same
amount of money that I make. It's not that I'm not worthy of where
I am, financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Note to Owner  &UR; Richard Burke and GM  &UR; Bobby Smith: You might be
able to afford more by dealing away Roenick and his salary, but you
can't afford trading your most popular player. Not now, anyway. &QL; 
Weight problem &QL; 
A big reason why the Edmonton Oilers have fallen in the tank lately
is because their best player, center  &UR; Doug Weight, has been
swimming around with the Tidy Bowl Man. He's flushed his game down
the toilet since returning from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   He has just three goals in 30 games, partly, he said, because
he's been worrying too much about the knee since he's returned to
the lineup. General Manager  &UR; Glen Sather has reminded him to forget
it and move on _ now.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say I have to play better, you're damn right I do,'' Weight
said. ``If that's what Glen's saying, that's what I say, too. This
is the worst year of my career and now I've got to try and salvage
and play as hard as I can. I've been hurt, sure, but we're losing
and playing like crap. This sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Call me crazy, but I still wouldn't want to meet the Oilers in
the first round of the playoffs. Assuming they get there, of
course. &QL; 
Murphy's law
</P>
<P>
   Veteran forward  &UR; Joe Murphy of the San Jose Sharks created quite
a stir the other day while discussing the free-agent pool available
this summer. In doing so, he ragged on fellow veteran  &UR; Mark Recchi,
whom many claim will be the prized catch among the unrestricted
players on July 1 if he doesn't re-sign with the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll put my game up against his game any time, any situation,
any day,'' Murphy told the ``San Jose Mercury News.'' ``Everybody
back East where the so-called Hot Stove hockey experts are, are
sleeping by the time our games start. By the time they get the
score, it's second-day news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Recchi this, Mark Rechi that. Everybody's chirping that,
and I'm tired of hearing it. He's definitely got better (career)
numbers than I do, but that goes back to him playing with ( &UR; Mario)
 &UR; Lemieux and Eric Lindros and now he's playing with Lindros
again.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Murphy has 16 goals and 16 assists in 62 games.
Recchi has 14 goals and 35 assists in 65 games. &QL; 
They said it
</P>
<P>
   Nashville's  &UR; Jan Vopat, who has been battling a mysterious skin
irritation that has been covering his lower legs for the past
several days, on returning to the Predators' lineup after missing
four games: ``I'll be wearing new underwear, new shin pads, and
I'll put Vaseline on before I put the uniform on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa goalie  &UR; Ron Tugnutt, reminded that former teammate,  &UR; Guy
Hebert of the Mighty Ducks, said he once looked like an accountant,
not a professional hockey player: ``I was looking back at the team
picture of that first year (in 1993) and it seems to me Guy has
some hair since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Coach  &UR; Bob Hartley on Detroit  &UR; Kirk Maltby's four-game
suspension for a slash last Sunday that broke  &UR; Valeri
 &UR; Kamensky's forearm, sidelining him for the season: ``He ain't going
to get eight to 12 weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's  &UR; Alexandre Daigle, who was Philadelphia's union
representative after the Flyers picked his name out of a hat
because no one wanted the job: ``I think my name was the only name
in the hat.''
</P>
<P>
   Newly-acquired Coyotes forward  &UR; Brian Noonan, who has played for
former NHL Coach  &UR; Mike Keenan in four different cities, asked if he
thinks Keenan will resurface as an NHL coach again: ``Oh, I'm sure
someone will give him another chance. He deserves it. He's a
winner. I hope he gets another job. It means I might have another
place to play if I need one.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can &QL; 
be reached at 602 444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
