<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-GONZAGA-BOS     03-21 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-GONZAGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN HAS FINAL TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Final Four?
</P>
<P>
   Final Four!
</P>
<P>
   So it finally came to pass for the University of Connecticut
Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of what ifs, might have beens and if onlys at
places ranging from Miami to Oakland, from the Meadowlands to
Greensboro, the Huskies boldy will go where no men's basketball
team in school history had gone before: to the NCAA Final Four next
Saturday night in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   All of that became official at America West Arena Saturday as
the Huskies dug deep into their souls as they fought off surge
after surge from a gritty Gonzaga team, pulling out a 67-62 victory
in the NCAA West Regional final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if we worked any harder for a victory,'' said
Huskies coach Jim Calhoun, who now can shed the unwanted tag of
being The Best Coach Never to Reach The Final Four. ``In the last
10 years, we have had teams that have made runs (to the Final
Four). I love them all. This is for them as much as it is for this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, the top-seeded Huskies, who carry a 32-2 record
into their Final Four semifinal, earned this victory.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga, which came into the tournament as the 10th seed in the
West and quickly took on the Cinderella role capturing the hearts
of fans from salmon fishermen in Seattle to barbers in Scituate,
gave the Huskies all they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   That it wasn't enough came down to basically one or two plays in
the final seconds of a 40-minute game that had all the intensity
and tension that a regional championship brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was at the 30-second point when it (the game) changed,''
said Gonzaga forward Casey Calvary, whose last-second tip-in shot
against Florida gave the Bulldogs their first spot in a a Regional
final. ``I really felt confident until the six-second point. That
was the first time I felt we were going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   And until that point, no one at UConn, which came into the game
as a double-digit favorite, could predict the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Calhoun, who had agonzied through Regional final
losses to Duke in the Meadowlands, UCLA in Oakland, and North
Carolina in Greensboro, knew that anything could happen.
</P>
<P>
   It was that way through a first half in which Gonzaga had a
32-31 lead. It was that way through the tense final minutes as the
Huskies tried desperately to open a lead.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen until the final seconds because Gonzaga didn't
allow it to.
</P>
<P>
   With 8:28 remaining, the Huskies looked as if they finally might
open a gap when Ricky Moore completed a 3-point play to give them a
51-45 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But in a heartbeat, Gonzaga's 5-foot-8-inch senior guard Quentin
Hall wiped that out with a 20-foot 3-point shot and a drive and a
foul shot, which tied it at 53 with 6:45 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies realized they were in a last-possession type of
game. With 1:02 left, center Jake Voskuhl took a feed from Richard
Hamilton (21 points, Regional MVP) and put in a basket to give
UConn a 63-59 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun thought the trend was finally going his way. It was, but
not before a final few seconds of agony and uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Again it was Hall, who with the shot clock running down threw up
an offbalance prayer from 20 feet above the key with 36.6 seconds
left to make it 63-62.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that kid threw in the three, I said to myself, `Oh, no,'
'' said Calhoun, no doubt flashing back to Duke's Christian
Laettner's shot that cost UConn a Final Four slot in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   After a timeout, Gonzaga's strategy was clear. Foul quickly,
hope UConn missed from the foul line and come up with a buzzer
beater.
</P>
<P>
   After the timeout, the Huskies inbounded the ball to guard
Khalid El-Amin, who was having a horrible offensive day (0 for 12
from the field).
</P>
<P>
   But El-Amin, who may be UConn's toughest clutch player, made
both foul shots. Now the situation was desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga's Matt Santangelo, the self-proclaimed leader of the
team, made one last attempt to get the Bulldogs back within one
possession, but his shot was short. When the Huskies grabbed the
ball, were fouled, and made the two foul shots, Gonzaga's 28-7
dream season was over.
</P>
<P>
   As the final seconds ticked off, Kevin Freeman tossed the ball
high in the air, Calhoun, crouching on the sidelines, slowly stood
up, received a bear hug from longtime assistant and former player
Dave Leito, and looked at the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, someone asked him about his quest and how tough it
had been and what it would be like if UConn finally did reach the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do make it, I think I can skip Purgatory,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, after being drenched by his team in a football-like
water cooler dousing, Calhoun looked up with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is Purgatory,'' he said, looking around America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first stop on his way to UConn's first Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   But even with a victory, Calhoun was being tested.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting are the Buckeyes and Jim O'Brien, a former Big East
competitor but also a close enough friend that the men exchanged
good luck greetings before this weekend's games.
</P>
<P>
   That Calhoun had an 18-game winning streak when O'Brien was at
BC and an overall record of 20-3 against him doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday in St. Petersburg, it will be another test of faith
against another story that is even more feel-good than Calhoun's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
