<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-TRADE-DEADLINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DREAD TO RESIGNATION  
 PLAYERS REACT DIFFERENTLY TO TRADE DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   D-Day falls in 48 hours. The NHL is bracing itself. Especially
the players. Some are handling it better than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me about the trading deadline, please,'' begged one
Coyotes player the other day. ``I'm nervous enough as it is. I
think I'm going to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a deep breath and try to relax. It's not that bad. Trades
happen. They're part of the business. Every professional athlete
has to live with it, whether they like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, so is having to go to the dentist for root canal
surgery,'' our same Coyotes player said, still quivering in his
skates. ``I don't want to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, but just so the rest of you know: The league's moratorium on
wheeling and dealing will officially end at 1 p.m. Tuesday, Phoenix
time. The Coyotes? They finished shopping two days early, acquiring
on Saturday the second-line center they long have been searching
for by picking up Robert Reichel, the New York Islanders' leading
scorer, in exchange for Brad Isbister and a swap of some draft
picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made a lot of calls lately, but after getting this deal
done, I'd say it's pretty unlikely we'll do anything else between
now and Tuesday,'' Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, in his first season on the job, Smith said he had
been so busy chatting with other general managers in the days
leading up to the trading deadline that he had become hoarse _ so
hoarse he couldn't physically inform defenseman Dave Manson he had
just been traded to Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Last season was the most active of any Deadline Day in NHL
history. Go ahead, guess. How many trades do you think general
managers pulled off a year ago on the final day?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say eight,'' Montreal Canadiens center Trent McCleary
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Try 19. A record 38 players changed teams due to those
last-minute moves, which tied the most deals on Deadline Day ever.
Four years ago, the NHL also watched 19 trades go down. That
season, it involved 32 players.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way of telling how many trades will be made Tuesday.
Because some of the major stars who were rumored to be heading
elsewhere already have been shipped to different teams _ Toronto
sent Felix Potvin to the Islanders, Vancouver shipped Pavel Bure to
Florida, Calgary moved Theo Fleury to Colorado, and Montreal dealt
Mark Recchi to Philadelphia _ some think the numbers will be low.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be wrong, but I just don't think there's going to be a
flurry of activity this year,'' said Jim Devellano, a senior vice
president of the Detroit Red Wings. ``A lot of the big moves have
already happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Another huge one took place Saturday, when Edmonton made an
eight-player deal with Chicago that included the Oilers' Boris
Mironov and the Blackhawks' Chad Kilger. Then the Oilers got
Islanders goalie Tommy Salo for Mats Lindgren.
</P>
<P>
   Mironov, whose name had circulated in rumors for weeks, was
fully prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's coming,'' he said last week. ``There's no way not
to hear the rumors or read about them in the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone, of course. Brad Bombardir of the Islanders, who
was speculated to be part of the Mironov trade just a few days ago,
was keeping his eyes and ears open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I think about it for sure,'' he said. ``Any player who
doesn't this time of year is nuts. But thinking and worrying are
two different things. I'm thinking but not worrying.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the weekend, 85 players had been involved in trades
this season. A handful of players, such as Roman Vopat, Harry York,
Eric LaCroix and rookie Mike Maneluk, have actually been traded at
least twice.
</P>
<P>
   The deals picked up steam as March arrived with eight separate
deals in the first 15 days of the month. But more certainly await.
Maybe even more than the 19 that went down last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, who will host the Los Angeles Kings at 6 p.m.
today, had been eyeing a handful of experienced centers to play
between wingers Greg Adams and Rick Tocchet. They included Vincent
Damphousse of Montreal, Adam Oates of Washington and both Trevor
Linden and Bryan Smolinki of the Islanders, but they lucked out
while New York was gutting itself Saturday and plucked the Isles'
next-best player behind Ziggy Palffy _ the 27-year-old Reichel.
</P>
<P>
   Who's next? There's no way to be sure, of course. Anything can
and usually does happen on D-Day. Ask Detroit tough guy Joey Kocur,
who's been traded a few times on the last day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always worried, absolutely,'' he said. ``You not only
trade teams, you trade lives. Everything you've created here in
Detroit or wherever you're from is gone. Chances are, you'll never
be back. You gotta buy a new house in the next city. You gotta sell
this one. All your acquaintances, friends and connections are all
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Many, including Smith, would like to see the deadline pushed up,
perhaps moved to February, to create a more level playing field.
The general feeling around the league is that the high-priced stars
usually only go to the high-priced teams. Clubs out of the playoff
race are picked over like a leftover turkey. Those teams and
``bubble teams'' like them would have an extra month to get back
into the race if they were allowed to add players and/or protect
more of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like the deadline moved up a month,'' Edmonton General
Manager Glen Sather said. ``As it is, teams with money just rent
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Relax. The end is almost in sight. Just another 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the 24th, let's have a party so we can put all the rumors
behind us,'' quipped Islanders Coach Bill Stewart. ``But it's a
fact of life, a big day for everyone.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0024EST &QL; 
