<HEADLINE>
CRASHES TAKE JOY FROM RECORD RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Mat Mladin was happy. And mad.
</P>
<P>
   Happy because of a successful bid to capture the pole position
on Saturday in the American Motorcyclist Association Cruise America
Arizona Superbike Challenge at Phoenix International Raceway, where
Mladin uncorked a blistering record qualifying lap of 90.609 mph
over the 11-turn, 1.51-mile road course.
</P>
<P>
   But also mad, because of three vicious crashes that forced three
injured riders to be airlifted to St. Joseph's Hospital and Medical
Center for treatment of various injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Although none of the injuries appeared life threatening, the
constant summoning of helicopters turned PIR into what seemed like
a gruesome scene from an episode of ``MASH.''
</P>
<P>
   Awful, just awful.
</P>
<P>
   ``(PIR) is a nice little Mickey Mouse track,'' Mladin said. ``I
don't have anything against it. It's just that there's some areas
that aren't too safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Couple those concerns with a weather pattern that produced
unseasonably warm temperatures nearing 90 degrees, and riders were
hit with a double dose of bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track was hot and slippery,'' said Ducati's Ben Bostrom,
who will start third on today's grid behind Suzuki's Mladin and
Ducati's Anthony Gobert.
</P>
<P>
   Ty David Piz (250 Grand Prix) and Takahito Mori (Formula Xtreme)
both were airlifted after crashing into an unprotected concrete
wall. Piz suffered a closed head injury and a possible fractured
right arm, and Mori also had a head injury and suffered abrasions
on his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Both were listed in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Lopez crashed while leading the 25-lap Formula Xtreme
race, and although one eyewitness said it appeared as if the rider
hit a wall near Turn 5, another onlooker said Lopez struck the
pavement before barrel-rolling to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Lopez still needed to be transported via helicopter
with a head injury and a fractured left finger.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the 25-lap 750 SuperSport race concluded three laps early
following a spectacular crash involving rider Joseph Castillo of
Mesa. Although Castillo appeared to escape injury after crashing
into the hay bales near Turn 11, a fire erupted and it took course
workers several minutes to extinguish the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Canadian superbike champion Michael Taylor also had
to be airlifted following a horrific crash into the wall in Turn
11, which is Turn 4 on the 1-mile oval. Taylor, who was injured
during Formula Xtreme practice, suffered a concussion, a fractured
pelvis and a fractured right thumb. He underwent surgery Saturday
and remains in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track is awful,'' superbike rider Jamie Hacking said.
``There are red flags every five minutes. It's really dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get a grip on these dangerous tracks and we
need to eliminate some of them or they're going to eliminate us.''
</P>
<P>
   AMA spokesman Bill Nordquist said the problem will be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a Track Review Advisory Committee and I'm sure at the
next meeting this will be discussed,'' Nordquist said. ``I heard
people saying that in 10 years of covering this series, they've
never seen a day like this.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mladin hopes they never sees another one. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
