<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
WARD'S HUBBY WILL PAY FOR MISSING 68 
</HEADLINE>
 GLF-LPGA-PING-WARD  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Half of the dream weekend went awry, but former
Arizona State star Wendy Ward did her part to keep the second half
alive Saturday at the Standard Register PING at Moon Valley Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day at 3 under, Ward was determined to take the
smooth 4-under 68 she shot to move within 4 strokes of leader
Karrie Webb even lower.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, she wanted to punish her husband of five-plus
months, Nate Hair, for abandoning her during Saturday's round.
</P>
<P>
   Hair, a native of Spokane, Wash., was at America West Arena on a
kitchen pass, watching hometown Gonzaga's Cinderella story go up in
smoke against Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at the UConn-Iowa game Thursday night and about
halfway through it he looked at me and said, ``Well, is there
possibly any chance I could be excused on Saturday?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it was a once-in-a-lifetime chance and he could go.
But I kinda wanted to make him pay for it by going a couple of
shots lower today. But I own him now. It's probably good for a
couple of laundries, and I'll make sure I have a lot when I come
home from Sacramento in two weeks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ward, of course, is best known here for leading Arizona State to
three consecutive women's NCAA golf titles from 1993-95 and for
capping her senior season in 1995 by playing the final round with
final-day leaders Beth Daniel and Laura Davies en route to a
third-place finish in the Standard Register PING.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, she has been remembered for missing the cut in
the first three tournaments she played this season, before
surviving last week at Tucson and finishing in a tie for 39th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a full month off after the JCPenney Classic (in early
December) and I really needed it,'' said Ward, who has won once in
each of her last two seasons on the tour. ``I had a fun, exciting
year last year with a lot of events going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my best year financially ($342,495), the most traveling
I have ever done and I got married in September and bought a house.
It really was a full year and I needed the break, but it got me off
to a slow start. I also wasn't feeling well in January and I think
that slowed me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   She certainly was healthy enough Saturday, at one point going to
8 under during a six-birdie, two-bogey outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the second week of a four-week stretch for me _ that's
long for me _ but I'm excited to go out there because I'm hitting
the ball well. It was a little hard at the beginning of the year. I
was humbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't shot a round under par until Tucson last week. It
wasn't that I was uncomfortable shooting under par, I just wasn't
doing it. I wasn't birdieing anything. Every day this week I've
been capable of shooting 64 or 65, but I haven't gotten any putts
to drop. It's a matter of getting a few breaks around the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Comfort is one thing she has never worried about at Moon Valley.
She backed up her third-place finish as an amateur with a Top 15
finish here last year.
</P>
<P>
   But it always hasn't been that way. When she joined the tour in
1996,
especially coming off her 1995 performance here, she was viewed as
yet another incoming ``wunderkind.'' Instead, she has paid some
dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't pressure, but I wasn't ready to jump in and be
No 1 at this level,'' she said. ``It usually doesn't happen that
way. The Karrie Webbs and Se Ri Paks _ it doesn't seem they're few
and far between, but they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back on my career at each level, it has taken me a
couple years to feel comfortable. It was that way from high school
to college and college to here. It's OK. Some of us pay their dues
a little longer than others. Even Karrie played the European tour,
so she paid her dues, too.''
</P>
<P>
   She also believes she's a better player now than the kid who
finished third here as an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm much better,'' Ward said. ``I was very tough mentally that
year, but my overall game has really improved. It's why I'm
excited. I'm hitting my drives 10 yards farther. When I played with
Laura in 1995, I was keeping up with her 3 irons with my driver.
Now I can probably keep up with her 2 irons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can perform somewhat mediocre in college and still play
strong; shoot 71 or 72 and win a tournament. There's so much less
room for error out here. It's a matter of consistency and feeding
off lower scores.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
