<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-PING-COURSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LPGA PONDERS OPTIONS FOR 2000 TOURNEY SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Three golf courses are under consideration to host
next year's Standard Register PING, including one site that
temporarily could unite the LPGA and PGA tours.
</P>
<P>
   The TPC of Scottsdale, the venue for the Phoenix Open, is one of
those possibilities to pick up the void when the LPGA is
temporarily displaced from Moon Valley Country Club to accommodate
major reconstruction of the course's greens.
</P>
<P>
   The other layouts that Standard Register board of governors are
considering are Phoenix Country Club, probably the front-runner at
this point, and the Karsten Course at Arizona State, which is named
after Karsten Solheim, the founder of PING.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Grove, director of golf at the TPC of Scottsdale, said:
``We've had some contact about the possibility (of moving the
tournament to the TPC).''
</P>
<P>
   But the contact has not come from the LPGA Tour, said its new
commissioner, Ty Votaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not be adverse to the idea,'' Votaw said. ``It's good
to have choices, whether it's two or three or whatever many. It
helps your decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   Stu Smith, chief executive officer of the Samaritan Foundation,
said it will take about three to four weeks to decide which course
gets the nod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to reach a decision by May 1 or earlier,'' Smith
said. ``We currently are pursuing discussions with at least three
locations, and we expect the possibility of two more as backups.
One thing I'd like to emphasize is that we are not bartering one
course against the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that three criteria are being weighed to determine
the right fit:
</P>
<P>
   The temporary venue must be of championship quality and
attractive to the pros. The LPGA will be solicited for input to
determine the course's worthiness.
</P>
<P>
   The location of the course must not be in an extreme north,
south, east or west corner of the Valley. An accessible path to the
tournament must already be in place.
</P>
<P>
   The financial ramifications must continue to benefit the
Samaritan Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raise between $350,000 and $800,000 a year for cancer care
through the Samaritan Hospitals,'' Smith noted. ``We have to be
very cautious about jeopardizing our bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Country Club, the TPC of Scottsdale and Karsten all have
pluses and minuses, although the tournament committee favors the
tradition of PCC, which once hosted the Phoenix Open before it
moved to the TPC in 1987. The big hang-up with PCC, however, is
that not all of its members are willing to give up the course, even
though such influential members as Bob Goldwater, ``the Father of
the Phoenix Open,'' have given such a move their blessing. PCC also
has a small driving range and lacks parking facilities, although
several are nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The TPC might be a bit of a reach because of lost revenue
considerations to the PGA Tour, and the possibility that a
comparison would be made between men's and women's golf if the
crowds were significantly less than what the Phoenix Open draws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing about 180 to 190 rounds a day this week, and
that's at $172 a player,'' said Grove, meaning the TPC would have
to give up or be compensated for $200,000 to $250,000 in lost green
fees should the LPGA and PGA tours work out a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The big plus for the TPC, however, is that no other candidate
has the facilities or the championship quality that the TPC boasts.
Several of the LPGA players have said they endorse the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be interesting to see how we'd do at the TPC,'' said
Cindy Flom (formerly Rarick). ``Obviously, the atmosphere (at Moon
Valley) is great, but it would be nice to have more people. I'm
rooting for the TPC.''
</P>
<P>
   The Karsten Course, however, has the Solheim family name on it
already, a link that can't be overlooked considering the financial
commitment to the tournament from PING. Most of Karsten's
facilities also would work, as would the accessibility. The
negative is that the course is not of the same championship caliber
as the two alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   John Solheim, president of PING, said his family's preference is
the Karsten Course, ``although there is a lot of history at
Phoenix, and both Phoenix and the TPC are great courses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the family tie to Karsten is already there, plus it offers
accessibility, plenty of parking and a central location,'' Solheim
added. ``And I think it would be really nice to have it there
because the Lady Sun Devils have been national champs so many
times, and a lot of those (former ASU players) are now out here on
the tour.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
