<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBERS FASHIONS COMEBACK WITH BIRDIES ON ALL PAR 5S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN AND TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If Australian &UR; Karrie Webb had not distanced herself 2
strokes ahead of second-place &UR; Lorie Kane going into today's final
round of the Standard Register PING, &UR; Kristi Albers would have been
the talk of Saturday's third round.
</P>
<P>
   Albers, a 13-year LPGA Tour veteran from El Paso via the
University of New Mexico, started the day at par and finished it 6
under. She had seven birdies and a bogey en route to the day's best
round of 66. She started the day so far back of the leaders that
she teed off with the morning's fourth group, moved into fifth
place by herself and is 5 shots behind Webb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played the par 5s really well, and I made some putts,''
Albers said. ``The last two days I got myself into trouble. I was
in trouble only once today, and I got out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to going lights out was the fact that she birdied all
four of the par 5s during the round, staggering only when she
missed a five-foot par putt on the par-3 second hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit good drives on all the par 5s and was able to reach them
in 2,'' she said. ``You can make some putts on these greens.
Obviously, the scores are lower. The wind was tough on a few holes
_ Numbers 15 and 16 were right into the wind. I used two clubs more
on Number 18 than I did Friday.'' &QL; 
Forget the ace &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Annika Sorenstam, the two-time player of the year who is coming
back from a one-month layoff, was upset following her 71.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, a career-first hole in one at the second hole, where
she holed out an 8-iron from 140 yards, did little to soothe
Sorenstam's mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us a little time, will you,'' said Sorenstam's husband,
 &UR; David
 &UR; Esch, who was consoling his wife after she bogeyed the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   The Swede had it to 5 under after the hole in one, but
immediately bogeyed the third hole. She got back to 5 under twice
on the back side before closing out with the bogey that came via a
greenside bunker.
</P>
<P>
   After Sorenstam recovered from the disappointment, she did have
a comment on the ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really psyched after I made it,'' she said, her mood not
reflecting her statement. &QL; 
No saving grace &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Grace Park, the super sophomore at Arizona State, is 1 over
after three rounds. But her 72 on Saturday left her in anything but
a good mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't putt,'' Park said, shaking her head in disgust. ``I
missed (birdie putts) of four, five, six, seven, eight, nine and 10
feet . . . and I'm not kidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably had 15 (birdie putts), and I made one. That's
terrible, because I'm hitting it so good (off the tee).''
</P>
<P>
   Park always has been plagued by her putting, but she had putted
well since going cross-handed last fall under the tutelage of her
instructor, Kierland's &UR; Mike LaBauve. The key to her U.S. Amateur
victory last year, has always been her incredible length.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hit three drives in a row _ at Nos. 6, 7 and 8 _ that were
all over 300 yards,'' LaBauve reported. ``The putting will come
back around, because Grace is a great player.'' &QL; 
For once, `Hi, Dad!' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tired of one athlete after another turning to the television
cameras to say, ``Hi, Mom!''? What about Dad? He's always been the
forgotten party until &UR; Lorie Kane came along. Kane is 2 shots behind
leader Webb and will be grouped with her today as she tries for her
first LPGA victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited to be in the final group,'' said Kane, from
Canada's Prince Edward Island. ``And with the satellite we bought
my dad for Christmas, he'll be able to watch me. It's fun. And
because we're on regular television, the people at home will get an
opportunity to see me. That keeps you sharp, and I'm looking
forward to it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
