<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON COULDN'T ESCAPE LIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the very end,  &UR; Tim Johnson was not about to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to get rid of me, they are going to have to fire
me,'' Johnson told a visitor in his office days before he was fired
by Toronto General Manager  &UR; Gord Ash last week.
</P>
<P>
   But after months of scrutiny, the Blue Jays could have no more
and did, indeed, fire Johnson, who guided Toronto to a surprising
88 victories in his only season as a major league manager.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the chaos surrounding Johnson's lies about being a
Vietnam veteran and having turned down a basketball scholarship to
UCLA proved too much of a distraction for the club to move forward,
the Blue Jays front office believed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was clear is that he needed some rest,'' said assistant
GM
 &UR; Dave Stewart, who stayed with Johnson until 2 a.m. the night he was
fired. ``I don't think the Tim Johnson we saw this spring was ever
the real Tim Johnson. There was too much going on. He could never
get a break from the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose brother  &UR; Sandy Johnson is the Diamondbacks
assistant general manager, was basically buried under an avalanche
of ill will and cheap shots from most every direction. Former Blue
Jays players such as  &UR; Ed Sprague wouldn't let the situation die.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most every question asked of anyone in the
organization, either from a reporter or an opposing player, had a
mention of Johnson's lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing the cards we had before us, the best thing was to fold
up the hand and try again,'' Toronto catcher  &UR; Darrin Fletcher said.
``I was willing to give him a second chance, but with all that
stuff hanging over his head, would he have survived the scrutiny
the first time we lost two in a row? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Johnson joins  &UR; Phil Cavaretta as the only managers ever
fired during spring training. Cavaretta was fired on March 29,
1954, after his Chicago Cubs had a 5-15 spring record and he
indicated to the club's owner that it would probably be a very long
season on Chicago's north side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became an issue that preoccupied our time, all this was
wearing on Tim and affecting his style of leadership,'' said Ash,
who hired
 &UR; Jim Fregosi to replace Johnson. ``We wanted a fresh guy; I don't
think we made a mistake. Now our mandate has changed. We needed
someone with experience.'' &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
Which pitcher has appeared in more games than anyone else during
the 1990s? &QL; 
Carrasco update &QL; 
Right-handed reliever  &UR; Hector Carrasco, who came within days of
being on the Diamondbacks opening day roster last season, could be
in serious medical danger.
</P>
<P>
   Carrasco, who was thought of as Arizona's first closer during
spring training, lost circulation in his right (pitching) arm last
week after a Minnesota Twins spring training game and was taken via
helicopter from Fort Myers, Fla., to a Tampa hospital for extensive
testing after his right arm became numb.
</P>
<P>
   Blood thinning medication managed to subside blood clots found
in his armpit and elbow and an emergency surgery was halted before
it began. However, Carrasco's condition remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared,'' said Carrasco, who may be forced to miss the
entire season. ``The doctors (in Fort Myers) didn't know what was
wrong and I had to see another doctor. This is serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors discovered a 40 percent narrowing of the arteries in
Carrasco's right shoulder. Twins general manager  &UR; Terry Ryan, who
acquired Carrasco from waivers after the Diamondbacks released him
last spring, was beside himself over the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in the prime of his career and was throwing the ball
well,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to enjoy being in this organization.'' &QL; 
Brown out &QL; 
If this event doesn't cement the Dodgers' leaving Vero Beach,
nothing will. While taking a shower at the club's complex in
Florida last weekend, star pitcher  &UR; Kevin Brown was scalded after a
teammate flushed a nearby toilet, causing the water in the shower
to jump in temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who recently signed baseball's richest contract ever at
$105 million, became so livid that he grabbed a baseball bat and
smashed the culprit _ the toilet, not the unknown player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's better to get that out,'' Dodgers Manager
 &UR; Davey
 &UR; Johnson said. ``No one was hurt by it. You can repair a toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown did suffer a bruised head after he shoved the door to the
toilet and it rebounded hard right back into his face. &QL; 
Drumming up support &QL; 
The Minnesota Twins drew 7,744 paying customers for their
Grapefruit League game against the Yankees last Wednesday. The
Twins had five smaller crowds and four others within 300 of that
figure in the Metrodome last season.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, at least the Twins know their clientele.
Minnesota announced its promotional schedule for the season and
there were some eye-catchers on the list.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins will start out with Kids Opening Day on April 11, when
children will be allowed to take over ballpark duties. The game on
June 5 between the Twins and Houston will feature fishing rods to
the first 5,000 fans under the age of 16.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it's on to Independence Day, when fans will be
allowed to bring their dogs to the Metrodome for the Twins-Tigers
game. The July 24 game will feature the Twins and Seattle wearing
futuristic uniforms for Turn Ahead the Clock Night. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Ridiculed as he may be at times, Cleveland left-handed reliever
 &UR; Paul &UR; Assenmacher holds the distinction with 589 games pitched
during this decade. Next on the list is teammate  &UR; Mike Jackson, who
has worked in 572 games in the 1990s. Assenmacher has 829 career
big-league appearances, 19th on the all-time list. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; There once was another rookie who took the majors by
 &UR; storm: For the sake of baseball (and the Cubs), let's hope  &UR; Kerry
Wood is not the next  &UR; Mark Fidrych, whose career flamed out because
of shoulder problems shortly after he became the rage of baseball
during his rookie season in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Appeasing the right guy: They say it had nothing to do with  &UR; Mo
Vaughn, but the Anaheim Angels decided last week to move in the
fences in center and left-center field by nine feet this season.
Just by coincidence, that's where most of Vaughn's home runs tend
to leave the yard.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Bill Singer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Messing with the wrong dude: Cleveland pitcher  &UR; Bartolo
 &UR; Colon declined a generous four-year offer worth $9 million from the
Indians. GM  &UR; John Hart, who had to be disturbed by the move, turned
around and renewed the young All-Star's contract for just $21,000
above the major league minimum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; That's nice, but why not pay them their due: San Diego
ownership recently picked up the 2000 option seasons for GM  &UR; Kevin
 &UR; Towers and Manager  &UR; Bruce Bochy, two high-quality individuals who
remain embarrassingly close to the bottom of their respective pay
scales. &QL; EXTRA BASES &QL; Florida starter  &UR; Alex
 &UR; Fernandez, who will certainly be the subject of trade talks later
this season if he proves he is healthy, designated Atlanta,
Baltimore, Cleveland, St. Louis, Tampa Bay, Texas and the Cubs as
the only clubs he could be traded to this season. Fernandez has a
limited no-trade clause that allows him to pick where he could go.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his negotiations during the winter, Kansas City
closer  &UR; Jeff Montgomery managed to add a clause in his contract
that calls for his base salary to jump from $2.5 million to $4
million if he is traded.
</P>
<P>
   Today is the first day pitcher  &UR; Orel Hershiser can entertain
offers from other clubs. Hershiser is in Cleveland's camp with a
chance to leave for any club that offers a major league job to his
liking. He also has an option to remain with the Indians. Clubs
that probably are interested include the Phillies, Tigers, Devil
Rays, Cubs, Red Sox and Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Before they decided to rename a stretch of a Manhattan highway
after  &UR; Joe DiMaggio, a New York state assemblyman actually wanted
to rename Yankee Stadium after DiMaggio. If they didn't do it for
 &UR; Babe Ruth,  &UR; Lou Gehrig or  &UR; Mickey Mantle, they rightfully couldn't
do it for DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles sent 15 players to its minor league camp for
reassignment. Among the players sent were  &UR; Pete Rose Jr. and  &UR; Gavin
 &UR; Osteen, the son of former Dodger pitcher  &UR; Claude Osteen.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals, who are forced into being creative
because of limited revenue, recently had a 37-year-old Canadian
softball pitcher in camp.  &UR; Mike Piechnik apparently throws a nasty
slider and screwball. There was one problem, though, he balks every
time he pitches. &QL; THE RUMOR MILL &QL; With
 &UR; Carlos Baerga booted out of St. Louis' camp for being overweight
and slowing, talks of the Cardinals looking to Milwaukee for second
baseman  &UR; Fernando Vina may start to heat up once again. The two
discussed a trade involving Vina during the winter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year after fleecing the Dodgers in a trade,
Cincinnati might be willing to consider a trade for left-handed
pitcher  &UR; Dennys Reyes. The Yankees and Tampa Bay have inquired
about the  &UR; Fernando Valenzuela look-alike.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Philadelphia first baseman  &UR; Rico Brogna and
Phillies management will not be able to make their relationship
work, at least not in the long run. Brogna was looking for a
long-term contract. The Phillies, who have first baseman  &UR; Pat
Burrell on the way, are not inclined to make that kind of offer.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado reliever  &UR; Curtis Leskanic seems to be the leading
candidate to become the closer for the Rockies.  &UR; Jerry Dipoto, last
season's closer, has a 7.20 ERA while Leskanic did not allow a run
in his first six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Basically run out of town in San Francisco and Anaheim for his
``laissez-faire'' attitude,  &UR; William VanLandingham is emerging as a
serious candidate to make Milwaukee's starting rotation. In his
first three spring outings, he allowed one run on three hits and
one walk. &QL; Includes information from other media sources. Pedro
Gomez
can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
