<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'BRIEN LEADS BUCKEYES TO NEW HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-ST. JOHN'S-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Here's the usual Jim O'Brien Final Four modus
operandi: arrive at the site, hang out in his room, go to as few
meetings as possible, attend no official social functions, spend no
time schmoozing in the hotel lobby, and get out of town as soon as
possible. There usually aren't six people who will even recall he's
been there.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   This time Obie's presence will be noted by several hundred media
members, the entire state of Ohio, and millions of American sports
fans. He will be seen at major press conferences and he will be
seen on the bench, guiding his Ohio State Buckeyes against
Connecticut in a Final Four semifinal affair next Saturday. That's
because those same Buckeyes led wire to harrowing wire, defeating
St. John's, 77-74, to win the South Regional championship before
24,248 fans at Thompson-Boling Arena Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Up by 13 (61-48) with 9:05 left, up by 9 (73-64) with 2:47
remaining and up by 6 (75-69) with 44.4 seconds to go, Ohio State
needed a missed free throw by St. John's Chudney Gray, one made
foul shot by tourney Most Outstanding Player Scoonie Penn, and a
welcome turnover by St. John's point guard Erick Barkley to secure
the school's first visit to the Final Four since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   For O'Brien, who left Boston College with a bowling ball-knot in
his stomach less than two years ago, this represents an almost
incomprehensible vindication of his coaching expertise and personal
integrity. For this Ohio State team was 8-22 (1-15) in the Big Ten
a year ago. This Ohio State team suffered through a 17-game losing
streak. And now this Ohio State team is marching off to the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just really hard to put into words the feeling shared by
all of us right now because it's hard to imagine that we've put
ourselves in this position,'' said O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State was in complete control for 38 or so minutes, seizing
early leads of 9-2 _ this on a 4-point play by the irrepressible
Penn _ and 19-11. And just when Mike Jarvis's Red Storm seemed to
be straightened out in the late stages of the first half, Ohio
State's mercurial slasher supreme Michael Redd (20 points) stepped
a bit out of character by nailing three 3-pointers over a Red Storm
zone in the final 2:12 of the half, the last of which, with 2.8
seconds left, sent Ohio State into the locker room holding a 41-33
lead.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the expected superb play of Penn and Redd (``If
they're not the best backcourt in the country, they're one of
them,'' said O'Brien), who combined for 42 points, 13 assists, and
14 rebounds, Ohio State also got big lifts from forward Jason
Singleton (13 points), and, most of all, from ``work in progress''
6-foot-11-inch junior center Ken Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   This was, frankly, the best game of his Buckeye career. The big
guy blocked seven shots, altered several others and even
contributed 12 points in only his fourth double-figure game of the
year. ``He was the difference,'' said Jarvis. ``He set the tone of
the game from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a fast-paced game, so well-played and hard-fought it was
that rare '99 contest even a neutral observer could love. Cast in
the catch-up role, such St. John's players as Lavor Postell (a
career-high 24 points) and Barkley (13 points, 7 assists) proved to
be resilient. The Johnnies never once hung their heads, no matter
how many Redd and Penn daggers were thrust into their mid-section.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just refused to go away nicely,'' observed O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnnies got back into it by forcing turnovers and making
some tough shots. With Ohio State up, 75-73 (12.2 left), Gray
missed one foul shot and made one. So did Penn. Down by 2, and with
Penn on him, Barkley lost his dribble, the ball rolling to Redd,
who likewise made one of two shots to put the game away with 0.7
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Was Barkley fouled by Penn? ``If I had a hand on him,'' said
Penn, ``it wasn't enough to make him lose the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter now. ``The game's over,'' confirmed Jarvis.
``They deserved to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And who, except for a few sadly ill-informed people at The
Heights, doesn't know that Jim O'Brien certainly deserved to win?
</P>
</TEXT>
