<HEADLINE>
UCONN TITLE HOPES BLOWN AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The University of Connecticut women's basketball
team, which six days ago dodged a bullet by beating Xavier to get
into the Sweet 16, couldn't do it Saturday. The top-seeded Huskies
(29-5) were upended by fourth seed Iowa State, 64-58, in a Mideast
Regional semifinal. It is the first time in seven trips to a
regional semifinal that UConn has lost the game, and it was the
lowest amount of points the Huskies scored all season.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Iowa State (25-7) advanced to the Elite
Eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a tremendous disappointment whenever the season
ends,'' said UConn coach Geno Auriemma, whose team has made 11
trips to the NCAA Tournament and had been to the Final Four four
times. ``You feel like you've been kicked in the gut, it really
hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Tamika Williams, who had scored the winning points last
Sunday against Xavier, scored 12 of her team-high 14 points in the
first half. A group of about 100 fans from her hometown of nearby
Dayton in the crowd of 5,772 at the University of Cincinnati's
Shoemaker Center was rooting loudly for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But there were some no-shows for UConn, mainly Svetlana
Abrosimova and Shea Ralph, who contributed 9 and 5 points,
respectively. Ralph shot 0 for 9 from behind the 3-point line,
while Abrosimova was 1 for 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had wide-open shots,'' said a red-eyed Ralph after the
game. ``I don't know what to tell you, but we just didn't hit
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the opposite was true for the Cyclones, who were cold from
behind the arc at the beginning of the second half, when they went
0 for 9, but hit the shots when they mattered, including five in a
row with just over five minutes to go in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to that point we weren't shooting our best, but coach just
keeps telling us to keep shooting, and luckily towards the end of
the game they were starting to fall,'' said junior guard Stacy
Frese, who scored a game-high 16 points, 14 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't probably aesthetically the kind of game that people
want to see, but we had to give up some open shots and luckily they
weren't making a lot of them,'' said Iowa State coach Bill
Fennelly. ``I thought we handled their pressure as much as we
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State held UConn to 29.9 percent shooting from the field,
its lowest of the season. The Huskies' previous low was in their
loss to Boston College in January, when they shot 38.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State led by as many as 6 in the first half, 18-12, but saw
the lead slip away on a layup and a 3-point play by Williams, and a
field goal by freshman Swin Cash. The Cyclones came back, however,
fueled by a 3-pointer by freshman Tracy Gahan, and got within 2.
</P>
<P>
   With time running out in the half, sophomore guard Erica Haugen
fired a court-length pass that was tipped by teammate Megan Taylor,
and then the junior forward grabbed it and took it in for a layup
just before the buzzer to tie the game at 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell the kids all the time that you've got to play till the
buzzer goes off, and that was a great example,'' Fennelly said.
``In a game like that, 28-28 sounds a heck of a lot better than
28-26.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn went on a 7-0 run five minutes into the second half.
Fennelly admitted he was squirming, as three of his players had
four fouls each. But the Huskies created their own trouble, as they
went four possessions in a row without scoring. Suddenly, Iowa
State was beating the Huskies at their own game, pressuring them
and making their defense collapse.
</P>
<P>
   With UConn ahead, 50-44, the Cyclones' fireworks truly began.
Junior Monica Huelman made a 3-pointer from the left side of the
key, and her teammates made four more in a row to give Iowa State a
59-55 lead. A 3-pointer by Marci Glenney was the Huskies' final
basket. Iowa State added three more free throws to finish the
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor scored 13 points for the Cyclones, while Angie Welle
added 10.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State had just two winning seasons in the 18 years before
Fennelly came to the program five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot to prove to everyone else,'' said Gahan. ``I
think our whole team and our coaching staff were the only ones who
believed in us.''
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's upset, there are a lot of believers.
</P>
</TEXT>
