<HEADLINE>
RODMAN EXPECTED TO RETURN SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Wherever Dennis Rodman was, whatever he did and
why he did it, the only thing certain now is he's back, and the
Lakers have never needed him more.
</P>
<P>
   Well, strike the ``certain'' part _ this is Rodman, after all _
but he was certainly (begin ital)expected(end ital) to arrive here
in time for the Lakers' 12:30 p.m. EST game against the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   The eccentric and troubled rebounding specialist was due to
arrive after 1 a.m. EST, having missed two earlier flights out of
Los Angeles. Lakers spokesman John Black confirmed Saturday evening
that the team expected Rodman's arrival and planned to have him in
uniform today.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman skipped the past four games to attend to unspecified
``personal business,'' which apparently included at least one trip
to Las Vegas. His public relations firm has denied rumors that he
also spent time in Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   While Rodman worked out his problems at the blackjack table, the
Lakers were going 1-3 on their toughest road trip of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, coach Kurt Rambis said Rodman would be put
back to work immediately, whenever he eventually arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he shows up, I'll give him a pat on the back and send him
in,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were 7-6 before Rodman started playing for them, then
went 9-0 with him in uniform. But they have struggled mightily of
late, having lost Rodman at the same time they traded away Eddie
Jones _ their other best defender _ for Glen Rice, leaving them
weak defensively. They've given up 100 points in each of the past
four games.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back: The Magic is celebrating its 10th anniversary this
season, honoring alumni as they pass through the city. But the top
player in franchise history wants no part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal would rather just pound a dozen dunks, crush
the Magic by 20 points and move on with his life. No such luck.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal left the city he called ``a dried-up little pond'' nearly
three years ago, but the locals will never let the Lakers star
forget his past. Especially the part where he dumped them for $121
million and a career in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the O-rena crowd booed and heckled his every move,
and the public-address system skewered him with songs _ ``Lies,
Lies, Lies,'' ``You're so Vain,'' ``Superman's Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, ironically, the team wants to honor O'Neal. The Magic
has presented 10-year anniversary plaques to former players Dennis
Scott and Bison Dele, and there's one with O'Neal's name on it, but
the team isn't sure what to do with it, fearful of crowd reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Shaq to settle the quandary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give me anything,'' he said. ``I play for the Lakers
now. (Playing for the Magic) is just a memory to me. They can keep
their awards, I don't care. I don't wanna be honored. Don't honor
me. It's all in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   And he insists the game has no special significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just gonna be another game. No matter what happens, I
built that arena. That's why they call it the O-apostrophe-arena,''
O-apostrophe-Neal said. ``No matter what happens the rest of my
career, ever, I built that arena, I built that city.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers know their leader is in for a rough day at the
office, and Rick Fox said he understands the fans' reaction to
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like getting in a relationship with a girl,'' Fox said.
``If it's a good one, it's unbelievable for a short period of time.
But all of a sudden, if you pick up and you leave, they go crazy.
They get vindictive and psycho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orlando is the girlfriend you can't leave, you shouldn't have
left. They're definitely the spurned lover, because they did
whatever they could to keep him. It's like, `I love you, don't
leave me.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
