<HEADLINE>
BC CAPTURES HOCKEY EAST CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston College completed a joyous run to the Hockey
East championship Saturday &UR;  &LR; night before a roaring 14,278 in the
FleetCenter as Blake Bellefeuille of Framingham completed a magical
two-night performance with a dramatic overtime goal.
</P>
<P>
   Bellefeuille's winner 6 minutes 58 seconds into the extra period
lifted the Eagles (25-11-4) to a dramatic 5-4 victory over the
University of New Hampshire (29-6-3). BC now has a head of steam
heading into next weekend's NCAA regionals in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles were able to win the title largely because goaltender
Scott Clemmensen (20 saves) played to the form he showed a year ago
when he was tremendous during the stretch run of the Eagles' NCAA
championship loss against Michigan on this same ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles saw a 4-1 first-period lead dissipate as the Wildcats
responded to the challenge. UNH created a 4-4 tie when unheralded
Johnny Rogers swept in front of Clemmensen and tucked it between
his pads 15:18 into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal bore a certain resemblance to the Wolverines'
title-clinching goal against BC last year. The puck wound up on the
stick of freshman defenseman Brooks Orpik on the left boards after
a scramble. Orpik sent Bellefeuille in, and Bellefeuille's shot
beat goaltender Ty Conklin. ``There was a turnover on the side
boards,'' said Bellefeuille, ``and I picked it up and just started
to bring it to the net. I tried to fire it as quickly as I could,
and catch him off guard. Luckily, I caught the far corner.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was a bitter setback for the Wildcats, whose history
in playoff hockey isn't something to write home about. They've been
in the playoffs 34 times and have just one victory in the ECAC
tournament 20 years ago at Boston Garden. They were 0-1 in ECAC
Division 2, 1-3 in the ECAC. UNH is now 0-10 in Hockey East and 0-8
entering the NCAAs next weekend, where it undoubtedly will draw a
first-round bye.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, who were picked No. 1 in the preseason but stumbled
a few times en route to Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, threatened to turn the
game into a rout. Farkas, who has been a major force in the stretch
run, broke in on the left wing to lift the Eagles to a 1-0 lead
just 2:22 into the game. After defenseman Jayme Filipowicz drew a
high-sticking penalty 7:47 into the period, the Eagles built a 2-0
lead when Farkas scored from the slot after defenseman Bobby Allen
started it in motion and Bellefeuille tipped it forward.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bellefeuille fielded a pass from Bobby Allen on the left
wing and rifled it in at 14:25 of the period. BC 3, UNH 0. The
Wildcats finally broke through when Jason Krog, a finalist for the
Hobey Baker Award as college hockey's best player, took a picture
feed from Steve O'Brien and put it past Clemmensen at 15:56 of the
period. The Eagles answered when Kevin Caulfield put in a rebound
of a shot by Tony Hutchins to go ahead 4-1 at the 17:33 mark.
</P>
<P>
   While it looked like the rout was on, things actually were just
getting interesting. David Busch scored 3:53 into the second
period, and just 10 seconds later Jason Shipulski tucked the puck
between Clemmensen's pads to make it BC 4, UNH 3. The two goals
within a 10-second span were the fastest in tournament history.
Maine had scored two within 12 seconds in 1990 against
UMass-Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen then went to work, making two big saves on Mike Souza
bids. It remained 4-3 until Rogers swept out in front after a pass
out from Corey-Joe Ficek and tied it. ``We were dead for a while,''
said Bellefeuille. ``The coach (Jerry York) and the captain
(Brendan Buckley) got us back. They got us back into it in the
third period and it carried over into overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to hurt for a while,'' said UNH coach Dick Umile.
``We'll get over it. We'll find out tomorrow who we're going to
play next weekend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
