<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH AWAITING SENATE`S INVITATION 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Will International Olympic Committee
president Juan Antonio Samaranch testify at the Senate Commerce
Committee's hearings next month? Perhaps _ if he is invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always very pleased to go to the United States, no?''
Samaranch said. ``But I have received no letter. If I received the
official invitation, I will think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear him tell it, Samaranch was more startled than anyone
else by the 86-2 vote of confidence from his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected eight or 10 or 12, even 15 members against me,''
said Samaranch, who appointed four-fifths of the Lords. ``I was
very surprised that there are only two votes against me.''
</P>
<P>
   With Samaranch vowing to stay on until his term ends in 2001,
the succession derby has been put on hold. As of now, the top
candidates are considered to be vice presidents Richard Pound of
Canada and Pal Schmitt of Hungary, and board members Jacques Rogge
of Belgium and Thomas Bach of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The purge of the Lords may not be done yet. The cases against
Kim Un Yong of South Korea and Phil Coles of Australia are still
open, and if the IOC's executive board gets the evidence it needs,
they could be expelled at the next full meeting in Seoul in June.
Coles may be done in by his ex-wife, who has confirmed that she has
a $6,000 necklace that the Athens bidders gave her husband. If the
IOC gets proof that Kim knew the Salt Lake bidders subsidized his
son's telecommunications job in Utah, he could be gone, too. That
expulsion would be delicate, though _ Kim lives in Seoul . . . The
IOC won't pursue allegations by former Salt Lake bid chief Tom
Welch that US member Anita DeFrantz was aware of improper payoffs.
DeFrantz, who is an SLOC board member, insists she knew nothing and
the inquiry board believes her. ``I consider these allegations
scandalous and am seeking counsel,'' she said . . . The IOC is in
no rush to fill the spots opened by the 10 members who resigned or
were expelled. ``We'll probably want to see how we'll restructure
ourselves before we start appointing members under the old
system,'' said Pound . . . Why were only 88 and not 90 members
voting when the IOC reached the end of the expulsion list last
week? ``We have some elderly members who get fatigued,'' said Pound
. . . The IOC says it is not necessary for its new selection group
to visit the six European bid cities before choosing the two
finalists for the 2006 Winter Games in June. ``Remember, until 1986
nobody visited cities,'' says DeFrantz. ``We have done it this way
before and it worked well.'' . . . Atlanta had its live bulldog,
Salt Lake had its bathroom fixtures. What was Sydney's most
imaginative gift to a Lord of the Rings? Shipping seven zoo-bred
horses to Mongolia for IOC member Shagdargav Magvan for a mere
$150,000 . . . Top priority for new Salt Lake Chief organizer Mitt
Romney is getting a computer hardware provider ASAP to work with
SEMA, the European system integrator he is stuck with courtesy of
the IOC. After Atlanta's IBM nightmare, Romney wants no
cybercrashes in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They may be broke and scrambling for ice time, but the Russians
still could win nine of the 12 medals at this week's World Figure
Skating Championships in Helsinki. Besides sweeping the men's
event, which no country has managed since 1956 (the US), the
Russians could grab two medals in each of the other three. What's
left? A gold for Michelle Kwan in the women's event, a silver for
the Chinese (yes, the Chinese) in pairs, and a silver for the
French in dance. Unless Michael Weiss can crack the men's troika of
Alexei Yagudin, Evgeny Plushenko, and Alexei Urmanov, the Americans
will win only one medal. That hasn't happened in a non-Olympic year
since they were blanked in 1993. What the Yanks are more worried
about is that their inexperienced squad implodes and loses spots
for next year . . . Think home cooking doesn't mean much in Nordic
skiing? The Austrians, who hadn't won a world cross-country medal
in 66 years, grabbed four at the recent world championships in
Ramsau, winning the men's by a ski tip ahead of the heavily favored
Norwegians, who had their worst overall showing (``only'' five
medals) this decade. Top individuals were Finland's Mika Myllylae,
who won three races and was runner-up in the fourth, and Italy's
Stefania Belmondo, who won two golds and a silver. The Norwegians
won both individual Nordic combined events, with the Finns taking
the team title, and the Germans swept the jumps. Nothing, as usual,
for the Americans. Best cross-country showing was 25th by Justin
Wadsworth in the 50K; no women cracked the top 30 . . . Ticklish
protocol issue for the Sydney organizers with their Opening
Ceremonies. The Olympic rule is that the head of state is supposed
to declare the Games open. But is that Queen Elizabeth of England,
who heads the British Commonwealth, or the Australian prime
minister? The Aussie cabinet says it is the prime minister; the
British Parliament says it is the queen. The Australian public will
have its say in November, when it votes either to keep the queen or
create a president.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What will the Sydney organizers do for cash if disillusioned
sponsors pull out because of the IOC scandal? One-armed bandits.
The Aussies are considering having slot machines installed in
clubs, with the organizing committee getting a piece of the take.
It's OK with the IOC, which considers slots a form of lottery . . .
New president of the Massachusetts Sports Partnership is Soosie
Lazenby, a former executive at Adidas and International Management
Group. She succeeds Bob Colarossi, who departed last year to become
president of USA Gymnastics . . . Significant boost for the US
baseball team, which will have access to any pro not on a 40-man
major league roster for both this summer's Olympic qualifier and
next year's Games. That means minor leaguers probably will replace
most of the collegians. And it is almost certain that they'll be
swinging wood at Olympus. After the pingfest in Atlanta (110 homers
in 28 games) aluminum bats have been scrapped . . . Long Beach,
Montreal, and Barcelona are the candidates to host the 2003 World
Aquatics Championships . . . Symbolic breakthrough for US
badminton: The men's doubles team of Mark Manha and Howard Bach has
cracked the world top 20. That has not happened since the sport was
added to the Olympics in 1992 . . . Yes, the torch for Sydney's
relay was meant to resemble a boomerang. It will be made out of
stainless steel and aluminum, and will weigh more than 2 pounds.
But unlike a boomerang, it won't return to the previous runner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
