<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SURVIVE SHARK ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the beginning, it looked like it was going to be so,
so easy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was so, so difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins did their best to give the game to the San Jose
Sharks
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at the FleetCenter. The Sharks said, ``No, that's OK,
let's split it.''
</P>
<P>
   So each team walked away with a point in a 2-2 tie. Had the
contest lasted longer than 65 minutes, Boston, still sitting in
eighth place in the Eastern Conference, would have been sunk. The
Sharks dominated the overtime, though the shots were only 3-1 San
Jose, and Bruins coach Pat Burns looked as if he was going to have
a coronary behind the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst I've seen my team play in an overtime since I
remember, since I've been coaching, I think,'' said Burns. ``In 10
years now, I've never seen a team play in overtime like that. We
were very, very fortunate to get a point. And probably not
deserving of a point.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks were swarming all over the Bruins in the extra
period, but it was the Bruins doing the dominating in the first
period, when they jumped out to a 2-0 lead. It should have been,
could have been more, as Boston hit five posts.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the first, Steve Heinze tallied his 17th goal of
the year. Heinze took a pass from Jason Allison and tried to beat
goalie Steve Shields with a forehander at the right post. His shot
clanged off but came right back to him and Heinze switched to his
backhand, jamming it in for the 1-0 lead at 10:28.
</P>
<P>
   With a little more than five minutes remaining in the first,
Heinze nearly scored again, his shot from the left circle rattling
off the right post.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins made it a two-goal lead on the power play at 17:36.
Allison dished a pass to the point for Ray Bourque. Bourque fired a
shot that deflected past Shields for his eighth goal. The Bruins
outshot the Sharks, 15-5, in the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we wanted the headlines,'' said Burns. ``It was so easy
to go the way we were going. We followed the game plan, I told
them, `Put speed on them, put speed on the outside, get the puck in
behind them, cycle the puck, roll, try to get in the front of the
net, and we're going to get some goals.' We did that. In the second
period, we decided to cheat a little bit here and cheat a little
bit there, and the next thing you know, the puck is in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second, the Bruins let the Sharks back into the game,
allowing both San Jose goals, including one with 17.7 seconds
remaining in the period.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing Boston could do about the goal that made it
2-1 at 10:36. Right wing Joe Murphy, who is best known for recently
saying he's as good as Mark Recchi, threw the puck at the net from
the left side. It caromed off the right skate of Kyle McLaren and
past Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   If they couldn't prevent the first, the Bruins most definitely
could have stopped the second. The Sharks gained tremendous
momentum from their first tally and put the heat on Boston. The
Sharks pinned the Bruins in their end and center Marco Sturm skated
the puck from behind the net to the right circle, evading Darren
Van Impe. With Dafoe on his way down in front, Sturm fired a
forehander that went between Dafoe's legs at 19:42 to pull the
Sharks even at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   In the third period and overtime, the teams were even in shots
with eight, but the Sharks outplayed Boston. In the third, Dafoe
made two brilliant stops _ on Sturm from the slot with 5:20
remaining and on Mike Ricci from the right circle with 5:08 left.
Ricci reacted by putting both hands on his head in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   In the extra period, it was all San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a big team, they're a strong team, they're an
experienced team,'' said Burns. ``They hit you all night long. We
were fortunate to pick up a point, it's a very important point, and
I'm happy to get the point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
