<HEADLINE>
MARLEAU, THORNTON HAVE FRIENDLY RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They were taken first and second in the 1997 draft, the
Bruins' Joe Thornton and San Jose's Patrick Marleau, and while both
apparently play in the same National Hockey League, Thornton might
as well play on Jupiter and Marleau on Mars for all the contact
between the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see each other that much,'' said Marleau, 19, of the
games every six months or so between the Bruins and Sharks. ``But I
check up on Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   It's only natural. Thornton was the top choice, Marleau just
behind, and Marleau checks the summaries to see how Thornton, also
19, is faring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a respect for each other and we want each
other to do well,'' said Marleau, ``but there's also a friendly
competition between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Marleau took the honors last season with 13 goals and 32 points,
while Thornton struggled. As the hockey gods would have it, each
had a chance to be the hero Saturday in the Bruins' 2-2
squander-a-thon against the travel-weary Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   It's very hard, said San Jose coach Darryl Sutter, ``to play a
night game at home and then travel cross-country for an afternoon
game. We were on a body clock that said 10:30 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that in the first period, San Jose goalie Steve
Shields ``was hearing `Jingle Bells' behind me'' with five Bruins
shots striking posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult morning,'' said Shields, his body
clock a few hours behind Causeway Street time.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second period it was Boston that donned its Santa
Claus suit, giving away two soft goals. By the third period and the
overtime, however, the Bruins might as well have been clanging
their Salvation Army bells as they were in need of help. And there
was Marleau sent in clean from the left circle on a two-on-one in
the first minute of overtime on Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Marleau now had a chance to do what Thornton, his friendly rival
and teammate on the Canada's world junior championship team two
years ago, couldn't do earlier, what the top choices in the draft
are expected to do _ put the puck in the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like Dafoe was going down when I was going in, but
then he stood up,'' said Marleau of the goal-that-wasn't. ``And he
just got a piece of my shot with his (right) shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have loved to have seen Patrick score then, because
there's always that thing with Marleau and Thornton every time they
play each other,'' Sutter said. ``Everybody wants to talk about it,
and it would have been great to see him score in overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   So neither Marleau nor Thornton could claim the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we were on the ice against each other at all,''
said Marleau, ``but I still had my eye on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter and Mars may pass close by each other in another six
months. In the meantime, reports from the distant planets say
Thornton has 11 goals and 21 assists, while Marleau has 19 goals
and 19 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be checking up on Joe,'' said Marleau. But from afar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
