<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-KNICKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON ROAD TO NOWHERE, CELTICS ARE LOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you are a Celtics fan, the best news for you is
this: You have options. You want to know why your team has lost
seven of its last eight games. You want to know why the young men
in green seem to have a fear of leaving the 617/508/781/978 area
codes, since they have lost eight straight away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the losses?
</P>
<P>
   Take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you are a Celtics player or coach, the worst news for
you is this: You have options. You want to know why you lost to the
Knicks Saturday at Madison Square Garden, 96-78. You want to know
why the game was over at the end of three quarters, when the New
Yorkers led, 80-60. You want to know how you can shoot 54 percent
in the first half _ an exceptional percentage _ and still trail by
10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the losses?
</P>
<P>
   Take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   Most people would start with the Knicks' bench. The last time
these teams met, on Feb. 26, the Celtics won by 14. ``They kicked
our butts royally the last time we played,'' said Knicks center
Patrick Ewing. ``We came out and gave it back to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell was in Boston Feb. 26, but he didn't play. He
came off the bench Saturday and had 21 points in his first 17
minutes. He finished with 27 in 31 minutes. Once, he came down
court and made a pull-up 3-pointer. Another time, he drove the lane
and dunked on 6-foot-10-inch center Vitaly Potapenko.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he's rounding into form,'' Celtics coach Rick
Pitino said of the 6-5 guard. ``He's a very unstoppable weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that stopped Sprewell last season was the NBA
office, which determined he was trying to use his hands as weapons,
weapons that would wrap themselves around the neck of his former
coach, P.J. Carlesimo. But when Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said,
``I thought (Sprewell's) aggression was good,'' everyone knew he
was talking about his work against Celtic guards, not league
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to remember that you have options. So know that
Sprewell is not the only reason the Celtics lost. You could also
point to the 15 rebounds by Marcus Camby, who also came off the
bench. Camby and Sprewell had nine offensive rebounds between them;
the Celtics totaled 10. But that wasn't the sole factor, either.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watched the first 17 minutes probably couldn't have
guessed that the Celtics would be reduced to Garbage Time fodder in
the final quarter. That's because they led, 30-25, after the first
quarter and were tied with the Knicks, 41-all, with just over five
minutes remaining in the first half. Ron Mercer (19 points) looked
as if he were on his way to a 60-point night, shooting and scoring
with ease over Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we didn't guard at all in the first six or eight
minutes,'' Van Gundy explained.
</P>
<P>
   As Van Gundy was lamenting that, Pitino was turning to players
on the bench and saying, ``Now that's good basketball.'' He was
talking about the passing of Mercer, Kenny Anderson, and Antoine
Walker. Later the coach would say, ``I thought we really had fun
passing the basketball. But then we reverted back to, `I may be
hot, so let me take my man (one-on-one).' ''
</P>
<P>
   So the passing stopped. The scoring did, too. In the last 5:04
of the second quarter, the Celtics were outscored, 14-4. And a tie
game had become a 10-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could keep telling you the same old thing after these
games,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have fallen apart on the road before. They have had
low-scoring quarters before, similar to the 15-point effort they
had in the third. But they have rarely had four starters sit on the
bench for the entire fourth quarter. Pitino said he did that
because his team has a game Sunday against the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino revisited a familiar topic after the game. He said the
Celtics will make the playoffs next season. He said that will
happen even if the Celtics have to get older. He said he will
observe his players and see who has character; who handles being
down by 15 points well, and who handles an eight-game road-losing
streak well.
</P>
<P>
   If he and his team decide to look at Saturday's game again, they
will have a lot to discuss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
