<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' RANSOM WASTED 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Kings needed power-play help _ who doesn't? _ and
so last July, only 24 hours into the open free agency period, they
showered Steve Duchesne with a three-year deal worth $11.75
million.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, not even nine months later, Duchesne was placed
on waivers. Now there's real bang for your buck.
</P>
<P>
   It's lucky these businesses are monopolies, folks, because if
pro teams had to operate under standard free-market conditions _
basics such as supply and demand, finding the best deal on paper
clips, and the most dreaded thought of all, competition _ some of
them wouldn't be around long enough to hear the anthem on opening
night.
</P>
<P>
   Not that LA is alone in the big, bad world of hoodwinkdom.
Hardly. What were the Blackhawks thinking when they pounded the
table to the tune of $18 million for Doug Gilmour? Answer: They had
to come up with someone after losing out on Brett Hull. Gilmour
hasn't been the total bust Duchesne has been in LA, but he has
skated in the same cloud of futility.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's decision in LA shows that Kings general manager Dave
Taylor feels more stable in his position than his counterpart in
Chicago, Bob Murray, did. Placing Gilmour on waivers would be
tantamount to Murray writing his own resignation letter. Taylor
won't be asked to leave, at least not yet, because the Kings still
have a slight chance of landing a postseason berth.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are bad, but they're not Blackhawk bad.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who has been GM for only two years of the Blackhawks'
38-year rebuilding program, will see his team miss the postseason
for a second consecutive time _ something that hasn't happened in
Chicago since the late 1950s. If he sticks around, he can go for
the hat trick next season.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL trade deadline is only some 48 hours away _ Tuesday, 3
p.m. _ and, contrary to prevailing opinion, from here it doesn't
appear that a flood of big deals will rush through the league. Big
deals call for big names, and all the game's big names now make big
bucks, too. Those big names who actually are earning their money,
such as Curtis Joseph in Toronto, aren't going to be dangled in the
next day or two. The bigger action could come in late June, around
the amateur draft and just prior to free agency kicking in July 1.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings could have dealt Duchesne, even while absorbing
some of the financial pain, they obviously would have done that.
The Blackhawks will have to do the same if they want to unload
Gilmour. Ditto for the Lightning with Stephane Richer.
</P>
<P>
   There will be moves made in the next couple of days, such as the
Chicago-Edmonton seven-man swap, maybe even one or two that will
lift an eyebrow (like Trevor Linden to Ottawa or back to the
Canucks), but nothing that will capture the imagination. The Kings
had that dream machine going last July, and look where it took
them. Buying out Duchesne's deal, which now appears inevitable,
would cost them approximately $5.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Flyers need (beyond a life raft, a Red Cross kit,
and archery lessons for Roger Neilson) is help at the point on the
power play. That, in part, is why rumors have had them acquiring
ex-Bruin Stephane Quintal from the Habs _ although Montreal's
Vladimir Malakhov has more of a slap shot than the ``Q'' . . .
Prior to sending Mark Recchi to the Flyers for Danius Zubrus, the
Habs tried to pry prospect Simon Gagne and a first-rounder out of
Philly. Flyer GM Bob Clarke wouldn't bite. A small center (6 feet,
165 pounds), Gagne was the Flyers' first pick last June and has
been lighting up the Quebec League this season . . . After
recording the fourth-best save percentage (.920) in the league last
season, Capitals netminder Olaf Kolzig has dipped into the
.890somethings, the numeric wasteland for No. 1 goalies. Wouldn't
it be ironic if, like ex-Capitals goalie Jim Carey, he went from
boom to bust in one season? . . . The Oilers, still reeling in net
from Joseph's walkaway over the summer, picked up the Islanders'
Tommy Salo Saturday. He's not CuJo, but he's a better bet than Bob
Essensa or Steve Passmore. Oiler boss Glen Sather on his club's
lackluster play of late: ``This is a big problem _ not a tweaking
problem.'' Sather gave up forward Mats Lindgren in the Salo swap,
after the Islanders reportedly were holding out for Ryan Smyth (now
recovering from a badly fractured jaw) . . . He was rendered a
spare part earlier this season, but Derek Plante dropped even
further from the picture in Buffalo when the Sabres picked up Stu
Barnes from Pittsburgh. He'll be elsewhere by midweek, perhaps for
as little as a third-round pick . . . Will he stay or will he go?
According to ``Hockey Night in Canada'' commentator John Davidson,
Chicago blue liner Chris Chelios recently informed management that
he would agree to be traded, but only to one of three teams. The
Blackhawks promptly denied it. Ditto for Chelios . . . Within hours
after opening up the doors to his new bar, Shayne 27, in downtown
Montreal, Canadiens winger Shayne Corson awoke to printed rumors
that he'll be dealt at the trade deadline _ perhaps to San Jose.
``It's been like this most of my career,'' Corson told the Montreal
Gazette. ``Teams know the kind of player I am, that I come to play
every night, and that's what you look for when you want someone to
help you make the playoffs.'' And if he has to bid adieu, what
happens to the bar? Corson: ``I have good people who can run the
place.'' . . . Different sports, different countries, different
times, but anyone else out there see the similarities between Joe
DiMaggio and Jean Beliveau in the dignity, style, and class
departments? . . . Ken Hitchcock, runner-up to Pat Burns as coach
of the year last season, has virtually eliminated practices for his
Dallas Stars the rest of the season. The Stars will have a brief
morning skate on game days _ if they practice at all _ and will
work in liberal offdays here for the last month of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone believed otherwise, but the new deal Adam Graves
signed with the Rangers last week gives an idea how lofty the
bidding will be for unrestricted free agents this summer. Graves,
who will turn 31 next month (and therefore would have been
unrestricted come July 1), will collect a minimum $12 million over
three years. The Blueshirts can pick up another year at the back
end for $3.5 million. Still unresolved: a new pact for
free-agent-to-be Brian Leetch. He turned 31 earlier this month and
figures to bank upwards of $30 million on a four-year pact . . .
The Rangers have gone 6-3-2 without Wayne Gretzky in their lineup.
The Great One has had a cortisone shot to soothe the pain in his
neck (herniated disk). He got word Tuesday that he can start back
skating _ on his own, without contact _ and could be back in action
next weekend . . . Seconds into his first shift with the Penguins,
ex-Sabre Matthew Barnaby goaded the Flyers' Roman Vopat into a
roughing penalty. No big deal, but the Penguins went on to a
relatively easy 4-0 victory and Barnaby was sporting that smug ``go
ahead, punch me'' look most every shift . . . Word around Tampa Bay
is that the Bolts could push ex-Bruin Bill Ranford to the minors
before the season ends. There's virtually no chance of his being
grabbed in the expansion draft, raising the likelihood that he'll
be bought out over the summer . . . Last weekend, the Red Wings
surprisingly went with Norm Maracle over Chris Osgood in
back-to-back starts in net. It could be one of two things: Scotty
Bowman, master of the mind game, is playing his cerebral shuffle;
or Maracle is getting showcased for a possible trade. The Wings
would like to get some blue line help for the playoffs, fueling
rumors much of the second half that they've had an eye on the
Rangers' Ulf Samuelsson . . . Anaheim superstar Teemu Selanne, upon
seeing his 17-game point streak come to an end when a power-play
goal was rubbed off the board because of yet another controversial
player-in-the-crease call: ``This is ruining hockey. I feel shame
for hockey.'' . . . As expected, former Pittsburgh superstar Mario
Lemieux submitted his reorganization plan to purchase the Penguins
out of bankruptcy Thursday. A second group, headed by trucking
magnate Harvey Gainey, is expected to submit a similar plan early
this week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember the red-hot Coyotes? They've dropped like a rock in the
second half, so much so that speculation ran hot last weekend that
head coach Jim Schoenfeld could be headed to the unemployment line.
ESPN's Al Morganti reported Tuesday night that Jeremy Roenick will
not be back with the Coyotes next season. GM Bobby Smith played
down the Schoenfeld rumors. Following a 1-0 victory over Anaheim,
Schoenfeld bolted the building without talking to the media. Too
late in the season to make such a drastic coaching change? Bruins
fans know better. Fred Creighton had his '79-80 Bruins (with rookie
Ray Bourque in the lineup) flying high when Harry Sinden canned him
with 14 games to go. The Bruins went 7-6-1 under Sinden, finished
with 105 points, and made it into the second round of the playoffs,
where they were dumped by the Islanders (first of four straight Cup
runs for New York) . . . A Kirk Maltby slash left Valeri Kamensky
with a broken arm, likely ending the Russian striker's season _ and
perhaps his stay in Denver. Kamensky, an unrestricted free agent
this summer, wants to return to the Avalanche, but it's doubtful
they'll pay him the $2 million or more per year he'll command.
He'll be 33 when this season ends and won't have a lot of clubs
chasing him. Maltby was suspended four games for delivering the
hack . . . Ex-Canucks coach Mike Keenan incensed Vancouver
management with recent remarks on Canadian TV, including his
suggestion that his old pal, Mark Messier, wouldn't be with the
club through the end of his contract. GM Brian Burke sent
videotapes of Keenan's remarks to lawyers to consider whether
Keenan broke his contract's confidentiality clause. He still has
about $1 million coming from the Canucks, including $800,000 for
next season. Burke: ``I think it's really lame that he would drag
Mark Messier into this. He should be worried about finding another
job and not about the Vancouver Canucks.'' . . . Sinden will be
honored, along with the '98 US Olympic women's hockey team, with
the Lester Patrick Award (for outstanding contributions to hockey
in the US) at a noon luncheon March 30 at the Fairmont Copley
Plaza. Tickets are $125 each. For information, call 617-624-1923.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
