<HEADLINE>
DECISION DUE SOON ON DUCHESNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Steve Duchesne's status remained unresolved
Saturday, with no conclusion to his saga likely until Tuesday's NHL
trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, the Kings either will buy Duchesne out of his
contract, trade him, send him to the minors or keep him on the
team. The Kings waived Duchesne on Wednesday and he cleared waivers
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Buying out Duchesne's contract would be costly. Last summer, the
Kings signed him as a free agent to a three-year contract worth
$3.75 million a year. There also is a fourth year on the contract,
at Duchesne's option, for $3.75 million. Under terms of the NHL's
collective bargaining agreement, the Kings would have to pay
two-thirds of the remaining $11.25 million on the contract, or $7.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings were to trade Duchesne, they would probably have to
pay a large portion of Duchesne's remaining salary to get another
team to take him. If the Kings were to buy out Duchesne, he could
turn around and sign a new contract as a free agent with another
NHL team. He would have to sign by noon Tuesday, however, to be
eligible to compete in this year's Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, Florida, Detroit and Carolina are some of the
teams that might be interested in adding Duchesne for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Duchesne was a healthy scratch for the fifth straight game when
the Kings played host to Florida on Saturday night but was
scheduled to travel with the team for tonight's game in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Trade rumor: A Kings spokesman denied a rumor that the team was
considering trading defenseman Doug Bodger and winger Russ
Courtnall to the Detroit Red Wings for 22-year-old Mathieu
Dandenault, a speedy defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro nominated: Center Ray Ferraro is the Kings' nominee for
the Bill Masterton Memorial Trophy, which is awarded annually to
the player who best exemplifies the qualities of ``perseverance,
sportsmanship and dedication to hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro overcame knee problems this year to have a solid season
in 1998-98.
</P>
<P>
   Previous Kings who have won the Masterton Trophy are Butch
Goring (1977-78), Bob Bourne (1987-88) and Dave Taylor (1990-91).
</P>
<P>
   Rare goal: Kings defenseman Mattias Norstrom scored his second
goal of the season during the Kings' four-goal first-period
outburst Saturday. Norstrom matched a career high set with the New
York Rangers in 1995-96, and after he scored, the Panthers replaced
starting goalie Kirk McLean with Sean Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels really good that I can contribute once in awhile
offensively,'' said Norstrom, a consistent defensive contributor.
``It hasn't happened often.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
