NASH WAKES UP, HELPS MaVERICKS TOP KINGS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Steve Nash played more like Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Trent played more like Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   And, most important, the Sacramento Kings played exactly like
the NBA's worst defense.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, those three elements led to an easy 104-90 Mavericks'
victory before 16,161 last night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little disheartened after some close losses, but
this was just what the doctor ordered,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson
said. ``If we would've shot like that all season, we'd have five
more wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks, who ended a three-game losing streak and improved
to 9-17, got 22 points and five 3-pointers from Nash, 22 points and
11 rebounds from Trent. The Mavericks made a season-high nine
3-pointers and topped 100 points for the first time in 10 games,
and only the fourth time this season. The porous Kings, 0-2 in
Dallas, surrendered 100 points for the eighth time in nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we could beat this team,'' Mavericks center Shawn
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   After a pregame pep talk from injured teammate Cedric Ceballos,
Nash melted Kings rookie Jason Williams with his hot hand. With a
shoot-first mentality for the first time this season, Nash made
7-of-16 shots, but more important, held Williams to six points on
3-of-11 shooting, including 0-6 from beyond the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out like it was all or nothing,'' said Nash. ``I was
going to take the open shots and not worry about it. I'm too good
of a shooter to keep in this slump. Ced just told me to stop
thinking and worrying and be more aggressive. After the first
quarter he wanted a 15 percent finder's fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent, despite fighting a stomach virus, dominated the Kings for
the second time. He had 29 points and 16 rebounds in a February
victory, and last night became an effective passer after a pregame
film session in which he and Nelson watched Barkley operate in the
low post.
</P>
<P>
   The result was Trent patiently backing down his defender into
the lane before either shooting, or if double-teamed, sending a
one-handed bounce pass to an open shooter on the perimeter. He
finished with four assists and was a main reason for Nash's
career-high 3-pointers and another four by Hubert Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've done before, but tonight it worked better
than ever,'' said Trent. ``It's a way to really control the
tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Michael Finley missed six of his first seven shots,
the Mavericks had their best offensive half of the season, building
a 56-47 halftime lead. Dallas shot 45 percent, hit six 3-pointers,
made 14-of-16 free throws and outrebounded the Kings, 27-16.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento was equally inept at both ends, going 5:30 without a
basket as the Mavericks built a 33-20 lead. Despite Chris Webber
picking up three fouls in a 30-second span and Williams being on
the bench after being badly outplayed by Nash, the Kings pulled
within 41-38 on back-to-back 3-pointers by Vernon Maxwell.
Inexplicably, however, Tariq Abdul-Wahad left Davis wide open on
the perimeter for three 3-pointers that rebuilt Dallas' lead.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
