<HEADLINE>
EGO TRIPS MAKE FOR BUMPY RIDE IN LA 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's getting harder and harder to decide which Los
Angeles team is more newsworthy these days. The Clippers keep
losing and their coach rips them. The Lakers lose Dennis Rodman and
a couple of games and once again are a bull's-eye for inquiring
minds.
</P>
<P>
   So, Rick Fox, what's the story?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a soap opera act all year,'' the ex-Celtic and
current Laker says. ``There's no reason to believe it's over. It's
a continuing saga.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it is. No sooner did it appear that the Lakers had all
their ducks in order than Rodman up and left. Jerry West would like
him to stay away, but it's not his call. Jerry Buss created this
and it's his baby. Now the Lakers have come East, and they started
the trip inauspicously with losses Thursday in Cleveland and Friday
in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has taken some heat for speaking out about the team's
deficiencies (maturity, lack of leadership). He was perceived as
being holier than thou, uppity, presumptuous, you name it. He feels
otherwise and clearly the darts haven't muzzled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things needed to be said,'' he said. ``If you think it's
fine, that it's good, you're just lying to yourself. Ever since
I've moved beyond the first phase of my career, I just don't have
time to play the b.s. game. It's not what everyone wants to hear. I
can live with myself. At least when I say something, people know
it's not b.s. They should respect you for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about any leaders stepping forward, he said, ``We're
getting closer to having a form of leadership and moving beyond the
`what's in it for me?' You can have all the talent in the world and
not go anywhere. We think (talent) is going to carry us.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``There's a power struggle getting everyone on
board. But if we're not all on the same page, we're not going
anywhere. We don't have as many guys who have personal agendas. But
is that enough? I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fox thinks the Lakers will hit some bumps in the next couple of
weeks. He noted that with the acquisition of Glen Rice and the
losses of Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell, the team is still in
flux, and this pseudo-season already is half-over. But he thinks
this year is better than last year, when he talked early and often
about the Lakers' woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew last year it was going to fall apart after one month,''
he said. ``That made me mad because I knew we were going to fall. I
think we were headed down that same path this year. It hasn't
settled yet. There are still a lot of distractions. A lot of
change.''
</P>
<P>
   He's watching the unfolding egodrama. Shaquille O'Neal is
scoring but is still an indifferent rebounder and doesn't seem
remotely interested in playing defense. He's also playing hurt _
the abdominal thing is bothering him _ and you have to wonder
whether reporting out of shape had anything to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant is playing terrific basketball. Rice? Who knows?
There's only one ball, but a lot of other stuff, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm watching this mix. Any one of these guys would be the guy
on another team,'' said Fox. ``You have egos. If it doesn't play
out to a smooth transition in a couple weeks, I'm sure I'll be
talking to you again.''
</P>
<P>
   Count on it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More Laker (non-Rodman) stuff: Sunday marks Shaq's second visit
back to Orlando and the fans in Hooterville are sure to give him a
typical reception. We asked Penny Hardaway recently about his
relationship with his former teammate and why it wasn't closer. ``I
think it was just two different guys,'' Hardaway said. ``I wanted
to be close to him, but, at the time, he didn't want to be close to
me.'' Hardaway said, however, that his arrival in Orlando also
stole some of Shaq's thunder and the Big Guy wasn't happy about it.
``What happened was, where the rubber meets the road, I came in and
basically stole his shots,'' said Hardaway. ``Not trying to, but
just (by) playing. Some guys can't handle that. I think he's a
really good guy. But you have people around that push the wrong
buttons, that tell him, `He's in your spot, he's taking too many
shots.' I think that's what happened with him because he has all
kinds of guys around him. I only told the truth, but the truth
hurts. I would love to have had a great relationship with him and
would still like to have a relationship with him now. I'd love to
sit down with him and say, `Hey, whatever happened in the past,
happened. Let's move on. At least we can be friends.' I don't want
to hate him.'' Hardaway said his relationship with Shaq has ``even
trickled over to Kobe.'' He said it started when Bryant was talking
trash a couple years back at Magic Johnson's game. ``He tried to go
at me, every time,'' Hardaway said. ``It's fine to be competitive,
but to start talking trash to a veteran guy, that's the worst thing
you can do. So that's what Kobe's into now, and he's sending
messages back, by people that I know, talking about how he's going
to kill me and all that type of stuff. And I'm like, I can remember
this guy when he was (in high school) in Philadelphia and he asked
me if he should come out or not. Now, he's all of a sudden talking
trash.'' Gee, think we could arrange for an Orlando-LA final? . . .
Attention Karl Malone: The next time you play the Clippers, you
might stride over to their bench, put your arm around trainer Ray
Melchiorre, and say, ``Sorry for all the trouble you've been
through.'' Melchiorre had to have neck surgery last season after
taking a spill caused by a Malone dive into the Clippers bench. It
wasn't the Mailman's fault, and Melchiorre doesn't even think
Malone knows about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee's George Karl said he would have agitated for Paul
Pierce had he been running the Bucks' draft last June. As it was,
he was, as they say, between jobs. ``I worked with Paul a couple
summers ago,'' said Karl, ``and even though he was out of shape, I
could tell what great basketball instincts he had. He has that feel
for the game. If I had been here, I would have had a high desire to
draft him. When you're a bad team, you gotta have players. What
position they play has never been that important to me.'' . . .
Speaking of Karl, he had been warned by the league to stop ripping
Sonics president Wally Walker, which is why he was so heavily fined
($25,000). Still, isn't trashing your ex-boss an unalienable right?
What happens when the next book comes out and Player A or Coach A
tears into his old organization? Sounds to me like David Stern
could find a better use for his billy club . . . Billy Curley
didn't stay unemployed for long. He was told by the Timberwolves
that they would bring him back if New Jersey waived him. The Nets
did their part and Curley was back playing for the wounded Wolves
as they made their third trip to the Pacific in the last two weeks.
They'll be in here next Wednesday, but they'll be hurting. Both
Anthony Peeler and Malik Sealy, their top two shooting guards, are
hurt and may miss the game. The Wolves also sent Chris Carr to New
Jersey in the Stephon Marbury trade, but were hoping to be able to
save him and package him to Vancouver for Sam Mack. Instead, Carr
had to go to Jersey to balance out the salaries and Mack ended up
in Houston. The Wolves are still fuming over David Falk's
machinations in getting Marbury out of town. (In case you missed
it, Marbury waited less than a week before calling some former
teammates and expressing regret about the whole thing.) Kevin
McHale wanted to call Falk's bluff, believing that Marbury would
not go to any of the three teams that have big cap room: the
Clippers, Raptors, and Bulls. Why not Chicago? Can you see Marbury
playing for a college coach in a triple-post offense? But Minnesota
owner Glen Taylor wanted to be certain he'd get something for
Marbury, and he signs the checks . . . NBA Operations Czar Rod
Thorn has advised the referees to do what they can to keep games
moving. So far, Thorn said, games are three minutes longer this
year than last, but that's mainly because of additional mandatory
timeouts in the second and fourth quarters. ``We're just urging the
refs to keep the games moving,'' Thorn said. ``Get people out of
the huddle, get players to the line, that sort of thing.'' Thorn
also said he's getting some satisfaction out of seeing the scores
come up. ``It was a pleasant surprise,'' he said. Added Celtics
coach Rick Pitino, ``In the last week, I've noticed that it's
starting to get better. The play is getting much better. The
assists are going up. The shot selection is getting better. Just in
the last week. Prior to that, it was difficult. I think you'll see
it continue to get better, and come the playoffs, you'll have teams
playing their best basketball and be fresh physically, unlike prior
years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers and Lorenzen Wright talked about doing an extension
prior to the deadline, which would have been a first for that team.
As you may know, the Clipper way is to lose their assets. How close
were they to getting it done? ``Well, I wasn't on the cusp of
history,'' said Wright's agent, Robert Fayne. ``There was a
difference, a significant difference, in value.'' He said the
Clippers were nothing if not consistent, and how they deal with
Wright, he feels, will send a message to the other players; the
Clippers have a slew of free agents, of which Wright is the most
valuable. ``You don't let a guy leave without making a very strong
effort to keep him,'' said Fayne. ``They made an effort. But not a
very strong one.'' Wright, Vin Baker, Joe Smith, and Erick Dampier
will be among the top frontcourt free agents this summer, but money
is tight all around and the opportunities are not all that great
(see Marbury, above). Asked about staying put, Wright said, ``If it
can turn around, I wouldn't mind being here to help. But if the
team is not ready to turn around, I don't want to stick around and
be in the same predicament. I want to win more than anything. We
haven't done too much of that.'' Wright is the top remaining pick
from the Class of '96 (No. 7 overall) who has not signed an
extension . . . The Spurs' turnaround can be traced directly to a
schedule that seems to have been designed by John Thompson. From
March 1 to April 4, the Spurs play 19 times and only five games are
against clubs with winning records. And of the five teams with
winning records, a couple of them, Phoenix and Seattle, are
struggling . . . So, Don Nelson, how is Dirk Nowitzki coming along?
``He's just not ready yet,'' Nellie said of his No. 1 pick, coveted
by Pitino. ``He's just not NBA-ready. We have to be patient with
him. But I like everything he does, his attitude and work ethic are
terrific.'' How about his shooting? ``I didn't think he'd struggle
this much with his shooting,'' Nellie said. ``I thought he'd be
able to shoot regardless. It's just going to take a while. He's not
used to the physicalness and the pace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
