<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA IS FAMILIAR BATTLEGROUND FOR DAVIS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ While the National Football League continues to search
for some way to put an expansion team in Los Angeles, Al Davis is
plotting how to get paid if it succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has long contended that he still holds the territorial
rights to that market despite having left it to return to Oakland
in 1995, and he is ready to file suit against the league in
California state court to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has always been an iconoclast, so when he voted against
the granting of the league's 32d franchise to Los Angeles last
week, it came as no surprise. Neither, frankly, does his belief
that in the end he and his ``Raidahs'' will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the future of the Raiders is gonna be great,'' said
Davis. ``Where we'll play, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Davis's contention that the city of Oakland has not lived
up to an agreement that guaranteed all the suites and club seats
would be sold at the refurbished Oakland Coliseum. Although he
concedes that such a condition is not in the contract he signed
with the city, Davis contends that, for once, the media is his
ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the representation made to the Raiders and the
community,'' Davis said during his annual State of the Al address
on the final day of the NFL owners meetings. ``That was a lie. It
was a fraudulent inducement (to leave LA).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have that in writing. Not in a contract but in their press
releases and in other places. They've admitted it. I was satisfied
I had a commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland city officials deny making such a guarantee, and the
Raiders have seldom sold out on the strength of their product.
Since returning to the site of their greatest glory, they have yet
to have a winning season or reach the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This lack of on-field success and in-the-stands support has cost
the Raiders in revenue and consequently hindered their ability to
pursue free agents, the same problem Patriots owner Bob Kraft says
drove him to seek a lucrative stadium deal in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to believe that Davis, a man once viewed as the
Darth Vader of pro football, was hornswoggled by Oakland
politicians or bamboozled by press releases, but time _ and surely
a court somewhere _ will tell about that. Until then, football's
most interesting owner will continue to pursue both the Oakland and
Los Angeles markets in search of what seems to be the most relevant
thing to NFL success today _ skyrocketing stadium income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stability is really what we're looking for,'' said Davis, who
once ran the winningest and most stable franchise in football. ``I
have optimism we'll come out all right. I don't worry about
problems. Problems are normal. But I'm in the later years of my
life and I want to get this resolved so we can get this team back
where it belongs. I don't want to stop the league from doing
anything. I just want to preserve the rights I have.''
</P>
<P>
   What Davis seeks is a payment known as ``territorial
enhancement,'' something NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue is on
record supporting. The idea is that if an existing team moves into
a more lucrative market and enhances its value, it pays a fee that
is divided among the other teams.
</P>
<P>
   This has been done in the past, such as when the Rams moved to
St. Louis and into one of the best stadium deals in history. It
happened when the Browns left Cleveland for Baltimore, and it is
something Kraft may face if he ever gets his stadium in Hartford
because New York Giants owner Wellington Mara believes the Patriots
are targeting Connecticut's Gold Coast for corporate sponsors,
territory the Giants now have a monopoly on.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, however, is seeking a unique double dip, claiming he
should be paid if he allows someone to move into ``his'' territory
in LA while also seeking a ``disenhancement'' payment for moving to
Oakland, a less lucrative market that he believes has reduced the
value of the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the law of the land,'' Davis contended.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to argue that in 1995 he had a chance to build a new
stadium at Hollywood Park in Inglewood, Calif., but allegedly was
undercut by the league's threat that the new venue would not
receive a Super Bowl that local politicians felt was necessary to
back the deal unless a second team were allowed to move in.
</P>
<P>
   The league denies Davis's accusations, but Davis insisted, ``We
finally acquiesced but asked for a three-year delay so we could get
started. They said no. At every avenue, the league put onerous
terms on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when discussion of LA's bid for an expansion team began
last week, Davis asked at a closed-door session whether the league
planned to put a second team in the new stadium it will help
finance. No one answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only team that's played at the (Los Angeles)
Coliseum for 17 years,'' Davis said of the aging stadium one LA
group wants to refurbish. ``LA has very carefully played to the
court system. They've been pretty cunning. I don't want to stop
them from doing anything. I just want the Raiders to be paid for
the Los Angeles opportunity (Davis would be giving up) and the
disenhancement in Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Davis is right (and he usually is in these matters once
the NFL's spinmeisters end up on a witness stand), why, when he
will soon be 70, does he continue to fight the league he's been a
part of for nearly 30 years? There are many reasons, some personal
and some professional, but in the end it all comes back to football
and what Al Davis has always been about _ finding a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between the worst quartile of the teams and the
top quartile in the NFL is between $30 million-$50 million in
revenue,'' Davis said. ``In some cases, it's $50 million in income.
I don't care how bright you are, you can't compete against that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in the end, it's about the money, as always. Davis no more
wants to return to LA than he wanted to leave in the first place.
What he wants is a place where he can win again. And that means a
place with a fat stadium deal and big stadium revenue. That place
could be Omaha and Davis would take the Raiders there if it led him
back to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has lived a gypsy life _ I don't mean to imply the
gypsy life isn't great, by the way _ for 20 years,'' Davis said.
``My preference is for Oakland to live up to its commitments and
for my team to be where it can function best.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, that's been in the courtroom, not on the field.
If that proves true one more time, just maybe Al Davis will finally
get his silver and black back on the attack on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After winning the coaches' golf tournament Monday, Oakland's Jon
Gruden lifted his putter over his head and joked, ``And with this
victory the Raiders secured the rights to Los Angeles.'' . . .
Carolina Panthers owner Jerry Richardson, who is cochairman of the
Expansion Committee, speculated that there may be more than the
present two groups seeking to buy the provisional LA franchise
after the stadium issue is resolved. ``I'd personally be surprised
if other people don't surface,'' Richardson said. One possible
suitor who could challenge the New Coliseum Partners group and the
one headed by Hollywood mogul Michael Eisner is Eisner's old boss,
the Disney Co. . . . George Seifert, the 59-year-old new coach of
the Panthers, called the NFC West ``the geriatric's division,'' a
reference to 62-year-old Dick Vermeil (St. Louis), 59-year-old Mike
Ditka (New Orleans), and 55-year-old Dan Reeves (Atlanta). Two of
the four have survived heart surgery and three have already retired
once. Only 43-year-old 49ers coach Steve Mariucci fits the present
youth movement, but he laughed at Seifert's position, saying,
``They've all been to the Super Bowl, too.'' He, of course, has not
. . . Seifert will use multimillion-dollar disappointment Sean
Gilbert as a traditional defensive tackle in 4-3 fronts, and even
when he's over a tackle in the 3-4 he will not be an outside pass
rusher. Gilbert has proven less than adept at rushing from the
outside . . . Reeves issued a cautionary draft note that both the
Patriots and Dolphins can appreciate. ``You've got to be careful
taking a wide receiver on the first round,'' Reeves said when asked
if he would consider one after releasing troubled Tony Martin. ``It
seems more and more you can get better players at that position
later in the draft.'' New England continues to hope former No. 1
pick Terry Glenn will return to his form of three years ago when he
was a rookie sensation with 90 catches. He has been plagued by
injuries, and the same applies in Miami, where Jimmy Johnson took
Yatil Green No. 1 two years ago and has yet to see him play a down
because of severe knee injuries. ``The doctors say he'll be ready
to go, but for two years in a row I counted on Yatil and bypassed
other receivers,'' Johnson said. ``I'll not take that approach this
year. My approach is not to pencil Yatil in as a starter.'' . . . A
year ago, Johnson strongly endorsed the Patriots as the favorite to
win the division. Not so this year. ``They've had a pretty good
run,'' said Johnson, ``and when you've had that success and go
through a bunch of injuries like they had, you're not quite the
elite team you were anymore. Sometimes you're not going to have
that same drive.'' Johnson still believes the AFC East is the most
competitive division in football. ``Most anybody in football who's
objective and looks at the AFC East will think it's the strongest
division in football,'' Johnson said. ``We have some of the premier
people in the league on the field and on the sidelines.'' A year
ago, Patriots coach Pete Carroll was lamenting the difficulty his
team faced because of the high expectations thrust upon it. When
told he has no such problem this year, Carroll said, ``It would be
better if they were still there. I don't think it's a reflection on
us. It's the emergence of the other clubs, like the Jets, that got
a whole lot better. Our expectations stay the same. The
expectations of the media may have changed.'' Apparently so have
the expectations of his AFC East rivals, because everyone picked
the Jets as the leaders in the clubhouse . . . The consensus in New
England may be that Glenn remains the key to their offense, but
Johnson disagrees. ``That would be putting more on Terry Glenn than
he deserves,'' Johnson said. ``A lot of players influence the
Patriots along with Terry Glenn. But Drew Bledsoe is the key guy.''
. . . Colts coach Jim Mora was irate last winter when Ryan Leaf did
not show for a scheduled meeting at the scouting combine in
Indianapolis and never called to say why. Leaf later said he had a
physical scheduled at the same time. Considering the problems with
immaturity Leaf struggled with all last season in San Diego, Mora
now says his choice of Peyton Manning was right all along. ``I got
blasted by (agent Leigh) Steinberg and Leaf for saying I was upset,
but it was a copout what he said for an excuse,'' Mora said. ``He
was right across the hall. All he had to say was, `I can't make
it.' Peyton came in with his notepad and pencil asking us questions
like who we had on the offensive line and who was going to protect
him. We evaluated Leaf as close as Peyton and we didn't get strong
vibes he'd be the way he was. It surprised me he self-destructed,
but I crossed myself many times last season. But he's still a
talent. If he matures he'll be a good player. But that's a big
question.'' It's a question Steinberg insists is being addressed.
``He's wholly cognizant of what went wrong, and it won't happen
again,'' Steinberg said. ``He got a real education on the demands
on an NFL quarterback and the need to be cordial and cooperative in
all situations. I think he'll do better and better.'' He couldn't
do worse, that's for sure . . . Word is the Eagles are fascinated
by Syracuse quarterback Donovan McNabb and may pass on Heisman
Trophy winner Ricky Williams to take McNabb with the draft's second
pick. If they do, Williams would likely slide further because
Cincinnati is likely to take Oregon quarterback Akili Smith with
the third selection if he isn't already gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
