<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRUPTION IS DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Eugenia Williams very probably didn't take a penny to
conclude that Evander Holyfield defeated Lennox Lewis last weekend
even though she did file for bankruptcy protection six weeks ago.
She quite simply may have known the sad story of a referee named
Octavio Meyran.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 11, 1990, Meyran was the third man in the ring in Tokyo
when Buster Douglas knocked Mike Tyson cold, winning the undisputed
heavyweight title despite being a 42-1 underdog. Only hours after
that upset, promoter Don King tried to steal the fight for Tyson
with the assistance of boxing's three crime families _ the World
Boxing Council, World Boxing Association, and International Boxing
Federation _ but King had a problem.
</P>
<P>
   King claimed Douglas had actually been knocked out earlier but
was saved by Meyran's ``slow count.'' He protested loudly and WBC
president Jose Sulaiman, who had named Meyran the referee, promised
this injustice would be rectified. Problem was, Meyran didn't go
along with the fiction.
</P>
<P>
   An honorable man in a den of snakes, Meyran loudly proclaimed
his innocence to a half-dozen American journalists who had traveled
to Tokyo expecting to get off work in time to get sushi before bed
and ended up filing for overtime and not eating until breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Meyran explained over and over during the long hours immediately
after the fight how he had picked up the count from the timekeeper
and that Douglas had arisen at the count of nine, clear-eyed and
ready to fight. Douglas had stared right at Meyran, listening to
the only thing that matters in a boxing ring _ the referee's count.
</P>
<P>
   Not once did Meyran waver, as British judge Larry O'Connell did
this past week after he returned to London amid a sea of
controversy and lamely declared that he now thought his decision to
call the Lewis-Holyfield fight a draw was in error. Meyran refused
to play that kind of game, and because of it, Sulaiman was forced
to back off, especially when tape of that fight backed Meyran's
count.
</P>
<P>
   But all was not forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Meyran worked one more title fight that year, a World Boxing
Organization flyweight bout in Acapulco on Nov. 3, 1990. There were
1,243 world title fights from then through 1997, the last year full
records are available. Octavio Meyran did not referee a single one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than 200 world title fights last year. He isn't
known to have worked one of those, either. He was not hit by a bus
or run over by a freight train. Octavio Meyran, a good referee in
an often bad sport, simply disappeared from the boxing scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a well-used world referee,'' said Mills Lane, one of
boxing's most respected figures. ``He refused to back down, and I
never heard of him doing another major fight. You can't tell me
people don't know those things are going on.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it's done in boxing today. That's how the three
monogrammed crime families and the promoters they support so often
seem to get what they want, even when all evidence might argue for
another result. They don't pay anybody off because they don't have
to. They just make sure the phone doesn't ring again at Octavio
Meyran's house.
</P>
<P>
   To have so much power concentrated in so few slimy hands is
corrupting, but boxing has done it that way for a long time, and it
has created a system ripe for manipulation and chicanery.
</P>
<P>
   As Lane explained, ``If you're at the mercy of the sanctioning
bodies for work and you like to travel but you live in Switzerland
and don't get to travel much and you're in San Antonio because the
WBC sent you there to do Julio Cesar Chavez against Pernell
Whitaker and you know Sulaiman is close to Chavez and the promoter
(King) is paying your expenses and he's close to Chavez, when the
round is close who do you go to?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the subtle pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   As Arizona Sen. John McCain wrote in a letter to New York State
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer four days after Lewis-Holyfield:
``Professional boxing's problem with controversial fight results is
not that experienced and objective judges sometimes reach
surprising or unpopular decisions. The very nature of the boxing
industry gives rise to conflicts of interest and fraudulent
practices in the arranging and conduct of boxing events. This is a
point I hope federal and state officials across the US will reflect
upon in the wake of this controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   In point of fact, Lewis won the unification fight with Holyfield
and deserves to hold all three belts, but he won them by a slight
margin not a wide one, even though the opportunity to do the latter
was there had he chosen to press his advantage. He did not,
however, and so a fight that was 6-1 after seven rounds suddenly
became close on the scorecards.
</P>
<P>
   Had anyone but King been promoting the fight, there probably
would have been far less controversy. Williams would have been
dismissed as incompetent, which she was on that night at least, and
most everyone would have moved on. But the systemic problems in
boxing lead to the kind of suspicions that have swirled around the
Holyfield-Lewis outcome and spawned four investigations in New York
that will most likely conclude that Williams didn't know what she
was looking at.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone thinks they're going to find bribery trails they can
forget it; the system makes out-and-out bribes unnecessary.
Williams earns about $30,000 as a municipal accounting clerk in
Atlantic City. Six weeks ago, she filed for bankruptcy protection,
owing nearly three times as much as she earns.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in recent years the IBF has assigned her to judge bouts in a
half-dozen countries, including two trips to South Africa, as well
as the United States, at the expense of promoters like King. That's
because in boxing, the judges' fees and expenses are not paid by
the organizations that appoint them but by the fight's promoter,
which is like Bob Kraft paying the officials when the Patriots play
in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   It is an absurd system on the face of it let alone behind the
scenes, where promoters have been seen with a table full of judges
at a fancy restaurant in the nights before a fight.
</P>
<P>
   What other sport would not think twice about having a promoter
pay the judges of his matches? What other sport would let anyone
off the street walk into a gym and call himself a trainer? What
other sport would have no understandable way to rank its
participants and no way to prevent the obvious manipulation of
those ratings?
</P>
<P>
   What other sport has anything like boxing's alphabetized crime
families deciding on the officials in the biggest events? And what
would you expect but trouble from a system in which being in the
good graces of one of the organizations is the only way to get
assigned as a judge or referee in a big fight?
</P>
<P>
   When somone in power, such as the guy who appointed Williams and
later defended her, IBF president Bob Lee, says, ``I looked at it
as no harm, no foul,'' it makes you wonder even further.
</P>
<P>
   The point is: Don't bother looking for bribery and influence
peddling at ringside. That is not necessary. A judge like Williams
doesn't have to be told how expendable she is; all she has to know
is what can happen to an honest guy like Meyran.
</P>
<P>
   We have ratings that everyone in the sport knows are so corrupt
and absurd they defy any form of logical analysis. King is not
alone at this, only the best at it.
</P>
<P>
   It does little good to condemn any one person or organization in
boxing. The big question is, how can this system be reformed?
</P>
<P>
   Good first steps would be to change the way officials are chosen
and paid. Give the responsibility to the state or country in which
the fight is being held. If there are not enough competent
officials in a particular state, or if neutral judges are called
for, have an international pool of judges and referees ready and
willing to be rotated to eliminate any hint of favoritism
regardless of which organization is sanctioning the show.
</P>
<P>
   Would this clean up the red light district of sports? Not by a
long shot, but it's a start. And that's what boxing needs right now
_ a new start. Before it finishes itself off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fistic marriage of IBF welterweight champion Felix Trinidad
and WBC titleholder Oscar De La Hoya continues in May when they
will appear on back-to-back HBO shows. De La Hoya will defend his
title against Oba Carr May 22 at the new Mandalay Bay Casino in Las
Vegas. A week later, Trinidad will defend his title against No. 1
challenger Vincent Pettway at Roberto Clemente Stadium in his
native San Juan. Negotiations are ongoing for a De La Hoya-Trinidad
unification match this fall, and the potential deal was helped
considerably by the pay-per-view success of Holyfield-Lewis.
Promoter Bob Arum and HBO executives closely watched how
Lewis-Holyfield sold, believing the closer it got to 1 million buys
the more likely it was that De La Hoya-Trinidad could be made. No
one believes a non-heavyweight fight can exceed Lewis-Holyfield, so
it effectively became the ceiling for De La Hoya-Trinidad's sales
potential. Holyfield-Lewis did 1.2 million buys . . . Hot
heavyweight contender Michael Grant gets another test June 19 at
Madison Square Garden when he takes on strapping Lou Savarese.
Andrew Golota may be a co-feature but only if his manager, Lou
Duva, agrees to a more formidable opponent than he has yet
mentioned. Originally, HBO hoped to match Grant with Shannon
Briggs, but Briggs's management turned down a $750,000 purse while
Savarese asked for the Grant fight . . . Vinny Pazienza returns to
the ring wars April 9 at Foxwoods vs. Joseph Kiwanuka. Pazienza
(44-7) continues to search for a title shot in the super
middleweight division. Kiwanuka is 26-3-2 with 19 KOs and is coming
off a win over Glen Johnson last August . . . Hartford heavyweight
Lawrence Clay-Bey plans to get back into the ring in June after a
bone graft to fix a broken finger . . . Hall of Fame middleweight
champion Marvelous Marvin Hagler will attend the International
Boxing Hall of Fame ceremonies June 10-13 in Canastota, N.Y. For
information on the event, call 315-697-7095 . . . Don't be
surprised to see Ike Quartey abandon the welterweight division soon
and move up to challenge young super welterweight champion Fernando
Vargas if he can't get back into the De La Hoya rematch mix . . .
James Toney recently returned to the ring in Phoenix with a win. He
had not fought since June 14, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
