<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT TURNS TO `TIMBER' 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Kentucky Derby picture has changed dramatically,
starting last Saturday when winter book favorite Exploit ran second
in the San Felipe Stakes at Santa Anita, his first defeat. On
Wednesday, it was announced that Exploit had chipped his left front
knee and would be retired.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber caught Exploit, who was 3-5, inside the 16th-pole
in the San Felipe and drew away. The next thing anyone knew,
Exploit, who is owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, owners of Silver
Charm, was off to the breeding shed. The loss was a blow to trainer
Bob Baffert, but he also trains Prime Timber.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have had surgery performed to remove the chip, but we
decided the horse was worth too much as a stallion prospect,'' said
Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   The injury will be allowed to heal naturally and a decision on
where to stand the son of Storm Cat will be made later.
</P>
<P>
   Exploit was favored at 6-1 after the first round of advance
betting sponsored by Churchill Downs. He went up to 14-1 as the
second round closed last Sunday, following his defeat. As is the
case with advance wagers, all bets on Exploit were lost because he
will not start.
</P>
<P>
   So Prime Timber, a son of Sultry Song, picks up the fallen flag
for Team Baffert. Owned by Aaron and Marie Jones, Prime Timber has
won three of five starts and been second in the other two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty comfortable race,'' said David Flores, who
rode Prime Timber in the San Felipe. ``I was patient until the last
turn, then I asked him to pick it up a little bit, and it took a
while for him to do it. But once he changed leads, he really took
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Next for Prime Timber is the Santa Anita Derby April 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another top Baffert 3-year-old, General Challenge, also tasted
his first defeat last weekend, finishing fifth in the Louisiana
Derby at Fair Grounds. General Challenge, who was off at 4-5, had
an excuse as he lunged at the break and trailed the field early. He
made a big run into contention at the top of the stretch but tired
badly. The race was won by 22-1 shot Kimberlite Pipe, with Answer
Lively, last year's 2-year-old champion, second. ``When you get
left like that in a race like this, it leaves a lot to do,'' said
Gary Stevens, who rode General Challenge. ``He just got tired. He
needs some experience.'' . . . Meanwhile, Baffert's fine 3-year-old
fillies just kept rolling along. Silverbulletday ran her record to
9-8-0-0 with a tally over a sloppy track in the Fair Grounds Oaks
Saturday, while Excellent Meeting took the Santa Anita Oaks Sunday
and now stands at 10-6-3-1. Silverbulletday, the 2-year-old filly
champion of 1998, won by 3 lengths under Stevens at 3-10. ``She
wasn't really relishing the off track, but she got the job done,''
said Stevens. ``I just wanted to keep her out of trouble and give
her a chance to win.'' Excellent Meeting prevailed by a neck over
Tout Charmant, another Baffert charge. Ridden by Kent Desormeaux,
Excellent Meeting was off at 1-10 and created a minus show pool of
nearly $120,000. She took the lead down the backstretch and lasted
at the wire. ``I put her in the position I put her in because she
was much the best, and she got her picture taken,'' said
Desormeaux. So far, Baffert has insisted his top fillies will race
in the Kentucky Oaks, but either one would be competitive in the
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is still a long way to go, but there is a chance that
Plainridge Racecourse will be an attractive little track. The
future home of harness racing in Massachusetts (live racing begins
April 19) is small, with a capacity of 2,800 and 1,680 seats, but
the decor in the five rooms will be modeled after the Mohegan Sun
casino, which is very nicely appointed. The racing surface will be
patterned after Rosecroft Raceway in Maryland, considered one of
the best in the business. At 83 feet, the track will be wide enough
to start nine horses across. The turns will have a high bank,
allowing a slingshot move into the stretch by closers. There will
be neither a tote board nor lights in the infield. Management
readily admits those items were omitted to save money, but it also
could be aesthetically pleasing, as the only thing in an infield
that faces a tree-lined backstretch will be a 2 1/2-acre manmade
lake. Plainridge officials have no interest in racing at night and
figure the bettors now watch the odds on TV screens, anyway. The
third room on the second floor could hold more than 450 slot
machines. If slots come to Bay State tracks, the only problem
Plainridge would have is that its 1,000 parking spaces wouldn't be
enough . . . The 2000 Breeders' Cup will not be held at Santa Anita
as expected. Frank Stronach recently purchased the Arcadia, Calif.,
track, and he announced that the facility will be undergoing
renovations at Breeders' Cup time next year. Churchill Downs, which
hosted last year, is eager to step in again, and is the most likely
site. This year's Breeders' Cup will be at Gulfstream Park Nov. 6,
and Belmont Park is considered the front-runner for 2001 . . . Real
Quiet, last year's Kentucky Derby winner and 3-year-old champion
colt, will race next in the $750,000 Oaklawn Handicap April 3.
Trained by Baffert, Real Quiet was second in the New Orleans
Handicap March 14, his 1999 debut . . . Puerto Madero, who will be
held out of the Dubai Breeders' Cup after suffering a filling in
his ankle while finishing fifth in the Santa Anita Handicap March
6, will be pointed for the California Handicap at Hollywood May 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
