<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLESTEROS, PALMER NEVER STOP TRYING 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ They could have been shots from another era _
Arnold Palmer putting his classic charge into a 35-foot putt for
birdie, Seve Ballesteros magically lifting a bunker shot from an
awkward downhill lie to within 2 feet of the pin _ but
unfortunately there is no pause button in life. Not even for golf
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they were merely footnotes to rounds put together by a
couple of proud gentlemen Friday morning in the Bay Hill
Invitational. It was cut day and, not surprisingly, both Palmer
(78-74) and Ballesteros (76-76) were on the wrong side of it. They
were joined in their threesome by Robert Friend, who finished 57th
on the money list last year but is perhaps better known for being
the son of former major league relief ace Bob Friend.
</P>
<P>
   Friend shot 73-71 to make it into weekend play. Palmer returned
to his office above the Bay Hill pro shop, from where he runs this
event, not to mention a golf empire. Ballesteros, meanwhile, left
quietly, headed toward the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Ballesteros will be inducted Monday in festivities at the World
Golf Village in St. Augustine, Fla. The Hall of Fame has opened its
doors to Ballesteros not for what he now does, which is struggle
mightily with this game; it has welcomed him because of what he
once did, which was play the game with a brilliant passion and
dashing skill that few could match. He was Houdini with a golf
club, whether his ball came to rest among trees, in a deep-faced
pot bunker, or in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   But with his 42d birthday a few weeks away, Ballesteros's only
magic act has been making his game disappear. Despite the snickers
of many, the three-time British Open champ and two-time Masters
winner is determined to rediscover it.
</P>
<P>
   For three days leading up to Bay Hill, Ballesteros virtually
lived on the practice range. In his quest to recapture the faded
skills, the proud Spaniard has turned to Butch Harmon and even the
zany Mac O'Grady. Now it is Robert Baker's turn. The hot name in
coaching circles is best known as Ernie Els's instructor but it was
at Seve's side that Baker spent several days this past week.
</P>
<P>
   It made for quite a spectacle. There was Baker, and his top
assistant holding a video camera; Greg Kraft and Tom Pernice Jr.,
also Baker guys, offered their suggestions; Vijay Singh took time
out from his 2,500 buckets of balls to contribute his thoughts. And
all the while Ballesteros listened and hit, stopped to study his
swing, then hit and hit and hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good Lord never gives good golfers everything,'' said Lee
Trevino, who was 130 miles away, playing in the Legends of Golf.
``He never gave (Jack) Nicklaus a wedge. He never gave me long
irons. He just doesn't give you everything. He always keeps
something from you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept nothing from Seve. Seve was pretty well-rounded when
it came to playing golf. Gave him a terrific temper, though. He
gave him killer instinct, but too much killer instinct, because
when Seve didn't win, he didn't know how to accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   He still doesn't accept it easily, which is why he has plans to
play in next week's TPC. Perhaps he is looking for something that
is gone forever, but even if that is true, he once had something
that few have ever possessed. He deserves respect, not ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, Palmer, who was asked if this would mark his last time
playing in his own tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given it any thought,'' he said. ``Should I?''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer flashed a sly grin as he said this, but the reporter
didn't have to answer because a large crowd did the honors by
swarming to him, six and seven people deep.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The answer: Palmer, Michael Jordan, Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge,
and singer Amy Grant. The question: Who were those people playing
with Pat Rooney in the Tuesday pro-am at Bay Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Only kidding, of course. Even though he is the CEO of Cooper
Tires, which presented this PGA Tour stop, there is little doubt
that only his closest friends knew Rooney was even in the group.
One could argue, too, that Palmer, Ridge, and Grant, despite their
celebrity stature, were invisible, too. That is how much star power
Jordan has.
</P>
<P>
   Though his appearance had been publicized for only a few days,
thousands turned out to watch the basketball player-turned-golf
nut, and tournament officials and volunteers were pressed into
serious work manning the ropes and keeping people back. All this
for a pro-am. Heck, there were barely a couple of dozen people
following the Tiger Woods group earlier that morning.
</P>
<P>
   Makes you wonder about the possible dynamics if Jordan pays a
visit to the Ryder Cup matches in September at The Country Club.
Several sources said they had heard that Jordan will indeed take in
the event, not surprising given the fact that he went all the way
to Spain for two hours of one day's matches in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, crowd control for a Jordan appearance at the Ryder
Cup is less of a factor since tickets can't be purchased at the
gate as they were Tuesday at Bay Hill.
</P>
<P>
   And celebrities are nothing new to the Ryder Cup, which has been
elevated recently to must-attend status. Don't be surprised if
Prince Andrew (who has played The Country Club) pays a visit in
September, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson leaned against a car in the Bay Hill parking lot,
signed autographs for two fans, then was left alone in his
thoughts. They couldn't have been pleasant. The soon-to-be
50-year-old Watson had shot a second-round 77, on top of an opening
80 that left him dead last in the field of 112. Incredibly, he had
gone 8-9 on the 543-yard, par-5 sixth, a dogleg left around water
that the field had roughed up to a 4.884 average, fourth easiest.
In a twist of irony, Watson was paired with John Daly last year
when Daly hit drive after drive into that pond before settling for
an 18. Watson is off to a rough start in 1999, having broken 70
just twice in 13 rounds, and since his victory at the Colonial
MasterCard last May, he has struggled. He will be in Augusta in
three weeks, trying to stop a slide of five straight missed cuts in
majors . . . Heartache at Bay Hill's 18th, Parts I and II: Stuart
Appleby was 1 over, figuring he needed a par to make the cut. He
hit his approach into rocks bordering a large pond and was forced
to take an unplayable. Thinking he needed to hole his chip, he was
too strong, and when he missed the 6-foot comebacker, he had made a
double to finish 3 over. Minutes later, Mark Calcavecchia, also 1
over, bounced his approach off the rocks into the water. He, too,
made a double and finished at 147. Later, they learned that the cut
was 2-over 146 . . . The march to Augusta is on, and for many Bay
Hill _ not Doral _ is the new springboard. Virtually every big name
was in this week's field, save for David Duval, Nick Price, Greg
Norman, Steve Elkington, and Jesper Parnevik. Duval prefers to play
no more than three weeks in a row, which means next week's TPC,
followed by BellSouth, then the Masters. The defending champion at
BellSouth, Woods, will not be in this year's field but before you
fire off your criticism, understand that he announced this a year
ago. His reason is acceptable: The BellSouth was moved to the week
before the Masters and Woods, like many others, prefers not to play
leading up to a major . . . The fields for the next four weeks (the
MCI Classic follows the Masters) should be superb, but look for the
Greater Greensboro Classic and the Houston Open to take big hits .
. . Mark O'Meara and Woods will be in Europe for a tournament
opposite Houston . . . O'Meara was asked about his passion for
skiing and said he was not fearful of an injury as much as he was
bothered by people telling him he shouldn't ski. On a recent
vacation, O'Meara skied with Phil Mickelson, who had shattered his
leg in a mishap on the slopes a few years ago. ``Phil is an
aggressive individual,'' said O'Meara. ``I mean, he skis like he
hits his flop shots off a tight lie, so he kind of lives on the
edge.'' . . . Pat Bradley, the pride of Westford, Mass., was named
captain of the US Solheim Cup team that will defend its title in
2000. Bradley played on three Solheim Cup teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
