<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CART CIRCUIT WON'T BE SAME THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bobby Rahal has parked it. Two-time defending champion
Alex Zanardi has bolted to Formula One. And Roger Penske's
sputtering outfit has been pared to a one-car operation. Those are
some of the significant changes the CART FedEx Championship series
will face when the 20-race series kicks off its 1999 season with
Sunday's Marlboro Grand Prix of Miami at the 1.5-mile
Homestead-Metro Dade Motorsports Complex.
</P>
<P>
   While Rahal's retirement and Zanardi's defection have depleted
the series, Michael Andretti, a two-time champion at Miami, Jimmy
Vasser, Paul Tracy, and Al Unser Jr. will return as its marquee
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But Team Kool Green driver Dario Franchitti, a 25-year-old from
Scotland, is widely regarded as the man to beat. Franchitti
finished third in the series last year, recording five poles and
his first three career victories, at Road America, Vancouver, and
Houston. He will be challenged by at least eight others for the PPG
Cup, which for the last three seasons has been the exclusive
property of the Target/Chip Ganassi Racing outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I learned last year is that you have to be
consistent over the course of the season,'' Franchitti said. ``It's
a balancing act between being aggressive and using your head. I'm
just happy to be considered a championship possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasser, who won the series championship in 1996, will attempt to
deliver Target/Ganassi its fourth consecutive title.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's built-in pressure just to perform at the highest level
that you can, to keep your team and your sponsors happy, and to
keep your job,'' said Vasser, who will be paired with rookie Juan
Pablo Montoya after losing Zanardi as a teammate. ``So there's not
really any more pressure because there is a fourth championship
possible for our team. I think we may have a shot at it, but it's
just going to take a little while for the whole scenario to
unfold.''
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years, Rahal will no longer be behind the wheel. He
retired as driver last November, his seat to be filled by Max
Papis, and will head into the season as a full-time owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it's going to feel quite yet,'' said the
three-time CART champion. ``I've been looking at it like it's still
my car, but Max is driving. At spring training, it felt a little
weird not wearing a driver's suit. And people kept telling me I was
out of uniform. Obviously, it's a strange sight seeing a different
helmet in the Miller Lite car. But I'm prepared for this change.''
</P>
<P>
   Other changes include Team Penske's decision to scale back to a
one-car operation. With Brazilian teammate Andre Ribeiro no longer
in the picture, Unser Jr. will be the focus of Team Penske's
resources and attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a one-car effort will be good for us,'' said Penske,
whose drivers last year struggled to compete while ironing out the
wrinkles of the new Mercedes power plant. ``It gives us a chance to
refocus our organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very desperate,'' said Unser. ``We're needing a win very
bad. For Roger, for Marlboro, for everybody. The crew guys haven't
won in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser Jr., who has not visited Victory Lane since September
1995, finished 11th in last year's PPG Cup standings with 72
points; Ribeiro was 22d with a mere 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I'm like in heaven,'' said Unser. ``All of Penske's
organization is geared to make Al Jr. go fast and win races. I love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still another change is Andretti's decision to switch to
Firestone tires, ending a long association with Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been great to be associated with Goodyear over the
years,'' said Andretti, who will attempt to become a three-peat
winner in Miami. ``They helped me become the winningest active
driver in CART (with 37 victories), and for that I will always be
thankful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodyear is a first-class organization, but, as a team, we
have a responsibility to our sponsors and we feel that Firestone
will help us meet those expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon, already the winner of four
consecutive Southern 500s, will attempt to add to his glittering
record at Darlington Raceway when he starts Sunday's TranSouth 400
from the pole position, which he earned with a fast lap of 173.167
miles per hour during Busch Pole qualifications Friday at the
1.366-mile oval. Dale Jarrett hurt his chances to tie David
Pearson's record of three consecutive victories in the Darlington
spring race when he qualified a disappointing 21st. Johnny Benson
won the outside pole in his Ford Taurus with a surprising lap of
172.541 m.p.h. . . . Bobby Labonte, who is 32 points behind Winston
Cup leader Mike Skinner, was dealt a huge setback Friday when he
broke his right shoulder in a crash as he practiced for the Diamond
Hill 200 Busch Grand National Series event at Darlington . . .
Skinner caught a huge break last Wednesday when his Busch Grand
National team won its appeal to have his victory and points
reinstated from the Yellow Freight 300 March 13 at Atlanta Motor
Speedway. NASCAR officials had disallowed the win when inspectors
found illegal cylinder heads on Skinner's Chevrolet. An independent
appeals commission did, however, levy a $19,000 fine, the largest
in NASCAR Busch Series history . . . After failing to get their car
into the Daytona 500, Mike Herbert, 43, of Winchester and his
partner, Dewey Parsons of Medfield, will make another go of it on
the Winston Cup circuit next week. The owners of Norwood-based
Panther Brewing Co., maker of Three Stooges Beer, will sponsor a
car in the CBS-televised Primestar 500 at Texas Motor Speedway.
Driver Ken Bouchard will carry the Three Stooges Beer logo on the
No. 84 Chevrolet Monte Carlo fielded by Petty Huggins Motorsports.
``For the product we're trying to market, it's the best bang for
your buck,'' said Herbert . . . In honor of Sunday night's Oscars,
here are our nominations for the top three racing movies, followed
by three we wish were never made. Checkered Flag: 1. ``LeMans.''
Steve McQueen would've made Dale Earnhardt wet his pants. 2.
``Winning.'' Paul Newman as the quintessential Indy 500 winner. 3
``Heart Like a Wheel.'' Bonnie Bedelia in the inspirational
true-life story of top fuel drag racer Shirley Muldowney. Wipeouts:
1. ``Stroker Ace.'' Burt Reynolds does NASCAR no favors in this
celluloid canine. 2. ``Days of Thunder.'' Ditto for Tom Cruise. 3.
``Six Pack.'' Kenny Rogers stars as a down-on-his-luck driver who
employs a brood of runaways as his pit crew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
