<SLUG> BC-SOC-DALLAS-KANSAS-CITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURN BLANKS REVAMPED WIZARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ On a night when the opponent had the big-name players
with the skills to take the spotlight, two of the Dallas Burn's
stars stole the show.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Wizards boasted a revitalized squad that
included the likes of holdover Yugoslavian star Preki, U.S.
national team defender Alexi Lalas and goalkeeper Tony Meola, who
was injured.
</P>
<P>
   But Burn forwards Jason Kreis and Mickey Trotman instead
thrilled Burn fans with an impressive season-opening debut. Kreis
notched a hat trick and an assist and Trotman added a goal and an
assist to lead the Burn to a 4-0 victory last night at the Cotton
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that I was fortunate,'' said Kreis, who has
eight goals and three assists all-time against Kansas City. ``A lot
of those shots were easier to make than they were to miss. I was
certainly happy with it, but it wasn't something I expected and it
won't be something that I'll expect every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the game, the Burn faithful _ the 17,112 fans, the
largest home crowd since 1996 _ might expect to see some compelling
soccer this season, if Dallas can stay healthy. Despite some
expected first-game slip-ups and several starters out with
injuries, the Burn played a controlled, pressing game that resulted
in a franchise-record four second-half goals.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Kansas City was without Meola. Rookie goalie Cesar
Delgado, who was signed in January as a discovery player, took the
net and showed his inexperience. But Dallas' goals still
demonstrated offensive hustle.
</P>
<P>
   Trotman scored the Burn's first goal in the 53rd minute, as he
and Kreis maneuvered through three Wizards players. Off a touch
from Kreis, Trotman fended off defender Sean Bowers before firing
the ball into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Trotman headed a ball to Kreis, who one-timed
a low shot past Delgado for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas effectively shut down Kansas City's offense for most of
the second half, holding the Wizards to only two shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   Preki got the most action through his array of creative passes.
But during a bizarre moment in the second half, a seemingly
intoxicated fan ran on to the field and up to Preki near midfield,
throwing confetti at him and widely waving his arms. Players from
both teams surrounded the fan before security guards escorted him
off the field.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Burn players provided the excitement. Kreis
notched an 80th-minute unassisted goal after a slip-up by Delgado.
On his final goal four minutes later, Kreis slipped the ball
through Delgado's legs after a brilliant crossover assist through
two Wizards defenders from Oscar Pareja.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no clue what to expect coming into the season,'' Burn
coach Dave Dir said. ``But we know it's just one game. It was a
great crowd, and to get them out and show them what we can do was
the most important thing. I don't want to get too excited with one
game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
