r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-WETTELAND     03-21 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WETTELAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WORRIED ABOUT WETTELAND'S HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers' concern about closer John
Wetteland's health reached such gloomy depths yesterday that
manager Johnny Oates canceled the right-hander's workouts until
Wednesday and discussed an alternative for Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, whose progress this spring suffered since a Feb. 22
ankle injury, has incurred further misfortune by experiencing
muscle spasms in his lower back. The All-Star closer will continue
his rehabilitation and be evaluated tomorrow by Dr. John Conway and
again Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Oates told Wetteland yesterday morning that he was holding him
out of action until midweek.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not go onto the field today,'' Oates said after the
Rangers' 5-4 victory against the Cincinnati Reds at Charlotte
County Stadium. ``John is not feeling that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates' original plan called for Wetteland to pitch either
yesterday or during today's game against the Reds in Sarasota, Fla.
The spasms prevented that, and it remains unclear whether this
latest affliction stems from his injured right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I've got, I've got,'' Wetteland said. ``All you can
do is go on and move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland questioned whether he could recapture the form of a
dominant closer by Opening Day after getting hit hard in his
one-inning appearance Thursday against the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, who admits experiencing pain in the ankle, cannot
spot his fastball with consistency. The injury prevents him from
driving his body toward the plate during his delivery from the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Wetteland surrendered 12 runs (11 earned) on 12 hits
_ which included two home runs _ during his two previous one-inning
appearances. Furthermore, the hard-throwing right-hander failed to
record a strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get him where he can push off that ankle,'' Oates
said. ``How? I don't know right now. When? I don't know that right
now, either.''
</P>
<P>
   That forces Oates to consider an alternative to Wetteland should
a save opportunity present itself Opening Day against the Detroit
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be a pessimist,'' Oates said. ``I don't want
to be overly optimistic. I'd like to be a realist. We're going to
have to face reality. Is he getting better?''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would enter the season with a closer-by-committee
likely composed of right-handers Tim Crabtree and Danny Patterson
and left-hander Eric Gunderson should Wetteland be unavailable,
Oates said. The manager would attempt to orchestrate as many
favorable situational matchups for those three relievers to
preserve late-inning leads.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree, Patterson and Gunderson have combined to convert only
eight of 33 save opportunities during their careers. Wetteland has
converted 253 of 300 opportunities during his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have that one go-to guy at the end,'' Oates said.
``If one of those guys emerges \Ras the closer\S, then fine.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
