<SLUG> BC-BKC-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY WOHLERS CRUCIAL FOR BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves are hopeful Mark Wohlers can be their closer
on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   That could be good news for a team that has taken one hit after
another since arriving at their plush Disney World complex. Their
optimism could also be interpreted as a sign of desperation setting
in on baseball's ``Team of the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves looked like a powerhouse coming into camp with the
off-season additions of right fielder Brian Jordan and second
baseman Brett Boone. Then came the news that first baseman Andres
Galarraga will miss the entire season with a tumor in his lower
back and closer Kerry Ligtenberg is doubtful because of a bad
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the best team in the National League looks vulnerable,
although general manager John Schuerholz believes the Braves will
survive with Ryan Klesko moving to first base and Otis Nixon taking
over in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set a club record for offense last year,'' Schuerholz said.
``We won't have the big guy in the middle now, pounding 500-foot
home runs. But we will still be a very effective offensive team. In
fact, we'll have more speed and offense spread more evenly
throughout the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   That's more spin than reality, but the Braves still have two
terrific prospects in first baseman Randall Simon and outfielder
George Lombard. One or both could be promoted during the season if
the Braves' offense has trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg rescued the Braves' bullpen last year when Wohlers
first got hurt, then lost all idea of where he was throwing the
ball. Now the Braves are insisting Wohlers is close to reclaiming
his old ability and returning to the closer's role.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' options without Wohlers or Ligtenberg would be go
with John Rocker or make a trade for Minnesota's Rick Aguilera or
Kansas City's Jeff Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' strength remains starting pitching. But they had
just 24 complete games last season as opposed to 62 save
opportunities. Denny Neagle, since traded, had five of those
complete games.
</P>
<P>
   Spotlight on Dean Palmer
Palmer and Tigers are good matches in several ways
</P>
<P>
   There are some good matchups for Dean Palmer as a member of the
Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably:
</P>
<P>
   Palmer and Tigers infield coach Perry Hill: Palmer did his best
defensive work with the Rangers when Hill was the infield coach.
Hill has developed a reputation for being one of the best defensive
minds in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's helped me tremendously,'' Palmer said. ``As far as
working, he's one of the hardest working coaches in the game. We've
been doing a lot of work on throwing mechanics and a lot of drills
with feet work.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer and Tiger Stadium: The old ballpark, in its final year,
is a great place for power hitters. Over the past three years,
there have been 27 percent more home runs hit at Tiger Stadium than
the average ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Palmer hit the second-longest home run in the majors
with a 475-foot shot at Tiger Stadium off pitcher David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer and a long-term contract: Palmer has been in the majors
since midway through the 1991 season, but signed his first
long-term deal in the off-season. The Tigers gave him a five-year,
$36 million contract, and Palmer also got a no-trade clause for the
first three years.
\Nsubheds:Baker gets reprieve
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Giants manager Dusty Baker is one of the most
respected men in the game, except by his own boss. Insiders say
Giants general manager Brian Sabean was just itching for the chance
to replace Baker with his buddy, Jim Fregosi.
</P>
<P>
   Baker never gave him that chance, winning a division title in
1997 and tying for the wild card last year. Now Fregosi has stepped
down as Sabean's special assistant to take over the Toronto Blue
Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim is irreplaceable,'' Sabean said last week. ``It's a tough
loss. Jim and I are very close. He brought a lot to the table. He
has one of the best baseball minds I've been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's status is still tenuous.
\Nsubheds:Schilling wavers
</P>
<P>
   Phillies ace Curt Schilling is starting to believe his team
won't be that bad. But it still doesn't mean he wants to hang
around through a rebuilding program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since camp opened, we've played well, and that adds a lot to
the enjoyment of showing up and doing your job,'' Schilling said.
``We are going to have a good club if we stay healthy and things
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   But as far as rescinding his willingness to be traded, Schilling
said, ``Don't ... don't go there. It's been fun. We've got a good
mix of guys, and I think when we leave here, there will be 25 guys
on the roster who belong in the big leagues. That was not the case
in the last couple years. This is the best team I've been on here
since 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not saying much. Schilling will be with the Cleveland
Indians by August.
\Nsubheds:Angels watch
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Chuck Finley is coming around slowly after being
bothered by shoulder and neck stiffness. The Angels aren't sure if
he'll be ready to start against the Rangers in the first week of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn also is having troubles adjusting to Arizona spring
training after years in Florida. Vaughn said he was having trouble
seeing at the Angels complex in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ought to put a dome over this place,'' said Vaughn, whose
average has been under .200 for most of the spring. ``I'm not
picking up the ball real well. I figured if I concentrate here,
once I get in major-league ballparks \Rthe ball\S will be as a big
as a pumpkin.''
\Nsubheds:Short hops
</P>
<P>
   One concern about the absence of manager Joe Torre is the
Yankees don't have anyone who can stand up to owner George
Steinbrenner. Torre served as a buffer to the volatile
Steinbrenner, and other club officials are worried what might
happen while he's out.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants appear to be leaning toward Marvin Bernard as their
centerfielder and are willing to move Stan Javier.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers love rookie outfielder Gabe Kapler, who hit
.322 with 28 homers and 146 in Double A last year. He could push
aside Brian Hunter, a great defensive outfielder with a lousy
on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas has changed his mind. He said the majority of his
playing time will be at DH. The White Sox have been impressed with
Paul Konerko this spring, and he should be their everyday first
baseman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
