<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-JOHNSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS WORLD SHOULD HEED MOTHERS' HONESTY POLICY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long ago, in what seems like another lifetime, I was abducted
into the U.S. Army and served in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   That's no lie. Can I manage the Toronto Blue Jays?
</P>
<P>
   Have I ever told you about the time we were ambushed on a trail
about six clicks south of Khe Sanh, or the time we chased Charlie
out of a village near Soc Trang?
</P>
<P>
   I didn't, because it never happened. But I can tell you a true
story about Christmas Day in 1971 when I got to see the Bob Hope
Christmas Show in Long Binh.
</P>
<P>
   I don't do war stories. And Tim Johnson shouldn't have, either.
</P>
<P>
   We live in a lying society, an age when convenient
prevarications are seen as more important than prevailing truths.
Ministers lie. Ex-football greats lie. The president of the United
States lies.
</P>
<P>
   Integrity has become a decidedly relative term. A lying man
simply needs a successful lawyer. A fibbing athlete simply needs a
weasel of an agent.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know Tim Johnson. If he is half the man that his
brother, Sandy, the Rangers' former personnel chief, is, then Tim
Johnson must be quite a man.
</P>
<P>
   But he violated a cardinal rule among those in charge of modern
sports: If you're in charge, don't let the public or your players
catch you lying. The public will never quite trust you again; the
players will use it, when needed, to brand you as a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a liar and a back stabber,'' Pittsburgh third baseman Ed
Sprague said of his former manager, Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that a struggling has-been who hasn't batted better
than .228 in the past two seasons might be looking for somebody
else to blame. The public took it as an appropriate condemnation of
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to note, too, that Johnson apparently did not
regularly regale the Blue Jays with tall tales about Vietnam
firefights waged by the amber glow of burning villages. No, he told
pitcher Pat Hentgen, who had his worst season in the major leagues
last season.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson tried to skip the slumping Hentgen in the rotation
and insert Roger Clemens in a key series in Boston, Hentgen
bristled. It prompted a clash between Johnson and pitching coach
Mel Queen. Once that rift was firmly a matter of public record,
Hentgen simply pulled back and let Johnson's original lie run its
course.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was fired Wednesday. Toronto general manager Gord Ash
blamed the fact that Johnson's Vietnam fib wouldn't go away.
</P>
<P>
   Ash is right. People love to chant ``liar, liar, pants on fire''
at the playground big shot. If he's an Oval Office big shot, all
the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get him fired,'' Queen told the Toronto Sun last
week. ``If he wants to see who got him fired, he should look in the
mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has to look in that mirror every day. From what I've
read, he already feels the pain of that.
</P>
<P>
   But in sports today, he made an easy target. Stretch the truth,
and you'll be branded faster than you can say Barry Switzer. A
coach or manager _ or a high-profile owner from Arkansas _ who gets
caught misstating the truth sets a dangerous precedent. A lying
coach or owner invites teamwide distrust.
</P>
<P>
   Modern players, in that regard, are no better than teen-agers,
returning home with a dent in the family car. How they respond
often depends on the integrity of the people they will be giving
their explanation to.
</P>
<P>
   By his Vietnam lie, Johnson's ability to run the Blue Jays was
compromised, probably permanently. The only policy is to tell the
truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth.
</P>
<P>
   I could tell you war stories about that, but I don't have any.
As a Vietnam veteran, I'm not as much offended by Tim Johnson's
masquerade as I am saddened by it.
</P>
<P>
   Honesty, as our mothers told us, is the best policy. Whether
you're running a country or a baseball team, the risks are not
worth the rationalizations.
</P>
<P>
   People still expect the truth, even in a fantasy business like
sports.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
