<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY WINS; CIENFUEGOS PLAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ In his luxury suite at the Rose Bowl, Major League
Soccer commissioner Doug Logan must have felt good about his
Saturday-morning meeting with midfield holdout Mauricio Cienfuegos.
</P>
<P>
   It was a meeting that convinced the three-time MLS All-Star to
end his holdout _ at least for now _ so that Cienfuegos could make
an appearance during the Galaxy's 2-1 shootout victory over
Colorado in the season opener for both teams Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Welton, Daniel Hernandez and Clint Mathis scored in the shootout
to give L.A. the victory while David Vaudreuil notched the lone
Rapids shootout goal.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, who sat near the end of the bench in the first half,
did more for his bargaining power by not playing than when he
actually entered in the 53rd minute to loud cheers from the measly
crowd of 17,343.
</P>
<P>
   Chants of ``Cienfuegos'' were heard throughout the opening half,
certainly loud enough for Logan to notice while the two sides argue
over his financial worth to the league.
</P>
<P>
   The midfield general came in and helped strengthen the so-so
performances of youngsters Daniel Hernandez and Joey Franchino, but
it wasn't enough to salvage a victory in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   With Cienfuegos itching to get in along the sideline, midfielder
Clint Mathis, expected to share a bulk of the midfield
responsibilities with Cienfuegos this season, needed only minutes
to display his one-legged something of a hop-dance goal celebration
in the 14th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Welton weaved his way through Colorado's central defense,
attempting a shot that bounced to the left of the Rapids goal off
defender David Vaudreuil's leg toward Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, unmarked on the right side, settled the ball from the
air with his chest, then one-touched a strike to the left corner to
give L.A. a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rapids answered in the 34th minute, getting a goal from
midfielder Ross Paule.
</P>
<P>
   Joey DiGiamarino sent a looping cross in the Galaxy box for
Jorge Dely Valdes, who was watched closely by Greg Vanney. Valdes
and Vanney lunged, but the ball appeared to sail off Vanney's head
toward Paule.
</P>
<P>
   Paule picked it out of the air, hammering home a 20-yard shot to
the left-corner past Galaxy keeper Kevin Hartman to notch the
score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
