<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8452 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-BRUTON-SMITH-TEX     03-21 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRUTON-SMITH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUTON SMITH GETS HIS KICKS FROM NASCAR WHEELS AND BIG-BUSINESS
DEALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Town and Country Ford is so huge. There are
dozens of spotless, shiny new cars on the cavernous showroom floor.
Outside, there are vehicles almost as far as the eye can see.
Everywhere, young men wearing the salesman's uniform of
short-sleeve shirt and tie earnestly buzz around.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this is a large-volume car dealership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been No. 1 in the nation, where we have outsold every
Ford dealership,'' Bruton Smith says. ``I think we kind of did it
to show we could.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way Bruton Smith does business, whether it's building
Texas Motor Speedway, the host to the Busch Grand National
Coca-Cola 300 and the Winston Cup Primestar 500 next weekend, or
spending $215 million to purchase Las Vegas Motor Speedway, or
running his 109 _ and counting _ car dealerships, or any of his
50-plus companies.
</P>
<P>
   It's the challenge, the competition, the desire to be No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love business,'' he said. ``I enjoy what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith makes money like the rest of us make a mess _
effortlessly, regularly.
</P>
<P>
   He says he isn't sure how much he's worth, but does admit to
owning 70 percent of Speedway Motorsports, Inc., which he says is
valued at $1.6 billion, and a tad less than 60 percent of Sonic
Automotive, the auto dealership conglomerate worth more than $600
million.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely that Smith really does know his net worth to the
penny _ give or take any pending deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to believe his IQ must be in the genius level,
because he never forgets anything,'' said Eddie Gossage, who runs
Texas Motor Speedway for Smith. ``He always does what he says he's
going to do. If I need a phone number, I don't look it up, I ask
him. He memorizes everything. He never has a schedule, but he can
tell you where he has to be on the 13th of next month.''
</P>
<P>
   So why not proudly state his value? Simply because it's not that
important. Making money is not Smith's motivation.
</P>
<P>
   You become the No. 1 Ford dealership in the nation just to say
you did it. You become a major player in the fastest-growing sport
in the country because you enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the fun,'' Smith said. ``I think we all need to have
fun in what we do. It doesn't make any difference what it is. We
all, hopefully, eat three meals a day and sleep in a bed. As long
as you're having fun, you can do a better job at whatever you do.''
\Nsubheds:The good life Smith knows how to have what most of us
consider fun. On a bright, sunny day in North Carolina, he tools
around Charlotte in a bright red Dodge Viper. He flies out on
weekends to go watch stock-car races.
</P>
<P>
   But fun also is turning Charlotte Motor Speedway into the first
racetrack with condos and luxury suites, being the first person to
take a motorsports company public and put it on the New York Stock
Exchange, building a 151,000-seat facility in an unproven market in
Fort Worth, building an opulent, private club on the premises,
purchasing a track in Las Vegas, and buying automobile dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``His hobby is business,'' Gossage said. ``He is the kind of
person it takes to make things happen. There's a perception about
him that he won't take `no' for an answer, and that's true. That's
a tremendous quality, because without people like him nothing would
get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has the vision and the gumption. He also has a cadre of
loyal employees who will do anything he asks. Gossage is one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes across to some people as distant, or short,'' Gossage
said. ``But the truth is he only has a small group of friends
around him, and if you're not one of his friends he's
uncomfortable. His friends are the people that run his
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage was afraid he might no longer be with Smith after the
problems at TMS the past two years. The Winston Cup drivers didn't
like the track configuration, water seeped up through the track
surface, and Gossage's once cute ``Shut Up and Race'' T-shirts
became a public relations nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easy thing to have done would have been to fire me and
blame me,'' Gossage said. ``I'm the guy out front. Instead, he kept
encouraging me along. I knew he took it personally, but he didn't
talk about how he felt. He talked about how I felt, and offered me
tremendous encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith never considered firing Gossage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was embarrassing, yeah,'' he said. ``But I'm a strong
believer that two wrongs do not make a right. Gee whiz, I've made
mistakes, and I'll make more. If I got clobbered every time I made
a mistake, I'd never amount to much.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of loyalty extends to his sport, even though he
doesn't always agree with the direction of that sport.
</P>
<P>
   Smith wants a second Winston Cup date at TMS and LVMS. That puts
him at odds with NASCAR president Bill France. In addition to being
the leader of the organization that makes the schedule, France is
chairman of the board of International Speedway Corp., which also
is in the business of building and acquiring tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Combine that with France's loyalty to older, smaller,
traditional tracks with two races _ such as Darlington, S.C.,
Rockingham, N.C., Martinsville, Va., and Richmond, Va. _ and it
makes dates tough to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think frustration is correct,'' Smith said. ``When you see
the success of Texas, no speedway to my knowledge, from the
opening, has ever had the success that speedway's had. Didn't that
speedway earn its right? The market is there.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Smith disagrees with France on the issue of dates, he
said tales of a rivalry between the two racetrack titans are
overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the media likes to play on that,'' he said. ``I've
tried repeatedly to stop it, unsuccessfully. Bill has tried to
help, maybe not as aggressively as he could have, but we've tried
to put that out. Bill knows that he has my commitment of helping
him build NASCAR. As NASCAR grows, that positively affects me. The
better I can make it, the better it is for Speedway Motorsports.''
\Nsubheds:Thinking ahead Smith points to the agreement between SMI
and ISC to join forces to seek a national TV deal for NASCAR races
as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   He also has advocated splitting the Winston Cup circuit into two
leagues, but France opposes it, so Smith isn't pushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. France and I have discussed it,'' Smith said. ``If it's
done, it's a NASCAR thing to do. It's not going to be easy. There
will be some opposition from drivers, some from fans. But it's
something that could take us to another level. We could have a race
at 1 o'clock Eastern and another race that starts 3 1/2 hours later
on the West Coast. It certainly would afford our sport more dates,
and we would create tremendous growth. I think that someday it will
be done, but it will only be done when NASCAR is ready to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Smith continues to look for other
opportunities, other ways to have fun. In February, he sold the
naming rights to Charlotte Motor Speedway to Lowe's Home
Improvement Warehouse. He said a similar deal might be coming to
TMS, but not any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to buy automobile dealerships. He's about to launch
an Internet auction company called SoldUSA.com.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, Smith is a sharp businessman. But through it
all, he keeps a twinkle in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   Bruton Smith is having fun, just like he did as a boy growing up
on a farm in Oakboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't know that he's on the Forbes list,'' Gossage
said. ``Wednesday before our first race here, we were busy and
didn't take time to go eat lunch. We were hungry, and so my
secretary fixed peanut butter sandwiches. I had to go answer the
phone, and when I came back I took a bite of my peanut butter
sandwich and it crunched. He looked at me with a grin on his face.
I opened my sandwich up, and he had put potato chips on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said `that's how I ate them as a kid. Try it, you'll love
it.' I thought, if people could only see this big-shot millionaire
eating peanut-butter-and-potato-chip sandwiches. But he's a
peanut-butter-and-potato-chip kind of a guy. He really is.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 0127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
