<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8453 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-MIDDLEBURY-WIS.SU     03-21 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-MIDDLEBURY-WIS.SUPERIOR-BOS </SLUG>
  
 MIDDLEBURY CLAIMS 5TH STRAIGHT TITLE
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Vt. _ They proceeded in single file, arms rigidly
upraised, fingers pointed stiffly skyward, like a surrendering
army. But this was a gesture of conquest.
</P>
<P>
   The Middlebury College hockey players were merely celebrating _
and signifying _ the latest achievement in their metronome of
success. With a 5-0 throttling of Wisconsin-Superior
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, they claimed their fifth consecutive NCAA Division
3 championship, padding a record of domination unrivaled at any
level of college hockey.
</P>
<P>
   So their impromptu victory parade featured a high five on each
hand, a symbol for their ecstatic fans on both sides of Kreitzberg
Arena, who stood in salute for the last three minutes of the game
and serenaded the Panthers for a half-hour afterward. Yes, there
was mutual adulation, but this revelry was probably the most
poignant of the bunch, because it was the most unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   That's why coach Bill Beaney stood off to one side in the
immediate aftermath, joining a circle of embrace with his four
seniors _ cocaptains Nickolai Bobrov and Ross Sealfon, plus Jeff
Anastasio and Brady Priest, who represent the second straight
graduating class that has gone 4 for 4 in national finals.
</P>
<P>
   As the rest of the team indulged in a pig pile of delirium,
Beaney and the seniors bowed their heads, and he quietly told them,
``Thank you for the strength of your conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a conviction that not even the coach had at the start of
the season, after he lost the six-player core that had been the
foundation of this dynasty, and looked at the flock of youth in its
place. His forecast for another NCAA plaque: ``I didn't expect it
of them,'' said Beaney, ``and they knew I didn't expect it of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   How did they know that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I told them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bobrov and his fellow elders also had a message for the
peach-fuzz brigade: ``Why can't we be the class that keeps it going
instead of the one that ends it?''
</P>
<P>
   With that resolve, the Panthers endured what Bobrov called ``a
roller coaster of a season,'' struggling to a 2-2 start, then
finishing with an 8-0-1 flourish yet still barely squeezing into
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Then came an emergence that was as spectacular as it was
surprising, capped by Middlebury's utter domination of the Final
Four, starting with a 9-3 whipping of Rochester Institute of
Technology and climaxing with Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's rout of the
Yellowjackets, which wound up as a 12-save shutout for Jon Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Bobrov had a storybook farewell by scoring twice and assisting
twice as Middlebury built a 4-0 lead in the first 22:55. Junior
defenseman Ben Barnett triggered the first three goals with
blue-line lasers, scoring two and assisting on one.
</P>
<P>
   When Barnett's afterthought of a blue-line blast during a line
change found the far corner of the Wisconsin-Superior net at 1:05
of the second period, he figured this was going to be Middlebury's
night. ``When the puck starts bouncing your way,'' he said, ``you
know things are going well.''
</P>
<P>
   So well that this was the first final during the joyride in
which Middlebury (21-5-1) prevailed by more than a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this was a dream finish, Bobrov said, ``When no one
believes in you except 20 guys amd thousands of others don't think
you can do it and you make it happen, I can't describe the
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaney tried. ``In a lot of ways, it is (the most special),'' he
said. ``The first one is always the biggest surprise, but in all
honesty, this one was more so because we'd lost so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   What about yet another encore? Athletic director Russ Reilly
believes Beaney's greatest coaching challenge will be in how he
handles the next Panther team that doesn't win it all. And still,
Beaney keeps him waiting.
</P>
<P>
   A new millennium approaches, and the dynasty is not done. ``Like
the sap that runs from the trees,'' said Beaney, ``anything is
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He never bothered to explain that bit of Green Mountain wisdom.
But he did give a preview of his welcoming speech to the 1999-2000
Panthers: ``I'm gonna tell them they don't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He's already proven to be a lousy prophet. Hey, nobody's
perfect. Though Middlebury comes close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
