<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS HOLD ON 4-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ So many times this season, the Kings have
fallen behind early, then spent the remainder of the night
frantically attempting to battle back.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, they altered their modus operandi.
</P>
<P>
   In a span of 7 minutes, 17 seconds in the first period, the
Kings fired four goals past two Florida Panthers goalies. Then they
simply held on for 40 minutes, trying not to let a crucial victory
slip away.
</P>
<P>
   They survived in the end to win 4-3 before a Forum crowd of
14,551. It was the Kings' fourth win in their last five games, as
they concluded a season-long seven game home stand with a 4-3
record.
</P>
<P>
   The home stand wasn't easy, but if the Kings are going to squeak
into the playoffs, the hard part comes now. Thirteen games remain,
nine on the road, beginning this evening in Phoenix against the
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's victory left the Kings (27-37-5) three points behind
Calgary and Edmonton, which are tied for the eighth and final
playoff berth in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Florida (25-26-17) has problems of its own. The Panthers, who
were without star right wing Pavel Bure (knee injury), are four
points out of an Eastern Conference playoff berth with 14 games
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Kings appeared headed for a blowout after their
4-0 first period, the hero of the opening 20 minutes was goalie
Stephane Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety seconds into the game, Fiset sprawled to rob Radek Dvorak
on a breakaway. Two minutes later, with the Kings on a power play,
Fiset stopped another breakaway, this one by Bill Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
   Without Fiset's effort, the Kings might have found themselves in
an early 2-0 hole.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when Donald Audette scored off a Luc Robitaille rebound
on a power play at 6:04, the Kings had a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Audette's shot was the Kings' second of the game; on their
fourth shot, on another power play at 8:11, they took a 2-0 lead on
a blast from the right point by Rob Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, with Blake screening goalie Kirk McLean,
Mattias Norstrom scored his second goal of the season, on the
Kings' sixth shot of the game. It was the last shot faced by
McLean, who was replaced by Sean Burke. Less than three minutes
after Burke entered the game, Russ Courtnall scored on a
shorthanded breakaway, increasing the lead to 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   But the Panthers fought back in the second period, cutting their
deficit in half and outshooting the Kings, 15-3. Their first goal
was scored by Viktor Kozlov on a power play at 8:12. Less than one
minute later, on an outnumbered rush, rookie Mark Parrish scored
his 18th goal this season, off a Lindsay pass, to make it 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that would be the end of the Panthers' rally.
Through much of the third period, the Kings played solid
defensively and limited Florida's scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But in the closing minutes, Doug Bodger and Blake received
penalties, providing Florida with a two-man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   It took Florida little time to capitalize, Ray Whitney scoring
from point-blank range to draw Florida within a goal.
</P>
<P>
   After Whitney's goal, the Panthers still had 1:51 left on a
Blake penalty to try to tie the score, and though they applied
plenty of pressure they were unable to get the puck past Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing minute, the Panthers pulled Burke for an extra
skater, but the Kings kept Florida out of their zone, and were not
threatened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
