<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-PLAYERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN INTRIGUE: MAVERICKS ROOKIE NOWITZKI ADJUSTS TO AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
WITH SIDEBARS 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It's a good thing Dirk Nowitzki has broad shoulders,
considering that he carries with him the future of basketball in
his native Germany, the future of the long-downtrodden Mavericks
and, right this minute, an acute craving for a TV dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too homesick,'' Nowitzki said of adjusting to life
away from Germany. ``But I miss most of all Mom's kitchen. She
cooks everything. My cooking, it doesn't taste pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   How together were you at the age of 20? Now imagine yourself 7
feet tall. Now imagine yourself leaving the comfort of your home,
your friends and your family to live 3,000 miles away. Now imagine
that you've done all this while saddled with the expectation that
you are destined to be an all-star, a Great White Hope, a messiah.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki is the latest experiment in the growing trend of pro
teams in North America going international. The Mavericks' Nowitzki
and Chris Anstey (Australia), two first-round draft picks, are from
overseas. The Stars have used eight of 15 draft picks the past two
years on foreign players. The Rangers have 75 players in their
minor-league system from Latin America, including their No. 1
prospect, center fielder Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks general manager Don Nelson doesn't dismiss the
difficulty foreign players have in adjusting to life in the United
States. That doesn't stop him, however, from gambling on their
talent. He said the learning curve for a player like Nowitzki is
longer than for U.S. players but that that's no reason to not take
a chance on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 4 billion people in the world,'' Nelson said. ``It's
a little silly, maybe even a little arrogant, to think that the
only good basketball players are within some tiny radius of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nowitzki to succeed, however, Nelson knows he needs to make
the transition to American life off the court, as well as on, where
he has struggled to keep up physically with the pro game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy America,'' Nowitzki said. ``But I don't think when I'm
old I'll be here. And when the season ends, I'm gone.''
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea of how he's making the adjustment, put yourself
in Nowitzki's size-15 shoes. Slip into 48 hours of being Dirk.
Starting now:
Tuesday evening The Suns-Mavericks game should have been over by
now. But moisture on the Reunion Arena floor causes a delay of more
than an hour. Nowitzki's body clock is confused, believing it's
time to do postgame interviews, then time to eat a snack, then time
to be in bed before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead,'' Nowitzki said after the loss in which he plays only
10 minutes, ``I was still up at midnight. Shopping. I had no food
in my household.'' So, he made a midnight run to Albertson's.
``Weird. Nobody else in the whole place.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV dinner scarfed, Nowitzki went to bed, first with music,
then with a book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to everything,'' he said. ``I like Lauryn Hill. Rap,
soul, black music. When I was young I liked AC/DC. In Germany we
have something called `technogroove.' I like it.''
Wednesday morning Nowitzki is up at 9 a.m. and feeling sheepish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually get up earlier than this,'' he said, almost
apologetically. ``But it's OK, because my apartment is so close to
\Rthe team's practice facility.\S''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the arrangement is cozy. Mavericks teammates Hubert
Davis, Anstey and Steve Nash live in the same complex. Logically,
Anstey _ a 7-foot-tall second-year pro who shares Nowitzki's
passion and skill for tennis _ has become a close friend. Nash,
meanwhile, is a baby sitter of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve helps me so much,'' Nowitzki said.
</P>
<P>
   How?
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me how to write checks,'' Nowitzki said. ``I'd never
done anything like that before.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson of the living
arrangements: ``It was sort of a coincidence. But Steve helps take
care of that homesickness thing. It's kind of preventative
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   For breakfast, Nowitzki has Frosted Flakes. A steady diet of TV
dinners and Frosted Flakes? One can't help but suggest that
Nowitzki will someday need some sort of medicine, preventative or
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki arrives at the practice facility at 10 a.m. driving a
rental car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big long car, so I like it,'' he said. ``I just decided
to rent it for three months. Maybe next year I'll buy one. When I
was little I always liked Mercedes-Benz, but it's not important
now.'' Besides, he added, ``I'm hardly ever driving. Apartment,
Reunion, practice, and to the airport. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   At practice, Nowitzki gets schooled by veteran A.C. Green.
Nowitzki is three inches taller and forever wider than ``Gramps,''
but the vet knows tricks. Green's side runs a series of
pick-and-rolls, forcing Nowitzki's side to adjust and switch men.
In one sequence, Nowitzki finds himself guarding the 6-9 Green,
then bullish forward Gary Trent, then Davis, a guard.
</P>
<P>
   Green _ who implores his unit with screams of ``Fourth quarter,
who wants it?'' _ leads his team to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Green assaults Nowitzki with good old-fashioned American trash
talk. Nowitzki grins. The kid may have the easiest smile in the
NBA, except sometimes one gets the impression he guffaws at the
joke although he doesn't get the punchline.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's just that trash talk is absolutely not my style, so I
laugh,'' Nowitzki said. ``I don't know who needs it. I'm a shy
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   To end practice, most of the Mavericks disband from the
scrimmage to work individually on free throws. But Nowitzki, Anstey
and fellow young big man Samaki Walker are summoned to one end of
the gym, where they work one-on-one on their inside games.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Nowitzki and the Mavericks embark on the tiresome
part of their work day. First comes a practice-ending session with
coaches. Then comes an NBA security meeting. Then come visits with
the media. Then comes a mandatory weight-lifting session.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there's the 20-20 rule,'' Nowitzki said. ``If you
don't play 20 minutes \Rin the previous night's game\S, you've got
to ride the \Rexercise\S bike for 20 minutes. Fun.''
Wednesday evening Time for another $30 visit to the grocery in
preparation for tomorrow's visit from Nowitzki's father and in
satisfaction of two more dietary cravings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love sweets,'' Nowitzki said. ``And I drink lots of Sprite.
Lots.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki also stops by Target to purchase sheets and pillows for
the new bed he bought for the visit from his father, Joerg.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 p.m., the bed is set up, the sweets are gone and it's time
for a rare look at the TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Americanized in that I don't watch any TV, really,''
said Nowitzki, who is watching the National Invitation Tournament
on ESPN with Nash as his visitor. ``I watch some basketball games
on TV, but nothing like soap operas or anything. In Germany, we get
CNN. And there's a superchannel that shows Jay Leno and Seinfeld
and The Cosby Show, all translated. But it's not my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki is asleep by 10:30, anticipating a home game tomorrow
night against the tough Orlando Magic, dreaming of performing well
in front of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw my first game in Seattle because it was broadcast on
German TV,'' Nowitzki said. ``But this will be the first time he's
seen me in person in America. And it will be his first time in the
States. Both of us are excited.''
Thursday morning Nowitzki is happy to clear up misconceptions about
his hometown of Wurzburg, misportrayed by the Fort Worth-Dallas
media as a sleepy little backwater village.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is small by American standards, I think, but quite large by
German standards,'' he said. ``Very cultural. It was completely
bombed in the Second War. But it's been rebuilt. A cultural center.
A castle. Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Nowitzki's day would normally follow a typical NBA
player's game-day pattern, except for the fact that his father and
the boyfriend of Dirk's sister will soon arrive at Dallas/Fort
Worth Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to talk to my girlfriend back home every day,'' Nowitzki
said, speaking softly as he mentions Sybille Gerer, 20. ``I do miss
her. She's been here twice, and wants to come back again soon. But
she doesn't like the States too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Nowitzki, Gerer is a basketball standout. She plays forward
on a club team in Germany. But Nowitzki said they almost never talk
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if Gerer lived here, he would go out more. More
restrictive, however, is his age. While his father is visiting,
he'll try to get out to a Dallas steakhouse. But that's as
adventurous as his nightlife gets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried going out a bit, but every time I go to the bar,
they want to see my passport,'' said Nowitzki, adding that he
half-expected the occasional barkeep to not bother carding a 7-foot
man. ``In Germany, 18 is the age you can drive. And 16 is the age
you can drink a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything especially American Nowitzki is looking forward to as
part of his 21st birthday June 19?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be able to drink here,'' he said. ``But to be honest, I
don't like your beer. Ugh. It's like lemonade.''
Thursday afternoon Joerg Nowitzki and his daughter's boyfriend
arrive. After Dirk picks them up, Joerg expresses disappointment at
his first glimpse of the States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't it be hot?'' he said, smiling. ``It's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Dirk drops his guests off at the apartment, arranges for them to
take a cab to Reunion and bids them goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 p.m., it's time for the short drive that precedes a
seven-hour night at Reunion Arena that, for him, will produce only
a few minutes of on-court time.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:20 p.m., Nowitzki makes his first appearance with 5:55 left
in the second quarter, the ninth man in Dallas' rotation. He scores
a basket on his first shot and commits a foul on each of the next
two possessions. But at least he contributes something (seven
points and two rebounds) in what will be a 93-76 upset victory
against Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Near halftime, Joerg Nowitzki is interviewed on the Mavs' TV
broadcast. ``Hello, Dallas Mavericks!'' Joerg said into the
microphone. ``I love you!''
</P>
<P>
   At game's end, and a 48-hour peek into his life, Nowitzki has
time to reflect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about the pressure of being a German, or about
my role in the future,'' he said in a festive post-game locker
room. ``No, not at all. I'm just 20. I'm struggling the last two or
three weeks. Riding the bench. I must just worry about my game.
That's enough for me right now.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
