<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-HUNDLEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON VOICES CONCERN OVER HUNDLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he is
contemplating opening the season with three catchers because time
is running out for injured Todd Hundley to prove he could handle
the everyday rigors of catching.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added that Hundley, bothered by a sore right elbow,
could begin the season on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be something we have to deal with,'' Johnson said
before the Dodgers and Baltimore Orioles played Saturday. ``We're
kind of running out of time. It's probably doubtful that Hundley
will show me enough between now and opening day that I can go with
two catchers, and I don't want to get caught short.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hundley can't catch, 24-year-old rookie Angel Pena could be
the Dodgers' opening-day catcher. Paul LoDuca is the favored
backup, but Johnson brought four catchers to play against the
Orioles _ Pena, LoDuca, Rick Wilkins and Tim Laker _ to maximize
his evaluation time on each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't voiced it, but it's an issue,'' Johnson said. ``I've
been thinking about it for 10 days. When Hundley had the setback,
(carrying three catchers) immediately jumped through my mind. It
may not be a distinct possibility. It may be a necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Hundley won't catch before Tuesday's day off, which
will leave less than two weeks before the April 5 opener against
the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Hundley, I want to be able to find out what he can do and
can't do,'' Johnson said. ``Can he play four or five days a week or
can he play two days a week?''
</P>
<P>
   Until this time, the Dodgers have maintained Hundley would be
ready for the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley hasn't caught a game during the spring training. He's
been the designated hitter twice but not since March 10. He injured
his right elbow the day before that when he hit left-handed for
more than 30 minutes in an extended batting cage session. According
to team doctors, that caused inflammation in his right elbow,
though doctors say it's unrelated to the reconstructive surgery he
had on the same elbow Sept. 26, 1997, as a member of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley played in 53 games for the Mets last season but caught
just twice. He spent most of his time in an ill-faded left-field
experiment. He was acquired in a trade with minor-league pitcher
Arnold Gooch for Charles Johnson and Roger Cedeno on December 1,
1998, in a move that will help define general manager Kevin
Malone's tenure with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson and Malone both said they wouldn't have traded for
Hundley if Pena wasn't in the organization and ready to play at the
major-league level. Pena is supposed to start the season with
Triple-A Albuquerque, but Hundley's availability could change that.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought he had a chance to start the season
with the Dodgers, Pena said: ``For some reason, yes, I feel like I
do. The pitchers say they like me, and that's the best thing they
can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's played in two Grapefruit League games and has one hit
in eight at-bats. He's being counted on to handle a veteran
pitching staff expected to be one of the best in baseball. The
switch-hitting Hundley also is expected to be the much-needed
left-handed bat in a lineup dominated by right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley also brings power. His 41 homers with the Mets in 1996
is a major-league record for catchers. He followed that by hitting
.273 with 30 homers and 86 RBI in 132 games before elbow problems
ended in 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the guys we have backing up are capable,'' said
Dodgers pitcher Darren Dreifort, speaking particularly about their
defense. ``LoDuca's good back there, Pena's good back there.
Wilkins is an experienced guy who's been around for a while and
Laker is another guy who's been around for a long while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
