<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY WINS IN SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- In his luxury suite at the Rose Bowl, Major League
Soccer commissioner Doug Logan must have felt good about his
Saturday morning meeting with midfield holdout Mauricio Cienfuegos
-- a meeting that convinced the three-time MLS all-star to end his
holdout -- at least for now -- so that Cienfuegos could make an
appearance during Saturday's 2-1 shootout victory over Colorado in
the season opener for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, who sat near the end of the bench in the first half,
did more for his bargaining power by not playing than when he
actually entered in the 53rd minute to loud cheers from the measly
crowd of 17,343.
</P>
<P>
   Chants of ``Cienfuegos were heard throughout the opening half --
certainly loud enough for Logan to notice while the two sides argue
over his financial worth to the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Issues over specific worth are issues left to the negotiating
process,'' said Logan, avoiding direct questions about Cienfuegos'
worth to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can come up with a solution that lengthens his
career here and his value to the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The midfield general came in and helped strengthen the so-so
performances of youngsters Daniel Hernandez and Joey Franchino, but
it wasn't enough to salvage a victory in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Given the long days coach Octavio Zambrano has spent dealing
with Cienfuegos' uncertainty and trying to prepare his team, a
positive result, even if its worth only a point in the standings,
was something to feel good about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first game and it's good to get a win,'' he said.
``Sometimes you have to take what you get. Certainly we were close
enough and did most of the work to get the win but it didn't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was our first match with Mauricio and we felt the loss
of him for a while, but he will get back in the swing of things and
so will this team.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cienfuegos itching to get in along the sideline, midfielder
Clint Mathis, expected to share a bulk of the midfield
responsibilities with Cienfuegos this season, needed only minutes
to display his one-legged something of a hop-dance goal celebration
in the 14th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Welton wieved his way through Colorado's central defense,
attempting a shot that riocheted to the left of the Rapids goal off
defender David Vaudreuil's leg toward Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, unmarked on the right side, settled the ball from the
air with his chest, then one-touched a strike to the left corner to
give L.A. a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rapids answered in the 34th minute, getting a sweet goal
from midfielder Ross Paule to tie the match.
</P>
<P>
   In the shootout, Daniel Hernandez, Welton and Mathis each scored
goals to give L.A. a 3-1 edge. David Vaudreuil scored for the
Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, who spent the off-season auditioning for the U.S.
National team, showed the flashes of creativeness that Zambrano has
been talking about all preseason.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old roamed behind strikers Cobi Jones and Welton,
picking his spots to get good looks at the goal and it paid off
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to get out here and see the chemistry for the
first time with our guys,'' Mathis said. ``I thought at times we
played real well and had opportunites, but then again we had mental
lapses that come with the beginning of a season.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis was pleased to share his midfield duties with Cienfuegos
in the second half. And Cienfuegos will certainly help with the
development of Franchino and Hernandez, who are expected to be
regular starters in their second full-seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, right when he came in he got the crowd into it,''
Mathis said of Cienfuegos. ``He's just such a phenominal player and
we all feed off him when he's in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootout victory wasn't what the Galaxy had in mind, but
with a long season ahead, Mathis wasn't ready to lower his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not three-points, but it's a win and that's more
important than anything else, he said. ``Sure it would have been
nice to win in regulation but getting a `W' is the most important
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
