<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 03:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8473 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN     03-21 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA REACHES FINAL EIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They lost their point guard, but not their cool.
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded UCLA lost Erica Gomez to a sprained ankle 35
seconds into the game but stuck to its game plan of getting the
ball into the post. It also got some timely outside shooting in the
second half and and made enough free throws down the stretch to
secure a 77-68 victory Saturday night over second-seeded Colorado
State in an NCAA West Regional semifinal before a crowd of 4,583 at
the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (26-7) advance to the regional final Monday night at
9 p.m. against top-seeded Louisiana Tech, with a berth in the Final
Four on the line. Colorado State, which got 24 points from Kate
Cronin and 21 points from All-American Becky Hammon, finished 33-3.
</P>
<P>
   No UCLA team has ever reached this level in the NCAA Tournament.
The 1978 team won the AIAW national title.
</P>
<P>
   Just 35 seconds into the game, Gomez stumbled in the back court
and sprained her right ankle. She pounded the floor and pulled her
jersey over her face before being carried off the court. Gomez did
not return to the game.
</P>
<P>
   She said from the trainers' room that Roxanne Manning had
stepped on her.
</P>
<P>
   She later returned to the bench with her foot wrapped in a towel
and her eyes red.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins continued on anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of our team,'' UCLA coach Kathy Olivier said.
``When Gomez went down, they showed character. They had a lot of
confidence and they took it to them. It was a total team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to go down low and use the height advantage with
6-foot-4 Janae Hubbard and 6-3 Maylana Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard was virtually unstoppable, scoring 21 points, including
12 in the first half. Martin finished with 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our size was too much for (them),'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Melanie Pearson found the zone for the
Bruins. She scored 15 of her 17 points in the second half,
including all nine in a 9-0 run that put the Bruins ahead 52-42
with 9 minutes, 42 seconds to play in the game.
</P>
<P>
   LaCresha Flannigan also chipped in with 14 of her 16 in the
second half, including eight by free throw and five by free throw
in the final two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Greco replaced Gomez at the point and played all 40
minutes, scoring eight points _ including the team's only field
goal in the last six minutes _ and getting two assists.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the free-throw shooting. Colorado State battled
back to within one point, 67-66, with 2:12 left. UCLA made 9 of 14
free throws in the final two minutes to stay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA dominated the inside game in the first half. Hubbard, who
at 6-4 is taller than the entire Colorado State team, scored 12
points.
</P>
<P>
   The other post players, Maylana Martin and 6-4 Carly Funicello,
scored four points apiece, but Martin seemed content to stay at the
top of the key and throw the ball into Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   The teams began the game shooting from outside _ and missing.
Colorado State, which relies on its 3-point shooting, stuck to its
game plan, not attempting anything from inside the 3-point line for
the first 6:45. In that span, the Rams scored once, by Jacque
Johnson with 13:52 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, UCLA wasn't shooting much better, having scored
just six points.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State also had troubles dribbling the ball, being
called for traveling eight times in the first half and 10 for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   After Flannigan hit an outside jumper to give the Bruins a 10-3
lead, Colorado State scored 12 of the game's next 16 points to take
a 15-12 lead. In that span, five people scored points.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA closed the half with a 10-4 run and take a 26-25 halftime
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams finished the first half shooting 27.6 percent, compared
to 35.1 percent for the Bruins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
