<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8513 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-GOP22-COX     03-21 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-GOP22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOTH WINGS OF GOP TAKING SOFTER LINE ON ABORTION
 &HT;    620&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opposition to abortion appears to be fading as a
political litmus test for candidates at all levels of the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP presidential front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
is drawing both criticism and support with his kinder, gentler
rhetoric that counsels patience on outlawing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But the rhetoric is kinder and gentler still among those charged
with recruiting GOP candidates for the crucial 2000 congressional
races. In fact, the chief House recruiter, Rep. Tom Davis of
Virginia, says he rarely broaches the subject with prospective
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't discuss it all,'' Davis said at a breakfast with
political reporters last week. ``If it comes up, it's only in the
context of where your district is and how you are going to handle
the issue. I don't have a litmus test on that issue for the party,
and I don't think it's appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Never in the two decades since the Ronald Reagan-led Republican
Party first made a constitutional ban on abortions a part of its
party platform has the GOP seemed so tolerant of those who disagree
that ``the unborn child has a fundamental individual right to life
which cannot be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   The party is ``hungry for victory,'' explained Frank Luntz, the
Republican pollster behind the ``Contract With America'' that led
to the GOP takeover of Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the hunger has produced unusual political theater as
some of the staunchest foes of abortion rally around Bush to
protect him from attacks by other abortion opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Pat Robertson, founder of the Christian Coalition, the
main supporters of the GOP's anti-abortion platform plank, said
recently on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' that he ``totally'' agrees
with Bush's approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might as well take the incremental approach,'' Robertson
said, at least until Supreme Court has changed enough to overturn
Roe v. Wade, the 1973 ruling that established abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   And late last week, the National Right to Life Committee urging
anti-abortion candidates and their supporters to refrain from
criticizing Bush. ``Governor Bush has a pro-life record and has
taken a pro-life position,'' said the group's executive director,
David N. O'Steen.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he opposes abortions except in cases involving
rape, incest and a threat to the life of the mother. He also has
said that Roe v. Wade will not be overturned ``until our hearts are
changed'' and that, until then, ``we should focus on ways to reduce
abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   But while he has stated that the Republican Party should
``maintain its pro-life tenor,'' he has deliberately avoided
endorsing the anti-abortion language of the 1996 GOP platform.
</P>
<P>
   That has left him open to attacks from Gary Bauer, Dan Quayle,
Pat Buchanan and Steve Forbes, all of whom are starting to raise
questions about Bush's commitment to ending abortion as a way of
slowing the Texas governor's juggernaut to the presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is human life, and when Republicans begin to play
games with it, we send a signal that we are not a serious governing
party,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Rev. Jerry Falwell said on CNN last week that the
Republican Party would be a ``losing minority'' if it abandoned its
anti-abortion principles.
</P>
<P>
   On the same program, though, conservative author David Horowitz
predicted the GOP would remain ``a minority party for a
generation'' if it keeps its ``pro-life'' platform intact.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma for Republican candidates is that their party's
nominating process is often dominated by anti-abortion activists.
Candidates must walk a tightrope, taking a stand firm enough to win
the nomination, but not so rigid as to alienate the more centrist
voters in general elections.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Davis suggested that the party's platform is not important in
his job of recruiting the kind of candidates who can help keep
Republicans a majority in the House after 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the party platforms are traditionally big
winners or losers,'' he said. ``I think the presidential candidates
set the tone, not the party platforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to abortion ``is not a litmus test to join the
Republican Party,'' he added, ``and even if it's in the platform,
we have a wide variety of views.''
</P>
<P>
   In recruiting candidates for the party, ``you have to cut the
cloth to fit the coat,'' he added. And in American politics today,
``where the rubber is meeting the road is in the suburbs,'' where
libertarianism sentiments often run strong, the Republican Party's
anti-abortion stand is not always popular, he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kate Michelman, president of the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, said the GOP's moderation on
abortion is ``nothing more than a campaign strategy'' and that the
party's ultimate goal is still ultimately to outlaw abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Michelman vowed that her organization, the nation's largest
abortion-rights advocacy group, would work to expose the ``great
pretenders'' in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
