<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-RDP (Hollywood) _ The Academy Awards ceremony and
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-KAZAN (Hollywood) _ Elia Kazan is presented with an
Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   SALESMAN-WITHOUT-WARES (Undated) _ Willy Loman is the world's
most famous failed salesman, but what did he sell? During the
50-year existence of ``Death of a Salesman,'' Arthur Miller's words
have entranced audiences with Willy's inflated dreams for his sons,
his affair and his suicide: all the while refusing to disclose what
Willy lugged in his valises. Willy's real wares may appear to be
inconsequential because what he sold was himself, and ultimately,
there was no demand for his product. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   DIVERSITY-POETS (Undated) _ The Academy of American Poets, a
65-year-old organization that is at the symbolic heart of the
American poetry establishment, is making what it calls significant
changes in its structure in response to criticism that it is an
elitist group, dominated by white male poets. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   FREDY-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ The subtitle of ``Fredy Neptune: A
Novel in Verse'' suggests that this suspiciously hyper-picaresque
ricochet through the hells of our century is a novel disguised as a
poem. In fact, it is a poem disguised as a novel disguised as a
poem, as written by Les Murray. Reviewed by Richard Eder.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-THEATER-REVIEW (New Haven) _ ``Working'' is a musical
about people who are never in musicals. The hard hats, cleaning
women, parking lot attendants and bricklayers portrayed in this
sweet-tempered revue are propelled from the chorus line of life
into unlikely leading roles. All get the chance in this show to
exercise their inalienable American right to life, liberty and the
pursuit of a boffo production number. Reviewed by Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   RAVEL-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ Ravel at home was small,
fastidious, and obsessively elegant in dress. Ravel also collected
figurines and porcelain ranging, his friends said, from the
discreet to the ``quite bad.'' ``L'Heure Espagnole'' and ``L'Enfant
et les Sortileges,'' which played at the New York City Opera on
Friday night, would have fit nicely on his shelves. Reviewed by
Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   BORDERLESS-BOOK-BUYING (Undated) _ Computer users in the
expanding world of electronic commerce in literature can ignore
global borders with ease. When a book published in London is
purchased from a computer attached to a desk in New York is the
sale taking place in England or the United States? What takes
precedence in defining international publisher's rights: cyberspace
or actual geography? The answers are still evolving. By Doreen
Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-FOR-GIRLS (San Francisco) _ It is hard to be small and
unknown, particularly in the CD-ROM games market. Purple Moon,
which sought and failed to make a viable business out of computer
games for girls _ games that unlike current top-sellers in the
category, were not about eyeshadow selection or nail polish tricks
_ faced an unforgiving battle for shelf space with Mattel, which
claimed six of the top 10 girls' titles last year. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   GATES-BOOK-CHAMELEON (Washington) _ Which is the real Bill
Gates? Is it the author who insists, in his new book, ``Business
(at) the Speed of Thought,'' that all inter-office communications
should flow ``over e-mail so workers can act on news with
reflex-like speed''? Or is it the witness who testified in the
government's antitrust case against his company that he could not
remember dozens of e-mail messages he wrote or received over the
last several years? By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   OUTRAGEOUS-CABLE-TV (Undated) _ The rambunctious next generation
of cable television shows owes a debt to two phenomena of recent
cable seasons: the rude and crude Comedy Central animated series
``South Park'' and the apparently bottomless popularity of
professional wrestling. Programmers are seeking to up the ante in
terms of, in their own words, the ``edginess'' and
``outrageousness'' of their new programming. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL-DESIGN (Undated) _ This has been the decade in which
software moved, big time, into the industrial designer's world. In
corporate offices across the country, engineers have been booting
up programs that let them tinker, in three dimensions, with every
permutation and combination of a product's design. It was just a
matter of time before engineers would aim their computers at
designing and refining the assembly lines on which those products
are made. And apparently, that time has come. By Claudia H.
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Protecting online privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
