<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIVERSITY-POETS-NYT &LR;      03-21 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVERSITY-POETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICIZED AS ELITIST, POETS' ORGANIZATION REVAMPS ITS STRUCTURE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)   By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Academy of American Poets, a 65-year-old
organization that is at the symbolic heart of the American poetry
establishment, is making what it calls significant changes in its
structure in response to criticism that it is an elitist group,
dominated by white male poets.
</P>
<P>
   Ten new poets have been elected to augment the academy's
nine-member board of chancellors, which oversees the awarding of
the $100,000 Tanning Prize, one of the nation's biggest literary
awards, and also has a symbolic importance with a membership that
includes many of America's best known poets. Among those elected
are three African-Americans, Yusef Komunyakaa, Lucille Clifton and
Jay Wright. ( Wright declined to serve, saying he wanted to devote
his time to his work.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Ms. Clifton, four women have been elected: Louise
Glueck, Heather McHugh, Adrienne Rich and Rosanna Warren. Also
elected were three white men: Charles Wright, Robert Creeley and
Michael Palmer. Several of the new members are known for their
experimentalism.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Jonathan Galassi, the president of the academy's
board of directors, its governing body, said, ``The difference is
now it's all over the map.'' Referring to the board of chancellors,
he said: ``There are different age groups. The board is more
representative of the many things going on in poetry today.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year two prominent poets, Maxine Kumin and Carolyn Kizer,
brought longstanding criticism of the academy to the fore when they
resigned from the board of chancellors to protest the absence of
blacks and women. The German writer Fred Viebahn, who is married to
Rita Dove, a black poet and former Poet Laureate of the United
States, criticized the academy in International Quarterly for what
he called ``unapologetic racial `purity' and gross gender
imbalance.''
</P>
<P>
   The chancellors and the board of directors met in January to
discuss ways of revamping the organization, said Bill Wadsworth,
the executive director. Questionnaires were sent out to 500 poets
and arts administrators, asking for suggestions. The directors
voted on the new chancellors early this month.
</P>
<P>
   Galassi said that broadening the organization's board of
directors was ``our next project.'' While there are 10 women on the
28-member board, there is only one black, Jamaica Kincaid.
</P>
<P>
   Galassi said in a written statement: ``All of us involved in the
academy, directors, chancellors and staff, soon came to recognize
that the controversy in which the organization was embroiled
represented an opportunity to evaluate from the ground up how it
could best carry out its mission to support and promote the work of
American poets.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chancellors will join John Ashbery, Jorie Graham, John
Hollander, Richard Howard, Donald Justice, J.D. McClatchy, W.S.
Merwin, Mark Strand and David Wagoner.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to overseeing the Tanning Prize, the board of
chancellors also gives out the academy's prestigious $20,000
fellowships.
</P>
<P>
   Normally the chancellors choose their fellow board members, but
the new members were elected on March 10 by the board of directors.
In the future the board of chancellors will continue to elect its
own members, Galassi said, but with more restrictive term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Until now chancellors have been allowed to serve for two 12-year
terms. Their terms will now be limited to six years, but they will
eligible for re-election after they have been off the board for
three years.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent the board of chancellors from becoming static, the
academy has also set up a rotation system, Wadsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Each year three chancellors whose terms are up will rotate off
the board and be replaced by three new poets.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this year three longtime chancellors, Wagoner,
Hollander and Ashbery, will retire from the board.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a change in the way the Tanning Prize is
awarded. In the past the chancellors have been criticized for
giving the prize mainly to white male poets, including one of their
own members, Merwin, in 1994, and Anthony Hecht, a chancellor
emeritus, in 1997. Ms. Rich received the prize in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Galassi said the chancellors would be ineligible to receive any
academy prize during their tenure.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellors also are being asked to take a more active role
in the organization. Until now they have not met regularly. In the
future they will be asked to meet annually.
</P>
<P>
   The academy, based in New York, was founded in 1934. In addition
to awarding prizes it sponsors readings and panels, the ``On-Line
Poetry Classroom'' and other educational programs and the Poetry
Book Club. It also coordinates National Poetry Month, which is in
April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
