<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-BOOK-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANS-ATLANTIC DRAWING POWER FOR U.S. SCANDAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash., U.K, France, Germany, Norway)   By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, England _ Lindsey Calderbank, a sales clerk at the
Stencil Store, did not really know how she felt about Monica S.
Lewinsky, or what inexorable force had propelled her across one of
Britain's biggest malls to catch a glimpse of the woman herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the interest,'' Ms. Calderbank said, straining to
find Ms. Lewinsky, the biggest celebrity to appear in Manchester
for some time, who was deep in the bowels of the County Bookshop.
``I saw one of the interviews,'' she said. ``I don't remember which
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Having metamorphosed from a voiceless cipher in the eye of a
Washington storm into an international figure on a whistle-stop
book-selling tour of Britain, Ms. Lewinsky last week drew gawkers
and book buyers wherever she went. Traveling with her own entourage
_ driver, bodyguard, publisher and publicist _ she signed and sold
some 900 books at each appearance, helping to muscle her tell-all
book, ``Monica's Story,'' to its current place at No. 1 on the
best-seller list of The Sunday Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has watched the scandal unfold from afar, with a mix of
horror and bewilderment. But the story has been so ubiquitous here
that Ms. Lewinsky has come to be viewed as the world's celebrity,
not just America's.
</P>
<P>
   David Crombie, the sales director for Michael O'Mara, the book's
British publisher, said 40,000 copies of the first printing of
100,000 copies had sold. By comparison, he said, the average first
printing of a hardcover book in Britain is 3,000 copies. ``By the
end of the tour, she will have signed 25,000 copies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the appearances, which require Ms. Lewinsky to smile,
sign and say ``thank you'' for hours at a time, seem destined to
leave her with repetitive strain injury of the mouth as well as the
hand, they appear to have gone smoothly so far. Authors on book
tours tend to be surrounded by bubbles of good will, and most of
the people Ms. Lewinsky has met have been alternately awe-struck
and supportive. (The one exception was at Harrods in London, where
the rude questions of the boisterous paparazzi caused her to burst
into tears and flee the room.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky _ who in Manchester was an eggshell-blue-suited
vision of equanimity in a sea of chaos, her hair sprayed into
submission _ remained politely sphinx-like, hoping to let the book
speak for itself. ``The interest has been phenomenal,'' said
Crombie, describing how Britons' jaws drop when they catch a
glimpse of Ms. Lewinsky strolling into a hotel or restaurant. ``She
scared the living daylights out of a guy in a lift the other day.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Lewinsky's grueling 17-day tour of Britain has her
publishers rubbing their hands in glee, her American publishers,
St. Martin's Press, do not have as much cause for elation. After a
huge initial burst of sales, ``Monica's Story'' has slipped to No.
3 from No. 1 on the New York Times best-seller list, behind books
by George Stephanopoulos and Tom Brokaw.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly because after her much-watched interview with
Barbara Walters, which sent people flocking to the stores, Ms.
Lewinsky left the United States and did not do any more publicity.
``We didn't want to oversaturate the audience,'' said John Murphy,
a spokesman for St. Martin's, a unit of Macmillian Publishers Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   But while she has been away, sales have fallen off
precipitously. At Borders, for instance, sales last Thursday were
only half of what they had been the Thursday before, said Jody
Kohn, the director of public relations for the Borders Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky was expected back in the United States Sunday, to
attend the Vanity Fair Oscar party in Los Angeles and then to do a
book signing in Century City on Monday. She was then to return to
England briefly before heading to Paris, Germany and Norway.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, Ms. Lewinsky has been given the full celebrity
treatment at every appearance, but many newspapers, frustrated at
her no-interview policy, have been snippy. Writing in The Daily
Telegraph, Vicki Woods called her a ``bubbleheaded dingbat with
California smog for brains,'' and several papers have gleefully
pointed out that ``Monica's Story'' is selling at a discount at
some stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this book is a disaster,'' Crombie said, ``give me more
disasters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
