<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARCEAU-MIME-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFORMANCE ART REVIEW: THE WIGGLE OF A FINGER SAYS A LOT
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JACK ANDERSON    
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marcel Marceau presented another program of solo
sketches on Saturday night as part of his season at the Kaye
Playhouse. The works of this great French mime can be whimsical,
farcical, bitter, sweet and bittersweet. But most of them are
gentle in tone.
</P>
<P>
   He called one of his offerings ``The Seven Deadly Sins.'' Yet
this was in no way a portrait of human beings at their most
monstrous. Most of the follies depicted in this suite, which
received its first New York performance since 1964, were mere
peccadilloes.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of the piece was evident in the way Marceau yawned,
bustled and then sank back into sloth in the laziness solo. He
mimed gobbling food and guzzling drinks at a charity dinner to
symbolize greed. Avarice was represented by a hunched-up and
supposedly meek beggar who, when out of everyone else's sight,
luxuriated in riches. Pride was a pompous chess-playing general.
Two artists of different temperaments evoked lust and envy, and
what began as a quiet automobile trip turned into a manic outing in
the anger episode.
</P>
<P>
   Marceau's ability to make even the slightest wiggle of a finger
expressive was evident in ``The Hands,'' in which, as the title
promised, his hands pointed, beckoned, implored and flew up in
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   The entire second half of the program was devoted to sketches
concerning Bip, the fellow whose big hat has a red flower growing
out of it and who serves as Marceau's equivalent of Everyman. A new
solo, ``Bip Remembers,'' had its somber moments, as Bip mimetically
looked back upon his life and our own century, gesturally recalling
war and the gesticulations of a Hitler-like demagogue. But Bip also
had memories of going to parties, embracing a beloved and riding a
merry-go-round.
</P>
<P>
   The other Bip sketches were essentially comic. Even ``Bip
Commits Suicide'' was far from distressing. In this solo, Bip did
indeed try to end his life. Yet he discovered that every method of
suicide he contemplated was either unappealing or ineffectual. Thus
he realized that if he was going to shoot himself, he had to cover
an ear so as not to be disturbed by the noise. And a supposedly
poisonous concoction he invented apparently tasted delicious when
he drank it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bip as a Baby Sitter'' found him trying to entertain some
children. The tots were invisible, but one knew from his reactions
that they could be little devils. ``Bip as a Street Musician'' made
effective use of recorded music as Marceau portrayed a violinist
whose fiddling was drowned out by a passing parade.
</P>
<P>
   Gyongyi Biro and Alexander Neander introduced each sketch by
holding a placard bearing its title. And the poses these young
mimes adopted to do so ranged from the elegant to the comical.
</P>
<P>
   Marceau's performances continue through March 28 at the Kaye
Playhouse at Hunter College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 1631EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAVEL-OPERA-REVIEW-NY     03-21 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAVEL-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY OPERA: A LOVE OF GLITTER IN WORKS BY RAVEL
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ravel at home was small, fastidious, obsessively
elegant in dress and well satisfied that visitors walking through
his rooms could find no trace, other than a piano, that he was
connected to music. Ravel also collected figurines and porcelain
ranging, his friends said, from the discreet to the ``quite bad.''
``L'Heure Espagnole'' and ``L'Enfant et les Sortileges,'' which
played at the New York City Opera on Friday night, would have fit
nicely on his shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the more graphic songs, these brief one-acters
constitute the composer's adventures into musical theater.
``L'Heure Espagnole'' is by far the thinner of the two. The
adulterous triangle of a Paisiello or Rossini comic opera is
expanded to five sides (three lovers, one husband, one wife), all
choreographed to the ticking of many clocks.
</P>
<P>
   In the Maurice Sendak-Frank Corsaro production, the Clockmaker
(ominously named Torquemada but gently played by John Lankston)
acts as a magical ringmaster, summoning his mechanical devices to
action with a wave and directing the people around him with similar
omniscience. Gonzalve the tenorial poet, done agreeably here by
Thomas Trotter, competes with the overweight charms of Don Inigo
Gomez, sung in a lovely baritone by Kevin Glavin.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Ollmann and Amy Burton take the principal parts. Both sing
with great competence and occasionally with real charm, and would
have made an even better effect without the self-referential smirks
and slightly exaggerated gestures imposed upon them.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have a hard time grasping humor that resides in the
material alone, the kind that comes through only if offered with
deadly and unimpeded seriousness. Farce played by Hamlet is funnier
than farce in the hands of clowns. Corsaro is far from excessive,
but there is just enough editorial comment in his direction to
spoil the effect.
</P>
<P>
   Sendak's set is as mild as the material he is working with:
cutouts of a Spanish cityscape and various props of mechanical
simplicity. Ravel's score, like his house, is charming, meticulous
and somewhat precious. The smoothed-over rhythms and phrygian
melody sound a little like musical Spain as Yves Saint Laurent
might market it.
</P>
<P>
   ``L'Enfant et les Sortileges'' inspires Sendak with more
ambition. Animated illustration and real people onstage collide
boldly. Cartoon flames leap around the flailing Child; clouds roll
in and out; the nursery is framed by the artist's fancifully drawn
house and trees. It is a fascinating attempt to connect the human
and the artificial, and one that needs more exploring. One day it
will truly convince the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Ravel's opera _ the story of a bad boy whose toys, pets and
books take anthropomorphic revenge for his cruelty toward them _ is
much more substantial than its companion piece. Marguerite Krull
sings passionately as the Child. Surrounding her is a parade of
dancers and singers portraying armchairs, teacups, amorous cats,
trees and birds, all presented with great musical variety.
</P>
<P>
   Both works issue from the tinselly side of Ravel's brain, the
source of his love for ornament, glitter and the tastefully
sentimental. Absent is the austere, simple Ravel, the reverential
Classicist, the one, by the way, that I prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences who tolerate whimsy well will find satisfaction in the
City Opera double bill. George Manahan leads clean and competently
played performances. The productions provoke interest. The singing
is seamlessly good if only occasionally arresting. The next
performances come on March 25 and are worth a trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 1635EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
