</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: WASH., PAKISTAN, INDIA, CHINA, U.K.)  
 CULTURE NOTES: CONSIDERING JAMES BALDWIN, SEAMUS HEANEY, HILARY
HAHN AND THE GODDESS DEVI 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By   KATHRYN   SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Choice Words
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the last year alone, James Baldwin's writings
landed on the Modern Library's list of the 100 finest
English-language novels and in New York University's picks of
20th-century American journalism classics. More recently, the
Library of Congress published a comprehensive collection of
Baldwin's oeuvre, edited by Toni Morrison. Monday night Baldwin
will become the latest in a succession of writers, including Robert
Pinsky, Dante, Mark Twain and Casanova, to be heralded by the
Manhattan Theater Club. S. Epatha Merkerson, Dael Orlandersmith and
Roger Guenveur Smith will read from Baldwin's unfliching essays on
social issues. Information: (212) 399-3030.
</P>
<P>
   Big Talkers
</P>
<P>
   Several Irish performers will bare their souls in ``From the
Heart,'' a five-day festival billed as a collaboration of music and
the spoken word, beginning Saturday at the Barbican Center in
London. Among those demonstrating a gift for gab: the Nobel
Prize-winning poet Seamus Heaney, accompanied by the uilleann piper
Liam O'Flynn, and the folk singers and storytellers Tommy Makem,
Arty McGlynn, Davy Hammond and Jean Ritchie, virtual heroes in
Northern Ireland. The finale features new artists like Kila, Iarla
O'Lionaird and Eimear Quinn, a singer who rose to fame while
dancing her way through ``Riverdance.'' Information:
011-44-171-638-8891.
</P>
<P>
   Wise Youth
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hilary Hahn has been called living proof that not all
teen-agers want to be Spice Girls. Since February, the 18-year-old
violinist has been sharing _ online _ the ups and downs of her
career with three groups of children she hopes will see her as a
mentor. In ``Hilary's Journal,'' at www.sonyclassical.com, she uses
both written entries and snapshots to describe the rigors of
traveling as a young woman in a ``very grown-up world.'' Ms. Hahn
will meet her new friends from the Computer School and P.S. 183
Monday, before heading off to tackle Stravinsky's very grown-up
Violin Concerto with the New York Philharmonic Tuesday at Avery
Fisher Hall. Information: (212) 721-6500.
</P>
<P>
   Earth Mother
</P>
<P>
   Devi, the Great Goddess of Hindu India, and her myriad
incarnations over 2,000 years can be examined through 120
sculptures and paintings at the Smithsonian's Arthur M. Sackler
Gallery in Washington, beginning on Sunday. Primarily Indian in
origin, but including examples from Nepal, China and Pakistan, the
works in ``Devi: The Great Goddess'' trace the transformation of a
prehistoric mother goddess into a deity of cosmic powers in
6th-century India, described simultaneously as ``approachable,''
``detached,'' ``benign and benevolent'' and ``most powerful.''
Information: (202) 357-2700.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
