<P>
   ECON-SUSTAIN (Des Moines) _ Improvements in workers'
productivity help to explain the central puzzle of today's economy.
Eight years into the current expansion, labor shortages and rising
wages should be raising the annual inflation rate, now only 1.7
percent. That happened in the 1980s, during the last growth cycle,
when the Consumer Price Index reached 4.6 percent. Nor are profits
suffering noticeably, despite somewhat slower gains recently. By
past standards, profits should be hurting, caught as they are
between rising pay and stagnant prices. But many corporations have
come up with numerous ways to dodge the bullet, and confound the
view, so widely shared, that inflation is an inevitable result of
sustained prosperity. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
