<HEADER>
A8637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTRAGEOUS-CABLE-TV-7     03-21 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTRAGEOUS-CABLE-TV-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EDGY AND OUTRAGEOUS FIND FAVOR ON CABLE TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Please note the use of the word ``retard,'' which may be
offensive to some readers, in the 2nd graf.) 
(lh) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the next few months, as the broadcast network channels grow
more and more congested with repeats, you may find yourself channel
surfing and running into some unusual sights and sounds on cable
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangers With Candy'' on Comedy Central is a sitcom featuring
a 46-year-old former drug addict who returns home to finish high
school, to live with her father, who is apparently already dead and
suffering from rigor mortis, and to have such adventures as being
recruited by the principal to investigate whether her lockermate is
what they call a ``retard'' passing herself off as normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asphalt Beach'' on MTV centers on life in a reform school and
stars four young men, two of whom just happen to be playing women.
``And we never own up to that,'' says Brian Graden, MTV's executive
vice president of programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy Hour'' on the USA Network is a variety-style show
starring Ahmet and Dweezil Zappa, the sons of the late avant-garde
rock performer Frank Zappa, and features games and sing-along
competitions among guest stars like Christopher Darden, a
prosecutor of O.J. Simpson, warbling ``Louie, Louie'' and guessing
whether a close-up picture is of a rock star or a rodent.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the rambunctious next generation of cable television
shows. It is a generation of programming that owes a debt to two
phenomena of recent cable seasons: the rude and crude Comedy
Central animated series ``South Park,'' which for a time was the
most successful entertainment series on any cable channel, and the
apparently bottomless popularity, on three separate cable channels,
of professional wrestling, with its various programs accounting for
21 of the top 25 shows on all cable channels in the February sweeps
period.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for shows that can feed off the ground-breaking (and
chair-breaking) tone of these genres, cable television programmers
are seeking to up the ante in terms of, in their own words, the
``edginess'' and ``outrageousness'' of their new programming.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, they are rewriting the old rules of television
program development, forgetting the tried-and-true method of
writers, backed by studio money, pitching ideas to network
development executives, in favor of new approaches like scouring
the Internet, independent film festivals and alternative books and
magazines. They are also on the alert for shows rejected by the
broadcast networks for pushing the issues of taste and content
beyond their limits.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to build the kind of audience base that brings in
advertising revenue. For channels like MTV Networks, which is owned
by Viacom Inc., and Comedy Central, owned by Time Warner Inc. and
Viacom, the concentration of young affluent viewers often results
in advertisers paying a premium above what they would normally pay
for the same-size audience. MTV, for example, is the leading cable
channel among viewers between 18 and 34 in homes with more than
$75,000 in income. Comedy Central is second.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central, with an audience 60 percent male, another
attraction to many advertisers, is also advancing an argument,
based on what the channel calls ``attentive studies'' that comedy
viewers pay more attention to shows they watch because they are
listening for punch lines and are ready to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The new cable strategy is built around the desire to capture the
allegiance of an audience that more and more is asking programmers
to, as Stephen Chao, the president of programming for the USA
Network, put it, ``Freak me out with the unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: ``The Man Show,'' the upcoming series that Comedy
Central is most bullish on, a comedy-sketch show with an audience
that celebrates the most basic (as in the root word ``base'') side
of the male gender. That means go-go girls in the audience, a video
with one of the hosts asking women in the street of all ages if
they will have sex with him, numerous references to flatulence, and
various shots of sexy women jumping on trampolines with their
skirts flying up.
</P>
<P>
   Does that sound like wrestling? Eileen Katz, Comedy Central's
head of programming, hopes so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is working in wrestling,'' Ms. Katz said. ``We think
`The Man Show' can exploit the same sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Chao, whose USA network owns about half of the growing cable
wrestling franchise, would like nothing better than to develop
entertainment shows that take advantage of what he called, ``this
diamond in our own backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Chao said: ``Wrestling is great populist entertainment. No one
has successfully leveraged off its strength.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But he would like to, both on the USA Network and its sister
cable channel Sci-Fi. Ms. Chao cited an upcoming show for the
Sci-Fi Channel called ``Metropolis'' (two cops investigate
paranormal and absurd crimes, but in the video verite style of
``Cops''), which is being created by Jason Hightman, a writer of
feature films, and Spike Jonze, the director of music videos for
the Beastie Boys, Weezer and the Breeders.
</P>
<P>
   Chao also mentioned ``GvsE'' for USA, which is an offbeat take
on the fight of good versus evil featuring a resurrected cop. That
one is ``completely different from anything I've seen on TV,'' and
has ``a Tarantino quality,'' Chao said _ referring to Quentin
Tarantino, the ``Pulp Fiction'' director. ``I like the idea of
putting Tarantino next to wrestling. People would get it, that
contemporary rambunctiousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central does not have wrestling, but it does have ``South
Park,'' the almost toxically irreverent cartoon series, which
instantly became the signature show for the channel when it went on
the air in the fall of 1997. The show did more than bring viewers
to Comedy Central; it defined the channel, or, in network executive
parlance, it ``branded'' it.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Katz described it, Comedy Central is now totally about
maintaining that brand image, one she said is based on ``attitude
and comic sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never do `Frasier' or `Everybody Loves Raymond,''' Ms.
Katz said, though she acknowledged that these shows, which make
millions for their broadcast networks and have audiences each week
comparable to what a Comedy Central series might attract in a month
or perhaps a year, are indeed successful at delivering ``comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   She simply said that in itself would not be enough for Comedy
Central, which demands attitude with comedy. But she denied that
her channel was considering changing its name to ``Attitude
Central.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``The Man Show'' added to ``South Park'' and such other
coming fare as a new game show called ``Versus'' which pairs rocket
scientists against body piercers, bikers against soccer moms, and
cowboys against Indians (real ones from India) in a quiz format,
the ``comic sensibility'' of the channel might be best defined as
young and exceedingly male.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Katz said there were Comedy Central shows that had
substantial female viewership but, at least where comedy is
concerned, ``If you're talking about trend setters and taste
makers, it's that generation and that gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Before ``South Park,'' of course, another animated series
emerged as a hit for MTV in the early 1990s: ``Beavis and
Butthead.'' Graden was not at MTV then but he had a deep personal
connection to ``South Park.'' He was the executive who first
identified the talent of the show's creators, Trey Parker and Matt
Stone, and commissioned them to create an animated Christmas card,
which Graden sent out to friends in the entertainment industry.
That led to the deal with Comedy Central, for the series, which
originally listed Graden as an executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   Now ensconced at MTV, Graden said he intended to rewrite the
rules for developing shows.
</P>
<P>
   Graden said his approach was to look for shows that came from
``natural sources rather than from process sources.'' As an
example, he cites how a performer named Jackie Beat came to star in
``Asphalt Beach'' playing one of the female leads. ``He is a drag
queen we saw in a short independent film and we put him together
with a couple of writers named Peter and Tom Spears, '' Graden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposed MTV series, ``Sifl and Olly,'' is a
relationship comedy starring two sock puppets. Shows like this do
not come from pitches or deals with agents, Graden said. Instead
they come out of an idiosyncratic system at MTV that relies on
``two people whose job it is to be scavengers.''
</P>
<P>
   These two scavenger executives, who were hired by MTV's senior
vice president for original series, John Miller, have been charged
with screening independent films, surfing the Internet, reading
books and magazines by the scores seeking to identify people and
ideas that might be turned into television shows. One of these
executives, Kim Carranza, Graden labeled ``someone with just a
groovy bent on things''; the other, Drew Tappon, he called ``a
culturally obsessed person.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his own approach, Chao said, ``What I'd like to do
is break the patterns.'' He is the same executive who earlier in
his career broke several patterns and barriers by creating shows
like ``Cops'' and ``America's Most Wanted'' for News Corp.'s Fox
network as well as the game show, ``Studs,'' for syndication.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Katz at Comedy Central may have the best definition of
what it is these cable networks are looking for in this new form of
television series. ``I think we're looking for voices that say what
the network's point of view is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, ``The Man Show,'' a series originally developed and
ultimately rejected by ABC _ one clear reason for the bullishness
about it at Comedy Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled that ABC was not willing to do the show,'' Ms.
Katz said. ``But it does show me that they're getting closer on our
tail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
