<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, March 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Windswept rain will cover most of New England early Monday as
strengthening low pressure moves north through upstate New York.
Wind gusts over 50 miles an hour from the southeast will lead to
areas of coastal flooding in eastern New England on Monday morning.
In far northern Maine, an icy mixture will fall until late Monday,
when the precipitation will become all snow.
</P>
<P>
   To the west and south of the storm center, colder air will surge
into the interior Northeast and Middle Atlantic States on strong
winds from the northwest. Periods of snow will linger most of the
day over western New York and the mountains of northern New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, snow showers will dust areas near the eastern
Great Lakes and central Appalachians. Meanwhile, clouds will break
east of the Appalachians in the Middle Atlantic region.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will have ample sunshine with afternoon
temperatures near or below the seasonal average. A few clouds will
linger along the southern Appalachians as well as near the east
coast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Patchy rain will develop across the central Plains as a
fast-moving disturbance streaks east from the Rockies. A bit of wet
snow is expected from along the northern periphery of the
precipitation from eastern Wyoming to northern Nebraska. Farther
south, scattered showers will develop in central Texas and Oklahoma
late Monday and Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, interior sections will be mainly dry and mild. A
front with showers and intermittent mountain snow will reach the
coast from northern California to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Gusty Trades
</P>
<P>
   Winds that reached 30 to 50 mph in some areas swept across
Hawaii at the weekend. The unusual winds resulted from
intensification of the normal trade winds that bring steady breezes
to the island chain which average 20 miles an hour. The
northeasterly trade winds in Hawaii are consequence of the
clockwise circulation around the permanent high-pressure area that
girdles the globe around 30 degrees of latitude from the equator.
This past weekend, weak low pressure south of Hawaii combined with
high pressure to the north to enhance the pressure difference that
energizes the tropical trade winds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 1759EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DETOX-RAWFOOD21-COX     03-21 1628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETOX-RAWFOOD21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Health the hard way
 &HT;    WITH DETOX-WHEATGRASS
 &HT;    By Julie Bonin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Who would have thought the road to health would
lead here, down a rural blacktop lined with mobile homes and rustic
homesteads in Bastrop County?
</P>
<P>
   But this is where people are coming, from all over the world,
for a nutritional and spiritual body purge called cellular
detoxification.
</P>
<P>
   At Optimum Health Institute, students are paying $600 to $700 a
week for an a spalike antidote to a toxic world.
</P>
<P>
   Name your poison: chemicals and preservatives in food and
cosmetics; diets heavy in fat and drained of important enzymes;
pollutants in the air, water and soil; spiritually bereft,
stressed-out lives.
</P>
<P>
   All of it leaves our bodies full of toxins, or so goes the
theory that spawned the first Optimum Health Institute 25 years ago
in California.
</P>
<P>
   Since a USA Today reporter, a cancer survivor, wrote about her
experiences at the Central Texas spa in a story that appeared last
month, CBS and ABC camera crews have been descending on the usually
peaceful place. The British Broadcasting Corp. is reportedly
planning a visit.
</P>
<P>
   But OHI, established two years ago, isn't well-known here.
Clients come to the 30-bed nonprofit facility from all over the
world, probably fewer than 10 percent from Texas, says director
Judith Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   Participants _ about 22 check in each week _ typically fall into
three categories: people who are very sick, people who want to lose
weight, and people who want to stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The carefully controlled program isn't for everyone. The diet
revolves around wheatgrass juice, plates full of raw vegetables, or
juices made from the juiced remains of those plates full of
uncooked veggies.
</P>
<P>
   Think ears of corn straight from the shuck, fermented foods like
sauerkraut and something called seed cheese. Even the fruit juice
is unconventional: a glass of watermelon juice served for breakfast
includes the pulverized rind. The system-cleansing regime includes
daily enemas and colon therapy, classes on basic human biology
(taught by a registered nurse) and instruction in meditation and
other techniques designed to enhance the body's ability to heal
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Walden, 75, came to Optimum Health Institute wanting a
fresh start on feeling better. Walden, a silver-haired woman in a
pale periwinkle blouse, sat outside reading Cosmopolitan magazine
in a rocking chair at the facility OHI one February day.
</P>
<P>
   Three of her friends were supposed to come with her, but they
backed out, Walden says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mentioned the enemas and for some strange reason they just
dropped me like a fly,'' said Walden, who lives in Colorado and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they have done battle with cancer, are dealing with
health problems such as arthritis or diabetes, or are just trying
to feel better, it seems safe to say that everyone enrolled in the
program believes that eating a traditional American diet, taking
nutritional supplements and exercising is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   It's a message retired Presbyterian minister Russell Nees has
been preaching for much of his life. Nees, 69, helped his brother
Bob Nees open the original Optimum Health Institute in San Diego
more than two decades ago. Russell Nees was teaching classes on
expanded consciousness, and he and his brother were exploring
natural healing techniques when they learned about a
then-Boston-based program called the Hippocrates Health Institute.
</P>
<P>
   That program, devoted to teaching its students how to rid their
bodies body of toxins, inspired the Neeses' institute. OHI also
emphasizes the importance of the mind-body connection, says Nees,
who leads classes in meditation and biofeedback and credits the
diet with helping him beat a disabling case of angina.
</P>
<P>
   Nees, frequently seen pedaling around the grounds on a bicycle,
is the institute's spiritual guide. He often leads the healing
circles that precede meals, and emphasizes a connection between the
institute' s OHI diet and biblical teachings.
</P>
<P>
   After his wife Mary Helon was diagnosed with cancer and given
three months to live, she committed to the detox diet for two years
and was declared cancer-free, Nees says. Her death last year was
unrelated to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Though he and other staff members offer testimonials on the OHI
regime, the institute _ which draws clients mostly from word of
mouth and limited advertising _ makes no claims of curing anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in competition with the medical profession,'' Nees
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a clinic at all. We're a school and a health spa.''
</P>
<P>
   But does any of this really work?
</P>
<P>
   Terry Shaw, a licensed dietitian and nutrition professor at
Austin Community College, has known people who've followed a raw
food regime and seemed to benefit as long as they followed the
diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't overlook the success some people have had,'' Shaw
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scientific realm, there's not much to validate it or
refute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every theory can find a line of research to back it up.
However, some recent research has shown that nutrients may be more
easily assimilated from slightly cooked foods than from raw. Some
raw foods, Shaw says, actually inhibit the assimilation of
nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   The program's reliance on daily enemas and colon therapy also
raises questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just washing out your colon has no therapeutic advantages,''
says gastroenterologist Tom McHorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good, healthy diet certainly won' t hurt anybody. I'm not
aware of any research showing this as being beneficial or really
detoxifying the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before spending your money, you'd like to know that this is
scientifically useful. You'd like some proof that it works, other
than hearsay.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellular detox is not sanctioned by many practitioners of
conventional, traditional medicine. And because it's a school, the
facility is not state-regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, the concept of cellular detox has caught on
among people interested in natural healing .
</P>
<P>
   ``Their bodies are breaking down, they feel bad, they start
reading publications or on the Internet that detox is a big part of
staying healthy,'' says Harry Lipp, a massage therapist who helps
customers choose vitamins and herbal supplements at Whole Foods.
</P>
<P>
   Those who aren't ready to commit to programs like OHI's are
picking up products. Companies are pitching everything from bathing
salts to herbal laxatives, all in the name of soothing bodies
reeling from toxicity.
</P>
<P>
   Austinite Henley Green, 33, began reading about the immune
system after back-to-back bouts with the flu a few years ago. She
had tried to detox on her own, but ``couldn't seem to do it,'' and
then heard about the spa in Bastrop County. After a week there,
Green, a freelance wardrobe consultant for films, was still having
a hard time getting the wheatgrass juice down. But she felt so well
and rested that she decided to stay another week, and had even
enticed her mother to experience it with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place, to me, feels very calming,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   To Walden, the stay at the spa was an energizer. She'd tried
fasting and had eliminated red meat from her diet, and was
intrigued with the idea of a program that was experiential,
something she could learn and practice at home.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of her third week at the institute, Walden said
she felt rejuvenated and better than she had in a long while. She'd
lost a few pounds. Certainly her energy didn't flag during
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody would just sew my mouth shut at 6 p.m. _ that long
evening is what gets to me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually eat very fast,'' she continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you're going to eat a plate of raw food fast.
You'd strangle to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatively healthy people like Walden and Green are advised to
stick to the detox diet for two or three months. A less-restrictive
maintenance diet (occasional cooked food, meat and dairy) follows.
</P>
<P>
   Those with ``health challenges'' (the word ``disease'' has been
banished by the positive-thought devotees here) are encouraged to
stick to the raw food regime for at least four to six several
months, Connelly says.
</P>
<P>
   The OHI kitchen is locked at night, and guests are asked not to
bring in contraband food, ``but there's no Gestapo that's going to
follow you around,'' says Connelly, who trained horses before
coming to work at the spa. ``If you want to go off and eat
someplace, no one is going to say one word. This is a
take-responsibility-for-your-health place.''
</P>
<P>
   Weeklong guests learn to grow their own wheatgrass, those who
stay two weeks learn to sprout their own seeds, and three-week
guests spend much of their time preparing OHI recipes in a
stove-free kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   But once back in the real world, sticking to the diet proves too
big a challenge for many students, Connelly says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people do a week or two and come back in six months
to clean up their act,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what students are told at OHI is information they've
heard somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eat right, get some exercise,'' says Lou Ann King, a nurse and
colon therapist who teaches at the institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know this stuff. The problem is we don't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But people ready to make a drastic change in diet and lifestyle
in the name of health are hoping the Optimum Health Institute OHI
will help put them on the right path.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any magic bullet here,'' King tells her
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not some magic bullet in a sprout bulb that we dole
out to every 10th person. If there is a magic bullet, you have it
inside of you. All we do is give you the tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
