<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Get it down one way or another'
 &HT;    By Julie Bonnin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Wheatgrass, lovingly tended and ground into
jade-green juice, is a cornerstone of the Optimum Health
Institute's OHI's program.
</P>
<P>
   Director Judith Connelly says the spa's OHI's wheatgrass,
continually serenaded in the greenhouse by classical music, is
``unusually sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone can stomach the chlorophyll-rich liquid food,
which tastes something like the distilled essence of newly mown
grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have people who gag when they pass by the juicing room,''
Connelly says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just encourage them to get it down. It's so desperately
important to the process. People need to get it down one way or
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   At OHI, they don't just drink wheatgrass, rich in vitamins,
minerals, enzymes and amino acids. Here and elsewhere, it's touted
as an externally applied tonic for everything from stuffy noses to
hair loss.
</P>
<P>
   Students are taught and encouraged to grow their own wheatgrass,
though the institute also ships fresh sprouts for juicing to those
who don' t.
</P>
<P>
   Powdered and tablet forms are sold at natural food stores. One
company is marketing its wheatgrass products as ``the perfect
survival food in the face of Y2K and other millennial surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
