<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8648 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCOVERIES22-COX     03-21 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCOVERIES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Physicists to mark a century of feats
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the 10,000 physicists attending the world's
biggest physics meeting ever in Atlanta this week, it will be a
time to remember.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting marks the 100th anniversary of the American Physical
Society. To commemorate it, numerous sessions at the weeklong
meeting will focus on the milestones of physics during the past
century and offer new insights on how they came to be.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight at the Georgia World Congress Center, Energy Secretary
William Richardson will help unveil a giant time-line wall chart
developed by the APS: ``A Century of Physics.'' At 23 feet long and
4 feet high and consisting of 11 panels, the time line is a work of
art and a permanently open textbook and photo album covering the
last 100 years in physics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time line will serve as a gift from the (APS) to more than
20,000 high schools, colleges and universities throughout the
country, as well as hundreds of research laboratories, museums,
libraries and corporate offices,'' says Brian Schwartz of the APS.
</P>
<P>
   The chart was planned in 1995 to celebrate the APS's 100th
birthday. Emory University physicist Sidney Perkowitz assembled a
database of more than 1,000 scientific events, from which he chose
130 for a series of posters that became the time line. One section
of the wall chart covers physics on the ``cosmic scale,'' telling
the story of the quest to understand the universe. Another deals
with physics on the ``atomic scale,'' the submicroscopic world of
atoms and quarks, the tiniest particles of matter known to science.
</P>
<P>
   The bedrock of modern physics, the wall chart notes, was
developed during this century _ Albert Einstein's theory of general
relativity, which explains gravity; his theory of special
relativity, which deals with the relationship between space and
time; and the development of quantum mechanics, which governs the
interactions of protons, neutrons and electrons.
</P>
<P>
   Those stunning advances helped pave the way for developments
such as nuclear energy, computers, lasers and rocketry. Einstein's
theories helped scientists understand the big bang that created the
universe some 15 billion years ago; the expansion of the universe;
and the discovery of mind-boggling structures such as neutron
stars, black holes and galactic clusters.
</P>
<P>
   During this week's meeting, scientists will recount these
developments in more than 30 symposiums and discuss what scientists
are still struggling to understand and discover. The symposiums
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Search for the Ultimate Structure of Matter.''
Scientists will discuss what is known _ and unknown _ about the
point at which matter ceases to exist and becomes pure energy.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Einstein's Legacy.'' Scientists will discuss new insights
into gravity. Researchers want to know, for instance, if there is
enough matter in the universe for gravity to eventually halt the
expansion of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Impact of the Laser on Contemporary Physics.'' The laser
is nearly 40 years old and continues to have enormous impact in
physics and fields such as electronics, medicine and chemistry. A
look at the technology of light, and what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
