<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN22-COX     03-21 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer advocate's office would serve Georgia as well as Texas
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the final analysis, it wasn't Gov. Roy Barnes' bold
initiative to impose liability on managed care companies _ which
only two other states have _ that faced the greatest obstacles in
the Legislature. It was Senate Bill 200, the legislation to create
an office of insurance consumer advocate. The governor caved in to
supplemental insurance carriers (who also happen to be campaign
donors) and to legislators in the property and casualty business.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm still willing to bet the new independent consumer office
will serve the people well, especially in health care disputes.
That has certainly been the case in Texas, one of a handful of
states that have an independent insurance consumer office. That
office reported saving consumers $1.9 billion last year in proposed
industry-wide rate increases, and $65 million in individual company
increases. Of course, those figures are exaggerated in that the
insurance commissioner probably wouldn't have granted all of them.
</P>
<P>
   The most important job of the new consumer office will be to
collect and analyze data for rate hearings so the commissioner has
more than the insurance company's ``side'' to consider. Of course,
the counsel can intervene in lawsuits on behalf of classes of
consumers as well.
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly important in Georgia, where the
commissioner relies largely on the industry for campaign donations,
some $1.5 million in the recent re-election of Commissioner John
Oxendine. Whether that affects the commissioner's judgment or not,
there's a public perception that the consumer has little voice.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hunter, a former Texas insurance commissioner, said the
Georgia commissioner should welcome the new office. It's
impossible, he said to act as an advocate for the people and a
judge on proposed industry rate increases. Hunter supported the
legislation Texas lawmakers approved to create a similar ``Office
of Public Insurance Counsel'' in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter is an insurance actuary by profession. He now heads the
insurance division of the Consumer Federation of America, and
admits he was more inclined to listen to consumer complaints as
commissioner than some of his predecessors. But the industry also
profited from the advocate's office, he said. ``Having professional
data from both sides in front of me resulted many times in
decisions that were more favorable to the insurance companies than
looking at just one side might have allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Though opponents of the consumer advocate office won't admit it,
a professional advocate actually helps prevent decision-making on
the basis of emotional individual stories. The advocate collects
data to determine whether an abuse is based on facts or is
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   During the current Texas legislative session, lawmakers asked
the consumer office to investigate whether insurance companies are
following a law that requires them to give reasons for denial or
non-renewal. Lawmakers will examine data from the companies and
from the consumer office to see if the law needs tightening. If the
consumer office can't get the data, the committee will be asking
the companies why not. That's just one example of how the office
spurs openness and better enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the proposed Georgia office, which will depend on the
general fund, the Texas office is funded by a nickel charge on
every insurance policy. Although consumers would willingly throw in
an extra nickel for such, the state insurance lobby isn't likely
ever to let such a ``radical'' notion surface under Georgia's Gold
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is on the editorial board of The Atlanta Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
