<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX     03-21 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hit with right hook(er)
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A former hooker has come up with a novel line of work that could
be coming to a street corner near you.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Hotaling, according to the New York Times, helped found
the world's first ``john school'' where she is paid to humiliate
and frighten men caught trying to buy sex from street walkers.
</P>
<P>
   Her partners in this thriving new business are the cops and
prosecutors who used to bust her for selling her services on San
Francisco's streets.
</P>
<P>
   Now rather than getting arrested for taking money to pleasure
johns, or customers, she is being paid by the cops to torment johns
in a form of hooker-aversion therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the years when she shivered on street corners trying to
pick up customers, nowadays Hotaling's johns are rounded up for her
by San Francisco's finest who, decked out in spiked heels and just
enough spandex to hide their badges, do the street-corner
shivering.
</P>
<P>
   In a way the johns are still paying for Hotaling's services
because their $500 fines must more than cover the cost of San
Francisco's First Offender Prostituiton Program, which is being
credited with sharp reductions in the city's outdoor sex trade.
</P>
<P>
   According toTimes writer Evelyn Nieves, four SFPD decoy hookers
and a dozen backup officers arrested 43 johns in only four hours on
a slow night. Virturally every man arrested chose john school over
prosecution, according to Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   Big bucks city
</P>
<P>
   That's $20,000 right there if 40 men took the daylong class
rather than have their arrest premanently recorded.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, 2,181 men opted to take the class. Of
those, records show only 18 were re-arrested and prosecuted for
attempting to buy sex outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's indoor sex trade evidently is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   The reason this new line of work for former prostitutes could be
coming to a street corner near you is because all the nation's best
fads start out in California, except those invented by Al Gore, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, perhaps Gore invented the Internet during a visit to
California.
</P>
<P>
   A more likely reason that Hotaling's program could spread to
communities across the country is because cops, prosecutors and
city officials like it. No doubt former prostitutes who get paid to
shout ``I hated you!'' at the johns also like it.
</P>
<P>
   Already, according to Nieves, Las Vegas, Fresno, Toronto and
Nashville have come up with similar john schools.
</P>
<P>
   Last month 45 officials from Pittsburgh, Washington, D.C.;
Seattle, Portland, Ore.; Jacksonville, Fla., St. Paul, Minn. and
Springfield, Mo., traveled to San Francisco to study the program
modeled on all-day traffic schools where traffic scofflaws can keep
their tickets off their driving records.
</P>
<P>
   I've attended bad-boy (and bad-girl) traffic school, but it was
not a daylong humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   TheTimes story reported that the ex-hookers hurled insults at
the men in the john school. ``I wanted to stick a knife in you!''
one former prostitute shouted at an old man so hard that the
startled man knocked the glasses off his face.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors lectured the men on the soliciting law. The men were
shown close-up color slides of the effects of venereal disease. The
men received more lectures from police officers and residents and
business owners of neighborhoods tormented by prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants street walkers ruining his neighborhood. And
attacking the demand side of the problem, the johns, makes sense in
fighting prostitution just as it should make sense in fighting
illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing is certain, prostitution isn't called the world's
oldest profession for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCOVERIES22-COX     03-21 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCOVERIES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Physicists to mark a century of feats
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the 10,000 physicists attending the world's
biggest physics meeting ever in Atlanta this week, it will be a
time to remember.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting marks the 100th anniversary of the American Physical
