<P>
   HAITI-FUTURE _ PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ With American taxpayers
more than $2 billion in the hole when it comes to Haiti, a growing
number of Congressmen are increasingly concerned about the
effectiveness of U.S. aid to the h00emisphere's poorest country.
But as Haiti faces its worst political crisis since a U.S.-led
force restored the democratic process there in 1994, what could
make aid more effective? Many Haiti watchers argue aid should be
more focused on rural areas, noting that only 7 percent of U.S. aid
now goes to rural areas, home to two-thirds of Haiti's population.
Still others argue that all aid should be cut off except emergency
food aid. Bottom line: Whatever the solution, U.S. policy toward
Haiti cannot continue as it now stands. (Emling, Cox News Service)
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With GRAPHICS (Made available by The Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-HANDICAPPED _ PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ Extremely shy,
Maderges is the type of child who greets strangers by turning her
head. Nine years old, she's of the age when typical American girls
might be enjoying soccer, cooking, or playing with Barbie dolls.
But she's not like American girls. Born with no arms, and born in
Haiti -- the hemisphere's poorest country -- Maderges was abandoned
by her parents0 when s he was three months old. But, fortunately,
she was deposited at the front door of the privately funded St.
Vincent's School for Handicapped Children, the only place in this
Caribbean country that takes care of children with disabilities. At
the school, a dilapidated building that looks more like an old
motel, she has learned to accept the challenges of her disability
by using her feet -- to eat, to write and to dress. Developing.
(Emling, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With GRAPHICS: Made available by The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
