<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NAIA-LIFE-COX     03-21 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NAIA-LIFE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life University coach appreciates run of success
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All the way down to the minute before his team began
Sunday's practice in preparation for tonight's 8 o'clock appearance
against favored Mobile (Ala.) in the NAIA National Championship
game in Tulsa, Okla., Life University coach Roger Kaiser was still
raving about the run of success his suburban Atlanta team has had
during a push toward its second national title in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that this team entered the tournament unseeded and
saddled with the worst regular-season record in the eight-year
history of the program. After posting a 77-71 upset of No. 7-seeded
Azusa Pacific (27-6) Saturday night in a semifinal-round game, the
Running Eagles (28-10) are in the finals for the third time in six
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it amazing? This has been an incredible run for us _ no
matter what happens,'' Kaiser said.
</P>
<P>
   Life, beaten at home by Auburn-Montgomery in the Southeast
Regionals 10 days ago, had to depend on an at-large bid to make the
32-team tournament. But in its first game last Wednesday, Kaiser's
squad knocked off No. 11-seeded Faulkner (Ala.) State 64-58.
</P>
<P>
   Then Thursday night, while Kaiser was in a Tulsa hospital
recuperating from kidney stone surgery, the Running Eagles, with
assistant John Barrett in charge, registered an 87-74 upset of No.
6-seeded Oklahoma City, a team that had beaten Life twice in
previous Final Four appearances.
</P>
<P>
   With Kaiser back in the lead chair Friday night, guard Corey
Evans, a 6-1 junior from Cocoa, Fla., and forward Derrick Shaw, a
6-1 junior from Pearson, continued to lead the way to victory _ as
the Eagles fought from a 16-point halftime deficit to defeat
Concordia (Calif.), 83-67.
</P>
<P>
   With Life down by nine with seven minutes left against Asuza
Pacific Saturday night, Evans responded with eight of his
career-high 35 points en route to the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't stop Evans. He just went off tonight,'' Asuza
Pacific coach Bill Odell lamented after his team's loss.
</P>
<P>
   While Shaw, despite his size, has dominated the boards,
indicated by 12 and 13 rebounds in the first and fourth tournament
games, Evans has scored 99 points. His 24.9 point average in the
tournament is 10.5 points higher than his regular-season average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evans has been unbelievable,'' Kaiser said. ``But everybody on
the team has stepped up when they had to. It's a bunch that has
come together and shown a lot of deternination.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Mobile (32-2), which was ranked No. 4 in the nation the
first week in March, Life will again be an underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're big and they're quick,'' Kaiser said of the
Rams. ``But it's great for us to be in the championship against
them. If we can keep playing as well as we have since we've been
here, we've got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Life, which suffered a 99-81 loss to Oklahoma City in the '94
finals, won the NAIA national title in '97 with a 73-64 victory
over Oklahoma Baptist in the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
