<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8659 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS-MIDSEASON-C     03-21 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-MIDSEASON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks progressing at halfway point
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a fragile team, one in which the parts appear to
exceed the sum of the whole. Fresh faces, lockout hangover, injury,
bad habits among old hands. All of that.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do the Hawks rate at the midpoint of this abbreviated
season? Could be better or marginally worse. Be nice _ give them a
C.
</P>
<P>
   The good part is that they appear headed to better days. When
Pete Babcock, Lenny Wilkens and Stan Kasten put this team together,
they moved with one eye on today and the other on tomorrow. It
isn't simply desirable that the Hawks start to peak next fall in
their first year at the Philips Arena; it's mandatory, with all
those luxury boxes and club seats and the ordinary seats filled
with people who want a good time. That means more than the arena's
sophisticated video equipment. It means winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be a better team next year,'' Wilkens said, ``because
we'll have a full training camp and because we'll know one
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Dikembe Mutombo said, ``It's gotten to the point where
every year a few of us walk in and all we see are new faces. How
can you play together when guys don't know each other?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the bosses would argue logically that they feel an
obligation to field the 12 best players they can find within the
salary cap. And with as many as four draft picks possible, plus a
$4.4 million trade exception, look for more change next season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the modest record, it is clear that management has moved
this club forward. And if injury and unfamiliarity among players
has brought confusion over the first 25 games, it's a price the
organization is willing to pay for progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would take 20 games,'' Wilkens said. ``I thought
it would take at least that long for us to come together. We did it
in pieces, but we also had a few setbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season, the reserves gave back leads carved out by
the starters. So Wilkens cut short his rotations.
</P>
<P>
   When Steve Smith went out for six games with a sprained right
knee and Alan Henderson sat four games with back spasms, the
coach's hand was forced. Young Anthony Johnson and Roshown McLeod
got their chance. When McLeod got sick, Chris Crawford got to play.
Then LaPhonso Ellis suffered his rib-cage injury, giving Lenny's
Kids more time. For veteran swingman Ty Corbin, too. When Ed Gray
went south, Corbin stepped in and made half his shots over a span
of eight games.
</P>
<P>
   But the starters also faltered. Mutombo only now is emerging
from his lockout-induced haze, rebounding and blocking shots with
better timing and focus. Henderson has had brilliant moments and
some sour ones. A free agent then, he did not play ball during the
lockout, fearing injury. His good efforts have tended to come in
alternate games. Mookie Blaylock tends to stand around, pound the
ball and take ugly long shots that miss. He admits he is at his
best coming off a pick, catching a pass from Smith and shooting in
rhythm. Why don't the Hawks do that more often?
</P>
<P>
   On defense, why don't they always make those crisp rotations,
forcing shooters to give up the ball? Why do they sometimes defend
the pick-and-roll as though they've never seen it?
</P>
<P>
   Lack of intensity, absence of energy, new faces. And remember,
they were away from the game for about eight months. That's what's
wrong league-wide. Utah might be an exception. The Hawks are not.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for Grant Long, it would be far worse.
</P>
<P>
   Long, in his second tour with the team, was the last member of
the 12-man roster to sign a contract. If you factor out the
statistics and only look at the plays that turn games around, Long
is the most valuable player on the team, the deciding factor in at
least six victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love Grant Long,'' Babcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks sold Long and Stacy Augmon to Detroit for draft picks
so they could open cap room for Mutombo. They are not about to let
him get away again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say we want to keep Grant here for the
foreseeable future,'' Babcock said.
</P>
<P>
   There's stability for you.
</P>
<P>
   HAWKS REPORT CARD
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE: D
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks are among the lowest-scoring teams in the league.
Outside shooting often is a disaster, with Blaylock and Gray
struggling. The team does not have enough passing, ranking near the
bottom in assists.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE: B
</P>
<P>
   Long and Johnson join Mutombo in forming a much-stronger weapon.
Improved switching is holding down shooters. The press is
potentially the team's best since the days when Mike Fratello was
coach.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDING: B
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo and Long are strong, but Henderson is lacking. On
offense, the numbers look good because the shooting is so bad. On
defense, with Mutombo, it's a staple.
</P>
<P>
   STARTERS: C+
</P>
<P>
   They tend to stand around but are making strides.
</P>
<P>
   BENCH: B
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start, the subs are coming on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
