<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8662 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-NYT     03-21 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: FOR MILOSEVIC, A LAST CHANCE TO PEACEFUL SOLUTION
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-U.S. and KOSOVO-ASSESS) 
(ms) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ By preference and habit, Slobodan
Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, has always waited until the last
moment before revealing his real bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   In the bloody game of chicken that is now the Kosovo crisis,
Washington and NATO want Milosevic to believe the last moment is
here _to understand that both his options and his time to choose
one of them are limited.
</P>
<P>
   But reading Milosevic's mind is never easy for Washington, since
the preservation of his power comes first, before patriotism or the
welfare of his people. And a pure ultimatum that says capitulate or
get clobbered is not likely to produce a deal, some Serbian and
Western officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Of all his Western interlocutors, Milosevic is said to put most
trust in the American, Richard C. Holbrooke, who is headed here
Monday for what Washington calls a last chance for a peaceful
solution before the bombing begins.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs feel Holbrooke at least understands that peace in the end
requires compromise and face-saving, especially given the
importance of Kosovo, site of the finest Serbian Orthodox monuments
and their greatest historic battle, for Serbian tradition and
national myth.
</P>
<P>
   But Serbian officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, are
concerned that Holbrooke will arrive from Washington with limited
instructions and little ability to negotiate, and that his mission
is really designed to placate nervous NATO allies more than to stop
bloodshed. Milosevic understands that NATO's bombers can do him and
his military great harm. But he also understands that NATO is still
divided, with its credibility on the line just ahead of its 50th
anniversary celebration in Washington next month.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has heard congressional doubts from Washington about
the wisdom of American policy, and he has heard doubts from other
NATO countries over what might amount to a NATO declaration of war
against a sovereign state dealing with an internal insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   And Milosevic understands, a senior Western official suggested,
that once bombing starts _ marking the failure of the threat of
force as a diplomatic tool _ NATO loses considerable control over
what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Milosevic does not comply, does NATO keep bombing?'' asked
a Belgrade journalist, Ljiljana Smajlovic, no fan of Milosevic.
``And if bombing fails, will NATO have to invade? I don't agree
with this notion that just a little bombing will be enough to get
him to comply.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is also exercising a degree of care in his military
operations in Kosovo, senior Western diplomats and officials said.
Using an unusually high level of professional troops with some of
the Yugoslav Army's best equipment _ M-84 tanks, for instance, the
Yugoslav version of the Russian T-72 _ he is moving to disrupt the
Kosovo Liberation Army's hold on the province.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces, these officials say, are driving large numbers
of ethnic Albanian civilians out of their villages to create an
added burden on the Albanian fighters. But the Serbian security
forces have not been killing large numbers of people, the officials
say, so much as trying to disrupt the still fragile organizational
structure of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army and cause new
recruits to think of peeling away to take care of their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more channeling and moving people now rather than
destroying and killing,'' said a senior official with access to
intelligence reports. ``They can deal with that later on. These
troops are professional enough so that if they're ordered not to
massacre people, they seem to be able to restrain themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic clearly is in violation of the October cease-fire
agreement he negotiated with Holbrooke. But the Yugoslav leader has
been out of compliance almost from the moment the deal was sealed,
without any NATO retaliation. Even now, he is apparently hoping
that an effort to keep civilian casualties down will keep NATO from
attacking while his troops take the opportunity to strike the armed
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The West's decision to withdraw the 1,400 unarmed foreign
monitors on Saturday _ apparently intended to underscore the threat
of imminent bombing _ has given the Serbian military an opportunity
to try to disrupt and damage the ethnic Albanian guerrillas.
Popular support for the rebels is strong in Kosovo, a province of
southern Serbia where 90 percent of the 2 million residents are
ethnic Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Milosevic decides to accept the peace plan for Kosovo,
he will be able to argue that he did so under duress, and only
after dealing out real punishment to the rebel army, which under
the agreement is supposed to disarm anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic retains almost complete freedom of action at home to
resist NATO or to do a deal. In October, Serbs were more panicky at
the thought of bombing and ran around hoarding sugar and cooking
oil. ``Now, people are oddly resigned and ready to take whatever
Milosevic brings them,'' Ms. Smajlovic said. ``It's amazing. People
are saying, `Let's get it over with.'''
</P>
<P>
   The current joke, said a young woman named Zorica, is, ``Are
they going to bomb or shall I paint the house?'' The cover of the
weekly Vreme showed the Serbian president, Milan Milutinovic,
throwing up his hands under the headline: ``The Serb strategy: Que
sera, sera.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zorica, on a Sunday walk near the conjunction of the Sava
and Danube rivers with her husband, Danko, said she expected, in
the end, that NATO forces under some rubric or other will come to
Kosovo, as much as she and other Serbs detest the idea. ``We are a
small country,'' she said. ``Power is power. You can't change
that.''
</P>
<P>
   State television and media bristle with nationalistic bravado,
punctuated by citizens' rallies in support of Kosovo and Milosevic,
who has used the current tension to move against independent
newspapers in Serbia proper and Albanian-language ones in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the bluster of official propaganda, Holbrooke's
trip here was not mentioned until the 33rd minute of the main state
news Sunday night. And then it merited only one sentence, which
noted the request of the U.S. Embassy here for assistance in
arranging a meeting for Holbrooke with Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
