<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT &LR;      03-21 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHEN LEADER SURVIVES ASSASSINATION ATTEMPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The leader of the breakaway republic of Chechnya
survived an assassination attempt Sunday when a bomb exploded near
his motorcade in the region's major city.
</P>
<P>
   Several people were wounded in the blast in central Grozny,
including some of the bodyguards in the motorcade. But Aslan
Maskhadov, the leader of the separatist region, was unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion came just two days after a devastating bomb attack
in Vladikavkaz, 30 miles from Chechnya. The Vladikavkaz attack,
which took place in a busy marketplace, killed more than 50 people.
And it shocked many Russians, who already are accustomed to a
regular diet of accidents, tragedies and contract killings.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, flags flew at half-staff as Russia held an official day
of mourning for the Vladikavkaz attack victims. Interior Minister
Sergei Stepashin declared that religious extremists might have
carried out the bombing in Vladikavkaz, the capital of the Russian
republic of North Ossetia and the scene of ethnic clashes between
Ossetians and the Ingush, a Muslim people, in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian government does not appear to have any firm
clues about the culprits or about how to prevent such assaults in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Both bombings, as well as chronic kidnappings, underscore the
lawlessness in the Caucasus region more than two years after the
end of the bloody Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov, who led Chechnya's fight for independence, is one of
his republic's most moderate politicians. He was elected president
of Chechnya, which calls itself the independent nation of Ichkeria,
by an overwhelming margin in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Russia does not recognize Chechnya's independence,
it accepts Maskhadov as the republic's leader. He is one of the few
Chechen politicians with whom the Kremlin can communicate, even
when the two sides differ.
</P>
<P>
   Georgi Bovt, a Russian journalist, summed up the prevailing
attitude in Moscow when he wrote in 1997 that the Kremlin should
support the ``sane'' Maskhadov against the ``insane'' Chechen
warlords and former field commanders, like Shamil Basayev. And
Alexander Lebed, the Siberian governor who negotiated with
Maskhadov, has also described Maskhadov as a useful interlocutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I insist that Aslan Maskhadov is a man who is in full command
of his senses,'' Lebed said. ``There is a difference between the
rhetoric and the actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Maskhadov's rhetoric was on full display Sunday
night. Striking a nationalist pose, he said the assassination
attempt was part of a conspiracy by ``certain forces'' in Moscow to
create an excuse for declaring a state of emergency and canceling
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's bomb attack in Grozny and the explosion in Vladikavkaz,
he said, were ``links in single chain.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Putin, the director of Russia's internal intelligence
service, insisted that the charge was ludicrous, asserting that the
plotters of Sunday's assassination attempt could be found among the
faction leaders and criminals in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov certainly has plenty of enemies at home. He escaped a
similar assassination attempt in July. By some counts, Sunday's was
the fifth assassination attempt against him.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov has his differences with local faction leaders, who
have resisted his efforts to establish order and who have pushed
for the establishment of a radical Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he promised to solve the kidnapping of Gen. Gennadi
Shpigun, a senior Russian Interior Ministry official who was
abducted at the Grozny airport early this month. Six suspects have
been arrested as part of that investigation.
</P>
<P>
   There have been also been reports that Maskhadov was planning to
meet soon with Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov or other senior
Russian leaders. Analysts said the plotters might have been trying
to thwart such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's blast occurred near the presidential residence in
Grozny. NTV, the independent Russian television network, reported
Sunday night that the bomb consisted of two antitank shells and a
mine. It was hidden by a tree and went off just a moment after
Maskhadov's car passed by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maskhadov,'' NTV said, ``survived by sheer luck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
