<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8667 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT &LR;      03-21 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE TO MEET MILOSEVIC IN FINAL PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story will be updated and expanded with a 1st lead as
soon as possible.) 
(See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-ASSESS and KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration on Sunday dispatched a
special envoy, Richard Holbrooke, to meet with President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia in what senior officials described as a
final effort to persuade him to accept a peace agreement for Kosovo
and avoid a NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after President Clinton warned that the Serbs had gone
beyond ``the threshold'' of violence in their southern province,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said she was sending
Holbrooke to present Milosevic with a ``stark choice.''
</P>
<P>
   That choice, she said, was for him to agree to the settlement
signed in Paris last week by the ethnic Albanians who make up most
of Kosovo's population, or face NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   As Holbrooke prepared to leave Sunday night, Milosevic's forces
remained unintimidated. Taking advantage of the absence of 1,400
international monitors who withdrew from Kosovo on Saturday, they
continued their rampage through Kosovo, burning ethnic Albanian
villages.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, where Holbrooke will
stop Monday morning before flying on to Belgrade, U.S. officials
presented NATO ambassadors with a plan for stepped-up bombing
targets in Kosovo, a move intended to strengthen Holbrooke's
position with the Yugoslav leader.
</P>
<P>
   The president's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said
Sunday that another diplomatic push by Holbrooke was justified
``one final time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we owe it to the American people,'' Berger said on the
CBS program ``Face the Nation.'' ``We owe it to our military
people, our allies, to make that final attempt, even as the
preparations continue.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed that plans for NATO airstrikes were simultaneously
moving forward. ``The preference is to find a peace agreement that
will bring stability to Kosovo, peace to Kosovo, and rights to the
Kosovar people,'' Berger said. ``If we can achieve that with the
imminent threat of force, that will be a good result.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who has negotiated for hundreds of hours with
Milosevic over the last four years, appeared to have a particularly
difficult assignment this time.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Clinton administration officials said Sunday that
Holbrooke was being sent to deliver Milosevic the message of peace
or war.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic has shown a pattern in the past of backing down at
the last minute. Should he show signs of doing so this time,
Holbrooke will likely be left with the task of negotiating around
the edges of the peace settlement that the ethnic Albanians signed
at the Paris peace talks last week. Changes to the terms of the
peace settlement could well drive the ethnic Albanians to renege on
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Milosevic is ready to agree to a NATO-led force which
can include other nations, we're ready to discuss it without
betraying the ethnic Albanians,'' a senior administration official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The official acknowledged that there was ``very little
maneuvering room, because of the 81-page document out of Paris.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 1828EST &QL; 
