</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S ELITE KEEP A POSTHUMOUS WATCH OVER ONE OF THEIR OWN  
 TV VIES FOR INTERVIEWS WITH REAL LIFE GRIFTERS  
 A WEB SITE BECOMES A BOOK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Eric M. Breindel, the conservative talk-show
moderator and former editor of The New York Post opinion page, died
last year at the age of 42, his funeral drew hundreds of mourners,
including Henry A. Kissinger, Alfonse M. D'Amato and Daniel Patrick
Moynihan. There were so many eulogies that the ceremony lasted four
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those people are keeping a careful eye on his image.
When a New York magazine reporter, Craig Horowitz, was preparing a
profile of Breindel for the magazine's March 21 issue, its editors
got calls from concerned relatives like his mother, Sonia; friends
like Lally Weymouth, a columnist for The Washington Post, and even
representatives of public figures like Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Cristyne F. Lategano, the mayor's communications director,
called New York's editor in chief, Caroline Miller, to register
concern about the article, which highlights the mayor's friendship
with Breindel and says that in 1993 Breindel used his working
relationship with Rupert Murdoch, the chairman of News Corp. to
persuade Murdoch to endorse Giuliani as a mayoral candidate. But
Ms. Miller said that Ms. Lategano's concern was mostly personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cristyne was calling as a friend of the Breindel family to
discourage me from running this piece,'' Ms. Miller said. ``And I
assured her that I thought the piece was fair and civilized, and
even generous, and that I planned to run it.''
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz attributed the number of phone calls to the fact that
powerful people are anxious to preserve the memory of one of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``To what can one attribute the concern?'' Horowitz said. ``I
think that he was a beloved member of the ruling class in New York.
And as such, the people around him were very protective of his
memory. He was a friend and an ideological ally for many of those
people and it's a friendship they took very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Breindel used to say that you could tell who was
your friend by who would help you bury a body at 3 o'clock in the
morning, and by that measure he had a lot of very good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ALEX KUCZYNSKI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Battle for Interviews with Sante and Kenneth Kimes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes,'' it seemed, had won. After battling off the
competition, the CBS news program had landed one of the biggest
Manhattan crime-story interviews of the year.
</P>
<P>
   On March 11, Sante and Kenneth Kimes, the reputed mother and son
``grifters'' con artist team who are charged murder in the
disappearance of an Upper East Side millionaire last summer, sat
down with the reporter Steve Kroft for their first extensive
on-camera interview. The mother and son are scheduled to go on
trial in the murder of Irene Silverman later this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the interview, in the Manhattan Detention Center, was brief
and ended badly, say jail officials who were present. After 30
largely innocuous minutes of talk, in which the Kimeses professed
their innocence and discussed life before they landed behind
Manhattan bars, the Kimes' lawyers objected when Kroft asked a
question about their life style.
</P>
<P>
   The interview resumed again, jail personnel said, but was
repeatedly halted by the Kimes lawyers, who said the mother and son
could not answer any questions about alleged past ``bad acts'' that
could be raised against them at trial. The end came when Kroft
asked Kimes about college, beginning a question with ``I see from
your transcripts that you got an A in acting.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyer, Matthew Weissman, leapt to his feet and
shouted ``Cut!'', according to jail personnel. Despite much
negotiation, the interview never resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Tedesco, a spokesman for ``60 Minutes,'' said he could not
comment on a piece currently in production. Weissman said the
Kimeses complied with the ground rules agreed to prior to the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The false start was far from a first. Last August, the program
``Fox Files'' spent $15,000 to fly two members of the Kimes defense
team to Grand Cayman to shoot supporting footage for a promised
exclusive interview with the mother and son.
</P>
<P>
   But while Fox was shooting in Grand Cayman, Cindy Adams of The
New York Post printed a telephone interview with Mrs. Kimes from
jail. Eric Shawn, a senior correspondent on ``Fox Files,'' said the
Kimes' lawyer, Mel A. Sachs, never told him about The Post
interview, which was conducted the night before the group left for
the tropics. Fox ended up broadcasting a statement Mrs. Kimes left
on Shawn's answering machine on Fox News Channel on March 2.
</P>
<P>
   But Shawn has not given up. He was back in the Criminal Courts
Building on Friday, talking to Mrs. Kimes and seeking an on-camera
interview.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID RHODE
</P>
<P>
   From the New Media Back to the Old
</P>
<P>
   The world of work _ not to mention, publishing _ is vastly
different from the days when the oral historian Studs Terkel set
about chronicling it in his book ``Working'' 25 years ago. Which is
why the staff at the online magazine Word (http://www.word.com) was
inspired to conduct a series of interviews about how people make
their livings in a regular column published on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the column is to be collected in a book, part of a growing
trend of such Web-inspired publications. The built-in audience that
a Web site provides is a growing attraction to publishers who were
once dismissive of the electronic medium. The Web also provides a
testing ground for material, a dry run for potential publishers to
see what works and what does not.
</P>
<P>
   For the Word book, Crown Books has signed a deal in the ``high
five figures,'' said Marisa Bowe, the publisher of Word, to publish
the collection. Included in the book, to be titled ``Gig,'' are
interviews with people who offer a decidedly hip twist on Terkel's
original.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: a tofu manufacturer, a workfare street cleaner, a
UPS driver, a heavy-metal roadie, a drug dealer and a squash
instructor. (``I'm a prostitute, a therapist and a squash pro, in
that order.'')
</P>
<P>
   While 70 percent of the book will be interviews that have been
published on line in Word and are archived on the site, the rest of
the interviews will be newly generated. Release is scheduled for
spring 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Pepper, the editor at Crown who bought ``Gig,'' said the
publisher had printed another book inspired by a Web site. The
creators of the Onion (http://www.theonion.com), an online news
satire site, came up with Our Dumb Century, a collection of 150
fictitious front pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, we have a really funny book here, whether you've
heard of the Onion or not,'' Pepper said. ``It's not really a Web
or Net book. It's a book that happens to stem from a Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Rufus Griscom, the co-founder of a Web site about sex called
Nerve.com (http://www.nerve.com/), said that the notion of a book
was foremost in his mind when he started the site. ``Nerve,
Literate Smut: The Book'' (Bantam), which contains 33 essays
originally published on the site, was released in October, and is
in its third printing.
</P>
<P>
   He said the anthology had helped him raise money for his
business. ``There's something persuasive about physical matter,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
