</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE SEPARATES PERSONAL TELEPHONE CALLS FROM BUSINESS CHARGES  
 JELLYFISH EXTRACT MAKES FOOD GLOW IN THE DARK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Canada)   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad news for workers everywhere who surreptitiously award
themselves an unofficial perk: a Canadian inventor has patented
software that can identify personal long-distance calls made from
telephones in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-distance charges total about $100 billion a year in the
states, and half of that is business related,'' said David Yanor,
an entrepreneur and sales manager in Vancouver, British Columbia.
``Experts say anywhere from 10 to 30 percent is unreimbursed
personal long-distance calls. That's a black hole for most
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Yanor recently discovered for himself what that was like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a visitor in my house who made copious phone calls to
friends across the continent on the same phone I used for
business,'' he said, ``and I had a very hard time determining which
were mine and which had to be collected from someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, businesses have had few remedies to control this
abuse other than installing systems that block all outgoing
long-distance calls. Phone companies have not offered much help,
especially since they charge for these long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   Yanor hopes his software will change that. His system enables a
business to establish a directory of approved business numbers,
such as those of other branch offices, customers, clients and
suppliers. The system then cross-references phone bills with that
directory, matching numbers called with those in the authorized
directory. Finally, it produces one of two reports: either bills
with enhanced information about who was called, or a list of
unauthorized long-distance numbers only. The latter can identify
the holders of those numbers with data taken from directory
assistance information.
</P>
<P>
   Yanor's patent says his software would search national and even
international telephone directory data bases. Presumably, a
business owner would thus be able to determine if an unauthorized
call was placed to a potential new client, or to an employee's
friend or relative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially how it works is that I will license it to phone
companies that will offer it as an additional enhancement, which is
where they're making all their money these days, for corporate
customers and even residential customers,'' Yanor said. ``All it is
is an enhancement to a phone bill, so a business gets on every line
the name of the company and person called. It's not Greek anymore,
you can actually see it all on the phone bill. I call it Call
Recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would suddenly permit the company, without saying
anything, to change behavior in employees, because people would
know they are being monitored closely,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Yanor said he had approached phone companies in Canada and the
United States with his idea, but they were less than enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phone companies feel this would diminish their long-distance
revenues,'' he said. ``But bill enhancements typically have a 75
percent profit margin, while long distance typically has a 10 to 11
percent profit margin.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, however, that many phone numbers, such as
unlisted numbers or cellular phone numbers, would remain
unidentifiable.
</P>
<P>
   Yanor received patent 5,842,174. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Food That Glows In the Dark
</P>
<P>
   Birthday cakes look especially impressive when presented in a
darkened room with candles ablaze. They might look even more
dramatic if the ``happy birthday'' wishes on the cake glowed in the
dark, even after the candles were blown out. Partygoers might then
toast the guest of honor with luminescent soda pop or beer.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is extract of jellyfish, glow worm or firefly mixed
into the cake frosting or the drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bryan, a surgeon and founder of a Pittsburgh company
called Prolume Ltd. has won a patent for a self-illuminating
extract made from bioluminescent creatures. His patent covers using
the extract to create glowing textiles, ink, paints, paper, toys
(``particularly reloadable squirt guns that eject a bioluminescent
fluid''), dolls (and ``dummies with internal organs or parts that
glow'') toy cigarettes (``that produce glowing smoke''), toy eggs
(``with glowing yolks and/or whites''), bubble-blowers, fountains
that expel glowing fluid, and bioluminescent ``fireworks.'' He even
envisions glowing fish food to feed transgenic fish so they'll
light up after they've eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Additives that make the food or beverages glow are derived from
the genes of a variety of creatures, most of them underwater
inhabitants like jellyfish, crustaceans, molluscs and vampire
squid. Some worms and fireflies qualify as well. Bioluminescence is
rare, and occurs when an enzyme or other protein is combined with a
fuel molecule. The addition of oxygen energizes the molecule. As
the energy subsides, it is released in the form of light.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it is working on a cake frosting that glows
bright blue for up to half an hour, and on luminescent yogurt, ice
cream and beverages.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement of the patent explains that the company's
researchers ``believe that these additives are safe since they are
present in the ocean's food chain.'' But the Food and Drug
Administration still has to examine and approve them for human
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bryan's patent also covers using bioluminescence to
``attract attention, such as for advertising goods and/or services
that are associated with a logo or trademark.'' He received patent
5,876,995. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
