<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BORN-TEXAS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS AIM TO EASE CULTURAL ADJUSTMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STAR-TELEGRAM STAFF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Twenty-one-year-old Ruben Mateo is the
hottest prospect in the Rangers' organization. He could be
patrolling center field in Arlington by next season.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the Rangers believe the Dominican Republic native will be
much better prepared to handle the move to the majors off the field
than young stars they've promoted from Latin America in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, for example, speaks better English than Rangers all-stars
Juan Gonzalez and Ivan Rodriguez did at a similar stage in their
careers. Mateo said he appreciates the effort the Rangers are
making to help him adjust to a new culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rangers try to make you a better player on and off the
field,'' Mateo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' effort to ease the cultural shock of adjusting to a
foreign country is understandable. The organization has long been a
leader in tapping the pipeline of talent from Latin America. There
are 75 Latin American players in the farm system, but immigration
laws limit the team to having a maximum of 32 playing in the United
States at one time. The rest play in the Rangers' Dominican summer
league and the farm club in the Venezuelan league.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the faster they make the cultural
transition the more successful they can become on the field,'' farm
director Reid Nichols said. ``We try to go the extra mile.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers began a computer program last year to help foreign
players speed their grasp of English.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell our guys that different instructors can say the same
things over and over, but it will be that one sentence or phrase
that clicks with them,'' Nichols said. ``We don't want them to miss
that one sentence or phrase that can change their careers, so we
tell them they need to learn as much English as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers hired a cultural director for their Dominican
Baseball Academy, Juan Peralta, this winter. He instructs players
on how to organize their lives away from the park, including basics
such as renting an apartment and ordering food at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Rangers hired Jaime Garcia as their Latin
American liaison in the United States. He helps players throughout
the minor-league system in this country make the adjustment. Last
week, for example, he worked with Latin players to get Social
Security cards. Garcia is also a pitching coach for the Rangers'
rookie league affiliate in the Gulf Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also ask major-leaguers to talk to younger prospects
about adapting to life in the United States. Gonzalez, Rodriguez
and Rangers infielder Luis Alicea went to the minor-league complex
recently to talk to players.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Rangers have a Rookie Career Development
Program to educate teammates about the problems Latin players face.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they know what's going on,'' Nichols said. ``So they won't
be judgmental, so they'll be understanding and try to help these
guys make the adjustment.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 1851EST &QL; 
