<HEADER>
A8681 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BORN-TCU-ATHL     03-21 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BORN-TCU-ATHLETES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN ATHLETES AT TCU STRUGGLE WITH A VARIETY OF THINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
WITH FOREIGN PLAYERS PACKAGE 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A chance to play basketball brought TCU
guard Vladimir Jaksic to Texas from Croatia two summers ago.
</P>
<P>
   He just had a small problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``English,'' Jaksic admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Jaksic, few programs existed at Blinn College,
a two-year school, to help him adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned by practicing,'' Jaksic said of his English. ``Some
days were hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaksic, like many foreign student-athletes, realized many
challenges awaited him when he left Zagreb, Croatia. He soon
realized he would be dealing with a lot of them by himself.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of foreign athletes participate in college
athletics in America, and universities such as TCU, UT-Arlington
and North Texas find themselves trying to discover ways to help
them adjust to the differences in language and culture as well as
the demands of being a student and athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four or five percent of our students are international
students,'' said Dr. David Keitges, associate director of
international studies and programs at North Texas. ``I would think
foreign athletes would have the same needs as other foreign
students.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU and UNT have programs for foreign students, although the
schools lack specific programs for foreign student-athletes. Jaksic
said TCU coaches have played a big role in helping him adjust to a
new culture, and advisers available to all student-athletes have
provided academic help.
</P>
<P>
   Gladys Keitany, a TCU distance runner from Kenya, said fellow
foreign students have been helped her adjust to everyday issues
like laundry.
</P>
<P>
   It was David Lagat, another distance runner from Kenya, who
explained a washer and dryer to Keitany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' Keitany said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
