<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BORN-DALLAS-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' GLOBAL CHANGE SPARKS NEED TO ADAPT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
WITH FOREIGN PLAYERS PACKAGE 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When the Stars moved to Texas in 1993, about the
biggest transition a Stars player had was adapting to Southern
cooking and learning to say y'all. But then the Stars' organization
began to change.
</P>
<P>
   Taking note of the success of division rival Detroit in bringing
in foreign talent, the Stars beefed up their European scouting and
began the move to a more global organization. They drafted four
Finnish players _ including Jere Lehtinen, the Selke Trophy winner
as best defensive forward last season _ and a Swede in the 1992 and
1993 drafts. In 1994, they drafted their first Russian-born player,
Evgeny Petrochinin. In the past two seasons they have used eight of
15 draft picks on foreign players.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest change for the organization came in 1996, when
they traded for Sergei Zubov, signed Sergei Makarov and Arturs Irbe
as free agents, brought Lehtinen from Finland and assigned goalie
Roman Turek from the Czech Republic to their minor-league affiliate
in Kalamazoo, Mich. Then, the European transition became an issue
the club had to tackle head-on.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we traded for Zubov, we decided it was very
important that as an organization we do everything we could to help
him adapt,'' said Dan Stuchal, director of team services for the
Stars. ``We had heard things were a lot harder for him in
Pittsburgh than they were in New York, and we didn't want that to
play any role in him not enjoying his time here.''
</P>
<P>
   Zubov had been traded from the New York Rangers to the Penguins
the previous season and had a difficult time adjusting in
Pittsburgh after leaving friends he had made in a Russian community
in Brighton Beach, N.Y. So Stuchal went out of his way to find a
similar community in Dallas. He scouted Russian bookstores,
restaurants, delis and clubs. He found Zubov a real-estate agent
who speaks Russian, as well as providing help in continuing to
learn English.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was most interesting to me is that I learned Dallas
really does have a very large and very strong Russian community,''
Stuchal said. ``I think sometimes we don't really see the world
around us when we're not looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Zubov didn't grow up with dreams of playing for the Stanley Cup.
He didn't think about big-dollar contracts and fancy cars. He
certainly didn't think much about the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just played hockey,'' the Stars defenseman said of his
youth in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   So, when NHL teams began plucking players out of the Soviet
Union in the early 1990s, he wasn't prepared for the move. All he
knew, he said, was: ``It was time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with only a few words of English, Zubov was shuffled into
the Rangers organization in 1992 and was sent to minor-league
Binghamton, N.Y. Along the way, he simply went where the team went,
did what the team told him and kept to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, very hard,'' Zubov said. ``You leave your family
and friends, you come to a new place and can't speak the
language.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still hard for Zubov, 28, though he communicates well in
English. There are still times, he said, when he doesn't get a
joke, when he feels left out in a conversation, when it would be so
much easier to speak Russian. He is smart but self-conscious, and
struggles with on-camera interviews. He rarely does them for fear
of sounding unintelligent.
</P>
<P>
   But, he's become comfortable in his Dallas surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes time, but it's good now,'' said Zubov, 28, who is
married and has a young son. ``You get friends, it works.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Stuchal and the Stars have helped assimilate
Lehtinen and Lind from Finland, Sergey Gusev from Russia and Turek
and Petr Buzek from the Czech Republic. In the process, the Stars
have shed their image as a North American stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an organization, I think it is something that can be
important to your success,'' Stuchal said. ``We're going to do
everything we can to make it easy for them to adapt. Because we
know how hard it is.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
