<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      03-21 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SAID TO BE FAVORING PLAN FOR HEAVY BOMBING IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-U.S. and KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC) 
(ms) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO Sunday appeared to be moving toward
agreement on a U.S. plan that would authorize heavy bombing
directly against elite Serbian units carrying out attacks on ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the allied ambassadors had authorized a short, sharp
attack of cruise missiles on Serbian military installations,
followed if necessary by strikes at Serbia's air defenses, in their
effort to force the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, to accept
an agreement on autonomy for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, alliance members are increasingly convinced that
it will take heavy bombing against the 40,000 Serbian troops and
police now on the offensive in Kosovo, the southern Serbian
province whose two million people are almost all ethnic Albanians,
for Milosevic to back down.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, officials said, wants to give NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana authority to order strikes directly
against Milosevic's attacking forces. NATO commanders _ who have an
armada of more than 400 U.S., British and French airplanes as well
as ships with cruise missiles in the Adriatic _ could launch such
strikes within hours of getting the order, officers say.
</P>
<P>
   Presented with the U.S. plan here Sunday, the allies failed to
reach a decision, however, and said they would reconvene Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The deliberations were taking place in an atmosphere of mounting
crisis, not only for the tens of thousands of civilians now fleeing
the offensive in Kosovo but for the alliance's own credibility 50
years after its foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the alliance shows that it is prepared carry out its
threats, one high-ranking NATO official said Sunday, Milosevic is
increasingly unlikely to halt his offensive and accept a peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``These attacks are no surprise,'' the official said.
``Milosevic has taught the West over many decades that he only
listens to force, or to threats of force.'' Milosevic responded to
heavy allied bombing in Bosnia in 1995 by agreeing to force Serbs
there to accept a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get across to President Milosevic that we are
serious,'' Britain's foreign secretary, Robin Cook, said on BBC
Radio Sunday. ``This is for real.''
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac and Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine have sounded equally tough since peace talks on Kosovo
sponsored by France and Britain collapsed on Friday, blaming the
failure on Serbian intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to use every opportunity we can get,'' said German
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, who chaired a meeting of the 15
European Union foreign ministers here Sunday, ``to achieve a
peaceful solution and avoid a confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment,'' he added, ``it seems Belgrade is determined
to risk that confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   They hoped that the threat alone would get Milosevic to agree to
peace talks in France. He did agree, but on his instructions
Serbian negotiators refused to accept a settlement that would
provide autonomy for the province and 28,000 alliance-led
peacekeepers to guarantee it for at least three years, and the
talks broke off in Paris last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Air strikes alone, an experienced military officer cautioned,
could not stop the Serbian forces in Kosovo from carrying out
further attacks against rebel forces and the civilian population
that supports them.
</P>
<P>
   They could disrupt and delay such attacks, but most importantly,
this officer said, air strikes would show Milosevic that, after
nearly half a year of verbal threats, the alliance actually meant
business.
</P>
<P>
   If air strikes do not make Milosevic back down, the allies could
yet be forced to decide whether the 28,000 planned peacekeepers
should fight their way into Kosovo from Macedonia to make the Serbs
accept peace. That is a step no one yet seems ready to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav leader has tested its credibility in the new,
post-Cold War era more directly than Soviet leaders ever did while
the Cold War lasted, even though they had an enormous army whose
tanks could have rolled westward into Germany over allied defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of United States nuclear retaliation for any such
attack was taken so seriously that Moscow never tried one. So
NATO's first 40 years ended with the collapse of communism in
Europe without a shot fired by the allies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the second time in four years, the alliance is
confronted with the need to respond to the threat of instability in
the Balkans caused by Milosevic. ``We're witnessing a tragic
escalation of the fighting, caused by Serb aggression against the
civilian populace,'' NATO's Supreme Allied Commander, Gen. Wesley
K. Clark of the United States, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Klaus Naumann of Germany, the chief of the alliance's
military committee, gave the ambassadors of its 19 countries _
including three formerly Communist ones, the Czech Republic,
Poland, and Hungary _ a report Sunday on what he called ``a very
rapidly deteriorating situation on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Defying earlier threats by the allies and breaching commitments
he gave last fall to the United States special envoy for the
region, Richard C. Holbrooke, Milosevic has now increased the size
of Yugoslav National Army and special police forces in the province
to about 40,000, a high-ranking NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied warplanes could strike those forces using intelligence on
their positions gathered from pilotless reconnaissance planes that
have been flying over the province.
</P>
<P>
   Three allied officers are still in Belgrade providing liaison
with the German units that carry out the missions.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes Sunday, officials said, Solana was consulting
with international leaders involved in the crisis to see whether
they all shared the determination, expressed by President Clinton
and the British and French leaders, to go ahead with bombing over
Russian opposition if that was what it finally takes to get
Milosevic to change his mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
