<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW THE NBA ENVELOPE, PLEASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ridiculous as it seems, the NBA's 50-game irregular season
reaches the halfway point this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Though Dennis Rodman's annual AWOL brought an ironic sense of
business as usual, this surreal spring has the Bulls with only
seven wins, the Clippers with only 21 losses and Don Nelson with
job security.
</P>
<P>
   You may have to look closer to see them while simultaneously
tuning out the critics screaming about woeful shooting and low
scoring, but there are some good players playing good basketball.
In lieu of an All-Star break and as an undercard to tonight's
Oscars, one observer's mid-season award winners:
</P>
<P>
   MVP: Allen Iverson, Sixers. Like Mike, he can create and make
any shot from anywhere on the court. Without him, the overachieving
Sixers are lottery fodder.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive Player of the Year: Alonzo Mourning, Heat. He
intimidates, rebounds, blocks shots and grabs every loose ball with
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the Year: Paul Pierce, Celtics. He can't dunk like
Vince Carter or pass like Jason Williams, but the versatile Pierce
is by far the most polished of an impressive new crop.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth Man of the Year: Darrell Armstrong, Magic. As Penny
Hardaway's energetic backup, Armstrong leads all players who have
not started a game in scoring (11.7 ppg), assists (6.2 apg) and
steals (2.1 spg).
</P>
<P>
   Most Improved Player of the Year: Joe Smith, Timberwolves. A
disaster in Golden State and Philadelphia, Smith is suddenly a
legitimate low-post threat in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the Year: Pat Riley, Heat. Despite injuries to starters
Jamal Mashburn and Voshon Lenard, the master motivator has
developed his team into the toughest mental bunch in the league.
</P>
<P>
   East All-Stars: PG: Tim Hardaway, Heat; SG: Allen Iverson,
Sixers; SF: Grant Hill, Pistons; PF: Shawn Kemp, Cavaliers; C:
Alonzo Mourning, Heat.
</P>
<P>
   West All-Stars: PG: Jason Kidd, Suns; SG: Kobe Bryant, Lakers;
SF: Rasheed Wallace, Blazers; PF: Karl Malone, Jazz; C: Shaquille
O'Neal, Lakers.
SPOTLIGHT ON ...
Teammates, fans not sure Pippen belongs with Rockets
</P>
<P>
   Consider Scottie Pippen's honeymoon over in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For years the lead ball-handler and devastating slasher in
Chicago's triangle offense, Pippen is now reduced to standing
around watching Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley plod in the low
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty frustrated,'' Pippen said. ``Playing the minutes
I'm playing \R40.6 per game, fourth in the NBA\S, I'm not involved
in the offense. It makes the game not any fun anymore. My next step
is to find why this organization wanted me. I want to sit down and
ask, `What's my position on this ballclub?' If it's just from the
defensive standpoint, if that's the point, then I can feel much
better.''
</P>
<P>
   After having Barkley rip him for taking his feelings public,
Pippen got a chance to sit down with coach Rudy Tomjanovich. Both
say the problems have been smoothed over, but teammates and fans
are beginning to wonder if Pippen is a good fit for the half-court
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a puppeteer,'' Tomjanovich said. ``The guy's got to
make that decision right there. That's what basketball is. It
becomes instinctive. My job is to put them in a situation where
they have freedom to be who they are. Then it's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS
Around the East
</P>
<P>
   With John Calipari fired across the Hudson River, focus in New
York is now on Jeff Van Gundy's future with the Knicks. ``I guess
basketball season has started in New York,'' he said. Don't forget,
this is the guy who still has a framed copy of the infamous New
York Post back page on his office wall, the one where his mug is
staring at a noose. ``If they ever let Jeff go,'' said Patrick
Ewing, ``they might as well trade me. It would be a stupid move.''
... Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse has been struggling mightily on the
court because of off-court concerns. Stackhouse's mother is ill
with diabetes, a disease that already has taken his sister's life
earlier this season and also has stricken his father.
</P>
<P>
   Best and worst
</P>
<P>
   Best crossover move: Sixers coach Larry Brown might have saved
his job and Iverson's career by switching the blur to shooting
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Worst crossover move: Though we see palming violations every
night, rarely is it called. Just ask Sacramento's Jason Williams.
Inexplicably, referee Bernie Fryer called a crucial turnover on
Chicago's Mark Bryant with the Bulls trailing by two with 2:33
remaining in a loss to Orlando. Can you say double-standard?
Numbers Game
</P>
<P>
   5-0: Pacers' record against the Celtics with Larry Bird as
coach. ``He doesn't really talk about it, but you can see the look
on his face,'' said Reggie Miller of Bird facing his old team. ``We
know we always have to beat the Celtics.''
Around the West
</P>
<P>
   Go figure: Portland has six players averaging nine points or
more, no national television appearances and a 14 percent
ticket-price decrease at the Rose Garden. ... Minnesota has until
April 1 to decide whether or not to take New Jersey's pick from the
Marbury trade unconditionally. ... Taking Hack-a-Shaq to a new
level, the Timberwolves activated 7-foot-1 center Trevor Winter for
one game last week. After fouling O'Neal six times in 13 minutes,
Winter went back on the injured list the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Quote to note
</P>
<P>
   ``Steph wants better endorsement, more TV exposure. I wonder if
he's noticed the Nets are 4-19. If he wants to be on TV with them,
he better get cable.'' _ Timberwolves general manager Kevin McHale
on Stephon Marbury desiring a trade to a bigger media market such
as New Jersey.
Offbeat beat
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers had been the butt of nightly jokes by Jay Leno on
the Tonight Show, one of which was a segment called ``Things you'll
never hear people say.'' There was a big picture of Chris Ford on
the screen, and Leno said this is what you won't hear the Clippers
coach say: ``We won.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after, the Clippers broke their 17-game slide, and Leno
hosted Ford and several of the Clippers, who paraded down the aisle
under a confetti shower and a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see it too much,'' said Clipper Sherman Douglas of
Leno's Clippers jokes. ``I didn't participate going on Leno. That's
not me, not with one win. I'm here to win games, not be laughed or
joked about.''
\Nsubheds:Inside the numbers
</P>
