<HEADER>
A8686 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-JUDGES-CONTROVERS     03-21 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JUDGES-CONTROVERSY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING MUST MAKE CHANGES TO REGAIN RESPECT, EXPERTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former boxing referee Mills Lane has worked more than 100 world
championship bouts, and seen his share of real deals and raw deals.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis decision a week
ago, he said, was a ``joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way the beleaguered sport can protect itself against
embarrassment, according to Lane and other boxing experts, is an
overhaul in the way fight judges are selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some changes have got to be made,'' Lane said. ``And they must
be made right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane stopped short of saying the fight last weekend at Madison
Square Garden _ declared a draw although most observers believed
Lewis was clearly dominant _ might have been rigged. But Manhattan
District Attorney Robert Morgenthau has convened a grand jury to
investigate the outcome, and whether the three judges were
improperly influenced.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the latest fiasco, politicians were involved in
boxing reform. The National Association of Attorneys General has
created a boxing task force, spearheaded by New York's Eliot
Spitzer. Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), an avid fight fan, has
introduced the Muhammad Ali Boxing Reform Act in conjunction with
Sen. Richard Bryan (D-Nev.).
</P>
<P>
   The Ali Act, introduced in June 1998 and brought back Jan. 26,
deals primarily with protecting boxers from exploitation at the
hands of promoters and sanctioning organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the \RHolyfield-Lewis\S controversy is symptomatic of
serious underlying problems in professional boxing,'' said McCain,
who watched the fight from ringside.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, a former Nevada district judge who hosts TV's Judge Mills
Lane Show and the referee who disqualified Mike Tyson for biting
Holyfield's ears, said officials for all bouts should be chosen by
state authorities. That would avoid conflict of interest or the
appearance of one, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The judges for the Lewis-Holyfield fight were chosen by
sanctioning organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Eugenia Williams, the American who judged the fight 115-113 in
favor of Holyfield, was picked by the International Boxing
Federation. The IBF and World Boxing Association recognize
Holyfield as heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   English judge Larry O'Connell had it 115-115. Stanley
Christodoulou of South Africa was the lone judge who saw Lewis as
the winner, 116-113.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell represented the World Boxing Council, which lists
Lewis as the champ. Christodoulou was selected by the WBA.
</P>
<P>
   That the judges were chosen by the competing boxing groups that
declare champions ``shows how deeply entrenched conflicts of
interest are in boxing,'' McCain said. ``I do not question the
judges' motives, but I do question the system which led to their
selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding fuel to the controversy, salaries and expenses of the
judges were paid by powerful fight promoter Don King, Lane said.
King counts Holyfield among his clients, and has considerable
influence with boxing's various alphabet groups. Lane said
promoters will always pay for judges, whether directly or
indirectly, because they handle financial aspects of a big fight,
such as pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem is that sanctioning groups should have no
involvement whatsoever in choosing officials,'' Lane said. ``Boxing
shouldn't have a system where officials can feel beholden to anyone
... not the sanctioning groups and especially not promoters.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas attorney Spider Bynum, who has judged or refereed several
dozen title fights, said he agrees that changes should be made in
how judges are picked. He said the judging of the Holyfield-Lewis
fight was ``horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bynum, a legal adviser to the WBC and the North American
Boxing Federation, said the problem isn't the involvement of boxing
groups. Rather, he said, too many incompetent judges are chosen to
work big fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas and Nevada and California, the states are going to
insist on a local referee in 90 percent of the occasions, and at
least one local judge,'' Bynum said. ``But judges should be
selected on their competence and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Many boxing officials, Bynum said, believe that in a
championship fight such as Holyfield-Lewis, no American or British
judge should be allowed to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My idea of neutrality,'' he said, ``is that we should choose
officials who are going to referee or judge a fight correctly,
regardless of who's in the ring, what country they're from and what
color they are. I don't think there is enough money to buy a
competent referee or judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Bynum said he has known O'Connell for 20 years and considers him
a good and honest judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can have a bad day at the office,'' he said. ``Most
good referees and judges know when they screw up, and Larry has
admitted it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bynum said, Williams has defended her
scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good judges are out there,'' Bynum said. ``But they aren't
always being used.''
nn
</P>
