<HEADER>
A8687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKTARVER-OBIT-COX     03-21 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKTARVER-OBIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jack Tarver, former Atlanta Journal-Constitution publisher and
AP chairman, dies at 82
 &HT;    (Eds: Write-thru with details expected by 8:30 p.m.)
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jack Tarver, who rose from a country editor to
publisher of The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution and
chairman of the Associated Press, died Sunday afternoon. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Cause of death was not immediately available. H.M. Patterson &AMP;
Son Funeral Home in Sandy Springs, Ga., is handling arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver wielded great influence in the fortunes of the
Journal and Constitution and in Atlanta. He was a newspaperman
first and last, a columnist with a biting wit, a business
executive, civic leader, corporate board member and raconteur.
</P>
<P>
   He served the newspapers as general manager in 1952-56; vice
president in 1956-57; president in 1957-58; publisher from 1958 to
1976; and vice-chairman of the parent Cox Enterprises Inc. from
1976 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   His influence spread in journalism circles around the world as
chairman of the Associated Press, a non-profit cooperative news
service serving 1,400 newspaper members and 3,600 broadcasters,
from 1977 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta and the state, he served in many roles. He was a
member of the state board of education at the age of 26, for
example, and he was chairman of the board of the Federal Reserve
Bank of Atlanta in 1961-68.
</P>
<P>
   The late Ralph McGill hired Mr. Tarver, then a Macon News
editor, to be a humor columnist for The Atlanta Constitution in
1943. ``I am, by way of background, a Georgian by birth, a
Methodist through sprinkling, and a Roosevelt man out of
obstinacy,'' Mr. Tarver wrote in his first column.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver's years in the management of the newspapers brought
some controversy. He was too close with a dollar for the papers'
good, his critics said. His supporters said Mr. Tarver made the
papers so prosperous that they could afford to take some unpopular
stands.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest payoff came in the years when publisher Ralph McGill
was preaching racial moderation in his front-page column. That was
an enormously controversial task, but one that won Mr. McGill a
Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. McGill's columns also yielded venomous hate mail,
circulation boycotts and threats to withdraw advertising from the
papers. Mr. Tarver stood in the middle, acting as a calming
influence on Mr. McGill and as his protector when more
business-oriented executives worried that an unmuzzled Mr. McGill
would bring the papers to ruin.
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Williams Tarver was born March 2, 1917, in Savannah, the
only son of Otis M. Tarver, a hotelkeeper, and Mrs. DeLuth Williams
Tarver. He entered the University of Georgia, intending to become a
veterinarian. However, he later told friends, the hard times forced
him to leave UGA and enroll at Mercer University in Macon.
</P>
<P>
   He went out for the Mercer football team, but a broken shoulder
ended that project. He became business manager of the football team
and sports editor of the student newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated with a degree in journalism in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started on a little old, teeny weeny weekly. He couldn't
have started on a lower level,'' recalled Jack Spalding, retired
editor of The Atlanta Journal.cq
</P>
<P>
   That weekly was the Vidalia Advance, where Mr. Tarver worked for
$15 a week. A year later, he was ready to launch his own newspaper.
He moved the six miles to Lyons, a town that was much smaller than
Vidalia but was the seat of Toombs County. Mr. Tarver established
the Toombs County Democrat in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   South Georgia was still recovering from the Depression, and Mr.
Tarver traded advertising for groceries, dry cleaning, even for
games of eight-ball at a pool hall. ``I also was one of the big
givers at the church,'' Mr. Tarver said later. ``I had a deal with
the preacher to print the weekly bulletin, and he would give me
credit for a contribution of $10 a week.''
</P>
<P>
   During his Lyons period, in 1940, Tarver married Margaret Birch
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   His first move toward the big city came as a result of a column
he wrote about ``Gone With The Wind,'' a movie that had put most
Southerners, and Southern editors, in a swoon.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver's thoughts were iconoclastic. He described Rhett
Butler as a cross between Jesse James and Little Boy Blue and said
Scarlett was ``as changeable as a baby's underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   The column was reprinted in about 40 newspapers, and the new
owner of the Macon News spotted it in the Chicago Tribune ``I had
just gotten married and the paper was well in the black, and I was
going to be satisfied just to spend the rest of my life being a
country editor.''
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNIST
</P>
<P>
   But the owner of the Macon News and talked Mr. Tarver into a new
job.
</P>
<P>
   He was hired by The Atlanta Constitution in 1943, with the dual
responsibilities of writing a humor column and handling a number of
administrative details.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Martin, a former associate of Mr. Tarver's, described him
at the time as a ``bespectacled, innocent-looking young man,''
whose style at the typewriter was ``verbal acupuncture.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, for example, Mr. Tarver reported that restrictions had
been placed on travel by Congressmen. ``And about time, too,'' he
wrote. ``We've had too many third-rate politicians traveling
first-class.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1950, a major career change was in the works. Post-war
expansion had made the Constitution a money-loser, and Mr. Tarver
was drafted to turn the situation around. Within months, he
converted losses of as much as $150,000 into modest profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution and Journal came under the same ownership in
1950, and Mr. Tarver was named assistant to the president of
Atlanta Newspapers Inc. In 1952, he was made general manager of the
corporation. He discontinued his column and made himself a
full-time manager.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIVE
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver joined the elite circle of powerful people who for
many years were credited with a leading role in running the city's
affairs. He did not seek publicity, but the signs of power were
there. In 1960, for example, when banker Mills B. Lane Jr. got up
the group that founded the Commerce Club, Mr. Tarver was one of the
14 original board members.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to make more fun of the power structure than anybody
else,'' former Journal editor Jack Spalding recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarver was as straight as hell,'' Spalding continued. ``He
would stand up and fight anybody who tried to influence the paper.
He'd say, `Hell, no!' He was absolutely incorruptible. That goes
back again to his personality. He was not impressed by anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He moved up to become president of the parent Cox Enterprises in
1969, and vice-chairman of Cox in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   WRITING AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver resumed writing his column in 1974, and it appeared
regularly until 1977, when he was named chairman of the Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Though his political attitudes seemed to have been formed in the
``old boy'' days, Mr. Tarver was not unhinged when the power of the
old bloc began to decline.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Spalding recalled: ``Tarver had a great sense of the
ridiculous. He could spot a fool or a phony five miles off, and he
loved to deflate anybody pompous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarver never took himself very seriously,'' Mr. Spalding
added.
</P>
<P>
   AFFILIATIONS
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his chairmanship of the Federal Reserve Bank of
Atlanta, Mr. Tarver was chairman and director of Theaters Service
Co., and a director of Southern Bell, American Motors and Maccabees
Mutual Insurance Co. until retiring from those three boards at age
70.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his chairmanship of Associated Press, he was a
member of the American Society of Newspaper Publishers, chairman of
its Bureau of Advertising in 1962-64 and president of the society
in 1976-77; member of the American Society of Newspaper Editors;
and member of Sigma Delta Chi.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the state Board of Education in 1942-43 and a
trustee of Mercer University. He belonged to the Capital City,
Piedmont Driving, Commerce and Stadium clubs. He was a member of
Sigma Alpha Epsilon.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver was awarded the humanitarian of the year award of the
Institute for Human Relations in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving are his wife, Margaret Birch Tarver; a son, Jack
Tarver Jr. of Atlanta; a daughter, Margaret Tarver Jason of
Jacksonville, Fla.; and four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. Staff
writer Tom Bennett contributed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
