<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GRIDIRON-550&AMP;     03-21 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GRIDIRON-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIDIRON CLUB SENDS UP AN APPRECIATIVE _ MOSTLY _ BILL CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the long and harrowing struggle to defeat
impeachment, President Clinton finally joined in the general
laughter at his plight on Saturday night when he sat through a
satirical dinner and had the last word with the announcement of his
White House memoir: ``My Story, and I'm Sticking to It.''
</P>
<P>
   A wave of guffaws and applause greeted the president as he
gingerly kidded himself in topping off a long night of political
ribbing by Washington's press establishment at The Gridiron Club's
annual dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past year I have learned valuable political lessons,
important personal lessons and more than I ever wanted to know
about the presidency of Andrew Johnson,'' Clinton observed after
being lambasted in song and sketch through all the embarrassing _
hilariously embarrassing _ details of the sex-and-mendacity scandal
that threatened his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, through it all, I still believe in a place
called ... Hell,'' the president from Hope, Ark., added with
perfect timing in doing a turn on his campaign theme as the
gathering of 600 guests cheered him.
</P>
<P>
   For a 114-year-old tradition that once eschewed off-color
material, The Gridiron plunged into the president's sex scandal
with abandon after a brief note of homage to the good old days
``when the Oval office was used to raise money and the Lincoln
bedroom was used for sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, scrutinized by his audience at each punch line, was
stalwart at some barbs, convulsed in laughter at others. He was
serenaded with such song parodies as ``Sex Is a Definition Thing''
(``Love Is a Many Splendored Thing'') and had to hear a character
posing as Vice President Al Gore wax jealous at how the scandal
only improved Clinton's poll ratings. To the tune of ``Embraceable
You,'' the ersatz Gore sang woodenly: ``Impeach me, so I can be
popular, too. Impeach me, I can be sleazy for you.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the clowning rehash of his troubles, the president
noted the political field is nevertheless already crowded with
fresh presidential aspirants. He shook his head, smiled and told
the gathering, ``Now who in the world could have looked at the
presidency over the last year and thought, `Wow! That could be
me!'''
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians were skewered _ notably former Sen. Bob Dole,
the Kosovo peace negotiator and Viagra pitchman, who suffered
repeated Viagra jokes. ``Does Slobodan Milosevic know what Bob is
on?'' Sen. John McCain, the featured Republican speaker, anxiously
asked. A skit performer asked of Dole's wife, Elizabeth, the
presidential candidate, ``Is Mrs. Dole running for the White House
or away from Bob?''
</P>
<P>
   But the brunt of the evening was born by the president and the
other major impeachment figures in performances stippled with
Monica Lewinsky berets. In a parody of ``I Believe,'' presidential
loyalists sang loudly of their unyielding belief in him, not to
mention their faith in ``Santa Claus and unicorns and Tinkerbell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you? Laughing away?'' Sen. John Kerry, the featured
Democratic speaker, suddenly asked the president after needling him
with a draft-dodging joke. Turning back to the audience, Kerry
asked, ``Did you ever think we'd see the day where the president
would sit there and say, `Oh good, they're changing the subject to
Vietnam.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McCain, a prisoner of war for five years in the Vietnam War,
drew some of the strongest laughs when he stepped up with his
tuxedo lapels covered in burlesque military medals and gently
offered himself as presidential hopeful, ``incredibly self-effacing
guy'' and ``genuine war hero.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that sustained me through those hellish years
was the thought that some day I would come home and invent the
Internet,'' McCain continued straight-faced in one of the evening's
several tauntings of Gore's assertion that he created the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's humor, too, was self-directed as he noted how he married
his wife, Teresa, the Heinz fortune heiress, after receiving a love
letter from her mailed in a big envelope he said was imprinted:
``You May Already Be a Winner!'' With a standup comic's polish, he
also zinged the Republicans' assortment of flat-tax and
``flat-earth'' candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Forbes is just Ross Perot without 35 voices in his
head,'' Kerry said, and the pundit-ridden audience loved it. Then
he gravely interrupted himself to announce: ``Ladies and gentlemen,
on a purely social note, I want you to know that last night in
South Carolina, Strom Thurmond's next wife was born.''
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, the star of the night was John Glenn, astronaut,
former senator, and rather courageous baritone. He was disguised in
the show's chorus while two singers posing codgerly as Sens. Strom
Thurmond and Jesse Helms, to the tune of ``There's a Place
Somewhere,'' pleaded: ``Save a place for us, a ride in space for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn suddenly stepped forward in his astronaut's suit and
finished the song, firmly serenading the two others: ``This may
sound just a little trite; you don't have stuff that's right.'' He
brought down the house with simple dedication and clean wordplay.
An encore was demanded in the evening's one clear sign that
impeachment jokes might be paling in favor of the sort of wholesome
anachronism that is The Gridiron Club's forte.
</P>
<P>
   The club's annual show is a whimsical, long-winded inner sanctum
affair put on by its 60 members braced by professionals who can
carry a tune. After enduring more than four hours of mixed
performances, Clinton arose to pronounce himself gratefully
``singed, but not burned.'' But also, he said, wearily mindful of
the country song, ``I Don't Know Whether to Kill Myself or Go
Bowling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's don't kid each other: this was an awful year,'' Clinton
finally conceded after joining in the laughter at his scandalous
travails. ``It was a year I wouldn't wish on my worst enemy.'' But
then he paused and slowly grinned. ``I take that back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
