<HEADER>
A8694 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DWELLINGS-DISABLED-82     03-21 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DWELLINGS-DISABLED-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE LAW, FEW NEW APARTMENT BUILDINGS ARE EQUIPPED FOR
HANDICAPPED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Nev., Fla., Ohio, Md., Ariz., Mont.)  (lh) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eight years after a federal law went into effect
requiring new multi-family dwellings to be accessible to people
with disabilities, the measure has been widely ignored, the Justice
Department and advocates for the disabled say.
</P>
<P>
   There are no nationwide figures on how many of the more than 2
million apartments and condominiums that have been constructed
since the law went into effect in 1991 comply with the regulations,
which among other things require that first-floor units and common
areas be accessible to people who use wheelchairs or walkers. But
surveys conducted by advocates for the disabled around the country
indicate that only a tiny percentage of the multi-family buildings
in their communities are in compliance.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Chicago, for example, advocates for the disabled
found that out of 50 newly constructed multi-family developments,
49 had not followed federal law. In Baltimore a similar survey
found that 75 percent of 59 new apartment and condominium complexes
were not in compliance. Arizona advocates found that 75 percent of
the new multi-family buildings in Tucson and 50 percent in Phoenix
had not followed the law.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and disability rights advocates in
Chicago, Baltimore, Cleveland, Miami, Las Vegas, and Cocoa Beach,
Fla., have begun suing architects and developers to force them to
conform to the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are popping out all over the place,'' said Chris
Brancart, a lawyer from Pescadero, Calif., who has sued a developer
of condominium projects in Billings and Missoula, Mont., over the
buildings' lack of accessibility. ``People are no longer willing to
say it's a new law, let's give people an opportunity to comply.
There is a feeling that this law has been on the books for a long
time, and it's time to start pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs in lawsuits against builders and architects generally
do not seek the complete reconstruction of apartment and
condominium complexes. Rather they ask the courts to order
developers and architects who have violated the law to rebuild the
common areas to make them accessible and to set up an escrow fund
so that individual owners and tenants can make the necessary
improvements if they so choose.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants have settled in virtually every lawsuit since
they cannot dispute the fact that they have designed or built a
building that violates the law. ``You can measure something and see
if it's in compliance, as opposed to a typical race discrimination
case, which is a `he said, she said situation,' '' said Lauren E.
Willis a lawyer in Baltimore who has sued the developers of six
projects in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the home building industry agree that many
architects and developers have not complied with federal
regulations. But they assert that the reason is lack of familiarity
with the law's provisions, rather than deliberate attempts to evade
their responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for builders and architects not to comply
with these requirements,'' said Rhonda Daniels, a lawyer with the
National Association of Home Builders. ``They were not properly
educated on what the requirements are. Our association attempted to
educate our members. But everybody is not a member of our
association, or if they are, they may not have been paying
attention at the time when the law was passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, a federal judge in Baltimore ruled that architects
and builders of a condominium development in Anne Arundel County,
Md., had violated the law by making the residence inaccessible to
people in wheelchairs or who require walkers. It was the first
ruling in favor of disabled plaintiffs alleging violation of the
1988 law, though the Justice Department and advocates for the
disabled have reached settlements in a number of cases.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter E. Black, Jr., ruled that the
architect and developer had failed to provide enough handicapped
parking spaces, that walkways from the parking lot to the housing
units contained needless steps, that people had to climb one step
to enter ground floor units and descend one step to exit onto
balconies, that interior doorways were too narrow for wheelchairs
and that there was insufficient clearance in bathrooms and kitchens
for people in wheelchairs to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was brought by Kevin Beverly, 39, who uses a wheelchair
and who had gone to the condominium development to possibly
purchase a unit. But he found he could not even get into the sales
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a person who is disabled, to see new construction going
up and to see that folks are still ignoring a law that says an
individual like me has right to live here, it makes you feel bad,''
said Beverly. ``My wife and I were out looking for a place to raise
our children. To run into a place like this, which is brand new,
which is optimum in all other ways, is disheartening.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Black has scheduled a trial to determine the extent of damages
the architects and builders of the development, known as Lions
Gates Garden Condominiums, must pay.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly widespread violation of the federal regulations
and the resulting spate of litigation is an example of how a
ground-breaking law that is passed with much fanfare is often
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by disability rights advocates and the Bush
administration, Congress amended federal fair housing laws in 1988,
requiring for the first time that multi-family buildings with at
least four units be accessible to people with physical
disabilities. The measure required all first floor apartments and
condominiums built after March 13, 1991, in buildings without
elevators and all units in structures with elevators be made
accessible.
</P>
<P>
   The law gives people with disabilities the right to sue
architects and builders if their building violates the law. People
who are able bodied when they rent an apartment or purchase a
condominium and later become disabled _ or have disabled relatives
or friends who cannot visit or live with them _ can also sue.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress did not require that municipal agencies that issue
building permits enforce the law. As a result, many architects and
developers were not told of the federal requirements by the only
governmental agencies _ municipal planning departments _ that
approve their blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a big defect in the law when it was passed, and
nobody realized it at the time,'' said Ms. Daniels. ``When they get
their permits they think they're in compliance with all rules and
regulations. But these federal requirements stand outside of the
normal local building requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Some disability-rights and fair-housing advocates are not
completely sympathetic to this argument, however. Advocates in
Baltimore, for example, noted that a local fair-housing
organization called Baltimore Neighborhoods, Inc. has been offering
seminars to architects and developers to acquaint them with the
law. Until the lawsuits started being filed, few showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're skeptical about the claim that people didn't know about
it,'' said Joan Magagna, chief of the Housing and Civil Enforcement
Section of the Justice Department's Civil Rights Division. ``There
has been a lot of information out there about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thea Spires, the special assistant for disability policy to
Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, said in a statement that the
department has over 150 ongoing investigations into violations of
laws requiring accessibility. The department has set aside $1
million for a nationwide study of accessiblity compliance and
provided $2 million to disability groups to assist in enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Some reluctance to comply with the law may have to do with
costs. Though complying with the federal regulations adds only
about one-quarter of 1 percent to the cost of building an apartment
or condominium unit, requiring ramps, handrails and other features
adds 6.4 percent to the costs of exterior site improvements,
according to a study by Steven Winter, a Norwalk, Conn., architect
who is an expert in designing accessible buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Winter and others say it is much cheaper to conform to
the regulations when the building is being constructed then to have
to go back and make the improvements later. ``To tear down walls
and rebuild them and rip apart bathrooms and redo them, there is no
question that that is more expensive,'' Winter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
