<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-625&AMP;     03-21 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCIDENT AT CABINET MEETING HINTS AT GERMAN TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ At Germany's most recent Cabinet meeting, Juergen
Trittin, the environment minister, pointedly took out a newspaper
and began reading while important government business was
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extraordinarily rude, apart from anything else,'' said
one astounded minister who was present and who watched as Joschka
Fischer, the foreign minister, called Trittin to order by whistling
at him across the table.
</P>
<P>
   The incident says much about the tensions and unpredictable
turbulence that persist in the government of Europe's most powerful
country 10 days after the abrupt resignation of Oskar Lafontaine as
finance minister. Far from bringing calm, Lafontaine's departure
has only shown further divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A center is missing, and in its place there is a bazaar,'' the
respected weekly Die Zeit commented. ``Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder's political style brings to mind those Spanish soap
operas in which the viewing public has the chance to write scripts
that will decide the fate of the show's characters.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Germany's 6-month-old governing coalition of Social
Democrats and environmentalist Greens remains unclear. But it is
already clear that the heady euphoria and bold ambitions that
marked the birth of the country's first Red-Green government have
vanished in a pall of confusion. Long stunningly predictable,
Germany today gives a frequent impression of being rudderless.
</P>
<P>
   Trittin, who is a Green, is angry because his plan to shut down
nuclear power stations that provide about a third of Germany's
energy needs has stalled as business leaders have pressed Schroeder
to reconsider or to postpone any action.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Trittin clearly shares Lafontaine's deep
frustration that the room for governing in some distinct and
reformist way in a closely united Europe is now extremely limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red-Green'' was supposed to stand for all sorts of new things:
an end to nuclear power, a different approach to economic policy
involving possible wage increases to stimulate demand and
elimination of NATO's first-strike nuclear option. But reality has
proved harsh for such bold ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   That reality is of a Germany where the business lobby is
extremely strong, where laws and regulations tend to inhibit
reform, where fear of experiments persists and where a European
central bank in Frankfurt sets a monetary policy for the continent
that Lafontaine tried haplessly to change.
</P>
<P>
   Trittin has grown impatient with the slowness of Germany's
consensus politics. And apparently convinced that the chancellor is
a friend of business with no interest in any left-leaning or
environmentalist reform, Trittin loses few opportunities to show
his contempt for the government of which he is a part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red-Green as a reform project is dead,'' Trittin told Stern
magazine last week, adding that he saw the Social Democrats as
virtually indistinguishable now from the Christian Democrats of
former Chancellor Helmut Kohl. He added that the Greens might even
consider future political alliances with the Christian Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   These extraordinary comments, later played down by Schroeder,
were made before Trittin pulled out his newspaper in the Cabinet
meeting. The chancellor, who has been touring European capitals,
was not present at the meeting, which was chaired by Fischer as
vice chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   The approach to government taken by these two men illustrates
the tensions within the Green Party, of which they are both
members. While Fischer has proved generally pragmatic, Trittin has
brought to governing the fervor and idealism that were strengths of
the party in opposition. But those qualities are hard to square
with the day-to-day grind of getting anything done in Germany.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Trittin raised his newspaper, Fischer was in the midst of a
presentation of foreign policy, said the minister who observed the
scene and spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Fischer whistled
sharply, and Trittin put his paper down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is now widespread that Trittin may follow
Lafontaine's example and resign. But the Greens, having never
before tasted power, are becoming attached to it, and Trittin may
swallow his misgivings and hang on.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder is clearly anxious to avoid further disruption. The
press here has been busy calling him ``the lifestyle chancellor'' _
a reference to his frequent appearances at fashionable parties and
on talk shows _ and referring to ``the unbearable lightness of
Schroeder.'' He badly needs a solid political success to bolster
his image.
</P>
<P>
   This week, at a European Union summit meeting in Berlin, he will
try to secure that boost through an agreement on reform of European
Union finances that would slowly cut Germany's huge contribution to
the European budget.
</P>
<P>
   It would be an important achievement, but it seems unlikely to
impress Trittin or to put an end to the dissent in a coalition that
still seems to find the discipline and strictures of government an
uncomfortable burden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
