<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8698 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-925&AMP;ADD-NY     03-21 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS IN KOSOVO FLEE SERB DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, and KOSOVO-ASSESS)  
(lh) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PREKAZ, Yugoslavia _ This village, birthplace a year ago of the
armed Albanian revolt against Serbia's rule of Kosovo, was empty
and burning Sunday, a symbol of the Serbs' sudden punch into the
guerrilla heartland, an assault born in vengeance and intended to
spread fear.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Prekaz that Adem Jashari, the first martyr of the
rebel cause, was killed along with dozens of members of his clan
last March. That daylong battle marked the beginning of Kosovo's
undeclared war. Earlier this month, the Kosovo Liberation Army, the
rebels' increasingly well-organized force, paraded hundreds of
troops before commanders and thousands of spectators to commemorate
Jashari's death, and the start of the armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, it was the Serbs who controlled Prekaz. As flames
and dense smoke engulfed the village, dark blue armored police
vehicles pulled away from the deserted, ruined settlement. Nearby,
more smoke rose from houses burning in the town of Srbica, which
was taken over by Serbian security forces on Saturday as they took
advantage of the departure of 1,300 unarmed foreign monitors and
pushed into the guerrilla heartland known as Drenica.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, refugees were still fleeing the region, pouring out
along roads and tracks southward, on foot and on tractors, as
shellfire reverberated behind them.
</P>
<P>
   On the move for hours, many were terrified and unsure where to
go. Nexhmije Haxha, 35, said she had spent 20 hours lying face down
in an open field, her seven young children about her, trapped by
fighting on either side.
</P>
<P>
   She fled her home in Prekaz at 6 a.m. on Saturday, she said,
after a shell landed near the village school. With her elderly
mother-in-law and her seven children, the youngest 8 months old,
the eldest 13, she headed down the hill toward the nearby village
of Gornja Klina. Her husband stayed behind, with fighters of the
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Haxha described hours spent in terror of the fighting. ``We
were lying in a dip in the land, face down, flat on our stomachs,''
she said. ``The children were screaming and crying, especially
these two daughters.'' She started to cry herself as she cuffed two
freckle-faced children on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The other children clung to her, silent and staring, their brows
creased and eyes anxious. ``It was cold, and we had no blankets,''
she said. ``But I had some bread and cheese and fed that to the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Only after midnight, she said, did the shooting cease. Mrs.
Haxha and her children dared to make the climb down to a relative's
house in Gornja Klina. They arrived at 2 a.m., she said. Hours
later, the Serbian police told her to leave Gornja Klina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police said we should move all the women and children out,
because they always get blamed for harming women and children,''
she said. They managed to board a bus for the nearby town of
Mitrovica. On the way, they passed their village, in flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all burning,'' she said. ``We probably have no home
now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the third time we have fled the village,'' Mrs. Haxha
added, alluding to the last year of fighting. ``I think this third
time they will just level the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke, Serbian tanks and heavy concentrations of troops
and artillery surrounded Drenica. Tanks looked down from the hills,
and a police squad aimed its guns from a sandbagged position on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting was continuing not far away in the village of Poljance.
Although the front line did not seem to have shifted much in the
last two days, floods of new refugees flowed down from villages
further west, as shellfire came closer.
</P>
<P>
   There was some indication Sunday night that the Serbian assault
had stung the Albanians into new tactics. In the deadliest incident
in recent memory in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, four Serbian
policemen died in a hail of automatic weapons fire from a passing
car, the Serbs' Media Center said. The Reuters news agency also
quoted witnesses as reporting the ambush of another police patrol
near the southern town of Suva Reka. In the town of Glogovac, one
bridge was blown up near its northern end, and another was damaged
by explosives, Reuters reported. It was not clear whether the
rebels were responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the U.N. high commissioner for refugees estimates
that 40,000 people have fled their homes in the last week alone and
some 20,000 in the last two days, according to Fernando del Mundo,
the agency's spokesman in Kosovo. They are virtually all from the
Drenica region, fleeing as the Serbian military operation has grown
in breadth and intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Del Mundo said he counted 1,000 refugees traveling in 20 trucks
and trailers on one muddy back road. They had fled eight different
villages in western Drenica. Hundreds more were still trying to
flee the town of Srbica as their houses were set alight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a replay of last summer,'' del Mundo said, recalling the
huge offensive of July and August, which eventually forced more
than 100,000 people to flee their homes across Kosovo and take
shelter in the woods and mountains. Snow prevented people from
doing that this time, so they are moving from village to village or
seeking safety in the towns.
</P>
<P>
   But del Mundo said he was now also anxious about the people in
the towns. The Serbian move into Srbica on Saturday set off a flood
of 14,000 refugees in two days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying that the next fighting will be in the
cities,'' he said. ``I do not know what will happen, but if this is
a foretaste, it is going to be terrible.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Glogovac, another town father south, had swelled with 4,000 more
refugees in recent days and was in a precarious position, close to
the front line, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily armed policemen blocked access to Srbica on Sunday, part
of an order issued throughout the province to prevent journalists
from reaching the Drenica region. Townspeople who had managed to
leave Srbica said the police were going from house to house,
arresting the men and telling the women and children to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Miftar Kerolli, 57, a house painter, was gathering his family
together to flee when the police arrived and arrested him, his
24-year-old son and dozens of other ethnic Albanian men.
</P>
<P>
   He said they were interrogated, driven to a nearby town, and
then released.
</P>
<P>
   They received only mild abuse at police hands, he said. People
seem to be emerging from the area physically unharmed but severely
traumatized.
</P>
<P>
   The police were in a swaggering, aggressive mood Sunday, and did
not temper their language.``I pray to God that NATO will bomb,''
said one policemen, adding a crudely expressed desire to do more
harm to the Albanians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
