<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-TAXES-760(2TAK     03-21 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-TAXES-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS LOOKING RIGHT AND LEFT FOR TAX-CUT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.M., Fla., Va., Texas, Ala., Wash., Conn.)  (lb) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John Kasich, the irrepressible Ohio congressman who
is running for president on a theme of grass-roots empowerment,
wants a 10 percent across-the-board cut in federal income-tax
rates. ``The more money people have in their pocket,'' he says,
``the more they control their destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich is hardly unique in the Republican presidential field.
Dan Quayle, the former vice president, is calling for a 30 percent
tax cut for every American. Steve Forbes, the publisher, is once
again advocating a flat tax. In fact, one way or another, every
potential Republican candidate has embraced the theme of tax
relief.
</P>
<P>
   But Kasich, unlike the others, is also the chairman of the House
Budget Committee, with an influential role in fiscal policy. The
budget plan he drafted along with other Republican leaders is
scheduled for a House vote this week.
</P>
<P>
   That blueprint sets aside at least $800 billion over a decade
for tax reductions, which is enough to phase in the 10 percent tax
cut. But Kasich has run into trouble selling his idea to the rest
of the Republican Congress even though he has such prominent
figures as Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, on
his side.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans of all stripes have made so many
counterproposals that the search for the right tax cut has begun to
look like a carpet auction. Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, the
chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, now calls a 10 percent tax
cut unlikely. And even Kasich concedes, ``We're going to have a big
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich's dilemma shows the strange situation in which the
Republicans find themselves nearly two decades after Ronald Reagan
swept into office with a call for a bold across-the-board tax cut.
Once, a tax cut was a sure-fire Republican battle cry. But just
when the new era of surpluses makes dreams of large tax cuts
possible again, the fickle American public seems less interested
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   A private poll that the National Republican Congressional
Committee distributed to House Republicans at a party retreat last
month in Williamsburg, Va., found that 67 percent of Americans
favored a 10 percent across-the-board tax cut. But the endorsement
looked less overwhelming, Republicans familiar with the poll say,
when people were asked more specifically how they wanted the
federal government to use the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Given a list of options, 31 percent of those questioned wanted
the money devoted to Social Security, 26 percent to reducing the
national debt and only 18 percent wanted tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in a New York Times/CBS News Poll taken last month,
64 percent of all Americans said they wanted any surplus money
devoted to Social Security. Only 12 percent said they wanted taxes
to be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Political strategists say that, in part, Americans are shying
away from tax cuts because they still do not believe there really
is a federal surplus. And with the strong economy putting money in
their pockets, voters are more focused on issues like retirement
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``People simply don't believe the surplus is large enough to
save Social Security and Medicare on the one hand and to have large
across-the-board tax cuts on the other,'' said Mark Mellman, who is
a pollster to the congressional Democratic leadership. ``People are
not fools.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla., argues that the falloff in support
for sweeping tax relief is partly a result of the economic
expansion. ``Republicans have always been dominated by
supply-siders who said `Cut taxes' at every possible moment and it
will cause the economy to boom,'' he said in an interview. ``The
lesson of 1995 and '96 has been if you cut federal spending,
markets respond, interest rates drop and the economy explodes that
way, too.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Williamsburg retreat, Scarborough reminded his House
colleagues of the 1996 presidential campaign when Bob Dole made the
promise of a 15 percent across-the-board tax cut a centerpiece of
his losing race. Of the proposal for a 10 percent across-the-board
tax cut, Scarborough said wryly, ``Maybe it will work as well for
us in '99 as it worked for Dole in '96.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, tax cuts remain important to the Republicans' core
voters, and other Republican strategists argue that tax relief is
not high on the broad public agenda, simply because their party has
failed to talk about the issue enough. ``As this debate goes on,''
said Jim McLaughlin, a Republican pollster, ``and the more people
think there's a surplus out there _ it will help the tax-cut
argument.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas Davis III of Virginia, the new head of the House
Republicans' re-election effort, argues that Dole never gave more
than glancing support to his plan for an across-the-board tax cut.
``He talked about it for a month and then abandoned it,'' Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   He points instead to the example of James Gilmore III, the
governor of Virginia, who won in 1997 by pledging to eliminate the
unpopular personal property tax on cars.
</P>
<P>
   So to fire up the public, Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House
majority leader, along with lobbying groups like the National
Federation of Independent Business and the National Association of
Manufacturers, has begun a series of town meetings across the
country to try to stoke the demand for tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   But Armey is not promoting any particular tax-relief plan
because the debate is still running high in Republican circles over
what kind of tax cuts will prove politically appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups favor measures like a reduction in the capital
gains tax. Some Republicans want to eliminate the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   Social conservatives want to eliminate the so-called marriage
penalty, which results in many married couples paying more in taxes
than they would if they were single. Rep. Bob Riley, R-Ala., said,
``It's just an abomination to me that we would penalize something
that we pay a tremendous amount of lip service to _ families and
family values.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans have come to believe that the kind of targeted
tax-credit approach that President Clinton has made his own _
proposing tax credits for particular needs like child care or
long-term health care or education _ might have greater resonance.
In his budget proposal, Clinton called for $4.1 billion in tightly
targeted tax credits in fiscal 2000 and $32.6 billion over five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't believe they get the bang for the buck with 10
percent, the way they do when we personalize tax reduction,'' said
Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Dunn is co-sponsor of a tax-cut package that she calls
the ``lifetime tax-relief act'' because it includes a potpourri of
things like eliminating the marriage tax, eliminating the estate
tax, and raising the personal exemption to provide tax relief for
single people too. Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., has proposed her
own tax-cut package that moderates have rallied around.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich argues that such an approach leaves broad swaths of
Americans without any benefit. ``We've done targeted tax cuts in
the past few years,'' he said, ``but there were too many people who
were left out.''
</P>
<P>
   He is still pushing hard for his own proposal. ``You ought to be
reducing taxes whether times are good or bad,'' he said last
Thursday as he headed for another weekend on the campaign trail.
``We're going to have a fight inside our party,'' he said. ``That's
OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
