<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE DOWNSIDE TO FREE SPEECH ON THE INTERNET
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JON SWARTZ &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Part of the Internet's allure is the ease with which anyone can
freely and anonymously exchange ideas on virtually any topic. The
constant flow of debate and criticism can be astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   And, unfortunately, it can sometimes be irresponsible and
destructive: Just ask a couple of Northwest companies that were
trashed in one of Yahoo's popular bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   In January, someone with the e-mail moniker ``Delusional5''
allegedly posted a message on Yahoo's finance message board,
claiming that Wade Cook, who runs an investment education firm, had
been arrested for accepting kickbacks from companies he touted
online.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Cook Financial Corp. denied the allegation, but Yahoo
refused to remove the remarks from its bulletin board, said Kiman
Lucas, general counsel for Seattle's Wade Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a right to their opinions, but to say our founder
is in jail is absurd,'' she said. ``This is a short-seller's dream
and a major concern to our shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, Wade Cook filed a slander suit against 10 as-yet
unidentified users of the Yahoo bulletin board. &UR;  &LR; Wade Cook hinted
it will subpoena Yahoo to get the real names of those users.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes this so egregious is that falsehoods are posted on
Yahoo message boards for millions of people to read, and we can't
remove them from the Internet,'' Lucas said. ``This isn't like
graffiti written on a bathroom wall'' that only a few hundred
people might see.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In a similar case, ITEX, a Portland, Ore., online financial
services company, is suing two former employees for allegedly
posting false and defamatory information about the company on the
same Yahoo message board last year, said Stephen Pearson, assistant
general counsel at ITEX.
</P>
<P>
   It is seeking up to $1.5 million in damages from the defendants,
who purportedly claim ITEX is in deep financial trouble and that
``corrupt'' management has engaged in bribery, extortion, shady
stock deals and the promotion of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ITEX obtained a subpoena to force Yahoo to track down the
message-board users' e-mail addresses. After Yahoo complied, ITEX
gained a court order to force Internet service providers to divulge
the names of the individuals who posted the messages, Pearson said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Communications Decency Act protects Yahoo and other Web
sites from being sued for libel for false statements that appear on
their bulletin boards and chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Yahoo officials are rightfully conflicted about
protecting users' privacy and not being a conduit for slander.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Lawyers say Internet users have a First Amendment right &UR;  &LR; to
rant online without divulging their identity.
</P>
<P>
   But with free speech, there also comes responsibility. And many
are abusing their rights when they knowingly spread malicious
rumors about a company or individual over the World Wide Web, which
reaches more than 100 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most everyone _ including the government _ believe that the
First Amendment allows individuals to post anonymous messages,''
said Michael Overly, a Los Angeles attorney who specializes in
Internet privacy. ``But that becomes a problem when the messages
are libelous. For the first time, any individual can cause a great
deal of harm to companies over the global communications network
for just a few dollars a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Fortune 500 firms are hiring cyber sleuths to find out what
the public is saying about them.
</P>
<P>
   EWatch, based in Dallas and New York, trolls thousands of
bulletin boards and chat rooms on behalf of corporate customers.
Its specialized software can sniff out negative comments about a
company, but it can't stop them from being posted.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo alone has about 1,000 bulletin boards and chat rooms that
get tens of thousands of messages daily.
</P>
<P>
   The posting of lies on bulletin boards ``is nearly impossible to
prevent,'' admits Patrick Naughton, executive vice president of
products for Infoseek, the Santa Clara, Calif., portal company.
</P>
<P>
   Even when someone is kicked off a bulletin board or chat room
for using profanity and or spreading falsehoods, they often pop up
the next day with a new e-mail account, Naughton said.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK 'EM, ABA: Independent booksellers, attempting to stave off
archrivals Amazon.com and Barnesandnoble.com, last week announced
the creation of their own national online bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The American Booksellers Association introduced Book Sense.com,
one in &UR;  &LR; a series of countermeasures to promote the faltering indie
market, which has lost members and market share to the big
franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, when it opens August 1, the virtual store will
feature 1.5 million titles, a search engine and credit-card
fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers don't expect to bowl over the online giants but hope
to stem a sharp decline in market share. Since 1992, the ABA's
membership has declined to about 3,300 from 5,200, while their
slice of consumer book sales shriveled by half, to 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the financing to take Amazon.com and others
straight up, but we can make sure customers of independent
bookstores have more than two choices on the Internet,'' said ABA
marketing director Michael Hoynes, who predicted more than 1,500
booksellers will be part of the site by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want a knowledgeable, passionate merchant who cares
about books, and they want to support community businesses,'' said
Hut Landon, executive director of the Northern California
Independent Booksellers Association in Corte Madera. ``It's like
the difference between going to a bed-and-breakfast and going to a
hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   THERE'S MUD IN YOUR EYE: Sure, the Webbies _ the Internet's
answer to the Oscars _ grabbed all of the attention at last week's
digital-do at Herbst Theater. But how about the list of
semifinalists for the ``Mud Brick Awards for World's Ugliest Web
sites,'' which were announced last Friday?
</P>
<P>
   Think of the Muddies as the ``beer-drinking, trailer park
counterpart'' of the Webbies, organizer Marty Moe said. One judge
said nominee eBay (www.ebay.com) ``looks like amateur hour,'' while
another claimed Yahoo (www.yahoo.com) ``desperately needs
updating.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of NETFILES (17959 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Winners'' of the brick-shaped awards will be dishonored next
month.
</P>
<P>
   SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Lightning-quick updates of scores from the NCAA Final Four
basketball tournament, National Basketball Association and National
Hockey League are just a mouse click away at www.totalcast.com. OK,
enough of frivolous entertainment. Time for some geography lessons
at www.capitals.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
