<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY TAKING IT SLOWLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ For the second straight day, Dodgers catcher
Todd Hundley threw on the side and was encouraged by it. But he
wasn't ready to proclaim himself on target for the April 5 season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   In acknowledging what manager Davey Johnson said a day earlier,
Hundley said Sunday he would rather start the season on the
disabled list and be healthy for the long haul rather than rush
into catching the opener against the Arizona Diamondbacks and wind
up hurt a month later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to deal with the reality of it,'' a frustrated
Hundley said. ``I'm going to do everything I possibly can to get
there and (catch the opener). But you have to be smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley has yet to catch a spring training game because of
soreness in his surgically repaired right elbow. He could be behind
the plate Wednesday when the Dodgers host Cleveland, but he's
expected to take a few more weeks to get into game shape.
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitter now wears a neoprene-type brace on his right
elbow, and took batting practice from the left side for the first
time in more than a week. But it's now time for Hundley to back off
a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few days I've thrown it's felt great so now we don't
want to push it over the edge,'' Hundley said. ``We're back on the
upswing now. The elbow is getting better. We went through a dead
time, which you're going to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Dodgers don't want to rush Hundley's recovery, so
he might catch only a few innings in his first few spring games.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some time next week he'll get in a game,'' said Johnson,
who added that it didn't mean Hundley would catch. ``We're going to
need to test him and see how he responds.''
</P>
<P>
   Peace of mind: Gary Sheffield returned to left field for the
Dodgers, his first appearance in eight days after getting a
cortisone shot for his ailing right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield wasn't in the original lineup, but after batting
practice he went to Johnson and asked to go in. ``I threw the ball
and felt fine,'' Sheffield said. ``I didn't have any pain. It's
improved. I felt pain-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who is 1 for 14 at the plate, said he'll try to play
again today against the Kansas City Royals so he can get a few more
at-bats. After the Dodgers' day off Tuesday, Sheffield said he
hopes to get four at-bats in most of the games.
</P>
<P>
   Peace of mind, Part II: Outside of the minor back stiffness that
knocked second baseman Eric Young out of the lineup for a few days,
everything was peachy during spring training. The last test he set
for himself was sliding, since the last time he did so he broke his
right foot.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Expos he slid for the first this spring, and about
five seconds later he slid again. Young led off the bottom of the
first with a single, stole second and went to third when the throw
went into center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of the way. I'm at peace with it now,'' said Young,
who went 2 for 3. ``Things are coming along well.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Right-hander Dave Mlicki pitched two
innings in a Triple-A game. A week ago, he experienced stiffness
near his right shoulder blade and hadn't pitched in a week. He
threw 31 pitches and pitching coach Charlie Hough said the results
were fine. . . . Right-hander Antonio Osuna, bothered by elbow
soreness, played long-toss with Johnson before the game. ``He had
giddy-up on his fastball,'' Johnson said. . . . Right fielder Raul
Mondesi and coach Manny Mota left Dodgertown to tend to personal
business in the Dominican Republic. Both are expected to return
Tuesday. . . . Utility infielder Jose Vizcaino started at third
base for the Dodgers, his first appearance there since 1992.
Johnson said he likes Vizcaino's versatility in the field, having
played second, shortstop and third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
