<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8733 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIELSEN-WEBRATINGS-SF     03-21 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIELSEN-WEBRATINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPETITION INTENSIFIES IN TRACKING WEB SURFERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CAROL EMERT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Knowing what Web sites surfers visit and for how long is crucial to
advertisers. Competition to measure that behavior intensifies
Monday as Nielsen/NetRatings, a partnership between the television
ratings giant and a local Web company, goes live with its tracking
service.
</P>
<P>
   N/NR will do battle with Media Metrix, a New York company with
three years of Web audience tracking under its belt. Media Metrix
has about 300 clients _ advertisers and Web sites that want to know
how they rank _ and a very large panel of computer users _ about
40,000 individuals whose every digital move is monitored.
</P>
<P>
   N/NR combines the sampling expertise of Nielsen Media Research
of Westport, Conn., and the Web skills of NetRatings, a Milpitas
company that used to be No.3 in the market, trailing Media Metrix
and Relevant Knowledge, which merged with Media Metrix late last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen last fall jettisoned its own Web measurement system
before it was launched to join forces with NetRatings. Today, NNR
has 50 clients and a panel of 9,000, which it hopes to expand to
12,000 by May.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While tracking Web surfers' behavior may seem an obscure
pastime, audience-measuring services are actually a crucial piece
of the Internet formula because so many Web sites are underwritten
by advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The Web currently attracts only about 2 percent of U.S. ad
dollars _ or about $2 billion projected for this year. Advertisers
say uncertainty about who their ads reach is a primary obstacle to
greater Web spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audience measurement is, no question, the bedrock of an
ad-supported Internet medium,'' said Rich LeFurgy, chairman of the
Internet Advertising Bureau, a trade association. ``Getting it
right is one of the industry's top priorities _ and we still have a
ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of NIELSEN2 (74150 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Media Metrix and N/NR each have distinct strengths and
weaknesses, industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Both services recruit panels that are representative of the
wired population. Participants initially provide information about
themselves, such as their age, income, address, hobbies and
vacation habits. Then software is installed on their computers to
track their digital travels. &UR;  &LR; That way advertisers can see which
sites are attracting, for example, male teenagers who live in the
Midwest or golfers who make at least $100,000 a year. Advertisers
rely on such information in all media, including television, radio
and newspapers, to help decide where to place ads. Web publishers
use the data to find out who their visitors are and to attract
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether both companies will ultimately survive is anybody's
guess. Here are some key differences between them:
</P>
<P>
   -- Media Metrix boasts a massive consumer panel, which it claims
allows measurement of 15,000 Web sites with some measure of
statistical accuracy. The corresponding number for N/NR is several
hundred, said Tim Meadows, a vice president at NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   But the importance of tracking smaller sites is a subject of
debate. &UR;  &LR; ``Even 12,000 (panelists) isn't a lot for an online sample
because the audience is so fragmented'' that a larger sample is
needed to project activity at sites with few visitors, said Jim
Spaeth, president of the Advertising Research Foundation. ``I would
guess you'd need sample sizes of 40,000 to 50,000'' to get a broad
picture of Web activity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Nail, an analyst with Forrester Research, said small
sites are largely irrelevant to advertisers. The 25 most popular
sites garner 60 percent of Web ad revenues, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts raise questions about Media Metrix's
sampling methodology since it combines data from two different
panels that are tracked in two different ways _ the former Relevant
Knowledge group and the original Media Metrix panel. ``People
really interested in methodological purity have some problems with
that,'' said Nail.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Ann Packo, Media Metrix president, said the data mesh
perfectly because both use the same ``clickstream'' method that
reveals when people click and where they go.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; -- N/NR receives results from its panel in real time, which
allows quick turnaround of reports. That's handy for measuring Web
activity related to specific events, like the Super Bowl or the
release of the Starr Report.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Media Metrix collects real-time data only from its former
Relevant Knowledge panel. Data from the original Media Metrix group
is sent to the company on disks at the end of each month, although
Media Metrix wants to speed up the information gathering, Packo
said.
</P>
<P>
   -- N/NR's greatest advantage is its ability to track viewing of
banner ads, said Nail. Web advertisers are eager to find out where
their competitors are putting their Web ad dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
   N/NR employs a proprietary technology to count the total number
of banner ads in a given campaign and the performance of individual
ads. It can track who saw the banners and who clicked on them.
Media Metrix does a very limited amount of banner analysis. ``To
me, this is sort of the trump card N/NR can play,'' said Nail.
</P>
<P>
   -- About 5,000 people in Media Metrix's sample are tracked at
work as well as home whereas N/NR tracks activity only on home
computers. The work side is critical because up to half of surfing
time occurs at work, said Nail.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of NIELSEN2 (74150 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  N/NR is working with employers and industry groups to get
permission to monitor work computers _ something many employers are
leery of, said Manish Bhatia, vice president of interactive
services with Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; -- Media Metrix can track what users see on ``offline''
services such as PointCast, which uses push technology, as well as
online movement. N/NR tracks only the Web, although it has begun
doing some limited monitoring of America Online's members-only
system.
</P>
<P>
   -- While not very relevant today, N/NR will have a significant
leg up when the Web and television merge into the same box because
of Nielsen's TV ratings system, said Spaeth. ``It's a huge
advantage to them,'' although WebTV isn't expected to be
commonplace for five years or so.
</P>
<P>
   -- Media Metrix comes to the table with the status of an
industry leader. Its list of top Web sites is frequently cited in
the media and it already has relationships with hundreds of
heavy-hitting clients.
</P>
<P>
   N/NR points out that Arbitron was the original TV audience
tracker but has ceded the job to Nielsen. With the Web, an infant
medium, the competitive situation is even more fluid.
</P>
<P>
   -- Media Metrix is expected to go public next month, which will
give it access to more capital. Like many Web companies it is
focused on growth and has never posted a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, a $402 million public company with 1998 profits of
$48.8 million, has the option of supporting its Internet division
with funds from its established operations. That could be an
advantage in the event of a protracted, expensive battle for market
share, although Bhatia said N/NR intends to become profitable as
soon as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
