<HEADLINE>
MAJOR FINANCIAL NEWS IN BRIEF
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNICREDITO MAKES OFFER FOR BANCA COMMERCIALE
</P>
<P>
   Unicredito Italiano, Italy's third-largest bank, said it would
offer to swap stock to buy out the smaller Banca Commerciale
Italiana and create a major European player that would be called
Eurobanca. The offer is worth around $16.4 billion. Unicredito said
merging the two Milan-based banks would create Europe's
fifth-largest lender in terms of assets and the seventh in terms of
stock market value. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEARING ON CHALLENGE TO MERGER
</P>
<P>
   A court in the Netherlands will hold a hearing Monday to
consider an opponent's effort to block the deal announced Friday
between the Gucci Group and the French investor Francois Pinnault. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW REPUBLIC GETS A NEW LOOK
</P>
<P>
   The New Republic, a weekly opinion magazine facing stagnant
circulation numbers, flat advertising revenue and an editorial
merry-go-round will get its first makeover in memory. The new
design begins with the April 12 issue. New Republic readers,
accustomed to pages dense with type, will now get internal color,
bold graphics, photographs, more illustrations and bigger type.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE PARTNERSHIPS FLOURISH
</P>
<P>
   Internet merchants are recruiting other Web sites to help sell
their goods. The partnerships range from deals between companies
with established brands to arrangements that retailers make with
individuals who have built personal home pages. Some retailers say
affiliate programs are becoming a crucial source of revenue because
advertising revenue cannot sustain most Internet businesses.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEET THE FAB 400
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment Weekly is creating what it calls the Fab 400,
focusing on what its editors consider to be the popular culture
milestones of the 1950s through 1990s. At the center of the program
are four themed issues of the magazine, which will be supplemented
by features on Entertainment Weekly sites on the World Wide Web and
related television programs.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GATES ON THE `DIGITAL INFRASTRUCTURE'
</P>
<P>
   Warner Books will begin selling a new 470-page book next week by
William H. Gates, chairman of Microsoft. It is a treatise on one of
Gates' favorite themes, the notion that just about every corporate
problem can be helped if not solved with the right hardware and
software, or ``digital infrastructure.'' The book never mentions
the continuing antitrust trial against the company now nearing its
end in Washington.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLUGGING A LONG-DISTANCE LEAK
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian inventor has patented software that can identify
personal long-distance calls made from telephones in the workplace.
Experts say anywhere from 10 to 30 percent of calling charges for
businesses are unreimbursed personal long-distance calls.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SNAP OPENS A NEW WEB PORTAL
</P>
<P>
   Snap, an Internet company partly owned by NBC, will introduce a
service Monday that is designed for users of the Internet who can
connect at high speeds. The site will be a showcase for bandwidth
intensive applications, like video clips and audio files, by making
them easier for users to find.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
