<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8735 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLERGY-BIOTECH-SFCHR     03-21 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLERGY-BIOTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIOTECH FIRMS TRYING TO NIP ALLERGIES IN THE BUD
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
T he blooms of spring, a source of joy for most of us, also fill
the air with pollen, causing stuffy noses and wheezy lungs for the
millions of people who suffer from hay fever and asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Those who dread the onset of the sneezing season might breath
easier in a few years, if biotech firms succeed in current efforts
to create a new class of drugs to nip hay fever and asthmatic
reactions to the bud.
</P>
<P>
   These potential remedies aim to go beyond today's antihistamine
pills, nasal sprays and steroid inhalers _ which treat hay fever
and asthma symptoms _ to attack the root causes of a body's
overreaction to pollen.
</P>
<P>
   But don't empty your medicine cabinets yet. Genentech Inc., the
company furthest along in developing these new hay fever blockers,
still has a huge hurdle to clear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Each month for the rest of the year, scientists working with
the South San Francisco biotech giant must inject some 1,100 hay
fever and asthma patients with a compound known as anti-IgE.
</P>
<P>
   If these test injections safely reduce hay fever and asthma
attacks, Genentech will seek Food and Drug Administration approval
next year to sell its new drug _ presumably under a catchier name.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Other experimental asthma drugs from biotech firms like
Seattle's Immunex Corp. are just beginning human tests, so they are
even further away from proving their safety and usefulness.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech firms have huge incentives to attack these respiratory
ailments. The American Academy of Allergy Asthma and Immunology
says 40 million of us suffer from allergic rhinitis, commonly known
as hay fever. Another 14 million Americans are afflicted with
asthma, a chronic swelling of the airways that can cause shortness
of breath _ with severe asthma attacks often triggered by hay fever
fits.
</P>
<P>
   Americans with hay fever and asthma spent roughly $6 billion
last year on prescription drugs to help them breath easier,
according to IMS Health Research.
</P>
<P>
   Homer Boushey, director of the University of California at San
Francisco's Asthma Research Center, has helped Genentech test its
anti-IgE compound on human volunteers. Boushey explained how the
drug tries to interrupt the hay fever cycle that can go on to
trigger asthma attacks.
</P>
<P>
   TRIGGERS IMMUNE SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   It all begins when pollen enters the nose, eyes or lungs. For
reasons not completely understood, in people who are allergy-prone,
the presence of invading pollen triggers the immune system to
produce extra amounts of an antibody known as IgE.
</P>
<P>
   As Boushey described it, IgE is a double agent in the war on
pollen. On the upside, IgE is one of several antibodies that sweep
free-floating pollen particles out of the bloodstream. That's good.
</P>
<P>
   But some IgE also binds to a certain type of cell _ called a
mast cell _ found in the mucosal lining of our airways. When this
``grounded'' IgE captures a pollen particle, it becomes a turncoat.
IgE and the pollen particle team up to trigger the mast cell to
release histamines and other chemicals associated with hay fever
and asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Umetsu, chief allergy and immunology researcher at Stanford
University, said the IgE-pollen-mast cell reaction amounts to an
immune system false alarm. Scientists think the histamine in mast
cells is meant to kill invading parasitic worms, not to attack
relatively harmless pollen that could be swept out by other bodily
defenses as simple as phlegm.
</P>
<P>
   RELEASING HISTAMINES
</P>
<P>
   But in people with allergies, IgE overproduction releases
histamines, whose effects can range from mild sneezing to serious
asthmatic attacks that can _ as happens over 5,000 times a year _
actually lead to death.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech is taking a deceptively simple approach to breaking
the allergy/asthma cycle.
</P>
<P>
   In the current trials, researchers will give patients monthly
shots of anti-IgE, a protein designed to seek out and bind to IgE
in the bloodstream. Robert Fick, Genentech's senior project
scientist, said the idea is to sop up the excess IgE before it can
land on a mast cell, team up with a pollen and cause a histamine
eruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Can IgE be removed from the body safely?''
Fick said. He hopes the tests will show that when anti-IgE
neutralizes excess IgE, other immune system agents _ the body has
backups for everything _ step in to remove pollen without IgE's
negative side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech's trial, which it is conducting with the help of the
Swiss drug firm Novartis and privately held Tanox Biosystems, is
designed with FDA regulators in mind. To win approval for the new
drug, Genentech must prove that anti-IgE's mopping-up action
greatly reduces the number and intensity of allergic or asthmatic
attacks in test patients.
</P>
<P>
   To amass this comparative data, Genentech will give half its
1,100 test patients a placebo. Neither the scientists nor the
patients know whether their monthly shots are the drug or the
placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, Genentech will compare the two groups _ those
with the placebo and those with anti-IgE _ and hope the data show
that the anti-IgE cohort had half as many allergy or asthma attacks
as the placebo group.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech would also like to show that patients treated with
anti-IgE made less use of inhaled steroids and other asthma drugs,
which can have their own side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with both sets of data _ proof that anti-IgE works and
that it reduces use of other medicines _ Genentech could make the
strongest case for FDA approval.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While Genentech is nearing the end of its test process,
Immunex is just beginning human trials on a drug that seeks to stop
the asthma reaction even earlier _ by disabling IL4, another immune
system protein, which plays a role in producing IgE.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Leung, editor of the Journal of Allergy and Clinical
Immunology in Denver, explained that IL4 is one of the chemicals
that is released when our immune system detects pollen inside the
body. Immunex intends to neutralize IL4 before it can stimulate the
production of IgE, heading off the allergic and asthmatic cascade
at an even earlier point.
</P>
<P>
   Immunex has so far only completed Phase I trials of its anti-IL4
drug, which it calls Nuvance. Those studies merely establish that
it seems safe to administer Nuvance to human subjects. An Immunex
spokesman said the company hopes to soon begin second-stage tests,
commending the long process of establishing whether or not Nuvance
helps control asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier still in the development cycle, privately held Rigel
Inc. is doing lab tests into the most fundamental level of the
allergy cycle. Don Payan, chief scientist at the South San
Francisco biotech startup, said scientists don't understand what
internal signals prompt immune system cells to make proteins like
IL4 or IgE.
</P>
<P>
   Rigel is trying to peer inside cells in the hopes of finding the
switch that can turn off the creation of such asthma-triggering
chemicals before they enter the bloodstream _ so we wouldn't need
other drugs like anti-IgE or Nuvance to perform their
search-and-destroy missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how biomedical discovery works,'' Payan said. ``Every
new advance creates a deeper understanding, and points to a new
drug strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Engelberg, who follows biotech finance for AmeriCal
Securities in San Francisco, said he doesn't pay too much attention
to scientific optimism until new drugs are almost ready for
pharmacists' shelves. He said it's still too early to estimate the
potential revenues of Genentech's anti-IgE, much less the earlier
stage efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But even if anti-IgE makes it to market, Engelberg questions
Genentech's marketing spiel. Genentech suggests consumers will find
rolling up their sleeves for a monthly shot of anti-IgE more
convenient than taking three to five pills and inhaled medications
each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most patients, given their druthers, would rather take
a pill or inhaler than a shot,'' Engelberg said. That would limit
use of anti-IgE to the sickest asthma patients, rather than the
larger group of hay fever sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   But Pamela Reed of Hayward is living proof that some people
would willingly brave a monthly needle to be freed from dependence
on a daily regime of pills, sprays and inhalers.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, 36, has suffered from allergy and asthma all her life.
Christmas is usually her worst season, because she's allergic to
pine. She recalls that it was during the holidays when she took
part in one of the earlier anti-IgE studies conducted by UCSF's
Boushey.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't tell me at the time whether I got the drug or
the placebo, but I was sure I got the anti-IgE,'' Reed said. ``Even
my husband noticed that my asthma didn't act up that winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who afterwards learned she was indeed part of the drugged
cohort, is hopeful that the final tests lead to approval.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I would gladly take the shot,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
