<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLERGYSIDE-RELIEF-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOW ALLERGY SUFFERERS CAN EASE THEIR PAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
In a couple of years, bioscience may create new drugs that can stop
allergies before the first sneeze. That's scant comfort during hay
fever season, but meanwhile there are steps allergy sufferers can
take to minimize or ward off problems.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alan Goldsobel, allergy doctor and president of the Northern
California Chapter of the Allergy and Asthma Foundation, had these
tips for hay fever and asthma sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Use air filtration system to limit exposure to indoor pollen.
Be pollen-aware when outdoors by using the National Allergy Bureau
Web site (www.aaaai.org/nab) to get daily pollen and mold counts.
</P>
<P>
   -- For serious conditions consult a physician. They can
prescribe new antihistamines, without the drowsy effects of older
remedies, and lung-opening inhalers. The American Academy of
Allergy, Asthma and Immunology (AAAAI) in Milwaukee, Wis., offers
free 24-hour physician referral at (800) 822-2762.
</P>
<P>
   -- The American Lung Association in New York is another source
of hay fever and asthma news. Reach it by phone at (800) 586-4872
or on the Web at www.lungusa.org _ and sign up for the Breathe Easy
Asthma Digest, a monthly e-mail newsletter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
