<SLUG> BC-POPCULTURE-ADCOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAB 400 SERIES LINKS MARKETERS TO POPULAR CULTURE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Beatles came to America, they were dubbed the Fab Four.
Thirty-five years later, an elaborate marketing and promotional
program centered on popular culture is being called the Fab 400.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the program is actually conflation, bringing
together advertisers and retailers seeking to associate themselves
with the growing American appetite for everything related to
entertainment, from celebrity biographies to box-office results to
awards shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about connecting with consumers through movies, music,
television and entertainers,'' said Michael J. Kelly, publisher at
Entertainment Weekly magazine in New York, ``looking at what has
shaped popular culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fab 400 is a project of Entertainment Weekly, part of the
Time Inc. unit of Time Warner Inc., focusing on what its editors
consider to be the popular culture milestones of the 1950s through
1990s. At the center of the program are four themed issues of the
magazine, which will be supplemented by features on Entertainment
Weekly sites on the World Wide Web (www.ew.com and www.fab400.com)
and related television programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see more people tying into the passion for pop culture to
reach the consumer,'' said Fred O. Nelson, vice president for
marketing and promotion at Entertainment Weekly, particularly ``the
young, urban entertainment junkie who buys the CD the week it's
released and sees the movie the weekend it comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishing executives at the magazine assert that such a culture
vulture is also on the cutting edge of consumerism _ likely to be,
as Nelson put it, ``the first to test-drive a new car, buy a new
fashion, try a new fragrance.''
</P>
<P>
   One marketer agreeing with that assessment is the Ford Motor Co.
Its Mercury brand of vehicles is a lead advertiser of the Fab 400,
both in the pages of the magazine and as the sole sponsor of an
online reader poll on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entertainment is highly relevant to the Mercury target we call
the individualists, the people who paddle their own canoe,'' said
Ian Beavis, marketing communications manager for the Lincoln
Mercury division of Ford in Irvine, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the opposite of all the other millennium proposals
that crossed our desks,'' he added, referring to programs from
other magazines related to 20th-century achievement and history.
``We didn't have one person not say it was a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   (How far the Mercury marque makes it into the next millennium
may be under discussion at Ford. USA Today reported on Friday that
after Ford recently announced plans to discontinue selling most
Mercury cars in Canada, automotive industry analysts suggested a
similar fate awaited the brand in the United States. Ford said the
Canadian cutback was not related to marketing plans for this
country.)
</P>
<P>
   The retail partner for the Fab 400 described the initial results
of the program as ``tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a true pop culture synergy going on,'' said Christos
Garkinos, vice president for marketing and product management in
Los Angeles for the Virgin Entertainment Group unit of Virgin
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The Virgin Megastore chain is promoting merchandise that can be
linked to the content of the four Fab 400 issues. For instance, in
connection with the first issue, published last month and devoted
to ``the 100 greatest moments in television,'' there were special
displays in the stores featuring tapes of television programs,
music from television soundtracks and books devoted to television
series like ``The Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The next issue of the Fab 400, due on May 28, will present ``the
100 defining moments in music.'' The movie issue is planned for
Sept. 24 and the one on ``the 100 greatest entertainers'' for Nov.
8. Each issue will have a rate base, the circulation guaranteed to
advertisers, of 1.55 million, 8.8 percent higher than the regular
Entertainment Weekly rate base of 1.425 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said some of the marketers in addition to Mercury that
had agreed to run ads were the Disney Channel unit of Walt Disney
Co., Hershey Foods Corp., the MTV and VH1 cable networks owned by
Viacom Inc., Philip Morris Cos. and Visa USA.
</P>
<P>
   As for the television tie-ins with the Fab 400, there is a
commitment from MTV for a music program in May, Nelson said, adding
that there are discussions with the TNT cable network, which like
Entertainment Weekly is part of Time Warner, for a show tied to the
entertainers issue.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Fab Four will be part of the Fab 400?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
