<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EGYPT-BALLOON22-COX     03-21 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-BALLOON22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BALLOONISTS, BACK ON EARTH, SPEAK OF IDEAL LIFE IN THE CLOUDS
 &HT;    670&AMP;adds.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ A day after they flew into history with the first
nonstop balloon trip around the world, Bertrand Piccard and Brian
Jones tried Sunday to explain the meaning of their voyage.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 21 days dangling miles above Earth in a small
capsule, they were entitled to some high-flown rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   For Piccard, the philosophical Swiss psychiatrist and scion of a
line of adventurers, the rigorous journey was a ``metaphor for
life'' _ about confronting the fear of the unknown and accepting
forces that cannot be controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Their trip had set, Piccard said, an ideal example of man's
place in nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not nature on one side and human beings trying to
make an advantage on the other side,'' he explained. ``There is no
separation between technology and ecology. There is a harmony, and
we lived 21 days in that harmony. It was absolutely beautiful, and
this is also something we want to share with you.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jones, a no-nonsense British balloon pilot, the trip was the
ultimate expression his craft. He noted that a balloon
circumnavigation of the globe has been sought since long before
there were airplanes, and long after all the feats of winged
aviation had been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the ultimate challenge for a balloon pilot,'' he
said. ``To anybody who would say it is frivolous, I would say you
simply don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Both appeared in good health, but tired. It had been a long day
for Jones, a 51-year-old grandfather, and Piccard, a 41-year-old
father of three girls.
</P>
<P>
   The pair completed a full trip around the globe over western
Africa on Saturday. They touched down early Sunday in the
southwestern Egyptian desert at dawn, when their 9-ton craft could
avoid the troubling winds that build as the desert day heats up.
</P>
<P>
   Steered by the winds to a remote area, they tried to set down
near one of the few roads in southwestern Egypt. But when they hit
the desert surface, ice that formed during the craft's
high-altitude flight broke free, and the balloon ``bounced'' 500
feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   It bounced again on a second approach, then landed smoothly, two
hours later than planned and on a hard-to-reach plateau about 300
miles southwest of Cairo, near the sparsely populated oasis region
of Dakhla.
</P>
<P>
   Though the balloon quickly deflated and lay on the ground, the
wind grabbed it and pulled the gondola nearly on its side. Piccard
and Jones cut holes in it to let the wind pass through.
</P>
<P>
   They tried to sleep, but ice water dripping into the gondola
kept Piccard awake. Both men washed their hair with leftover water
from their trip, and passed time contemplating the ancient deserts
in which their high-tech craft had deposited them.
</P>
<P>
   The rocky terrain thwarted a ground recovery by their chase
team, and roughly six hours after their landing, an Egyptian army
helicopter picked up the pair.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said it was fitting that they would be totally alone for
the first hours after emerging from the 18-foot-long metal capsule
they had shared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see absolutely nothing on any horizon, and it just
seemed right somehow,'' he said. ``We had time to collect our
thoughts, to get ourselves together.''
</P>
<P>
   Piccard said, ``It is incredible how well you can feel when you
are in front of emptiness, because you are really in front of
yourself,'' he said much later at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   And, the pair felt pretty good about themselves. They had
floated 29,056 miles since taking off from the Swiss Alps on March
1 on the third attempt sponsored by Swiss watchmaker Breitling.
</P>
<P>
   Though the trip cost untold millions of dollars _ the sponsor
refuses to disclose the costs _ the pair will receive a $1 million
prize from the Anheuser Busch brewing giant. Half will be donated
to a charity, and the two will divide the other $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   They said it won't be the money that will leave the biggest mark
on their lives. Piccard says he feels closer to God, thanks to the
``invisible hand'' that guided their craft.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The balloon crew withstood foul air and 45-degree temperatures
as their sealed pressurized cabin sailed in the swift jet stream
winds 30,000 feet above the planet. Piccard and Jones said they
alternately shored up each others' spirits during the trip.
</P>
<P>
   They had a third passenger _ a teddy bear named ``Sean'' given
to them by an airline crew member. Jones took a couple of books he
never had time to open. They listened to compact discs, including
the score to Les Miserables and selections from Eric Clapton.
</P>
<P>
   Piccard said the trip's worst period was over the Gulf of
Mexico, when they were sick and considered stopping because the air
currents had stalled. But they climbed to higher altitudes and
caught winds that moved them at more than 100 miles an hour across
the Atlantic and to their goal.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the two never exchanged a ``cross word.'' Piccard
came to tears a couple times as he met with reporters at an air
base immediately after their recovery.
</P>
<P>
   He would later describe their 21 days as ``paradise,'' but noted
that many of the countries they passed over were far from peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really heartbreaking to think that while we were having
so much pleasure there were people suffering on the ground,''
Piccard said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he looks forward to his place in the history books
and expects to get ``15 minutes'' as a hero at home in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   A sign of their new celebrity, the pair faced a gantlet of
photographers and well-wishers as they entered the Swissotel/El
Salam(cq) Hotel in Cairo on Sunday night. A quartet, in robes and
turbans, played traditional Arab music at the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Noble, the flight controller who had flown to Egypt on
Saturday after directing the voyage from a control tower at the
Geneva Airport, tried to explain how the trip played on people's
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the troubles in the world, Kosovo and such, here's a
story people can really like,'' he said, looking sunburnt from four
hours of trying to approach the balloon by car in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the Egyptian army to take another helicopter trip out
to the desert in order to recover the huge balloon and gondola,
which was left tilted on its side on rocky, hilly terrain that no
truck could cross.
</P>
<P>
   In the land of the pyramids and the Sphinx, he noted that
Egyptians are expert at recovering historic artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out there,'' he said, ``is a historic artifact.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
