<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ IS KIND TO ORLANDO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ Shaquille O'Neal's much-anticipated annual return to
the city he once dismissed as ``a dried-up little pond'' was
supposed to be another hate-fest, but turned into a shocking
display of nothing but peace, love and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   There were no taunts directed to the sellout crowd of 17,248, no
postgame crowing session after beating his old team 115-104, and
shockingly, not a single unkind word about the city that loves to
hate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``How the hell can I dislike the whole (bleeping) city? That
don't make no sense,'' O'Neal said afterward, abandoning his
formerly spiteful stance. ``It's a beautiful city, the people here
are beautiful, but we all do things in life. I don't regret what I
did three years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago'' being the July 1996 day he decided to pack
up his dunks and rap lyrics, and head to Hollywood and the promise
of $121 million from the Lakers. O'Neal, a the No. 1 draft pick in
1992 and the Magic's franchise player for four years, still has a
home here but has taken plenty of potshots at the city and team in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   And the city has fired back. Last year the fans booed lustily
and the public address system cranked tunes aimed at him such as
``Lies, Lies, Lies'' and ``Money Changes Everything.'' The Magic
won that game, and former teammate Nick Anderson openly mocked
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The booing was less frequent this time, as O'Neal scored 16
first-half points, and anti-Shaq signs were few.
</P>
<P>
   ``No human can hurt my feelings by what they say or by what they
write or by what they show on TV,'' O'Neal said. ``Nobody can hurt
my feelings. The reason they boo me is because they respect me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing special in the win?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good win for us, I'm glad we won,'' he said. ``I'm
glad to see my old friends in some of the media, some of the
organization, some on the team. . . . All that stuff that happened
three years ago, I forgot about it a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Harper, who played for the Magic last season, said he
sensed the win meant a little more than O'Neal let on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he wants to do well against this team,'' he said.
``He obviously was a huge piece of what they wanted to do as a
basketball team and a franchise, and he left. You have to move on
in life. That can't linger. It's a business and you deal with it
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: J.R. Reid did not play for the first time in six
games since joining the Lakers and was reported to have a swollen
left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The injury could pave the way for an anticipated move _ the
activation of rookie guard Tyronn Lue from the injured list. The
Lakers are overloaded on forwards again with the return of Dennis
Rodman but are carrying only four guards on the active roster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
