</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ST.JOHN'S-OHIOSTATE-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S LOOKING TO THE FUTURE, WITH OR WITHOUT ARTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tyrone Grant had finally poked his head out of the tent of
towels he had constructed in his despair after St. John's lost the
South Regional final to Ohio State, 77-74, on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Erick Barkley weeping beside him, Grant, the team jester,
now speaking in a whisper, was able to put this season in
perspective: ``I'm very happy the young guys got this experience.
Going into the season, they'll know how good they can be. As long
as Coach Jarvis doesn't change a thing, I don't see anything but
success for the young players.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis' Red Storm played perhaps its worst game of the
season Saturday night in Knoxville, Tenn., beaten in the backcourt
and intimidated in the frontcourt by Ohio State. It was a terrible
way for a terrific season to end.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody had expected the Red Storm to get within a few
seconds of the Final Four. St. John's did not appear in any
preseason polls, and there were plenty of questions about how
quickly the players, some of whom had considered leaving after Fran
Fraschilla was fired as coach, would take to Jarvis. During the
search for Fraschilla's replacement, Ron Artest, who would become
the focal point of the team, said he hoped the school would not
hire a knucklehead.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't. Even though Jarvis told his players on their first
day of practice that he agreed they could win a championship, he
knew that realistically it would be at least two years, and
probably three or four more players, before this sort of run was
possible. So despite the devastation in the locker room over the
mental mistakes that cost St. John's a rematch with Connecticut in
the national semifinal, this season was a resounding success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very encouraged to know that old-fashioned things like
teamwork and fundamentals and hard work still pay off,'' Jarvis
said. ``What you learn when you coach kids is that anything can
happen. Until they get to the point where they're older and more
mature, they're not going to get to the point of being consistent
every night. They're amateurs, and sometimes they are made to play
like amateurs. There's always a chance you're going to revert back
to old habits.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes will be made for next season, but by failing to make the
Final Four, St. John's may have averted a personnel switch it does
not want: Jarvis, who has never denied his interest in a NBA job,
was already being mentioned for a pro position. That talk will
probably cool for a while.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Jarvis will get Anthony Glover, who was
academically ineligible this season. Glover is a 6-foot-5-inch
forward so tough that Jarvis said of him, ``If Anthony Glover plays
Saturday, we win.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Ohio State center Ken Johnson, Jarvis added,
``After he blocked that first shot, Anthony would have put him 10
rows up, and he would have been looking over his shoulder the rest
of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis needs more depth. The bench gave him just seven points
against the Buckeyes. He needs a defensive stopper at guard, which
was obvious when Michael Redd scored 20 points for the Buckeyes. He
would like a big man, because he views the 6-10 signee Jack
Wolfinger as more of a long-term investment, and because 6-9 Carlos
Boozer, one of the top recruits in the country, is also considering
Duke and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   He would like a backup to Barkley, a splendid guard whom Jarvis
will be lucky to keep around beyond next season. And Jarvis talks
of the need to improve the attitude and maturity of the team. Some
little-used players will almost certainly be gone.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fate of Artest hangs over all this. His abysmal
performance against Ohio State showed why his game would benefit
from at least one more year in college. Artest had just nine points
and played only 11 minutes of the first half after picking up two
quick fouls and committing five turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   He played as if his mind were elsewhere, and it most likely
already is. After the game, Artest said the chances were 50-50 that
he would take his versatile but immature game to the NBA draft this
summer. But almost nobody believes he will return to St. John's,
especially because some scouts peg him as a lottery pick. Artest,
who has cited his desire to help his family as a prime factor in
his decision, said he would take a few days to think it over.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jarvis' job may be easier next season even if Artest leaves.
Artest is a huge talent, but he has also shown flashes of
hardheadedness and selfishness that have irritated his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that he will get some spiritual guidance as well as
monetary guidance before he makes the decision,'' Jarvis said.
``Whatever he decides to do, St. John's will continue to grow and
get better. It would be a tremendous loss, but if we're going to
build a great program, we're going to suffer great losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Artest's decision, the standard for success has been
raised sharply. A tournament run this year was a gleeful surprise.
Next season, it will be a requirement. This year, St. John's
players were alone in thinking they belonged in the Final Four.
Next year, the crowd of expectations will close in.
</P>
</TEXT>
