<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KERSHAW-HITLER-2TAKES     03-21 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KERSHAW-HITLER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECIPHERING HITLER AND THE NATION THAT NURTURED HIM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ian Kershaw was hard to miss. He was the one walking
around the Roosevelt Hotel in Manhattan with a picture of Hitler.
OK, it was an early photograph and it was on the cover of his new
book, ``Hitler, 1889-1936: Hubris'' (W.W. Norton), but anyway, he
stood out.
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, Kershaw, professor of modern history at the
University of Sheffield in England, has spent the last decade in
the shadow of Hitler, whom he calls ``the most central figure of
our century, possibly the most central figure of all.''
</P>
<P>
   A result, the first half of a two-volume biography that seeks to
demythologize Hitler and re-examine the environment from which he
sprang, has been received warmly by scholars and critics on both
sides of the Atlantic. Kershaw was in New York recently to
publicize his book, the first Hitler biography to make full use of
the diaries of Josef Goebbels, which were recently discovered in
Moscow. Goebbels, Hitler's minister of propaganda, portrays a
formative Hitler prone to bumbling and vacillation.
</P>
<P>
   In The New York Times Book Review Walter Reich, a former
director of the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum, praised Kershaw's
``masterly analysis'' and said he ``successfully illuminates the
strange and at times ecstatic dance in which Hitler and Germany
engaged as his power grew.''
</P>
<P>
   So what was it like to live so long in the company of a
repulsive figure who, in Kershaw's words, ``has not the slightest
attractive feature?''
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, he said in the sonorous northern burr of his native
Manchester, he approached his task as the medieval historian he has
long been, with an eye to exhaustive research and detached
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   On the other he was dealing with Hitler. ``That does grab hold
of you,'' he said. ``The moral dimension really does intervene.''
</P>
<P>
   What finally overwhelmed him, he said, were the personal tales
of anguish. He was going through the large Jewish archival
collection in a Vienna library, reading account after account of
family torments, when he felt ``almost physically nauseated and had
to go outside for a breath of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   He posed the next logical question: ``Numerous people said, `For
goodness sake, why are you working on this? It's so horrible. Why
not work on the Renaissance or papal history?' But it always struck
me it was of such vital importance to the 20th century.'' He
continued, ``This is not very long ago, and yet it seems to be on
another planet.''
</P>
<P>
   His detour from medieval history began almost 30 years ago when
he began learning German to read monastic records for a planned
work on peasant protests in medieval Europe. In 1972 he found
himself in Grafing outside Munich where, on a rainy Sunday
afternoon, he stopped at a cafe and fell into conversation with one
of the locals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to talking about the 30s,'' Kershaw recalled. ``I said
it must have been a bad time. He said, `Best times we ever had.'
Then he said: `You English, you missed the real chance here. You
should have come in the war with us. Together we would have
defeated the Bolsheviks and conquered the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Kershaw said he was trying to contain his astonishment when the
man blurted, ``The Jew is a louse.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode, he said, made him ponder what had gone on in that
little town and in Germany as a whole. He joined a research project
on Bavaria under the Nazis, studying the grass roots of German
society while scholarly debate was polarizing around the question
of Hitler's centrality. Was he the only one who mattered in the
Third Reich? Or, at the other extreme, was he a weak dictator
carried along by outside forces?
</P>
<P>
   There were many other questions, Kershaw said. Given Germany's
problems after World War I, it was not surprising that a strongman
would emerge. But how did a rank outsider like Hitler, with no
apparent talents beyond rabble-rousing in Munich beer halls, even
get close to the corridors of power?
</P>
<P>
   ``Before 1918 nobody sees or listens to him,'' Kershaw said.
``Then suddenly, as he says, `I can speak,' he finds he's got a
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``The answer is to be found more in the changed
circumstances in German society following the lost war and
revolution than it is in Hitler's personal attributes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitler's supposed physical abnormalities and sexual proclivities
interest him far less than they did, say, Ron Rosenbaum, in his
book, ``Explaining Hitler.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a character, who knows?'' Kershaw said of Hitler's
reputed penchant for masochism. ``I suppose it's possible.''
Efforts to document these and other such accounts proved fruitless.
``I searched worldwide for a picture of Hitler in the bathtub with
Eva Braun and failed to find it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most lurid stories about Hitler turn out to be shakily
sourced or spread by Hitler's enemies, Kershaw said. If Hitler was
masochistic or had unusual sexual tastes, ``what would it explain
about the development of the Third Reich?''
</P>
<P>
   There was no point in searching for the moment when Hitler
became Hitler, Kershaw said. It was a process, a cursed confluence
of the man and his times. Hitler came close to getting killed or
sidetracked on innumerable occasions before he led the world to
bloodshed, Kershaw said, but each time, to the world's colossal
misfortune, fate contrived to save him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luck of the devil,'' said Kershaw.
</P>
<P>
   Stories that Hitler had Jewish forebears, spread by the
condemned Hans Frank at Nuremberg, do not stand up, Kershaw said,
distancing himself as well from other sources he called dubious,
including Herman Rauschning's ``Hitler Speaks'' and the
``table-talk'' monologues supposedly transcribed in Hitler's
bunker.
</P>
<P>
   He said Hitler's deep hatred of Jews almost certainly did not
stem from any single encounter, as Hitler claimed in ``Mein
Kampf,'' but rather from associating Jews with the ``November
criminals'' who supposedly cost Germany World War I and plunged
Munich into chaotic Socialist rule.
</P>
<P>
   Like other scholars, Kershaw found no directive or utterance
from Hitler ordering the Final Solution, the extermination of the
Jews. ``Hitler never spoke, as far as we can tell, even in private,
about specific killing,'' he said. ``He spoke always in grandiose
terms, horrific but generalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kershaw said he found an intriguing entry in Heinrich
Himmler's desk diary, which came to light in Moscow only after the
fall of Communism. In an entry recording a private meeting with
Hitler on Dec. 18, 1941, Himmler, the SS chief, wrote ``Jewish
question'' on one side of the page and on the other, ``Jews to be
rooted out as partisans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings him as close as anything you're going to find, I
guess,'' Kershaw said. The disclosure is reported in the
biography's second volume, to be released next year.  &QL; 
(MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Why was the viciously anti-Semitic Hitler so careful to distance
himself from the slaughter? He was secretive by nature, Kershaw
said, but his rationale remains a mystery. Perhaps in an odd way,
he said, Hitler feared the Jews as more powerful even than the
Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   The hazards of putting incriminating words on paper, moreover,
became clear to Hitler after he was maneuvered into personally
authorizing the euthanasia program in 1939. When the Roman Catholic
Church later questioned the killings, he was exposed.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, said Kershaw, there was almost certainly no
Hitlerian Rosetta stone to be unearthed, despite new material about
the SS and killing squads likely to emerge from the former Soviet
bloc.
</P>
<P>
   If Hitler is a biographer's biggest challenge, he will probably
always remain so, a ``black hole'' to scholars, Kershaw said.
``Outside of his politics, he doesn't exist really.''
</P>
<P>
   The biographer himself has few memories of the war. Born in 1943
in Oldham, outside Manchester, he and his family largely were
spared suffering, although a few stray German V-1 rockets destined
for Manchester landed on Oldham.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother has graphic descriptions,'' he said. ``I'm in her
arms, there's the whine as the engine cuts out and then a crash.
I've dreamed of it. In my dream it's as if I'm there, but it's only
because she told me about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
