<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF A POINT GUARD COSTS CONNECTICUT A TRIP TO THE FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Although top-seeded Connecticut was favored to win
the Mideast Regional and advance to the Final Four, Iowa State had
one thing that the talent-rich Huskies did not _ a point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a great point guard is essential to being really good
in this tournament,'' UConn coach Geno Auriemma said, following his
team's 64-58 loss to the Cyclones on Saturday night in the NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-seeded Cyclones had that floor leader in Stacy Frese.
The junior guard scored 16 points, had five assists and was almost
flawless in the closing minutes at the Shoemaker Center. The
Cyclones hit five of their final seven 3-point attempts in the
closing minutes to clinch the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut finished the season at 29-5 after a 15-0 start. The
Huskies' struggles date to late December, when freshman point guard
Sue Bird tore the anterior cruciate ligament in her left knee. At
the time, the Huskies were 8-0. Since then, they often relied on
their two best scorers, Svetlana Abrosimova and Shea Ralph, to
handle the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the pair struggle running the offense in the
halfcourt, but the burden of handling the ball disrupted their
scoring responsibilities. The pressure on Abrosimova and Ralph was
most apparent on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph was 2-of-12 from the field and 0-of-9 from 3-point range.
Abrosimova missed 16 of her 19 shots, including 7-of-8 3-pointers.
She also committed seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different every night,'' said Ralph when asked who runs
UConn's offense, adding that the team really needed a floor leader.
``Svet and I have such a scorers' mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma played down Bird's injury as a factor in his team's not
advancing. He said his young team, which featured the top freshman
class in the nation, was not mentally prepared for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of younger players who are not quite able to get
over the hump yet, and it's a mental thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, who lose only one key contributor, senior Amy
Duran, figure to be a preseason top three team next season, and
perhaps No. 1. But Auriemma said his team must be more attacking,
more relentless to perform better in the NCAA tournament next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so tired of people saying how talented our freshman class
is,'' Auriemma said. ``This time of year, nobody cares how talented
you are. People only respond to aggression.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
