</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKn-LAKERS-RODMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN SAYS HE'S BACK TO STAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ Dennis Rodman returned to the Lakers on Sunday _ a
significant event because he says he considered not returning at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman arrived at 1 a.m. Sunday and just nine hours later
rejoined his teammates, ending an eight-day sabbatical during which
he attended to vague ``personal issues'' and cleared his head at
the craps tables in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the problems were, they are resolved for now, and
Rodman said he's back for the duration of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People gotta understand that you can't control Dennis Rodman.
He has to make his own decisions,'' Rodman said. ``Everything's
fine. All you guys wanna guess it's this or that, personal
problems, marriage, it had nothing to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to get away, because I didn't know if I really
wanted to play basketball. Even though we won 10 games in a row,
that still wasn't satisfying for me, to go out there and play and
to be snubbed by the NBA. And the lifestyle of being in L.A., I had
to fix that and visualize that.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't elaborate. Rodman had complained even before he signed
with the Lakers that the NBA's labor agreement restricted his
income _ to about $12,195 per game or $1 million in a normal,
full-length season.
</P>
<P>
   While Rodman was vague over what prompted his flight, he said
the issues have ``subsided, and I can go out there and just kind of
focus on what I can do. . . . I think people have to understand
this is me. Just let me do what I gotta do and everything will be
all right. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you're a basketball player, you're a human being. And
you've got to take care of that person first. The hell with this
game. This game don't mean anything to me. I'll always be happy as
long as I can keep my head (straight).''
</P>
<P>
   He thought seriously about retiring, but his actress wife,
Carmen Electra, talked him out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmen told me, `Dennis, go out there, suck it up and do it.
Just do it. I know you love the game,' '' he said. ``She's the only
one who really hasn't pressured me to do anything. She just said,
`I'm behind you 100 percent. If you want to quit, quit. If you
don't, just go out there and win.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There were no warm welcome-backs from teammates, just an
acknowledgment that the absence was essentially forgiven, and
everyone was grateful to have his defense and rebounding skills
back on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't expecting these guys to come over and shake my hand
or kiss my butt, anything like that,'' Rodman said, and he offered
no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to do that. I won't do that. Actions speak louder
than words. . . . My teammates know I'm gonna go out there and give
what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Are teammates forgiving?
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``It doesn't do us
any good to harbor ill feelings or resentment or anything like
that. . . . They wish it hadn't happened, but they're all fine with
him coming back and they're happy that he is back.''
</P>
<P>
   Said co-captain Shaquille O'Neal: ``We all said what we had to
say to him, and he said he's gonna be back the rest of the year. He
said he has some personal problems . . . but you just have to
respect the guy, and our organization was gracious enough to let
him go to Vegas and gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman said he was fined $700, or $100 per day. The team
initially called the absence ``excused,'' but imposed the fine once
Rodman extended his leave and detoured to Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Another such incident, and the Lakers would probably cut him
loose.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman said he was given no ultimatum upon his return but noted:
``I've used up my hall pass. I'll be here for the rest of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Converse has severed its shoe contract with Rodman,
allegedly reneging on a deal to pay him $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Converse wants to kind of screw me and take my money like
everybody else wants to screw me and take my money,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
