<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEINTS AND PARRIES APLENTY IN THE BATTLE FOR GUCCI  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The Netherlands, France, Italy)   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Earlier this month, over a lunch of baked fish at the
Paris town house of Francois Pinault, Domenico de Sole began
thinking he might be home safe.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole, 54, chief executive of the Gucci &UR;  &LR; group, found he had
quite a bit in common with Pinault, one of France's brashest and
most unconventional venture capitalists. Pinault, 62, who owns
France's biggest department store chain, Au Printemps, and the
London auction house, Christie's, had been mulling an entry into
the luxury goods business for about two years.
</P>
<P>
   On-again-off-again talks had taken place between Pinault and
Sanofi &UR;  &LR; SA, France's No. 2 drug maker, to buy Sanofi's cosmetics
and fashion units, which included the rights to such high-end
brands as Yves Saint Laurent and Oscar de la Renta. But in the end,
Sanofi's brands, as attractive as they were, were not judged to be
the ``right entry point,'' as one of Pinault's advisers put it.
</P>
<P>
   Enter de Sole. Since January, he had been feinting and parrying
to fend off a hostile bid for control of Gucci by another powerful
French investor, Bernard Arnault, the 49-year-old chairman of LVMH
Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the world's biggest maker of luxury
goods.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, de Sole objected to the shape of the LVMH offer.
Arnault was not willing to make a bid for all Gucci's outstanding
shares. Instead, using a technique he had honed carefully in
previous acquisitions, Arnault had assembled a 34 percent stake,
and was now seeking a voice on Gucci's board. For de Sole, that was
tantamount to opening the chicken coop to the wolf; Vuitton, one of
the jewels in Arnault's crown, was a head-on competitor of Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole, a lawyer by training, tried all the defensive tricks.
In February, he announced the creation of an employee stock option
plan that would increase Gucci's capital by issuing 20 million new
Gucci shares and dilute the Arnault stake. But Arnault countered by
dragging Gucci to court in the Netherlands, where Gucci is
incorporated, and the Dutch court ordered the two sides to
negotiate an amicable settlement.
</P>
<P>
   These developments attracted the attention of Pinault, who used
the investment bank Morgan Stanley Dean Witter to line up a meeting
with de Sole. Their first encounter took place March 8 in London,
where Pinault ``wanted the deal done immediately,'' said an
executive who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At the Paris lunch at his town house four days later, Pinault
was joined by the chief executive of his Pinault-Printemps-Redoute
group, Serge Weinberg. Accompanying de Sole was Gucci's chief
creative director, Tom Ford. The Gucci executives already had
concluded that the value of the Gucci brand had been mined nearly
to its limits. For further growth, they decided they needed a
multi-brand strategy. From such considerations an intricate plan
emerged:
</P>
<P>
   Pinault would proceed with a deal using his holding company,
Artemis, to take over the Sanofi brands. He would then use
Printemps to acquire a controlling stake in Gucci. As the final
step, Gucci would then acquire the Sanofi brands from Artemis to
form the nucleus of a global luxury goods producer _ one large
enough to compete even with giants like Arnault.
</P>
<P>
   Working at a fast pace, the companies had the terms of their
agreement drawn up and placed before Gucci's board, which approved
it. The deal was announced Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Gucci is the right company,'' Weinberg, 49, said in
an interview. ``We thought with them, we could really build a new
luxury goods group. We see a very good fit.''
</P>
<P>
   De Sole agrees. ``Pinault is not a competitor,'' he said in an
interview, ``and he is giving us $3 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Aligning Gucci with the much larger Printemps, whose 1998 sales,
at $18 billion, were double those of LVMH, would benefit Gucci.
Since de Sole and Ford took Gucci public in 1995, sales have
exploded to more than $1 billion. Gucci has weathered the crisis in
Asia well, and the sex appeal of its brand is unchallenged among
the young and acquisitive. Pinault has the cash and the
distribution reach to be of benefit to Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, if successful would eliminate Gucci's weakness _
vulnerability to takeover.
</P>
<P>
   But if de Sole and Printemps liked the idea of their fit,
Arnault thought otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, he began a counteroffer on Friday for all of the
Gucci shares he did not yet own. Then he petitioned the court in
the Netherlands to invalidate the Gucci-Pinault deal. A hearing is
set for Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault's executives openly accuse de Sole of a double standard.
In the past, de Sole has argued that the offer by Arnault offended
his sense of fair play, since LVMH sought to take control of Gucci
by buying only a majority stake and not making a tender offer to
all shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet de Sole, LVMH argues, has no apparent objections to
Pinault's doing exactly that _ controlling Gucci with only a 40
percent stake, hardly more than Arnault himself now holds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, laws in the Netherlands, allow such a tactic, known as a
creeping takeover. Pinault and Gucci contend that they have a
watertight case for the Dutch court. Their deal was signed in Paris
Friday morning and they say there is nothing in the Dutch court's
earlier ruling that bars the Gucci board from entering into such a
pact.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Gucci's board met in Amsterdam to discuss its
options. Gucci is expected to make a statement Monday morning,
before the courts, and the markets, open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
