<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS STUMBLE ON ROAD AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ To say that the Sonics experience uneasy times
away from KeyArena would be putting their situation mildly.
</P>
<P>
   The road has been downright brutal.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Sonics could blame their 3-7 road record
on the absence of simple basketball luck, having lost several tight
games in the final two minutes. However, about the only thing
gut-wrenching about Friday night's 90-78 loss to Golden State at
Oakland Arena was the Sonics' performance.
</P>
<P>
   In having their three-game losing streak snapped, the Sonics
brought very little to the court.
</P>
<P>
   No intensity. No baskets. No answer for a Golden State team that
had lost four straight but dominated from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not done the little things,'' said Sonics forward
Detlef Schrempf, who led the team with 21 points off the bench.
``We do a lot of the little things wrong when on the road you need
everything to win.''
</P>
<P>
   With point guard Gary Payton shooting 5 of 19, the Sonics played
with a huge void in their offense. The team shot just 34 percent
and tied a season-low with 23 field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Payton had company in the shooting doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker was 2-for-11 and Dale Ellis missed all eight of his
shots.
</P>
<P>
   One would have never known that the Sonics were coming off two
days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make shots it's a ballgame,'' Ellis said. `` ... We're
just not getting it done. We're just too inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics knew they were in for a long night from the start.
</P>
<P>
   After Payton hit a 3-pointer that put the Sonics ahead 3-0,
Seattle missed its next eight shots.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State went on a monstrous 16-0 run, scoring effortlessly
from inside and out. The Warriors were particularly forceful around
the rim while the Sonics seemed flatfooted.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect example was when 5-foot-3 Muggsy Bogues rebounded
Antawn Jamison's missed jumper. Bogues then fed Jamison, who cut to
the basket for an easy layup. The Sonics fell behind 26-9 on that
play, and they managed to score just 15 points in the opening
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a fast-starting team. We watched them on tape,''
Schrempf said. `` ... That (first quarter) set the tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden State's younger legs and aggressive play kept the Sonics
befuddled. The Warriors twice held 19-point leads in the second
quarter. Although the Sonics cut the deficit to 51-40 at the break,
the Warriors never relinquished a double-digit lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no acceptable explanation _ we respected the
Warriors,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``We didn't come in
thinking they couldn't take it to us. They've been a real
successful team at home. ... There's no reason not to match their
aggressiveness, but we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics finally welcomed back swingman Billy Owens, who
played after missing the past two games with a sore left knee. But
Owens did little to help. He played just four minutes and collected
two points _ all in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal frantically searched for someone to provide energy so
he inserted rookie Vladimir Stepania in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Stepania's energy _ on the boards and defensively _ compelled
Westphal to start him in place of Ellis in the second half.
Westphal, who searched for a sparkplug all night, even used
19-year-old rookie Rashard Lewis when Stepania got into foul
trouble with 8:22 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed some energy,'' Westphal said. ``We were sleepwalking
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepania gave the Sonics somewhat of a lift. Asked whether the
6-foot-11 forward would receive more playing time, Westphal said:
``I would think so. If a guy hustles as much as he does, we'll have
to find a place for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepania might be called upon to fulfill Baker's role.
</P>
<P>
   Baker also did not start the second half after suffering a
sprained right thumb in the second quarter. He went back on the
floor with 5:37 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to win the game,'' said Baker, who was in pain after
the game. ``It was hurting, but it would have been hurting worse
just sitting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he had already been advised to rest his injury three
to four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not going to wait,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   And the Sonics can't continue their lull on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to win on the road,'' Baker said. ``Teams are
playing well against us when we come to their gym. ... Regardless
of our record, teams come ready to play the Sonics. We have to
match their intensity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
