u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRI     03-21 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE TO MEET MILOSEVIC IN FINAL PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Expands and updates earlier story.)  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration on Sunday dispatched a
special envoy, Richard Holbrooke, to meet with Slobodan Milosevic
in what senior officials described as a ``last chance'' to persuade
the Yugoslav leader to accept a peace agreement for Kosovo and
avoid bombing by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after President Clinton warned that the Serbs had gone
beyond ``the threshold'' of violence in their southern province,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said she was sending
Holbrooke to present Milosevic with a ``stark choice.''
</P>
<P>
   That choice, she said, was for him to agree to the settlement
signed in Paris last week by the ethnic Albanians who make up most
of Kosovo's population, or face NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   As Holbrooke prepared to leave on Sunday night, Milosevic's
forces appeared unintimidated, however. Taking advantage of the
absence of more than 1,300 international monitors who withdrew from
Kosovo on Saturday, they continued their rampage through Kosovo,
burning ethnic Albanian villages in a region at the heart of the
revolt.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, where Holbrooke will
stop Monday morning before flying on to Belgrade, U.S. officials on
Sunday presented NATO ambassadors with a stepped-up plan for
bombing in Serbia, a move intended to strengthen Holbrooke's
position with the Yugoslav leader.
</P>
<P>
   The president's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said
Sunday that another diplomatic push by Holbrooke was justified
``one final time,'' even as the administration came under new
criticism that it was dithering over what to do about Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we owe it to the American people,'' Berger said on the
CBS News program ``Face the Nation.'' ``We owe it to our military
people, our allies, to make that final attempt, even as the
preparations continue.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed that plans for airstrikes were simultaneously moving
forward. ``The preference is to find a peace agreement that will
bring stability to Kosovo, peace to Kosovo, and rights to the
Kosovar people,'' Berger said. ``If we can achieve that with the
imminent threat of force, that will be a good result.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who negotiated a Kosovo cease-fire last October that
Milosevic has flouted for two months, appeared to have a
particularly difficult assignment this time.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Clinton administration officials said that Holbrooke
was being sent to deliver Milosevic the message of peace or war.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has shown a pattern of backing down at the last
minute. Should he give signs of doing so this time, Holbrooke will
likely be left with the task of negotiating around the edges of the
peace settlement that the ethnic Albanians signed at the Paris
peace talks last week. Changes to the terms of the peace settlement
could well drive the ethnic Albanians to renege on the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Milosevic is ready to agree to a NATO-led force which
can include other nations, we're ready to discuss it without
betraying the ethnic Albanians,'' a senior administration official
said. The official acknowledged that there was ``very little
maneuvering room, because of the 81-page document out of Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   By sending Holbrooke to what some officials are calling ``last
chance'' talks, the administration opened itself to accusations,
even by some supporters, of being too accommodating toward
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bob Dole, sent earlier this month by the
administration to break a logjam in the talks between the Serbs and
the ethnic Albanians, said he believed Holbrooke's visit was
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have to make any more overtures to
Milosevic,'' Dole said on NBC News' ``Meet the Press.'' We've done
enough of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., who has been a proponent of the
airstrikes, suggested that the administration was dithering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great alliances and great countries don't remain great if they
issue threats and don't keep them,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Others charged that the Holbrooke mission ran the risk of
allowing Milosevic more time to conduct his new military offensive
against the ethnic Albanian population and the guerrillas of the
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to send an emissary, every day you wait to do
so you give Milosevic more time to attack,'' said James Hooper, the
executive director of the Balkans Action Council, a nongovernmental
group that has supported airstrikes against the Yugoslav leader.
``Why wait until Monday? And at least get it over quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the ethnic Albanian delegation, who signed the
accords in Paris last Thursday, said they feared that Holbrooke, in
an attempt to forge an agreement with Milosevic and avoid bombing,
might undermine the terms of the accord.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed out that Holbrooke went to Belgrade 10 days ago on
a very limited mission _ to deliver a message about the terms of
the Kosovo settlement and to indicate that not signing would mean
NATO airstrikes _ and failed to convince Milosevic to back down.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they said, it appeared that Holbrooke would negotiate
with Milosevic, even as Serbian forces were using tanks, heavy
artillery and mortar in their new offensive in Kosovo, Serbia,
whose population is 90 percent ethnic Albanian. The region was
stripped of broad autonomy by Milosevic in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would agree that Ambassador Holbrooke should go to Belgrade
with an ultimatum, but this is not a new ultimatum,'' said Bujar
Bukoshi, the prime minister of the shadow government of ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, who is also a member of the delegation to the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, whose traveling party includes Lt. Gen. Edward
Anderson and Greg Schulte, a National Security Council specialist
on the Balkans, will be preceded in Belgrade by the three
negotiators from the Paris peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   According to one of the negotiators, Ambassador Wolfgang
Petritsch, the Austrian envoy to Belgrade, the trio _ Petritsch;
the U.S. ambassador, Christopher Hill; and the Russian ambassador,
Boris Mayorsky _ will meet Milosevic on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to put everything on the table with Mr.
Milosevic,'' Petritsch said. ``We want to make it clear to him what
is in the accord _ there has been such a propaganda war against the
accord in Belgrade people won't give credit to what is in the
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Petritsch said he would stress that the accord allows Kosovo to
stay within Serbia as an autonomous region and that it gives the
Serbian minority protection.
</P>
<P>
   To stress NATO unity, President Clinton spoke Sunday about the
situation in Kosovo with President Jacques Chirac of France, Prime
Minister Tony Blair of Britain and Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of
Germany, a White House spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials also said that the planned visit to
Washington by Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov of Russia would not
affect the timing of possible NATO action. Primakov, who opposes
the bombing by NATO, begins meeting with administration officials
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, questioned on whether the administration would ask
Primakov to postpone his visit, said, ``No, I think that would be
his decision to make if it came to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
