<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEMPLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPLE FINDS ITS BEST JUST ISN'T GOOD ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 
(With BKC-DUKE-TEMPLE)  (ms 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There were two and a half minutes left
in Sunday's National Collegiate Athletic Association East Regional
final, and Rasheed Brokenborough, Temple's shooting guard, peeked
at the scoreboard. Duke was leading by 18 points and was heading
toward the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point,'' Brokenborough said, ``I didn't feel we had
much of a chance. There's not much you can do. You're playing a
team with better players, and when you play with too much emotion
the way we did, you sometimes help the other team. You have to take
the loss like a man.''
</P>
<P>
   With 1 minutes 14 seconds remaining, John Chaney, Temple's
67-year-old coaching legend, took Brokenborough out of the game.
There was a long hug from Chaney for his only senior, a hometown
player from Philadelphia who paid his tuition as a freshman because
he lacked the grades to get an athletic scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   After Duke's 85-64 victory, the coach and the player left the
court together. When they arrived in the locker room, the other
players were sitting quietly on stools in front of makeshift
lockers, heads down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach came in and sat down and was crying,'' said Mark
Karcher, Temple's best 3-point shooter. ``That hurt me. He told us
to keep our heads up. He said we lost the battle Sunday, but
somebody had to win the game, somebody had to advance, somebody had
to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokenborough said: ``Coach showed a lot of emotion. He said,
`You played the best basketball you could.'''
</P>
<P>
   Did Brokenborough think his team played its best? ``Defensively,
no,'' he said. ``But I think we did the best job we could do and
lost to a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   A loss is a loss, but the realization that this Duke team is
something special seemed to ease the pain a bit for Temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``We faced maybe the best team in America,'' said Pepe Sanchez,
Temple's point guard, ``but if you want to win it all, you have to
face Duke. We did our best. We're very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Proud but helpless against Duke's inside-outside offensive
poison. On Saturday, Brokenborough said Temple was ready to shut
down Duke and its hefty All-America center, Elton Brand, and take a
chance on Duke's 3-point bombers.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Temple could do neither. With the game barely
six minutes old and Temple leading by 9-7, Trajan Langdon, Duke's
All-America guard, buried three 3-point shots in a span of 89
seconds. That led a Duke 17-2 run and made Temple change its
defensive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our hands in his face,'' Karcher said, ``and he still
hits those 3s. We put pressure on him after that, so they went to
something else.'
</P>
<P>
   That something else was Brand in the deep post. As Brokenborough
said: ``We became wild animals trying real hard on defense.
Eventually, we started cheating toward the outside shooter, and
they penetrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple did not stop Langdon but merely slowed him. He made 5 of
6 of his 3-point shots and scored 23 points. Inside, Brand made 8
of 10 shots and scored 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, a desperate Temple started trapping at
halfcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to trap them because we were losing,'' Brokenborough
said. ``We tried to slow them down a bit. We did a good job of
trapping, but they came up with easy buckets.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Langdon destroyed Temple, the Owls knew all about
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of times, we reached him and he shot over us,''
Sanchez said. ``We knew he would be good. We didn't know how good
he would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Langdon and associates were so good that they shot 60 percent
from the floor and 58.8 percent on 3-pointers against one of the
nation's premier defenses. That earned Temple's respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never let down,'' Karcher said, ``but I can't say we played
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez marveled at Duke's deep talent. ``Most teams have two
good players,'' he said. ``They have 10.''
</P>
<P>
   The Temple players felt bad for Chaney. He is only the 22d coach
in NCAA history to win 600 games, but this is his 27th year and he
has never reached the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm so disappointed,'' Karcher said. ``He's like a
father to me. I feel I let him down. But next year, all of us
except Rasheed will come back. We will be better next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't talk to Sanchez about next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he said, ``I don't feel like looking ahead. I
have to soak this up and suffer so next time we won't lose.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
