<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE NEW ABORTION RHETORIC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, March 22:
</P>
<P>
   Pragmatists within the Republican Party have come to regard the
abortion issue as an albatross that could ruin their chances of
maintaining control of Congress and winning the presidency in 2000.
While all of the party's declared presidential candidates describe
themselves as pro-life, the real issues debate among them has not
been over how to outlaw abortion, but how to keep it from playing a
central part in the upcoming campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the leading Republican
presidential hopeful, does not talk about ending the right to
abortion, but about reducing the number of abortions by encouraging
adoption and requiring that minors seeking abortions obtain
parental consent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also weaves the abortion issue into a larger ``reverence
for life'' agenda that includes everything from combatting drunken
driving to promoting sexual abstinence. It is far more appealing
than the old anti-abortion rhetoric, which frequently sounded harsh
and judgmental.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-choice movement, which has succeeded in portraying the
Republican abortion opponents as extremists who would deny
abortions even to victims of rape and incest, would have a far
harder time combatting this fuzzier and less threatening approach.
The American public always has been uncomfortable with abortion.
Polls show that a strong majority prefers the hands-off option of
leaving the issue up to a woman and her doctor. But when prodded
about specifics, people tend to be far more conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican strategists, including some from the religious
right, now favor chipping away at abortion through targeted fights
on the most winnable issues, like parental consent and the
procedure known as ``partial birth'' abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time we win one, we're going to find a new one and keep
pressing,'' says Ralph Reed, the social-conservative consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-abortion pragmatists are hoping to leave the pro-life
plank in their party platform intact as a sop to the social
conservatives, and then duck the issue through the presidential
campaign. Gov. George Pataki has made that more difficult with his
recent bold call for elimination of the plank. Pataki, who is
eyeing the presidential race, should be commended for tackling the
issue in a way that makes many other moderates look evasive by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   But the pro-choice movement cannot rely on a few brave voices
within the Republican Party. It must remind the public that the
abortion debate, no matter how it is presented, is always about
each woman's right to make her own intensely personal decisions
relating to pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, extremists within the Republican ranks made
things easy for the pro-choice side by portraying the abortion
fight in the starkest terms possible. But it is very likely that
the opponents of abortion will use much subtler strategies this
time around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
