<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      03-21 1683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAKENED OLYMPIC ORGANIZATION FACES TOUGH TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF AND JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Humbled and humiliated, the
International Olympic Committee last week sought to kick an
addiction to a potent mix of independence, power, and the reflected
prestige of the world's finest athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Like an addict on the first rungs of a 12-step ladder, the IOC
distanced itself from its most incorrigible friends, sought outside
help, rallied around its chastened leader, and vowed never to
indulge again.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the self-congratulatory statements and claims of
catharsis after the $1.2 million Salt Lake City bribery scandal,
the IOC fell into the trap that bedevils many would-be ex-addicts:
assuming that the mere act of claiming sobriety is the same thing
as being truly sober.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, as IOC members disperse to the far reaches of
the globe, the weakened organization faces even tougher tests in
the months and years ahead _ involving performance-enhancing
strategies by athletes, threatened congressional action, its
relationship to sponsors, and other challenges that observers say
will determine not only its own future but the future of the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Most notable among the hurdles confronting the IOC is its
inability to gain world consensus on the use of drugs and
performance-enhancers by athletes, or doping, a problem that
Olympic observers say could do far more damage to the Games than
the revelation that IOC members traded bid city votes for cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next to the doping issue, the bribery issue is a passing
cloud,'' said John MacAloon, professor of social science at the
University of Chicago and an Olympic historian. ``The entire
credibility of the Olympic movement is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the bribery uproar, Olympic boosters continually
reminded the public, the pollsters, and the pundits that, when the
smoke and stench clears, what really matters are the efforts and
achievements of Olympic athletes. Observers say the Games would
suffer immeasurable, perhaps irreversible, damage if those
achievements were seen as the product of doping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership crises and scandals such as we've been through can
be fixed,'' MacAloon said. ``The heart of the attraction is the
athletic competition, and if more and more publics around the world
become convinced that athletes can't be trusted to be clean then
the whole Olympic phenomenon is shaken at its core.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a February doping conference here, the IOC failed to win
worldwide support to create an agency that would conduct drug tests
on athletes in and out of competition, refine analyses of urine and
blood samples, and warn children about the dangers of doping. IOC
president Juan Antonio Samaranch had hoped to head the agency, with
day-to-day management being handled by Prince Alexandre de Merode,
head of the Olympics' antidrug committee since the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   It quickly became apparent that _ in light of the IOC's
credibility gap _ most industrialized nations had no interest in
seeing the IOC retain control of antidoping efforts. Also
unresolved was an IOC proposal to require a minimum two-year ban
for a first offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``These issues are bigger than the IOC,'' said British sports
minister Tony Banks. ``It might come as a surprise to the IOC to
find there is actually something bigger than the IOC, but there
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Those results proved that ``the international federations and
the IOC have lost moral authority over the doping question,''
MacAloon said. ``Whether the sports organizations can win their
moral authority back remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC also has to contend with an emboldened US Congress, most
notably a committee led by a senator with designs on the
presidency, that happily would upgrade its own image by claiming to
have cleaned up or cracked down on an organization that arguably is
held in even lower regard than it is.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the IOC's actions this week did little to cool the
ardor in Washington for a US legislative response. Among those IOC
actions were changing the way the 2006 Winter Games host city will
be chosen; establishing an ethics committee with a majority from
outside the IOC's ranks; and creating an IOC 2000 study commission
with carte blanche to suggest changes in everything from how the
IOC chooses its members to how it spends its money.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, an Arizona Republican who is chairman of
the Senate Commerce Committee, was unimpressed, pressing ahead with
plans for an April 14 hearing. McCain dismissed the reforms as ``a
sad commentary for an organization which exists to embody the
highest ideals of the human pursuit of excellence in competition.''
</P>
<P>
   He took particular umbrage at the announcement that Samaranch
would lead the ethics panel and the IOC 2000 Commission. Samaranch
said the Olympic charter required that he preside, but McCain
dismissed that as a blatant conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, who is 78, had heard widespread demands for his
resignation since the scandal broke in December. He began the week
by hinting he might step down before his term ends in 2001. But he
ended the week emboldened by an 86-2 vote of confidence and said he
would serve out his term.
</P>
<P>
   Among the topics to be considered at the Senate hearing are
removing the IOC's tax-exempt status in the United States and
redirecting hundreds of millions of dollars in television rights
fees from the IOC to its US affiliate, the United States Olympic
Committee. The tax and television rights issues are significant
because they could choke off the fuel that turns the Olympic rings:
American dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the committee indicated Friday that the results
of the IOC meeting had made congressional action more, rather than
less, likely.
</P>
<P>
   Another front on which the IOC may have to do battle is with its
biggest financial supporters, the 11 companies _ nine of them based
in the United States _ that are the worldwide Olympic sponsors. All
will have to decide whether to renew or end their relationships
with the IOC at various points within the next nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The most vocal, and most critical, sponsor has been Boston-based
John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. and its president, David
D'Alessandro.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to agree to have oversight and an ethics commission
and to study term limits is real progress. But it's not reform
yet,'' D'Alessandro said. For instance, he said, ``Samaranch can't
be seen as controlling these committees. Who are these `outsiders'
going to be, and does this group have authority?''
</P>
<P>
   Other sponsors have taken a more measured approach, but all have
said they are closely watching their investments, which average
between $40 million and $50 million each for a four-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectation is that they are going to continue to move
swiftly and forcefully through this issue,'' said Ben Deutsch,
spokesman for longtime Olympic sponsor Coca-Cola, whose commitment
to the IOC extends through 2008. ``If they do not, the IOC cannot
be successful in restoring confidence in its leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Less of a direct threat to the IOC _ but still a potential stain
on its reputation _ is an ongoing Justice Department investigation
of the Salt Lake bid efforts. Indictments, if any are forthcoming,
are considered most likely to affect American citizens involved in
the Salt Lake effort, as opposed to IOC members, who for a variety
of reasons are essentially immune from the process. Still, any
action by prosecutors can only serve to remind the public of the
scandal, possibly at a time when the IOC is basking in the expected
glory of the 2000 Games.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC might also find itself named a ``public international
organization'' by President Clinton. Such a designation would make
anyone who bribes an IOC member subject to penalties under the
chief federal law against international bribery, the Foreign
Corrupt Practices Act. The law only covers bribe-givers, as opposed
to takers, so IOC members would not be directly affected.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers have expressed doubts the IOC can be
named a public international organization. However, former Senator
George Mitchell of Maine _ who first made the suggestion as
chairman of an independent ethics commission _ has continued to
press for the designation as a sign that dealings with the IOC no
longer will be considered above or outside US laws.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the horizon is the question of whether the powerful
international sports federations that control the actual Olympic
competitions will seize the moment and demand financial and other
concessions from the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Another test for the IOC will be internal, involving its
ultimate acceptance of the very reforms its surviving members were
so proud of this week. Answering to other people is an unfamiliar,
some say unwelcome, concept to a self-appointed, self-perpetuating
oligarchy that was designed by founder Pierre de Coubertin to
answer to nobody on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the long-term results of the scandal seem certain to
strip the IOC of its most treasured possession: independence.
</P>
<P>
   A beloved part of IOC lore is a story about how the IOC forced
the Nazis to take down ``Dogs and Jews Not Allowed'' signs from
outside public toilets at the 1936 Winter Games in
Garmisch-Partenkirchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the five-ringed Olympic flag is raised over the stadium,
it is no longer Germany,'' IOC President Henri de Baillet-Latour
informed Adolf Hitler. ``It is Olympia, and we are masters there.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the Lords of the Rings left here last week after the
most important and agonizing meeting in their 105-year history, the
erosion of that storied independence _ as well as their moral
authority _ was plain to see. The question is whether the
organization that said no to Hitler now will have to say yes to
just about everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not deaf,'' said IOC vice president Anita DeFrantz of
the United States. ``We hear what people tell us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
