</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRESSIVE COMEBACK FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ Throw out all the drama _ and there's been a surplus _
strip away all the changes in players and coaches, ignore for a
second the soap-opera subplot of Dennis Rodman's sudden
disappearance and reappearance . . . and what you have left is the
Lakers team that dominated the second half of Sunday afternoon's
victory over the Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   When all the chaos subsided, all the parts were again in place.
And with all the missteps of the last several days behind them, the
Lakers displayed the best 24 minutes of basketball any team has
played this season.
</P>
<P>
   Their 72 second-half points were the most by any team this
season, and their 115-104 victory was the most impressive win in
recent memory, coming after a 24-point deficit in a disastrous
first half.
</P>
<P>
   It gave Shaquille O'Neal vengeance on his old team. Rodman,
immediate redemption for his one-week vacation. Kobe Bryant, a
career day with 38 points _ 33 in the second half. And the Lakers,
renewed cohesion after two straight losses and three in the last
four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a huge confidence builder,'' coach Kurt Rambis
said. ``It's something we have to build upon. It's a game that in
the grand of scheme of things that if we don't continue to build
on, it will mean absolutely nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that what the guys saw they're capable of doing in
the second half, they can realize if they do that on an
all-the-time basis, we're gonna be real tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   How tough?
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and O'Neal (31 points) both cleared 30 points. Glen Rice
and Derek Harper drilled seven huge 3-pointers between them in the
final two quarters. As a team, the Lakers were this dominant: a
17-8 rebounding margin, a season-high 41-point fourth quarter, a
season-high 60.3 percent shooting rate for the game, 83 percent in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   All of it combined to negate one of their worst first halves of
the season, in which they let the Magic shoot 50 percent and let
rookie Michael Doleac score 16 points en route to a career-high 25.
They also let reserve Darrell Armstrong fire away for 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in here (at halftime) and just jumped down each
other's throats,'' O'Neal said. ``I think when we can have that
type of camaraderie on this team, where we can yell at each other
and nobody will take it personal, it's good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt got on Kobe. Kobe got on me. Ruben (Patterson) got on me.
The rookies told us we needed to play harder. We did it. We came
out, sucked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The comeback started with stifling defense and a pick-and-roll
scheme adjustment that stunted Doleac and fueled the Lakers
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks flew as Bryant hit 7 of 8 shots in a 15-point third
quarter, and Harper and Rice started drilling open 3-pointers. But
it started with defense, and Rambis couldn't have been happier
after a mostly defenseless road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't believe the turnaround from the way we've been
playing,'' Rambis said, ``the way we played the first half, all the
adjustments we made, the intensity, guys helping each other, it was
beautiful to watch them, how they worked so well together
defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Down 20 to open the third quarter, the comeback came gradually _
a steal, a block, a fast-break dunk, a few Rodman rebounds. ``I'm
in good shape,'' he said after getting six boards, two assists and
four points after returning from his eight-day layoff.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of 3s from Harper got the margin down to six, but the
Magic fought back to make it 84-74 at the end of the quarter.
O'Neal and Bryant took over in the fourth again, keying a 20-10 run
that gave the Lakers their first lead since the first quarter.
Orlando never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very disappointing loss,'' Magic coach Chuck Daly
said, ``but they are what they are. They are a traveling All-Star
team.''
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, playing like one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
