<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8784 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CRISIS-BOS     03-21 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CRISIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE TO MEET WITH MILOSEVIC IN LAST TRY FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying that NATO bombers are already warming their
engines, the Clinton administration dispatched a top envoy to
Yugoslavia Sunday in ``a final attempt'' to warn its president,
Slobodan Milosevic, that he faces military attack if he does not
end the fighting in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Republicans cautioned that President Clinton
was close to entering a war without a clear plan for how to end it,
and a Democratic lawmaker, Senator John Breaux of Louisiana, said
the president had not yet convinced the American people that the
United States should get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's forces have been crushing an ethnic Albanian
separatist movement in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo. The
fighting has already driven 400,000 ethnic Albanians from their
homes, and Clinton has cautioned that a broader war could develop
as the refugees cross international borders, potentially drawing
Turkey, Greece, and Macedonia into the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   US officials announced Sunday that a special US envoy, Richard
Holbrooke, would meet Milosevic late Monday in Belgrade, the
Yugoslav capital. Holbrooke ``will make clear that Milosevic faces
a stark choice: to halt aggression against the Kosovar Albanians
... or bear the full responsiblity for the consequences of NATO
military action,'' Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   US officials emphasized that the mission gives Milosevic one
last chance to stop NATO airstrikes _ even ``with the smell of
exhaust fumes in the air from the aircraft,'' said Samuel R.
``Sandy'' Berger, Clinton's national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic appeared to ignore the threats Sunday, as several
reports said that his forces continued to pound rebel positions in
central Kosovo, setting houses ablaze and driving ethnic Albanians
into the hills. Government forces launched a powerful offensive on
Saturday, when 1,380 international monitors left Kosovo in advance
of the expected NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke Sunday about Kosovo with French President Jacques
Chirac, British Prime Minister Tony Blair, and German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder. The conversation with Blair lasted for 25
minutes, and ``they agreed the situation was increasingly
serious,'' Blair's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 NATO ambassadors met at the alliance's headquarters in
Brussels to discuss the situation and review military options. The
NATO allies have already authorized airstrikes, though separate
approval would be needed before ground troops could be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   While raising the rhetorical attack on Milosevic, the Clinton
administration faced two political tests of its Kosovo policy. The
second-ranking Senate Republican, Senator Don Nickles of Oklahoma,
said Senate debate begins Monday on Clinton's policy and on a
possible resolution authorizing the use of force in Kosovo _ a
measure he said would probably fail if it came to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a NATO attack could be complicated by the
expected arrival in Washington this week of Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov. The Russians oppose NATO airstrikes in Kosovo,
and initiating them while Primakov is on US soil would be seen as
an affront to the Russian official.
</P>
<P>
   Former senator Robert Dole, who traveled to the region at
Clinton's request in an unsuccessful attempt to win a peace
agreement, on Sunday said that Clinton should scrub Primakov's tour
to remove any possible impediment to the NATO strikes. ``Cancel
that visit. Just don't give Milosevic more time to create more
havoc in Kosovo, which is precisely what he's doing,'' Dole said on
the NBC program ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has not suggested to Primakov that he delay
the trip, and the decision to come is up to him, said Mike Hammer,
a spokesman for the White House National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer would not say directly whether the United States would
support initiating a bombing campaign while Primakov is on American
soil. ``We understand the Russian government is opposed to
airstrikes, but the determining factor for NATO will be the
situation on the ground in Kosovo and what Mr. Milosevic chooses,''
he said. ``We are well aware of Russian views, but that's not the
determining factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's primary goal on his visit is to win support from an
international lending agency for more aid for the ailing Russian
economy. A meeting with Clinton is set for Thursday, the last day
of his tour.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles, speaking on the ABC program ``This Week,'' said that
the Senate might debate whether to cut off funds for US
intervention in Kosovo, which he called ``a civil war.'' Kosovo is
a province of Serbia, which itself forms the majority of
Yugoslavia. Milosevic and his troops are ethnic Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles also said Clinton has not laid out what NATO should do
if the airstrikes fail to end the fighting. ``I just don't think
there is an endgame. I don't think there is a strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have absolutely no choice. We know what the
consequences are if we do not act,'' answered Senator Joseph Biden,
Democrat of Delaware, on the same program. ``It will be tens of
thousands of additional refugees, further destabilization of the
region. ... This is going to spread if we do not act.'' He said
Milosevic was ``engaged in what is essentially genocide and in the
middle of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Nickles, two other Republicans _ Senator Jon Kyl of
Arizona and Representative John Kasich of Ohio _ appeared on ``Fox
News Sunday'' and said Clinton did not have clear goals in the
potential attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``To simply bomb at this point without any strategy is not a
good thing for the US or NATO to do,'' Kyl said. He said airstrikes
alone would probably not repel Yugoslav forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On the CBS program ``Face the Nation,'' Breaux said he supported
Clinton's plan but said ``the American people are not yet convinced
of the importance of this. I mean, most people couldn't point out
Kosovo on a map if they had to.'' He said Clinton had kept Congress
informed of his plans, but he needed to lay out the reasons for
military action to the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke is scheduled to stop in Brussels on his way to
Belgrade, where he will consult with British and French officials
and with General Wesley C. Clark, the supreme commander of NATO.
Holbrooke will also meet NATO Secretary General Javier Solana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
