<HEADER>
A8792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE22-COX     03-21 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rain saves crashed Jeff Burton
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ For Winston Cup's best drivers, Sunday's
TranSouth 400 at Darlington Raceway wasn't a race against
pole-sitter Jeff Gordon or the worn asphalt dubbed the ``track too
tough to tame.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a race to beat inclement weather and darkness at the
50-year-old egg-shaped oval, but the clouds couldn't have come soon
enough for Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   After rain delayed the event for two hours and 47 minutes,
Burton won his first race here in 11 attempts. He earned his second
victory of the season, despite getting caught in a crash near the
end of the 162nd lap, only two laps shy of the finish in the
rain-shortened event.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who took over the Winston Cup points lead for the first
time in his career, was exiting the backstretch of lap 162 when
Ernie Irvan's No. 36 Pontiac spun out leaving turn 4. Irvin hit the
outside wall and collected five other cars, including Burton's and
Gordon's.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's No. 99 Ford Taurus smashed into the outside wall on the
frontstretch, but he still managed to maintain a slight lead over
Jeremy Mayfield and Gordon, who finished second and third,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the wreck and I got slowed down,'' Burton said. ``It was
really dark because of the weather and all of the smoke. I wrecked
that car and it's torn up good. I got into the wall hard. I rode
around the last lap on the wheel with sparks flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin sparked the accident, which also damaged the cars of Kenny
Irwin, Jerry Nadeau and Kenny Wallace. It brought out the third
yellow flag of the race. After two more laps, rain started to fall
again and NASCAR officials called for the red flag, which parked
the cars on the apron of the 1.366-mile track.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin ``just lost it off turn 4 and that just started it,'' said
Irwin, whose car hit head-on into the pit-road wall. ``It started
to sprinkle and everybody was on old tires, so I think that was the
cause of him spinning.''
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers, including Gordon, believed NASCAR officials were
too late in bringing out the caution flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have thrown a caution a lap earlier,'' Gordon
said. ``There would have been a lot less wrecked cars. My
windshield was just covered with rain. It was wet and we were all
sliding (into the pileup). Some of us made it out, some of us
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton didn't, but after waiting about 10 minutes after parking
his car, he received official word of his victory. After weather
reports indicated that the showers wouldn't stop anytime soon,
NASCAR officials cancelled the remaining 129 laps of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were praying for rain,'' Burton said. ``I just knew it
wasn't going to rain long. But I knew it didn't have to rain long
because it was so dark. I just kept thinking that we had the
fastest car all day, we made the best pit-stop decision and I
wrecked. I was mad at myself. If it hadn't rained, we wouldn't have
won the race. But if it's your day, it's your day.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a long day at Darlington. After completing only 44 laps
of the scheduled 293-lap event, the drivers spent nearly three
hours waiting for a restart. Shortly after 4 p.m., the restart
finally came, but radar indicated only an hour-long window to
complete 103 more laps, which would complete half of the event and
make it official.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who led the first 38 laps of the race, was back in front
on the restart and led 12 laps. There were eight lead changes
between five drivers over the next 63 laps, but when all the
remaining cars made their final green-flag pit stop on lap 119,
Burton had the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   And Burton gained it by gambling. On lap 114, Burton and Dale
Jarrett, who finished fourth, were the only drivers to make pit
stops. Burton, who was running third at the time, beat Jarrett off
pit road and pulled away shortly thereafter. Gordon, Mayfield and
Mark Martin pitted one lap later, but they could never challenge
Burton the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gordon) had newer tires (at the end),'' Burton said. ``He
would have been stronger on the long runs. If the caution had come
out while we were in the pits, we would have been a lap down. It
was a gamble based on the rain coming.''
</P>
<P>
   TRANSOUTH 400
</P>
<P>
   TOP 5
</P>
<P>
   1. Jeff Burton, Ford.
</P>
<P>
   2. Jeremy Mayfield, Ford.
</P>
<P>
   3. Jeff Gordon, Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   4. Dale Jarrett, Ford.
</P>
<P>
   5. Mark Martin, Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
