<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labonte lasts 44 laps
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ Despite driving with a broken right shoulder
blade, Bobby Labonte lasted 44 laps in Sunday's TranSouth 400 at
Darlington Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   After yielding to relief driver Matt Kenseth only one lap before
a nearly three-hour rain delay, Labonte watched his No. 18 Pontiac
finish 10th in the rain-shortened event, which helped him remain in
the top five in standings points, only 26 behind leader Jeff
Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte was expected to drive only one lap in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby wasn't feeling very good so we were lucky to get that
first rain,'' said Kenseth, a Busch series driver who plans on
jumping to the Winston Cup circuit next season. ``We were also
lucky to get that long green because pitting on the backstretch was
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who was injured in an accident during Friday's pole
qualifying, led the 44th lap before the driver change one lap
later. When the race restarted following the rain delay, Kenseth
was in the 34th postion, but he made his way through the field
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad Bobby could make it as long as he could in the race
car,'' Kenseth said. ``We had good pit stops and a fast race car.
I'm glad I did well and didn't hit the wall and was able to give
them a decent finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte expansion
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's Motor Speedwayin Charlotte, the nation's second-largest
auto track, will get even larger. Seating at the track will grow in
the next eight years by 62 percent from 157,000 seats to just over
255,000 seats. By 2007, Speedway Motorsports Inc., which owns the
facility, plans on having seats completely surrounding the 1.5-mile
track. Speedway officials have already added 40,000 seats since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in an exploding business, and we're in a strong growth
curve,'' said H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler, the speedway's president and
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to jump on it and be very aggressive, because the
day will come when it slows down.''
</P>
<P>
   School spirit
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Marlin will debut a paint scheme honoring Tennessee's
national title in college football in three Busch series races. The
skirt of the predominantly orange Chevrolet will feature the orange
and white checkerboard pattern, much like that of the end zones in
Knoxville's Neyland Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin will race the car in events at Nashville on April 3 and
Bristol, Tenn., on April 10 and Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've been a UT fan for as long as I can remember,''
said Marlin, a native of Franklin, Tenn. ``We're even inviting the
coaches to come to the races and cheer us on from the pits. If we
could get one of those linemen under the car, we probably wouldn't
need a jack.''
</P>
<P>
   Pit stops
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet officials, who were hoping to debut the `99 Monte
Carlo at the Brickyard 400 in Indianapolis on Aug. 7, now say the
car probably won't race this season. ... It didn't take Gordon long
to lap the No. 66 Ford of Waltrip. Gordon lapped Waltrip on lap 25,
then passed him a second time only 13 laps later. ... When Derrike
Cope failed to qualify for the second time this season, Bryan Foods
moved its sponsorship to the No. 90 Ford of owner Junie Donlavey.
Bryan says it's sticking by Cope for the long term, though. ...
Utah Jazz guard John Stockton isn't the only pro athlete from
Gonzaga. Jack Roush Racing driver Chad Little, a native of Spokane,
Wash., is a graduate of the Gonzaga School of Law. ... Former
points leader Mike Skinner struggled, finishing 32nd and two laps
behind the lead-lap cars. He fell to fifth in the standings points,
66 behind Burton. ... Tony Stewart got his first top-10 finish at
sixth and was the highest-finishing rookie for the fourth time this
season. ... By finishing 41st on Sunday, Waltrip dropped out of the
top 25 in owner points, meaning he'll have qualify on speed next
week at Texas to make the field.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
