<HEADER>
A8794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STONES-BUSINESS-BOS     03-21 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STONES-BUSINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ONLY ROCK AND BUSINESS, BUT THEY LIKE IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As an opening line, ``Please allow me to introduce
myself, I'm a man of wealth and taste'' is hard to beat. But when
the Rolling Stones play two dates at Boston's FleetCenter this
week, Mick Jagger's lyric could be borrowed by a mutual-fund
manager cozying up to a prospective client.
</P>
<P>
   With thousands of concert seats priced at $300 apiece, and $650
individual ticket packages that add perks like a backstage buffet,
exclusive parking, and autographed merchandise, the live album from
this high-rollers' Stones tour ought to be titled ``Get Yer
Platinum Card Out.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks into the group's 20-city tour, concert figures
already read like a Microsoft quarterly report, with the band
itself grossing around $2 million per date. The cheapest
FleetCenter seat costs $39.50. A Rod Stewart concert earlier this
month set a FleetCenter record of $85 a seat. The Stones shows are
obliterating that mark with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy was, `Will it work?' And it did work,'' says
local promoter Don Law, noting that both shows are sold out save
for a few $300 tickets to Monday night's concert.
</P>
<P>
   And how's this for sweet irony? Three decades ago, when the
Stones were rolling in notoriety, not dough, fans typically traded
in illegal substances and political tracts at their concerts.
Today, they're more apt to be dealing in account commissions and
strategic partnerships. ``Sticky Fingers,'' the title of the band's
seminal 1971 album, has taken on a whole new meaning in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Durant, chief executive officer of Techprint Inc. in
Lawrence, a specialty printer, snapped up six tickets to Monday
night's VIP reception. A longtime Stones fan, Durant, 57, calls the
outing with friends ``purely social'' but says if the chance to do
a little networking arises, well, he just might get some
entrepreneurial satisfaction, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales is a 24-hour deal, and everyone you encounter is a
potential customer,'' he says. ``You never know who you'll wind up
talking to. This could be an interesting crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   FleetCenter president Richard Krezwick agrees that part of the
VIP package appeal lies in its potential for winning friends and
influencing clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to put that prestige ticket in one of their
customer's hands,'' says Krezwick. ``For us, the goal isn't the
event's bottom line. It's to produce goodwill for our own preferred
customers, so they will renew (seat licenses and luxury-suite
leases).''
</P>
<P>
   He equates what Jagger &AMP; Co. offer to well-heeled fans to what
Disney World provides its customers, an analogy that would have put
diehard Stones fans in a coma 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk up to the Disney window and think tickets are
expensive,'' Krezwick explains. ``But when you leave the park, you
only think about what a good time you had, not what you spent. It's
the same for a Stones show here.''
</P>
<P>
   One hallmark of the No Security Tour is that graying fans with
green to spend have more than just ``Honky-Tonk Women'' on their
minds. The same crowd that's jockeying for Ryder Cup golf and Major
League All-Star Game invitations this summer is buying up, and in
some cases writing off, high-priced Stones tickets as business
expenses. Whether the draw is guitarist Ron Wood or golfer Tiger
Woods, it's much the same phenomenon: gaining access to a coveted
event that caters to those with the means to impress.
</P>
<P>
   As rock tours have become more corporation-driven, so has the
fan base for venerable acts including the Stones, Jimmy Buffett,
and the Eagles. With those fans not just aging but prospering,
concert promoters are delivering the same level of service that
patrons of golf tournaments and major museum openings have come to
expect. Claude Monet, meet Keith Richards.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at these Stones shows are bragging about how much they
paid for their tickets,'' says Bob Grossweiner, senior editor at
Performance magazine. ``The Stones are definitely going after the
people with money. They're not going after the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The oldsters are going after Broadway prices,'' adds Gary
Bongivanni, editor of the trade magazine Pollstar.
</P>
<P>
   Boomer troubadour Jimmy Buffett, who recently played the Fleet,
offered $400 packages to his fans, similar to what the Stones'
promoters are marketing. All the VIP tickets sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tickets are in such demand because people use them to
entertain other people,'' says Buffett, who knows plenty about the
corporate schmoozing game. ``I went to the Super Bowl this year
and, honestly, how many real football fans ever get to go to the
Super Bowl? The reality is that I go to my shows and see fans in
the front row and I'll say, `How did you get those tickets?'
They'll say, `Oh, we just buy them from scalpers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Buffett: ``Do I sit here as an artist and say, `Do I want a
piece of a $400 ticket that the scalpers are going to get anyway?'
And the answer is, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   One difference between a Stones concert and an event like the
Super Bowl is that rock shows have historically postured as
anti-establishment gatherings _ even if the performers themselves
were raking in more than Goldman, Sachs partners. The Stones, who
once sang ``Street Fighting Man'' as an anthem of defiance, now
ride into cities such as Boston on streets paved with gold. The
irony of the band's rebel image playing to an Armani-clad crowd is
not lost on industry veterans such as Peter Wolf, who once sang
lead in Boston's own J. Geils Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when selling even a T-shirt at a concert was
considered vulgar. No serious musician would dream of that,'' says
Wolf, adding that he has spurned six-figure offers to turn his
songs into advertising pitches. ``Now many people think that if
your song is used in a commercial, it's an accreditation. ...
Twenty years ago, they would have thought you had sold out. Now,
it's a case of `Hey, that's cool.'''
</P>
<P>
   Music historian James Isaacs, who won't be attending a Stones
show this week (``I wouldn't pay $5 to see them,'' he says), likens
big-ticket rockfests to the luxury-box syndrome that has infected
sports _ where, according to Isaacs, people go less to see the game
than to do deals, high above courtside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I queasy about this?'' Isaacs asks. ``Not really. Our
generation was the one that was going to change everything. But
Woodstock wasn't a beginning, it was an end. Everything since has
moved from the event to the marketing of the event.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeat that to rabid Stones fans such as Kevin Phelan and Tony
Pelusi, and they might say, `Who cares?' Both have tickets to see
the band in concert for the first time. They will occupy seats that
cost what a decent used family car did when the Stones first toured
America in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Phelen, a real estate executive who's in his early 50s, worries
mostly about what to wear. ``Do I dress up or down? That's the
question. After all, this is a once-in-a-lifetime experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelusi, a 46-year-old Cambridge lawyer, is taking his brother
and two friends to the show. ``I've never been motivated, or had
the financial ability, to see the Stones in concert before,'' he
says. ``Since this could be their last tour, if I'm going, I want
the best seats I can buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Another friend _ a chiropractor _ also bought tickets, says
Pelusi. Asked if a Stones concert sounds like a promising place for
his friend to drum up business, Pelusi laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not until you mentioned it,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
