<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8808 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN     03-21 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRECO MUST STEP UP FOR UCLA WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UCLA is counting on history to repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, point guard Tyus Edney's injured wrist kept him out of
the NCAA championship game, but the Bruins prevailed behind Ed
O'Bannon's leadership and capable play by Cameron Dollar at the
point.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the Bruins women (26-7) meet Louisiana Tech (29-2) in
the West Regional final at 9:07 in the Sports Arena. To the victor
goes the Final Four berth Friday in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Erica Gomez probably won't play, having sprained her
right ankle and suffered ligament damage just 35 seconds into
Saturday's game with Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   So the third-seeded Bruins know in order to beat the top-seeded
Lady Techsters _ something UCLA has never done in nine tries _ they
will need the leadership of Maylana Martin and Janae Hubbard. They
will need to stay out of foul trouble, as they did Saturday night
when Hubbard scored 21 points and took 16 rebounds, and the team
took 26 offensive boards.
</P>
<P>
   And they need freshman Michelle Greco.
</P>
<P>
   Greco is the Crescenta Valley graduate making just her third
start of the season. She proved she was capable Saturday night,
when she played 39 minutes, 25 seconds with just two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greco, she was the MVP of the game,'' Tech coach Leon Barmore
said. ``The kid makes two turnovers, two assists. Colorado State is
jumping up and down, pressing, and she had two turnovers. That girl
impressed me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana Tech, the Bruins will face a press unlike anything
they have seen this season in the Pac-10. The Lady Techsters thrive
on pressuring, causing turnovers, and running the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Amanda Wilson leads with 16.3 points and 7.9 rebounds a
game, followed by junior guard Tamicha Jackson with 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Greco has seen this kind of pressure before, at Tennessee on
Dec. 21. She didn't start that game but said Sunday she was
displeased with the way she handled it then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look to get the ball to everyone and not put so much on
Michelle,'' UCLA coach Kathy Olivier said. ``(Saturday) it wasn't
like we needed Michelle to touch the ball all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins must also use their height advantage and slow the
tempo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of our offense is forcing some turnovers so we can get
some easy baskets,'' Barmore said. ``If we can't put pressure on
them, we can't beat them. It's got to be pressure defense. We can't
back up and be passive, or it won't be a contest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-TEMPLE-NYT &LR;      03-21 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-TEMPLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE RETURNS TO FINAL FOUR AFTER A FOUR-YEAR ABSENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 BY JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ One is a self-described money player who
got that way on the glass-strewn, double-rimmed playgrounds of East
St. Louis, Ill. The other is a long-range sharpshooter who honed
his eye on the polished hardwood in Alaskan gyms. Before Chris
Carrawell and Trajan Langdon could share a triumphant hug Sunday in
the final minute of a tussle with a determined Temple team, they
first had to share the ball.
</P>
<P>
   And they did, over and over, in Duke's 85-64 victory over the
Owls in the East Regional final that sent the Blue Devils (36-1) to
the Final Four in the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament for the eighth time in Coach Mike Krzyzewski's 19 years.
Duke will play Michigan State next Saturday in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   It is a return trip that comes nearly a year to the day after
Duke blew an 18-point lead in the South Regional final against
Kentucky, and four years after Krzyzewski was sidelined with
fatigue and his program dangled in traction after a 13-18 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a long time coming,'' said Langdon, a fifth-year
senior guard and the only mainstay of Duke's Final Four-less years.
``Coming back off the year where coach missed part of the season,
he was very disappointed. He has the most dedication of anyone in
the nation in getting the program back up. The motivation comes
from him and the team just follows.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils had to trust Langdon and Carrawell Sunday to
break down the Owls' matchup zone defense _ a shape-shifting zone
called Rover that allowed No. 6-seeded Temple to win at least some
categories on the statistic sheet. Temple had fewer turnovers, 10
to 14; more second-chance points, 22 to 11; and wrestled the
top-seeded Blue Devils under the glass for a 32-32 tie in rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first half, the Owls (24-11) had the Blue Devils in
their first trouble of the tournament when they jumped out to a 9-5
lead by outhustling their higher-profile opponents. Langdon,
apparently, took it personally.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 11 consecutive points in the next 2 minutes 30
seconds, a streak that began with a graceful running one-hander and
was followed by three consecutive 3-pointers that were set up by
bone-rattling picks from Elton Brand, Chris Burgess and Shane
Battier.
</P>
<P>
   It was an outburst that keyed a 17-2 run and allowed the Blue
Devils to cruise into halftime with a 43-31 lead, despite Brand,
the consensus all-American, being held to just 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   Temple Coach John Chaney had prepared his team to concede
long-range jumpers, but warned his players that Langdon needed an
opening the size of an eye of a needle to get his shot off. But
after the Duke guard torched his Owls for 23 points on 6-of-7
shooting _ including five 3-pointers _ even he appeared stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Langdon was going to hit shots, but you don't know how
well,'' said Chaney, who lost his fourth regional final in 11
years. ``He was coming off screens, twisting and hitting three
pointers over 6-10 guys.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Carrawell told how he could watch tapes of upcoming
opponents and differentiate between suburban players and playground
types. He called his Langdon a ``picture-perfect suburban gym''
shooter. He said he knew Temple was a collection of city players,
like himself, that was intent on shutting down the Blue Devils'
inside game.
</P>
<P>
   Carrawell called himself a ``money player'' who had won a few
dollars against older guys on his East St. Louis playgrounds. He
predicted he might be able to hurt the Owls themselves. And he did,
by knifing his 6-foot-6-inch frame into the defense's massive guts
_ 6-10 Lamont Barnes, 6-9 Kevin Lyde and beefy 6-5 Mark Karcher _
and kicking the ball out to Langdon and Duke's other dead-eye
shooters. The Blue Devils found the bottom of the net 60 percent of
the time from the field and 58 percent from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could get by them because they are so big,'' said
Carrawell, who had seven assists without a turnover. ``Then I
wanted to keep my head up and get the ball to the open man.''
</P>
<P>
   But the junior's play was far more complete than just setting
the table. He grabbed 7 rebounds, added 12 points and hounded
Karcher into 7-of-25 shooting and 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``He arguably is as important as anybody on this team,''
Krzyzewski said o Carrawell. ``When he does his role at a high
level, we are an outstanding basketball team. When he plays like he
did today, it's beautiful to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his roles is to be the level head of a young
super-talented team. With 10:35 left, the Owls cut Duke's lead to
10 points with full-court pressure. Carrawell quietly reminded his
teammates of how the Blue Devils blew that 18-point lead with nine
minutes left in last year's South Regional final in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he went to work. He harassed Karcher into a bad shot,
threaded a nifty bounce pass inside to Brand for a dunk, then got a
hand on a pass intended for Barnes. It was Barnes, whose 19 points,
6 rebounds and terrific defense on Brand (21 points), kept the
Owls' hopes alive. But by the time Carrawell was done, the Blue
Devils had snuffed the Owls' run and were on their way back to the
site of last year's heartbreak and another Final Four appearance.
</P>
<P>
   So, with 41 seconds left, in front of the Duke bench, the
inner-city money player wrapped his arms around the shooter from
the Great White North. They both smiled. ``Last year, I was smiling
too early and we blew 18 points,'' Carrawell said. ``I looked up
and saw we were up 18 points and there were just a few ticks left.
I figured we were in the books.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week in Florida, they get the opportunity to write a few
more chapters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 2115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
