<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-EAST-FINAL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke too hot for Owls
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ From John Chaney's perspective, the only
thing that will stop Duke from winning the NCAA championship is
divine intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever plans on beating them.... I just hope they believe in
the Lord,'' the Temple coach said after watching the No. 1 Blue
Devils overwhelm his Owls 85-64 Sunday for the East Regional
championship at Continental Airlines Arena. ``Beyond that I have no
idea how you can beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke (36-1) extended its school-record winning streak to 31
games and gave coach Mike Krzyzewski his eighth Final Four
appearance since 1986 and fifth this decade. The Blue Devils will
play Michigan State in Saturday's semifinals in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Duke's first Final Four appearance since 1994 and
comes just four seasons after the program hit rock bottom in 1995
with a 13-18 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time coming. What a great, great feeling,''
said senior guard Trajan Langdon, who hit 6 of 7 shots (5 of 6 from
3-point range) and finished with 23 points. Langdon, who scored 24
in the semifinal victory against Southwest Missouri State on
Friday, was selected the regional's most outstanding player.
</P>
<P>
   Temple (24-11), winless in four regional finals under Chaney,
could not overcome a Duke team that shot 60 percent (69.6 in first
half) against one of the nation's best defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Temple, the No. 6 seed, had held its first three NCAA opponents
to fewer than 55 points and had given up 70 points only three times
in 34 games while holding teams to 37.8 percent shooting. It was
the most points Temple has ever allowed in an NCAA Tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly thought that we were the only team in our bracket
that could beat them,'' Chaney said. ``We played as well as we
could play. If we had shot a little better it might have looked
better. But the results would have still been the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke, which has won its four tournament games by an average of
30 points, had too many weapons for Temple to defend. When the Owls
shut off center Elton Brand inside, Langdon went on a tear of 11
consecutive points in the first half. When they finally got a
defender on Langdon, Brand pounded Temple inside to finish with 21
points and eight rebounds. When they put pressure on point guard
William Avery, forward Chris Carrawell split the Owls' defense for
12 points, seven rebounds and seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just a lot better than anyone we've played,'' Temple
guard Rasheed Brokenborough said. ``Every time we stopped one
thing, they came up with something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Up 43-31 at halftime, Duke quickly stretched the lead to 61-41
on a Langdon 3-pointer with 14:36 left. That's when Temple put
together its only meaningful run, a 13-3 spurt that cut it to 64-54
with 10:25 left. Temple could get no closer as Duke regained
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never worried,'' said Avery, who scored 13. ``This team
does not panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
