<SLUG> BC-BKC-EAST-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Langdon's timing as good as his touch
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When Duke won three games without Trajan
Langdon after he injured his left foot in the ACC Tournament, some
suggested the Blue Devils were so talented they really didn't need
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this proves we need him,'' coach Mike Krzyzewski said
after Langdon scored 23 points in the East Regional championship
against Temple. ``We really, really need him.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke's talented but young team had a chance to get rattled
early, falling behind 9-5. That'r when Langdon took control,
scoring 11 consecutive points, including three 3-pointers in a row,
to help put his team up 16-11.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon's scoring had a calming effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little nervous at the beginning, but Trajan
wasn't,'' Krzyzewski said. ``...What he did was bigger than the
points. Instinctively, he knew he had to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Langdon's teammates agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he hit those 3-pointers, he probably didn't have to hit a
shot the rest of the game,'' forward Chris Carrawell said. ``It
just opened everything else up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two games, Langdon has hit 15 of 21 shots, including
9-for-12 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to tell our guys that he could look at the basket
through the eye of a needle and get his shot off,'' Temple coach
John Chaney said. ``He is absolutely one of the best pure shooters
I have ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Milestones for Krzyzewski
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski moved into a tie with former UCLA coach John Wooden
for second on the career NCAA Tournament victory list with 47. In
first place is Krzyzewski's old nemesis, former North Carolina
coach Dean Smith, who had 65 wins. This is Krzyzewski's eighth
Final Four appearance, which is third behind Wooden (12) and Smith
(11).
</P>
<P>
   One for the highlight reel
</P>
<P>
   One of the most enduring images of this tournament is bound to
be a dunk on a follow shot by Duke freshman Corey Maggette with 2.5
seconds left in the first half. It came off a miss by William
Avery. Maggette jumped over several players in front of him.
``That,'' Krzyzewski said, ``was pretty awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   At home in New Jersey
</P>
<P>
   Duke has advanced to the Final Four five times by winning the
East Regional in East Rutherford. N.J. The others were in 1986,
'88, '89 and '90, and Duke is 10-0 in NCAA games played here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
