<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke joins Spartans in St. Pete
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Two of the teams will play a rematch of
a tough December game. Two of the coaches will renew their lopsided
rivalry. Those are just a couple of the story lines for the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Duke (36-1) defeated Temple 85-64 Sunday in the East
Regional final to advance to its fifth Final Four of the decade.
The Blue Devils will meet Michigan State (33-4), which knocked off
defending national champion Kentucky 73-66 Sunday in the Midwest
Regional. The two teams previously met on Dec. 2 in Chicago, with
Duke winning 73-67.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's other semifinal in St. Petersburg, Ohio State
(27-8), the South Regional champion, will meet Connecticut (32-2),
the West Regional champ. Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien was 0-18
against UConn's Jim Calhoun when he was at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at Saturday's games:
</P>
<P>
   _ Duke vs. Michigan State: With their victory against Temple,
the Blue Devils have won 31 consecutive games. But they have had
some challenges along the way. One of those came three months ago
against Michigan State, the Big Ten champion.
</P>
<P>
   In that regular-season meeting, Duke jumped to a 17-point lead
in the first half and then held on despite getting out-rebounded
41-25. Duke held Mateen Cleaves, the Big Ten Player of the Year, to
3-for-17 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're better than we were in December,'' Michigan State coach
Tim Rizzo said. ``Unfortunately, Duke's a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State is in its first Final Four since 1979, when Magic
Johnson led the Spartans to the national championship over Indiana
State and Larry Bird. Duke is in its first Final Four since 1994
and its fifth in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   _ UConn vs. Ohio State: After losing three regional finals under
Calhoun, UConn has finally reached its first Final Four. Ohio State
is in the Final Four for the first time since 1968, when the
Buckeyes lost to North Carolina in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, it will be a matchup of two of the nation's
best backcourts: Ohio State's Scoonie Penn and Michael Redd vs.
UConn's Khalid El-Amin and Richard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   THE FINAL FOUR
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   At Tropicana Field,
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (36-1) vs. Michigan State (33-4), 5:42 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State (27-8) vs. Connecticut (32-2), approx. 8:17 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   Championship game, 9:18 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
