<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-MEET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL CHIEFS EXUDE OPTIMISM ON PLANS TO CUT PRODUCTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DAVID IVANOVICH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VIENNA, Austria _ OPEC oil ministers began arriving here Sunday for
their spring meeting, voicing confidence that they will quickly be
able to ratchet down oil production in an effort to boost world
crude prices.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the 11-member Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, as well as officials from Mexico and other
non-OPEC oil-producing nations, are expected to ratify an accord
reached earlier this month to pull more than 2 million barrels a
day off global markets.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Saudi Oil Minister Ali Naimi, flush from a Saturday
meeting with other Persian Gulf producers, told reporters he
expects the parties to fully implement the proposed cuts within a
month. Libyan Energy Minister Abdalla Salem El-Badri said he
expects compliance even earlier, by April 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the members are agreed ... and will comply with the
agreement,'' said Venezuelan Energy Minister Ali Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Few oil analysts, however, believe this coalition of OPEC and
nonaffiliated producers actually will meet the 2 million-barrel
goal, which would represent about 2.7 percent of world production.
The OPEC producers alone would account for about 1.7 million
barrels of that reduction.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts, struck by the role OPEC heavyweight Saudi Arabia
played in spearheading the accord, are convinced they will follow
through with a sizable production cut of at least 1 million
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   For Saudi Arabia, the agreement will mean cutting production by
585,000 barrels a day, pushing the kingdom's production below an 8
million-barrel floor for the first time since the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   But the Saudis, facing the prospect of government revenues
plunging by a third if crude prices do not recover, decided
propping up prices was a greater priority. Saudi Arabia loses about
$2.5 billion in annual revenues for every $1 drop in the price of
crude.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials, in a sign of their growing cooperation with
the OPEC producers, are joining the summit. Mexico has been a key
player in all three efforts over the last year to cut production in
a bid to kick up prices.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure oil ministers would arrive in Vienna with a deal
already in hand, the Saudis agreed to a key concession demanded by
Iran, OPEC's second-largest producer and Saudi Arabia's chief
rival. The Iranians insisted that Tehran be allowed to cut
production from a starting point of 3.6 million barrels, rather
than a 3.3 million-barrel baseline that the Saudis and others would
have preferred.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations about the production cuts have helped send crude
prices up more than 10 percent in less than two weeks. On Friday,
oil for delivery in April rose 24 cents to close at $15.24 on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Nizam Sharief, director of energy policy for Hornsby &AMP; Co., a
Houston-based energy risk management services firm, estimates crude
prices could rise to $18 or even $20 a barrel by the fourth quarter
if the parties were to comply with only 75 percent of the accord.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to trim production is complicated, however, by Iraq's
effort to expand its production capacity. Iraq's production is
restricted by sanctions imposed by the U.N. Security Council and
its own production constraints in the wake of the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad is producing far less than U.N. sanctions would allow
for the purchase of much-needed food and medicine. Iraqi Oil
Minister Amer Rasheed said Sunday that his country already is
producing about 2.7 million barrels a day and plans to expand
production by another 200,000 barrels or so by the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
