u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WOMEN-FINAL4-COX     03-21 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WOMEN-FINAL4-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cyclones to be test; Dogs look to the final
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Talk about Elite Eight contrasts. On the one hand
there's Georgia and Andy Landers, sometimes churlish, sometimes
charming, trying to take another team of Lady Bulldogs to the
familiar terrain of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Iowa State and the eternally giddy Bill
Fennelly, who moved to his native state on a lark four years ago,
even took a pay cut and figured if resurrecting a woeful program
didn't pan out, he could always get a job at his brother's tavern
in Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time ever, the old guard of the SEC and the new
kid on the block from the Big 12 tangle at the Shoemaker Center
tonight in the Mideast Regional finals.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan ``40 minutes from the Final Four'' rolls easily off
Fennelly's lips, as easily as when he talked about the task of
toppling top-seeded and high-profile Connecticut on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After Iowa State sent the glamor girl Huskies packing, he
pondered his, and his program's, first foray into the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I never knew if I'd get here,'' said Fennelly,
who coached Toledo to six 20-win seasons and three NCAA trips.
``It's a dream come true. We've won 25 games and have gotten this
far, and I think we now have some credibility that we didn't have
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia perennially is faced with living up to its lofty
accomplishments as one of only four programs to go to at least four
Final Fours. But Landers has made any more talk about playing next
weekend in San Jose _ which the Lady Dogs did after beating Clemson
on Saturday _ strictly verboten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset because their minds have wandered away from what's
in front of us,'' Landers said. ``Instead of thinking about the
challenge of Iowa State, they're thinking about being one step away
from the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   His players got the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name `Georgia' establishes a target on our back,'' guard
Kiesha Brown said. ``But as far as Cinderella teams go, I don't
believe all that. Every team that's here now is supposed to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones, second in the country in 3-point shooting all
season, made five of six 3-pointers in a three-minute stretch to
stun UConn. Unlike Georgia, they're not fast, athletic or deep, but
they have a habit of sticking around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if other teams are going to overlook us
anymore,'' Iowa State forward Monica Huelman said.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST REGIONAL FINAL:
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA VS. IOWA STATE
</P>
<P>
   -- When; where: 7:30 tonight, Shoemaker Center, Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   -- TV; radio: ESPN2; WNGC (95.5 FM).
</P>
<P>
   -- Records: No. 3 seed Georgia is 26-6; No. 4 seed Iowa State is
25-7.
</P>
<P>
   -- Series: First meeting.
</P>
<P>
   -- Starting lineups: Georgia _ Guards, Coco Miller, 5 feet 10,
soph.; Kelly Miller, 5-10, soph.; center, Tawana McDonald, 6-4, fr;
forwards, Pam Irwin-Osbolt, 5-11, sr.; Angie Ball, 6-3, jr. Iowa
State _ guards, Tracy Gahan, 6-1, fr.; Stacy Frese, 5-8, jr.;
center, Angie Welle 6-4, fr.; forwards, Megan Taylor, 5-11, soph.;
Monica Huelman, 6-2, jr.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
