<SLUG> BC-RAC-GOTHAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-SHOT BADGE TROUNCES FAVORITES IN GOTHAM STAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his 7{-length, come-from-behind victory over favored
Apremont in the Gotham Stakes on Sunday, Badge proved he could do
more than handle six furlongs on the inner track at Aqueduct.
</P>
<P>
   But was the victory, Badge's fourth in his last five starts,
enough to propel the 3-year-old chestnut colt into the Kentucky
Derby?
</P>
<P>
   Shaun Bridgmohan, Badge's jockey, said he would love a trip to
Churchill Downs on the first Saturday of May, and for James Vena of
Southbelle Stable, who bought Badge as a yearling partly because
the colt reminded him of Secretariat, it would be a dream come
true.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the colt's trainer, Joe Aquilino, wants to
concentrate on the next step _ the $600,000 Wood Memorial on April
10, a race won by Badge's sire, Air Forbes Won, who also took the
Gotham in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, I want to see how he comes out of this race, but he
looks terrific and I don't expect any problems,'' Aquilino said.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few problems for Badge in the one-mile Gotham,
which was expected to pit the California-based Apremont, winner of
his first two starts by a combined 11{ lengths, against the John
Kimmel-trained Successful Appeal, winner of the Cowdin last year.
</P>
<P>
   While Apremont, who finished second, ran as expected _ at least
until the final 200 yards _ Successful Appeal ran into trouble on
the turn and was not a factor in the drive to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgmohan, meanwhile, allowed Badge to settle toward the back
of the 11-horse field during the early going as Apremont set
fractions of 22 1/5 seconds and 44 3/5 while being pressed by the
long shot Country Deed.
</P>
<P>
   Badge moved into striking position on the turn, despite being
crowded near the three-eighths pole, gathered himself and powered
between horses to grab the lead in the stretch as Apremont began
drifting out badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he saw that hole, he went right for it,'' said
Bridgmohan, who then rode the colt to the wire in 1:34 3/4. ``I
think it says a lot about him to overcome that trouble and still
come back to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The long shot Robin Goodfellow finished third. Apremont did not
win for the first time for the trainer Ron McAnally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only his third race and he's still green,'' the jockey
Chris McCarron said. ``He doesn't know yet what he's supposed to do
out there. He puts that game face on and rolls. He was getting out
bad at the end; that's what concerns me.''
</P>
<P>
   Badge, who returned $25.60 for a $2 bet to win, earned $90,000
for his first graded-stakes victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
