<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DINGELL-PROFILE-ART-N     03-21 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINGELL-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THROWBACK AS A POLITICAL SPOUSE WHO ISN'T AFRAID TO SPEAK OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 By   FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of the many reasons members of Congress gave for
attending a bipartisan civility retreat in Hershey, Pa., over the
weekend, Rep. John Dingell's was simplest: His wife made him do it.
</P>
<P>
   That explanation sounded a little too pat only if you had never
met the woman in question, a whirlwind of will as adamant about the
possibility of congressional healing as her husband was skeptical.
(``A prodigious waste of my time,'' he grumbled.)
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Dingell not only suggested Hershey as a family-friendly
location for the first bipartisan retreat two years ago and planned
many of the social activities this time around; she also wrote a
101-page master's thesis at Georgetown University last fall about
the discord rending Congress and ways to alleviate it.
</P>
<P>
   One of those ways, she said, was to give lawmakers and their
families exposure to one another away from Capitol Hill, where the
pace is too frenetic and the stakes too fraught for friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know each other,'' Mrs. Dingell said on Saturday
as she scuttled between events at the retreat. ``You can't feel a
sense of community if you don't know each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as John Dingell, D-Mich., is the most senior member of the
House, where he has served for more than 40 years, Mrs. Dingell is
arguably its most ubiquitous spouse, her fingers in just about
everything, which seems to be the way she likes it.
</P>
<P>
   There is nary a spouse's committee she has not supervised, a
charity she has not patronized, a party she has not attended (and
probably, in fact, planned).
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, she is a throwback to an era when political
spouses, almost always women, tailored their lives to accommodate
and augment those of their mates. After she married Dingell 18
years ago, she switched political parties because, she said,
``there's no room for a Republican married to John Dingell.''
</P>
<P>
   But in other ways, Mrs. Dingell's experience illuminates the
problems facing the modern political spouse who maintains an
independent career and outlook. Her longtime job as an executive
with General Motors, a potent political force in Michigan,
continually raises questions about conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, her nascent advocacy for more stringent gun
control laws collides with her husband's position. When she called
the National Rifle Association ``a bunch of nuts,'' it outraged
some supporters of her husband, a former member of that
organization's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a political spouse, if you've got a good partnership,''
Mrs. Dingell said last week over breakfast in a Washington hotel,
``you never want to do anything to embarrass your husband.'' But,
she added, the high profile of such a role compels her to speak her
mind, even if her position on an issue contradicts her husband's.
</P>
<P>
   The Dingells make a striking pair. He is infamously gruff, 72
years old and 6 feet 3 inches tall; she is famously ingratiating,
45 and more than a foot shorter. He refers to her as ``the lovely
Deborah,'' using the formal version of her first name. She refers
to him as ``John Dingell,'' using both of his.
</P>
<P>
   They gush. Describing his wife as ``charming, beautiful,
intelligent,'' Dingell said, ``She packs more of those qualities
into that little body of hers than any woman I know.'' Mrs. Dingell
said, ``If anything ever happens to him, I'll die.''
</P>
<P>
   They met on an airplane 20 years ago, when his first marriage
lay in ruins and she had only been out of Georgetown University,
where she did her undergraduate work, for a few years. They were
wed in 1981, prompting Mrs. Dingell to ask General Motors to
reassign her from a job as a lobbyist to a less political position.
</P>
<P>
   She is now president of the General Motors Foundation, a
philanthropic wing of the corporation, and the couple divide their
time between houses in McLean, Va., and Dearborn, Mich., just
outside Detroit. They never added any children to the four that he
already had.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dingell grew up wealthy in Michigan, a descendant on her
mother's side of the Fishers who founded Body by Fisher. As the
oldest of four children, she was perhaps most attuned to what she
described as violent quarreling between her parents.
</P>
<P>
   She said her father, David Insley, kept a collection of firearms
and sometimes waved them around during these fights. Insley
confirmed that he owned guns but said he could not recall
brandishing them, then sighed: ``I didn't do a very good job of
parenting with guns, and I feel badly about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dingell described her subsequently peaceful years at a
convent boarding school as the seeds of her conviction about the
value of bipartisan retreats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nuns gave me a community and taught me about its
importance,'' she said. ``I think the House as an institution is a
community.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she acknowledged, it is an increasingly fractured one. She
said that was partly because fewer spouses were moving to
Washington and getting involved in its routines. ``I think spouses
were a softening, or a glue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democratic and Republican aides privately grumbled that
Mrs. Dingell was more like an abrasive, always angling for credit
and glory, forever sniffing out power and serially befriending
anyone who had it. Then again, they conceded, that pretty much
summed up the average Washingtonian.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, there has long been speculation about Mrs.
Dingell's own political ambitions. She said that for now she was
content to be as much referee as player. But she added, ``Never say
never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
