<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKTARVER-OBIT-COX-1     03-21 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKTARVER-OBIT-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jack Tarver, former Atlanta Journal-Constitution publisher and
AP chairman, dies at 82
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell and Tom Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jack Tarver, who rose from a country editor to
publisher of The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution and
chairman of The Associated Press, died Sunday at his Atlanta home.
He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   His internist, Dr. Charles Upshaw, said the probable cause of
death was a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral, for which a date and time were not set as of Sunday
night, will be held at Arlington Memorial Park. H.M. Patterson and
Son, Spring Hill, is in charge of arrangements. The body will be
cremated.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver wielded great influence in the fortunes of the
Journal and Constitution and in Atlanta. He was a newspaperman
first and last, a columnist with a biting wit, a business
executive, civic leader, corporate board member and raconteur.
</P>
<P>
   He served the newspapers as general manager from 1952-56 vice
president from 1956-57, president from 1957-58, publisher from 1958
to 1976 and vice chairman of the parent Cox Enterprises Inc. from
1976 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The late Ralph McGill hired Mr. Tarver, then a Macon News
editor, to be a humor columnist for The Atlanta Constitution in
1943.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, he was made general manager of the corporation. Mr.
Tarver's years in the management of the newspapers brought some
controversy. He was too close with a dollar for the papers' good,
his critics said. His supporters said Mr. Tarver made the papers so
prosperous that they could afford to take some unpopular stands.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest payoff came in the years when publisher Ralph McGill
was preaching racial moderation in his front-page column. That was
an enormously controversial task, but one that won Mr. McGill a
Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Williams Tarver was born March 2, 1917, in Savannah, the
only son of Otis M. Tarver, a hotelkeeper, and Mrs. DeLuth Williams
Tarver. He graduated from Mercer University in Macon with a degree
in journalism in 1938. He joined the paper five years later.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution and Journal came under the same ownership in
1950, and Mr. Tarver was named assistant to the president of
Atlanta Newspapers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver joined the elite circle of powerful people in
Atlanta. In 1960, for example, He was one of the 14 original board
members of the Commerce Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to make more fun of the power structure than anybody
else,'' former Journal editor Jack Spalding recalled. ``He would
stand up and fight anybody who tried to influence the paper. He'd
say, `Hell, no!' He was absolutely incorruptible..''
</P>
<P>
   Tarver became president of Cox Enterprises in 1969, and vice
chairman of Cox in 1976. In 1977, he was named chairman of The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver was chairman and director of Theaters Service Co. and
a director of Southern Bell, American Motors and Maccabees Mutual
Insurance Co. until retiring from those three boards at age 70. He
also was a member of the American Society of Newspaper Publishers,
chairman of its Bureau of Advertising from 1962-64 and president of
the society in 1976-77; member of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors; and member of Sigma Delta Chi.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the state Board of Education in 1942-43 and a
trustee of Mercer University. He belonged to the Capital City Club,
Piedmont Driving Club, Commerce Club and Stadium Club.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tarver was awarded the humanitarian of the year award of the
Institute for Human Relations in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving are his wife, Margaret Birch Taylor Tarver; a son,
Jack Tarver Jr. of Atlanta; a daughter, Margaret Tarver Jason of
Jacksonville, Fla.; and four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
