<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8833 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BAYHILL-HNS &LR;      03-21 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BAY </SLUG>
 HILL-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Herron soars with birdie
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ In a strong rebuttal against fit-for-lifers, Tim
``Lumpy'' Herron proved Sunday that it's OK to be addicted to the
remote control and potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   Herron earned his third PGA Tour victory in four years as a pro
when he two-putted for birdie on the second playoff hole to beat
Tom Lehman in the Bay Hill Invitational, capping a blustery day
when birdies were few and far between for the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It said something about the windy conditions that the three
contenders could play a combined 54 holes Sunday and come up with
only four birdies among them _ and none after No. 11 _ until
Herron's winner at the par-5 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Herron, the 5-10, 210-pounder who manages to make Craig Stadler
look athletic, was too good for all the flat-bellies on Sunday. He
led or shared the lead after each round, then survived an
out-of-bounds shot early on Sunday to nick Lehman and Davis Love
III, with whom Herron was tied at the start of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to play the last two days with Davis, a
world-class player, and Tom, also a world-class player who has been
as good as anybody in the majors the last few years, and come out
on top,'' Herron said. ``It's just awesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm not far behind those guys. I'm trying to work on
my consistency, which I think is the difference between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Herron shot a final-round 72 for a total of 14-under 274. Lehman
matched his 72-hole total with a 1-under 71 on the final day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if I had got under par, I'd have a good chance,''
Lehman said. ``We all hung in there, Davis, Tim and myself. Tim
just hung in there a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   After a riveting finish in regulation, in which Lehman bogeyed
the par-3 17th hole to let Herron into the playoff, both players
made routine pars on the first extra hole, No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The playoff then proceeded to the par-5 16th, which none of the
leaders had birdied earlier in the day even though it plays as one
of Bay Hill's easiest holes.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, hitting first, opened the door when he hit his drive in
the right fairway bunker for the second time Sunday. He had a poor
lie and hit a pitching wedge across the fairway into the left
rough.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Herron pumped one of his best drives of the
tournament down the fairway, then knocked a 5-iron 188 yards to
within 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman hit his approach over the green and scrambled for par.
But Herron hit his first putt just a foot behind the hole for a
tap-in victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of putts and that's what it's all about,'' Herron
said. ``On the first hole, I made a 40-footer for birdie and Davis
had it in there five feet, but missed. That's the way it went. If
Davis had made some putts, he could have probably run away with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The day had featured Lehman, Herron and Love in a virtual
deadlock throughout the 18 holes. Neither could gain an advantage
because of constant 20-to 30-mph wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it was four or five shots harder today with the wind
than it was the first three days,'' Love said.
</P>
<P>
   Herron said he didn't plan on celebrating with any wild
partying, just in his traditional fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use to do that party thing,'' he said. ``But I'll just go
out to eat with my girlfriend and parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of eating, Herron was asked if he gets tired of
questions about his portly stature.
</P>
<P>
   He shot back to the room of sportswriters: ``Why, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   Point well taken.
</P>
<P>
   Herron and Love started the day with a one-shot edge over
Lehman. But that quickly was reversed as Lehman birdied Nos. 4 and
8 while Love was walking a tightrope of consecutive pars on the
front nine and Herron bogeyed twice after an early birdie. That
left him two strokes behind Lehman going into the final nine holes.
</P>
<P>
   Herron got a shot back with a 40-foot birdie putt on No. 10. But
nothing changed on the leader board over the next five holes. With
Lehman up by a shot over Love and Herron, all three players parred
Nos. 11-16 and the marathon looked like it would last forever. But
it set up a terrific finish on the final two holes.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, the cream-puff 16th, a 511-yard par-5 that most of
the pros were reaching in two shots, produced no movement atop the
leader board.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman played it first and blew the opportunity to pad his lead
when his drive hit a bunker on the right of the fairway and he had
to blast out. From 160 yards, he knocked a 7-iron 10 feet short,
but missed the putt for a par.
</P>
<P>
   Love hit the green in two, but 3-putted from 40 feet after
running his first putt seven feet past the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Herron's second shot rolled over the green. He chipped down to
six feet, but his putt lipped around the hole and stayed out for
par.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lehman had an 8-footer to save par at the
par-3 17th rim out. He had bunkered his 4-iron approach.
</P>
<P>
   So all three players were tied at 14-under. Lehman had one hole
left, Love and Herron had two to play.
</P>
<P>
   By then, it was a battle of attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Love found out that what goes around comes around. In the second
round, Love had buried a 4-iron in the front bunker and, after
blasting out 40 feet past the pin, he slammed his sand wedge onto a
water valve, starting a gusher that flooded the sand trap. Sunday,
it hit back.
</P>
<P>
   Love again saw his tee shot plug into the sand of the same
bunker, this time with a 5-iron. ``I didn't quite catch it all,''
he said. ``I was trying to hit a short club a long way rather than
feather a 4-iron in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Love blasted out eight feet away but missed the putt for a bogey
that would be his undoing. Unable to birdie the finishing hole, he
was out of the chase.
</P>
<P>
   Herron, meanwhile, got up-and-down from the thick grass in front
of the 17th green. Then, as Lehman made a routine par on 18, Herron
rifled his tee shot down the right side.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th is a menacing hole with water hugging the right side of
the green, which curves into a gentle ``U'' shape. The pin was cut
on the right edge of the green, with water front and right of that
portion of the green.
</P>
<P>
   Herron hit his approach onto the back of the green, then watched
it back up down the slope to within seven feet of the flag. He
couldn't capitalize as the putt slid by on the right edge of the
hole, forcing the playoff with Lehman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 2140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
