<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8834 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-EAST-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-21 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-EAST-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Duke's superiority borders on unfair
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The 3-pointer heaved up by William Avery
was almost from the distance that can win you a car or a bundle of
cash in one of those halftime contests. So it was no surprise when
it bounced high off the rim instead of settling into the bottom of
the net.
</P>
<P>
   The shock came next. That's when Corey Maggette soared in from
the right baseline as if he'd been shot from a cannon and closed
the first half with a circus play.
</P>
<P>
   Maggette's head and neck were above the rim when he grabbed the
ball and kept right on going toward the ceiling of the Continental
Airlines Arena. You're not supposed to be able to jump that high
without the aid of a trampoline. Or clearance from the controllers
in the tower.
</P>
<P>
   He hovered above the basket like a traffic helicopter over a
gridlocked freeway, slammed the ball, then used both hands to chin
himself skyward until his waist was even with the rim as the horn
sounded and Duke was running to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   It has come to this for the No. 1-ranked and untouchable Blue
Devils. They are using the rest of the NCAA field to do
calisthenics. Gotta break a sweat somehow.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a tournament, it's an exhibition. Each round merely a
canvas Duke uses to paint another masterpiece. Every game another
ordinary lump of clay that winds up looking like Michelangelo's
statue of David.
</P>
<P>
   Titanic effort
</P>
<P>
   This time it was the Temple Owls who were matted, framed and
hung on the wall of the gallery 85-64 in the East Regional title
game as Duke marches on. And on. And on.
</P>
<P>
   So fitting that it was Oscar night, because Mike Krzyzewski's
Blue Devils were looking like the producers of Titanic at the 1998
Academy Awards, making endless walks to the stage to accept another
gold figurine.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't we just give them ``Best Picture'' right now and save
everybody a trip to St. Petersburg, Fla.?
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing aspect of Maggette's high-wire play was not
that he was able to pull it off. It's the fact he is only a
freshman in the awesome Duke machine, coming off the bench to play
just 14 minutes, and yet he might be the most individually talented
player on the roster, if not the entire country. No, that's not a
typo.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this bracket, the only team capable of beating Duke, I
thought, was our team,'' said Temple coach John Chaney. ``For a
time, we were able to hold them down inside and it looked OK. But
we still knew what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like that story about the great old football coach, I
guess he was from Green Bay. It was a couple of days before a big
game and he told all the reporters that his plan was to run the
ball around the right end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reporters asked, `Coach, why are you saying all of this
before the game, letting them know your game plan?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And the coach said: `Yes, they'll know what we're going to do.
They just don't know how well.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it is with Duke. You don't know how well they do
it until you get out there with them and feel like a carrot in a
food processor. You get sliced, chopped, pured.
</P>
<P>
   Bruising, aggressive Temple trailed only 9-5 after the first
five minutes of the game and for maybe a half-second, you entertain
the silly notion this could finally be a real game. Then Trajan
Langdon, the fifth-year senior and sweetest shot in the college
game, takes over.
</P>
<P>
   First Langdon took a feed from William Avery and hit a running
10-footer down the right side of the lane. Then he squeezed off a
trio of 3-point baskets _ back-to-back-to-back bullets _ in the
space of just 80 seconds that shot the feathers off the Owls and
lifted Duke's confidence to its usual heights and another rout was
on.
</P>
<P>
   Best actor, supporting cast
</P>
<P>
   After Langdon (23 points on 6-for-7 shooting) softened up Temple
from the outside, things opened up on the inside for Elton Brand to
rumble for 21 points and eight rebounds. There was also Avery
collecting 13 points and four assists and Chris Carrawell with 12
points, seven assists and seven rebounds while drawing the toughest
defensive assignment, harassing the Owls' Mark Karcher into missing
18 of 25 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just hope whoever plays them next believes in the Lord,''
Chaney said. ``Or maybe they can take Frank and Jesse James with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke has won 31 games in a row and has won its four Tournament
games by an average of 30 points. Now it's Michigan State on
Saturday, somebody else next Monday and cutting down the nets
before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney, the stuffed Owl, nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, we played as well as we can,'' he said.
``If we had shot the ball better, it might have looked better. But
the end would have been the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils doing chin-ups on the rim to keep themselves
interested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
