<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-REMATCH-NYT &LR;      03-21 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-REMATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPTEMBER REMATCH OF HOLYFIELD AND LEWIS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A week after the controversial draw between Evander Holyfield
and Lennox Lewis at Madison Square Garden rocked the boxing world,
the stage has been set for a rematch of their heavyweight
unification bout sometime in September. But a date and site for the
fight have not been been selected.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thomas, Holyfield's lawyer, said Sunday the promoter Don
King had reached agreement with Holyfield late Saturday night and
had signed him to a contract for the rematch. King already had a
rematch clause in Lewis' initial contract. Each fighter is to be
paid $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   One major sticking point in signing Holyfield for the rematch
was resolved when Holyfield decided not to seek the $20 million
that he had earned for the first bout, or even more. Lewis, who
earned $10 million for the first bout, was guaranteed $15 million
for a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was with Lennox and his people shooting the wrap show
at HBO earlier this week, Lennox said in the clearest possible
terms that he would only do the fight if there was parity in the
purses,'' Thomas said. ``There is a very strong, legitimate
argument on behalf of Evander that he is still the major
pay-per-view draw. But Evander decided to give up that argument and
make it easier. He said it was in the best interest of the sport to
have a unified champion. He believes if it didn't happen now, it
would never happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield (36-3-1) is the World Boxing Association and
International Boxing Federation champion, and Lewis (34-0-1) is the
World Boxing Council champion. The draw, in a fight clearly
dominated by Lewis, meant that both boxers kept their titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only corrective we have in boxing when we have a
dispute, to have a rematch,'' King told the Fox News Channel
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the controversial decision, the heads of all three
sanctioning bodies agreed that there should be a rematch and
ordered that it occur within six months. A September date would
fulfill that requirement; King still has to sell the fight to a
site, possibly in Las Vegas, Nev., or New York.
</P>
<P>
   But other issues beyond the date and site remain to be resolved.
A television deal will need to be negotiated with TVKO, the
pay-per-view arm of HBO, which would carry a rematch because it has
an exclusive contract with Lewis. TVKO has set aside a September
pay-per-view date for its other star, the welterweight champion
Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no deal struck for a rematch,'' the HBO senior vice
president Lou DiBella told The Associated Press. ``We haven't sat
down yet and spoken to Lewis and his people.''
</P>
<P>
   The first bout between the two boxers on March 13 drew 1.2
million pay-per-view buys at $49.95 each and sold out Madison
Square Garden. The Garden paid $8.3 million for the bout and
grossed $11 million. It remains to be seen how much the taint of
the draw will affect the market for a second bout. Three different
investigations have been launched to investigate the judging of the
bout, including a criminal investigation by Manhattan District
Attorney Robert M. Morgenthau.
</P>
<P>
   A rematch could be a tough sell, not only because of the draw,
but because the first fight was dull, with Lewis content to use his
jab to keep Holyfield at bay and Holyfield ineffective in his
efforts to work inside.
</P>
<P>
   There is also some question as to whether Lewis' promoters,
Panos Eliades of London and Dino Duva of Main Events in Paterson,
N.J., will agree to King's being the lead promoter of a rematch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
