<P>
   (NYT7) ISTANBUL, Turkey -- March 21, 1999 -- TURKEY-KURDS-2,
3-21 -- Kurdish demonstrators try to help a man shot in the head,
allegedly by Turkish police, during confrontations on Sunday.
Violence and a police crackdown marked the Kurdish New Year in
Turkey on Sunday with authorities arresting 1,500 people across the
country and putting the Kurdish-dominated southeast under a virtual
state of siege. Tension has already been running high in Turkey
after a surge of violent attacks blamed on Kurdish rebels seeking
to avenge the Feb. 15 capture of their leader, Abdullah Ocalan.
(Staton Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ISTANBUL, Turkey -- March 21, 1999 -- TURKEY-KURDS-1,
3-21 -- Kurdish demonstrators throw rocks at an armored vehicle
with the Turkish Special Police force in the Gazi Mahallasi
district of Istanbul on Sunday. Violence and a police crackdown
marked the Kurdish New Year in Turkey on Sunday with authorities
arresting 1,500 people across the country and putting the
Kurdish-dominated southeast under a virtual state of siege. Tension
has already been running high in Turkey after a surge of violent
attacks blamed on Kurdish rebels seeking to avenge the Feb. 15
capture of their leader, Abdullah Ocalan. (Stanton Winter/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- March 21, 1999 -- NEW-REPUBLIC-MEDIA, 3-21 --
The old cover of ``The New Republic'' magazine, left, and the new.
Re-designed by Roger Black, who has jazzed up magazines from
Foreign Affairs and Reader's Digest to Harper's Bazaar and
Premiere, the 85-year old magazine with approximately 100,000
readers accustomed to arid-as-tundra pages dense with three-column
type and leavened only sporadically by a line drawing, will now get
a magazine with internal color, bold graphics, photographs, more
illustrations and bigger type. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- March 21, 1999 -- DINGELL-PROFILE, 3-21 --
Debbie Dingell, the wife of Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., waits to
board a train that will take her to the the bipartisan civility
retreat for House members in Hershey, Pa. Her husband, who is the
House's most senior member, thinks the whole conference is bunk.
But that's only the beginning of their tensions: Mrs. Dingell wants
to take a position in the vanguard for gun control, while Dingell
is a former board member of the NRA. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON-- March 21, 1999 -- REPUBS-TAXES, 3-21 -- Rep.
John Kasich, chairman of the House Budget Committee, during
budgetary discussions in his committee last week. Kasich, the
irrepressible Ohio congressman who is running for president on a
theme of grass-roots empowerment, wants a ten percent
across-the-board cut in federal income tax rates. ``The more money
people have in their pocket the more they control their destiny,''
he says. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEAR GORNJA KLINA, Yugoslavia -- March 21, 1999 --
KOSOVO-2, 3-21 -- A Yugoslav army tank during an attack on
positions held by rebels with the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) on
Saturday. As hundreds of foreign monitors left Kosovo and President
Clinton met his national security team to discuss the worsening
situation, Serbian forces took advantage of the vacuum to press a
heavy offensive against the separatist KLA. (Alan Chin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DENERAL JANKOVIC, Yugoslavia -- March 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO,
3-21 -- Amb. William Walker, the head of observers for the
Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe, checks on one
of his monitors evacuating the region late Saturday. As hundreds of
foreign monitors left Kosovo and President Clinton met his national
security team to discuss the worsening situation, Serbian forces
took advantage of the vacuum to press a heavy offensive against the
separatist Kosovo Liberation Army. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
