<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANEY GETS BEAT `BY THE RIGHT GUYS'
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Behind the blue curtains where the
coaches cross paths on their way in and out of the interview room,
John Chaney embraced Mike Krzyzewski without a tear, with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel all right,'' Chaney of Temple told Krzyzewski of Duke,
after the door to the Final Four had shut in his face, a fourth
time, one step away. ``I got beat by the right guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the raspy-voiced coach got a personalized introduction to
the Krzyzewski family, walked down the hall and had a good cry.
</P>
<P>
   Duke 85, Temple 64 was the least of it, the outcome as academic
as Duke is after Trajan Langdon stepped outside the outer
boundaries of Temple's matchup zone for a trio of 3-pointers in a
89-second span, less than 10 minutes into the East Regional final
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This was Chaney crying over one of his kids, which he often does
because he obviously cares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you have to realize in this business is that
someone has to be responsible for motivating youngsters,'' he was
saying. ``If you find out they're not interested, you get rid of
them. You're not going to save everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The player he did help rescue, the one he would weep for, was
Rasheed Brokenborough, a 6-foot-4-inch guard out of a tough West
Philadelphia neighborhood known as the Bottom. Raised by his
grandmother _ the mother of 18, grandma of 30 _ Brokenborough went
to Temple as a learning disabled and was ineligible to play as a
freshman, thanks to collegiate legislation that was recently
overturned in a federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Work that took most students an hour took Brokenborough hours,
he admitted, but he had made it to his senior year, graduation in
sight. He just won't be getting back a fourth go-round with Chaney,
unless the NCAA bureaucrats cut him a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to come back and play basketball and work toward
my master's,'' he said. ``If I don't get to come back to Temple,
life will go on, and I'll work toward another challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   It was when Chaney was asked about Brokenborough that his eyes
moistened and his voice quivered. ``That's what I would've wanted
him to say,'' he said, and then the owlish coach covered his eyes
to intercept the flow of tears. The interview proceeded, Chaney
choking out more. ``Rasheed's meant so much to us,'' he said.
``He's come so far.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to class and to those sunrise practices and he got after
opponents in the matchup zone and Chaney could ask for nothing
more. Not from Brokenborough, or his team, which held 19 of 34
opponents under 60 points this season, eight under 50. Duke's
response was to shoot a tranquilizing 60 percent from the field, 59
percent (10 of 17) from behind the 3-point line. Stretched by
Langdon, stuffed by Elton Brand, Chaney decided that ``we've never
played against a team better than this, all these guys with four
weapons _ dribble, pass, shoot and see.''
</P>
<P>
   It was more than athletic superiority, Chaney understood, more
than the freshman pogo stick named Corey Maggette practically
suspending himself above the rim on the way to a put-back slam that
registered on the Richter scale. This was another one of those
highlights for the sports news shows that are draining fundamental
artistry from the game, the kind that make most Duke possessions a
joyful expression of simplicity, a compelling watch in a
noncompetitive romp.
</P>
<P>
   How does one convince children of the highlight generation that
there might be a better shot than the one that gets you on ESPN? In
the second half Sunday, Duke's William Avery pushed the ball on the
break, with Chris Carrawell filling the right lane, a half-step on
the retreating defender. For a millisecond, Avery considered a lob,
thought better of it and waited for the trailer. Langdon appeared,
prompt and primed, only to miss the open jumper, his only misfire
of the game. But that's not the point.
</P>
<P>
   It is too easy to just rationalize Duke's success by calling it
Princeton with talent. As Chaney has proved for years now at
Temple, this is about coaching and the willingness to be coached,
more than it is about SATs. It is about commitment by adults as
much as it is about cooperation by kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can teach kids to be winners, if they're interested,''
Chaney said. ``Mike doesn't save everyone either, but he and I both
work to develop will and discipline. There is a class about that
team, a respect for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   If he had to lose, better it should be to Duke, than, say,
Michigan, which denied Chaney a few years ago with its Fab Five,
derided by Chaney as nothing more than a bunch of ``head jobs
running around fabulously, individually perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney did win a national championship once, at Division II
Cheney State. ``I really don't have many more mountains to climb,''
he said. ``It's about developing kids like Rasheed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about persuading his team to play like one. Temple had a
good run, but drew Duke, and that was that. You don't cry about the
breaks, only the kids. He cried yesterday for the one he lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
