<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC RETURNING TO OLD FORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when it looked like the defending national
champion USC baseball team might not even make it to the playoffs
this season.
</P>
<P>
   That time has passed. The Trojans, who were seven games under
.500 on Feb. 27, beat No. 23 Arizona on Sunday afternoon 8-5 in
front of 654 at Dedeaux Field.
</P>
<P>
   USC, which played one of the strongest nonconference schedules
in the nation, improved to 14-14 overall and 5-1 in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a fresh start in league,'' said senior Jason Lane, who
had a home run and also pitched the final two innings against the
No. 23 Wildcats. ``We have to basically do well in league to make
the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking two of three from Arizona (20-11) is a good sign. USC
fell behind the Wildcats 4-1 early but rallied for six runs in the
fifth. All-American catcher Eric Munson's two-run homer, his
team-leading 10th of the season, was the highlight of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty characteristic of our team to come back like
that,'' Munson said. ``Most of the time we dig ourselves a hole,
and when it isn't a big hole, we come back and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Munson's homer easily cleared the 365-foot mark in right field
and he said he didn't see where it landed. He was more impressed by
Lane's homer in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (my home run) went father than Lane's ball,''
Munson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, a left-hander who started the game in left field, said he
found out later that his blast went over the screen in center
field, more than 400 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see the ball I hit,'' Lane said, ``but Munson's went
a long way. I had a good look at that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Home-run derby aside, the Trojans are gaining confidence. Their
lowest point came in a 5-2 home loss to Stanford that dropped them
to 4-11.
</P>
<P>
   USC, which won its 12th College World Series title last year,
has rebounded to win 10 of 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last month we've been playing a lot better baseball,''
Munson said. ``Lately we've been finding a way to win. We're
starting to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Better pitching has been the key. On Friday night, left-hander
Barry Zito (Pierce College) struck out 16 in USC's series-opening
17-1 win. Senior right-hander Justin Lehr (2-1) overcame a slow
start and won his second consecutive game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats had a combined six hits in the second and third
innings against Lehr, and Shelley Duncan's two-run homer gave
Arizona a 4-1 lead. It was Duncan's 11th of the season, setting a
school record for freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr retired 13 of the next 14 batters. He struck out six and
walked none in 62/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making better pitches,'' Lehr said. ``It's been a big help
showing the coaches I could throw all four pitches for strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   The unranked Trojans play at No. 6 Pepperdine on Wednesday at 2
p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 2145EST &QL; 
