<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BAYHILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERRON DEFEATS LEHMAN IN PLAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ It was the most difficult victory of Tim
Herron's career, and by far the most impressive. It took two
playoff holes for him to prevail. He outplayed two former major
winners, Tom Lehman and Davis Love III, who battled with Herron on
Sunday in a pressure-packed, final-round showdown at the Bay Hill
Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   But as dusk fell, so did Lehman and Love. Love was the first to
go, making a crucial bogey at No. 17, and finishing one stroke out
of the playoff. Then on the second hole of the playoff between
Lehman and Herron, it was Lehman who faltered on the par-5 No. 16,
hitting a poor tee shot into a bunker that made it impossible for
him to reach the green in two shots.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Herron did reach the 16th green in two shots. And
after he 2-putted for a birdie to clinch the tournament, Herron
earned a prestigious victory, a spot in next month's Masters, and
added respect that will force people to pay more attention to his
game, and less attention to his physique.
</P>
<P>
   Capturing the first-place check worth $450,000, and winning his
third tournament on the PGA Tour at age 29, Herron finished at 14
under par for the tournament (274) after Sunday's par 72. Lehman
(14-under 71 on Sunday) settled for second place, while Love (276,
13-under 73 on Sunday) was third.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed Lumpy for his portly dimensions, Herron raised his
game and his stature with a victory that was worth savoring. He
showed coolness under pressure, superb ball-striking in windy
conditions and a refusal to be intimidated by Love or Lehman, two
players who know how to close on Sunday. On this Sunday, Herron
closed the deal. And afterward, there was no reason to hide his
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot, playing the last two days with Davis Love, a
world-class player, and Tom Lehman, a world-class player,'' said
Herron, who began the final round tied with Love and one stroke
ahead of Lehman. ``It's a great feeling. It's hard to reflect right
now, because I'm still on the high. But it was just awesome. The
putts were rolling and things were happening. I was comfortable,
kind of in a zone. I made a lot of putts coming down the stretch,
and that is what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   While Herron avoided crucial miscues, Love and Lehman did not.
Love was betrayed by his putter, missing birdie putts of 5 feet on
Nos. 1, 3 and 4, which could have given him an early cushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had made some putts, Davis could have almost run away
with it,'' said Herron, who was Love's playing partner on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Love never made a birdie on Sunday, and he never recovered
from his bogey at the par-3, 219-yard No. 17, which was
particularly difficult because of swirling winds that gusted up to
25 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   When Love and Herron reached the 17th tee, they were locked in a
three-way tie at 14 under par with Lehman, who was one group ahead
playing No. 18. Love's 5-iron tee shot at No. 17 landed in the
front bunker, the same bunker that Love hit into on Friday, when he
broke a sprinkler head with his club in frustration and triggered a
steady flow of water that flooded the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Love held his temper on Sunday, but he failed to get up and down
for par, missing a 10-foot putt after his bunker shot.
</P>
<P>
   That dropped Love to 13 under, and when he failed to birdie No.
18, he knew he couldn't win. Bay Hill continued to be a tournament
with bitter endings for Love, who finished second in both 1989 and
1993 but has never won the tournament hosted by Arnold Palmer, who
was standing near the 18th green to console Love. ``One of these
years,'' Love said to Palmer as they shook hands.
</P>
<P>
   Herron almost ended the tournament at No. 18 in regulation,
after hitting a terrific 6-iron approach shot within 8 feet. But
Herron missed the putt and settled for par, forcing the playoff.
Then Lehman missed an opportunity to win on the first playoff hole,
No. 18, when his 14-foot putt for birdie was short.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big disappointment not winning,'' said Lehman, the 1996
British Open champion, who was in contention for the first time
since shoulder surgery in November. ``I had a really good chance to
win on the first playoff hole. I misread it. But you have to take
the good with the bad. If you had told me before the week started
that I would have been in a playoff, I probably would have been
overjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   On the second playoff hole, Lehman hit the poor tee shot, and
then Herron hit a great drive, reached the par-5 green in two
shots, and watched as Lehman eventually made a 25-footer to save
par. But it wasn't enough. Herron hit his first putt from 14 feet
on the final hole 2 feet long, and then made the comeback putt for
birdie and the win. Herron won the Honda Classic in 1996, and the
LaCantera Texas Open in 1997. But this victory meant more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my girlfriend some things are going to change,'' Herron
said. ``I was going to go up to Minnesota to see her. We're going
to the Masters instead. That's not a bad deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
