<SLUG> BC-BKW-COACHES-SECRETS-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETIVE COACHES DON'T TIP THEIR HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ind.)  (lb) 
 By ZACK BURGESS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAL, Ill. _ Just the mere thought of losing has both coaches
_ Rutgers' Vivian Stringer and Purdue's Carolyn Peck _ a little
secretive about what to expect from each other's very tenacious
basketball teams Monday night in the Midwest Regional final of the
National Collegiate Athletic Association women's basketball
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Peck refused to say anything about third-seeded Rutgers' matchup
zone and how to beat it. And Stringer talked about the
extraordinary guard play of Purdue's Ukari Figgs, Stephanie
White-McCarty and Katie Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   And while it is probably healthy for both coaches to express
what they respect, admire or just do not like about each other, the
talk will have to be delayed until the two teams meet.
</P>
<P>
   After all, for Stringer, it is an opportunity to get back to the
Final Four and finally win the one thing that has eluded her
throughout her collegiate coaching career _ an NCAA championship.
For Peck, it is a chance to cement her place in Purdue history
before she becomes the coach this summer of the Orlando franchise
of the Women's National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   So the talk of setting picks, splitting the defense or cutting
off the angles of an excellent offense were going to have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have to continue to work,'' said Stringer, who
took her University of Iowa team to the Final Four in 1993. ``We
have to be in control. Our defense arrived _ always does. It
arrives much earlier than our offense. The offense is beginning to
arrive with the same level of expectation and intensity that the
defense has. But it's still chugging a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive year in the tournament, Rutgers will
face a No. 1-ranked team. Last year it was the eventual champion,
Tennessee, which was on its way to a 39-0 season. This time it's
Purdue, a team with a 29-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Rutgers may be the best defensive team left in
the tournament, Purdue hasn't just given away points. The
Boilermakers have allowed 49.3 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must keep focused for 40 minutes because the only way we
are going to beat Purdue is a nip-and-tuck game,'' Rutgers forward
Shawnetta Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams come into Monday night's matchup with a great deal of
confidence, after trouncing their opponents on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue (31-1), which shot 62 percent from the field, overwhelmed
North Carolina, 82-59. Rutgers (29-5) defensively frustrated Texas
Tech into innumerable season lows and won by 53-42.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights thwarted Texas Tech into tying a record low
in a half with 11 first-half points. And Texas Tech's leading
scorer, Angie Brazeil, was held to a season-low six points.
</P>
<P>
   This is Purdue's second consecutive year in the final eight and
Rutgers' first time here since 1987. For Purdue, it's a chance to
go where it believes it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``All year we've gone out and we've attacked one game at a
time,'' Figgs said. ``This is the game that's going to get us
there. But if we keep our focus on the Final Four, it's not going
to help us in the game. We know that. We're just going to go out
and do the things we need to do in the game. We'll worry about the
Final Four after the game.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   UCLA 77, COLORADO STATE 68
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State lives at the 3-point line, and that's where the
Rams went down shooting against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Janae Hubbard had 21 points and 13 rebounds and the reserve
Melanie Pearson had 15 of her 17 points in the final 13 minutes 7
seconds as the third-seeded Bruins defeated second-seeded Colorado
State 77-68 Saturday night in the West Regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (26-7) advanced to their first NCAA regional final
Monday night against top-seeded Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA TECH 73, LOUISIANA STATE 52
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Wilson scored 27 points, and the reserve Betty Lennox had
17 of her 19 in the first half Saturday night as Louisiana Tech
overpowered Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the 21st straight for Tech (29-2).
</P>
</TEXT>
