<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANKER-EXPLOSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCK BLOWS UP ON HIGHWAY SENDING FIREBALL SKKWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ZACHARY DOWDY AND BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Southeast Expressway burst into a ``field of
flames'' Sunday afternoon when a tanker truck carrying more than
10,000 gallons of gasoline slammed into a guardrail and slid along
the southbound lanes before exploding into a spectacular fireball
100 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, the truck's driver and the occupants of two other
cars that were incinerated in the explosion suffered only minor
cuts after they scrambled out their vehicles and vaulted over a
guardrail to escape the trail of flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I saw was a tanker truck sliding by me on its side going
60 or 70 miles an hour,'' said Andrew Cappuccio, a resident of
Boston's Dorchester section who was walking his dog on Savin Hill
Beach shortly before the 4:30 p.m. explosion. The blast occurred
near the Savin Hill area of Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I heard the explosions, then a couple more. I saw maybe
six people jumping over the barrier to get away. I don't know how
anyone survived, it looked like an oil field on fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The expressway _ both north and southbound _ turned into a
parking lot for more than two miles as emergency crews tried to
clear the scene and contain environmental damage.
</P>
<P>
   Foam was spread to prevent the gasoline from leaking into
fragile adjoining marshland and beaches and Coast Guard officials
were vacuuming the gasoline from drainage pipes to prevent it from
igniting in waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino said Sunday night that state officials
assured him that both sides of the highway would be open by the
morning commute. He said that if the lanes were still closed,
transportation and public safety officials would be on hand to make
alternate plans. He urged commuters to use public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, drivers reported up to an 1 1/2-hour delay as
police rerouted traffic to local streets.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the truck's driver, William S. Leonard, 43, of
Duxbury, had just picked up 10,200 gallons of gasoline from an
Exxon station in Everett and was taking it to another Exxon station
in Holliston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said `something snapped in the truck,' '' said State Police
trooper Gary Smith, who was the first police officer to arrive on
the scene. Leonard was driving the truck for Volta Oil of Plymouth.
He will be not charged in the accident, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said it appeared that the truck drifted into the right
guardrail, flipped on its side and then slid several hundred feet.
</P>
<P>
   Residents from Boston's Jamaica Plain section to the town of
Arlington paused to gaze at the thick, black plumes of smoke
billowing over the city's skyline. Drivers in Dorchester and the
city of Quincy abandoned their cars to search for the smoke's
origin.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard told police it appeared that the tanker was already on
fire when the truck flipped. He escaped by punching out a window in
the truck when it stopped sliding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like napalm going off,'' said Smith, a
16-year-veteran of the force. The truck was so badly melted that a
heavy plow had to be brought in to get it off the road. ``I've
never seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the northbound side of the expressway was filled with
traffic at the time of the explosion, only two cars were near the
tanker when it exploded on the southbound side, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Randall J. Hallett and Donna Johnson fled from their
car, jumping over bushes and barriers to escape the flames.
</P>
<P>
   A family of three from Malden, Andre P. Marc, 48, Marie M. Marc,
43, and their daughter Marie, 18, also escaped with cuts and
bruises. Marie Marc also had a sprained ankle. They were
transported to Boston Medical Center for treatment. An unidentified
firefighter also received minor injuries, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When the smoke cleared around 5 p.m., the truck could be seen on
its side, its body reduced to a smoking steel skeleton. The other
burned cars were parked in the passing lane, both charred and
unrecognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Toner, of Dorchester, said he was walking through McConnell
Park and happened to look up and see the truck in distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It flipped and started scraping,'' he said. ``It was like
something you see in the movies. I saw a wall of flame 30 feet high
and 900 yards long. You could feel the heat from here.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash set off several explosions, which nearby residents
first said they thought were gunshots. Later, they said, it
appeared several compartments of the tanker exploded separately,
and then the cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars all exploded. That's all you could hear,'' said
Christine O'Leary, of Dorchester, who was helping a friend paint
her kitchen when the truck veered out of control and overturned.
</P>
<P>
   The MBTA shut down its Red Line service for an hour because of
the explosion and resulting smoke. Logan airport officials said the
wind was favorable and did not blow the acrid, black smoke near
runways. Police said the wind also prevented cars in the northbound
lanes from catching fire.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the scene were most concerned about the unburned
gas leaking into the ocean, and possibly reigniting.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Devine, from Coast Guard Marine Safety Office in Boston
said clean-up crews were waiting for a cleaning truck to try and
vacuum out gasoline that had seeped into the sewer drains and
emptied into the discharge point on the otherside of the northbound
lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more it gathers the more you have to deal with fumes. It
doesn't take much to set gasoline on fire,'' Devine said.
</P>
<P>
   But for commuters, the tanker's explosion will likely be felt
into this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to think about it,'' said Brian Donovan, of
Quincy, who was diverted from the expressway and found himself or
Dorchester Avenue. He said he had gone about a mile in an hour at
5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I about it on the radio and thought how bad could it be? Well,
its bad. If it's like this tomorrow, I'm giving up. It's going to
take me four hours to get five miles at this rate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
