<HEADLINE>
ZAMBONI DELAYS THE INEVITABLE: RANGER LEAD SLIPS AWAY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Zamboni machine that resurfaces the ice
accidentally delays a game for 35 minutes by gouging long gashes
into the playing surface, the witnesses seek meaning in such an
omen. Does it suggest that winter is over and it is time for the
ice to go away? Or could it be that the Rangers' playoff hopes,
already on thin ice, are about to be ripped to shreds?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the symbolism, the Rangers squandered a lead again
Sunday at Madison Square Garden. After leading the Pittsburgh
Penguins by two goals, they settled for a 2-2 tie that left them,
temporarily at least, in ninth place, 3 points behind the Boston
Bruins for the eighth and final playoff berth in the National
Hockey League's Eastern Conference. The Rangers also were 1 point
ahead of 10th-place Florida before the Bruins and Panthers played
Sunday night. As they begin a three-game trip Monday night at Tampa
Bay and wait for the NHL trading deadline Tuesday night, the
Rangers face some intriguing personnel decisions involving injured
players.
</P>
<P>
   One of them involves Ulf Samuelsson, the veteran defenseman, who
may be available to a Stanley Cup contender willing to exchange a
player of value for an intimidator who can become an unrestricted
free agent July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The situation became complicated late in Sunday's game when
Samuelsson broke his right foot when he blocked a shot. It forced
him to leave the game and will idle him for two to three weeks, the
Rangers said. Should Samuelsson heal in that time, he could return
in time for the end of the regular season and the beginning of the
two-month Stanley Cup tournament. But what if the injury does not
heal as expected?
</P>
<P>
   The other injured player is Wayne Gretzky, the star center, who
has not played since Feb. 22 because of a protruding disc in his
neck. Gretzky, who recently had a cortisone injection, traveled
with the team to Tampa, Fla., and said he hoped to return on
Saturday at Philadelphia or next Monday night, when the Rangers
return to the Garden to play the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Rangers have slumped to 1-3-2 in their last six
games and do not have a victory in their last three, they are 6-3-3
in Gretzky's absence, thanks in part to the play of centers Petr
Nedved, Marc Savard and Manny Malhotra, who have skated in
Gretzky's place.
</P>
<P>
   Blending Gretzky back into the mix without limiting the
contributions of the others will be a challenge for John Muckler,
the veteran coach, who calls Gretzky his game breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved scored the second Rangers goal Sunday, giving them a 2-0
lead, on the power play just 15 seconds after the beginning of the
second period. The first intermission lasted 53 minutes because the
ice-making machine accidentally scooped up a rubber-and-metal piece
that helps anchor the goal net. By dragging this piece around, the
Zamboni created ruts that were, at worst, about an inch wide and an
inch deep, according to Rangers goalie Mike Richter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone could have broken their ankle,'' Richter said. At
first, players for both teams tried to fill the ruts by standing in
what looked like a dance line and using their skates to scrape snow
and ice chips. When that didn't work, the referee, Paul Stewart,
ordered the two Zambonis back on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   They were followed by nine workers with shovels, water bottles
and squeegees. Also assisting were Stewart and his linesmen.
Stewart, on hands and knees, jammed fistfuls of shavings into the
cracks. To soothe impatient fans, the Garden announced that soft
drinks and bottled water would sell for half-price for the
remainder of the game. Jaromir Jagr, the Penguins' captain, lay
back on the bench and put a towel over his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He used to play with Nedved and Kevin Stevens when they were on
the Penguins, and he joshed with Stevens after finishing his nap.
Stevens had given the Rangers a 1-0 lead at 6 minutes 19 seconds of
the first period. Both Rangers goals were scored on their first
shots of the periods against Jean-Sebastien Aubin, subbing for the
injured Tom Barrasso. But Pittsburgh cut the Rangers' lead to 2-1
at 7:11 of the second on a goal by Bobby Dollas, who finished off a
play created by Jagr, who is a leading candidate for the Hart
Trophy as most valuable player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   German Titov made it 2-2 at 16:26 of the second on the power
play after the Rangers captain Brian Leetch, trying to clear the
puck away from the crease, unintentionally kicked it to Titov.
</P>
<P>
   The best moment of the overtime, and of the game, came when Adam
Graves of the Rangers lost the puck to Jagr near the Pittsburgh
blue line. Jagr roared in alone on Richter, brought him down with a
fake, but was stopped on a backhanded shot by Richter's left leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read it,'' Richter said of Jagr's fakes. ``You mirror what
he does to you. You hope he hits you.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
