<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-CAVALIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU COULD SEE IT COMING: ANOTHER DEFLATING LOSS FOR NETS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Anyone who has watched a couple of Nets games knew
that Keith Van Horn was going to take a few dribbles, spin and
shoot. That is the heralded forward's go-to move, and Sunday night,
when the Nets needed a basket, he went to it.
</P>
<P>
   But Cavaliers forward Shawn Kemp has watched the Nets on
videotape. So he was waiting for the spin. When it came, with the
Nets trailing by a point with 17 seconds remaining in the game,
Kemp stripped Van Horn of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's Brevin Knight made two free throws eight seconds
later and, when Stephon Marbury's last-gasp 3-point attempt bounced
high and off the rim, the Cavaliers claimed an 88-85 victory before
a crowd of 13,806 at Gund Arena. The loss dropped the Nets to 4-20.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, who highlighted the fourth-quarter rally with 8 points,
led the Nets for the fifth time in his five games with the team
with 20 points. Van Horn scored a season-low 12, and the
little-used reserve Chris Carr scored 18.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpshooting Wesley Person led the Cavaliers (12-11) with
22 points, and Andrew DeClercq added 14. Kemp and Cedric Henderson
followed with 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   After more than three quarters of lethargy, the Nets awoke to
challenge the Cavaliers down the stretch. Trailing by 84-75 with
four minutes remaining, Marbury made two 3-pointers and a driving
layup to spark a 10-2 run that put the end in doubt. His final
3-pointer, from 26 feet and over Knight, cut the Cavaliers' lead to
86-85 with 1 minute 46 seconds left. But the Nets' offense crumbled
after that, as Van Horn and Kerry Kittles missed shots in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   Carr kept the Nets alive early. Hitting two 3-pointers, dropping
midrange jumpers and driving aggressively to the basket, the
6-foot-6-inch swingman scored 16 points before the break. It was an
astounding display, considering Carr had played only eight minutes
and scored just 2 points since joining the Nets in the Marbury
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Carr's inspiring play was not enough to get the Nets a lead,
though, as his teammates struggled. Marbury, with 7 points, was the
only other Nets player to score more than 4 in the half, and with
the Nets shooting their usual 37 percent, Cleveland built a 49-40
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The only change the third quarter brought was Carr's return to
earth. He went scoreless in six minutes, and the Nets continued to
trail, entering the final period with a 72-64 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets hope their coming four consecutive home games will help
them mount a turnaround. The stretch starts Monday against Toronto,
a 100-85 winner over the Nets last Tuesday. Though the Raptors won
that one easily, they are beatable, as are Detroit, Indiana and
Cleveland, which also visit Continental Arena this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Meadowlands will be a welcome site for the Nets, one that
coach Don Casey says can rejuvenate a reeling team that is sorely
in need of a spark. ``I think that's very important, to play at
home, especially with what we did against Dallas,'' said Casey,
referring to last Wednesday's victory over the Mavericks. ``The
energy was there, the effort factor was there. I think it'll be
good for all of us. We need it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
