<HEADER>
A8858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-KENTUCKY-MICHSTAT     03-21 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KENTUCKY-MICHSTATE-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
20 YEARS LATER, ANOTHER MAGICAL TRIP TO THE FINAL FOUR FOR MICHIGAN
STATE  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Magic Johnson stood on a folding chair about 10 rows
from the crowded court, smiling and acting like a proud father as
he watched Michigan State celebrate after defeating Kentucky,
73-66, in the championship game of the Midwest Regional on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The joyful scene brought back so many memories for Johnson, from
as long as 20 years ago, when he was the starting point guard and
as recently as 10 months ago, when he was an imposing practice
player against these Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   Call Michigan State's businesslike triumph over Kentucky
magical, although there was no mystery about how the Spartans did
it. They never wilted when the Wildcats rushed to a 13-point lead
in the first half, they played a smothering defense that frustrated
Kentucky and they performed like the more experienced team while
dominating the final eight minutes of a crisp and classic game.
</P>
<P>
   Why else was Sunday magical? Because the Spartans are returning
to the Final Four for the first time since Johnson was a sophomore
and they won the national title over Larry Bird and Indiana State
in 1979. Because Johnson, the most famous pickup player to join
games with Michigan State, has helped nurture these players on
humid days when the Final Four was simply two 20-year-old words and
not a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great because after playing against these guys every
summer, I know what they've been through,'' Johnson said. ``I know
how hard coach Izzo has worked. You can see how each of them has
developed every year. This just feels wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Izzo, the coach with the red face and the overflowing
emotions, who watched his team win its 22nd straight game to earn a
matchup with Duke on Saturday, said, ``Other than my daughter being
born, this is the greatest day of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone tossed Johnson a white T-shirt and a tan cap with
``Final Four'' emblazoned across them, and Johnson immediately wore
the cap. Even as Johnson answered questions, he never stopped
staring at the Spartans on the court. There was so much to see, so
much for Johnson and everyone clad in green around him to absorb on
this magical day.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson saw Mateen Cleaves, his buddy and fellow point guard who
had 11 assists and a critical 3-pointer to end the first half. He
saw Morris Peterson, who poured in 19 points and had 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   He saw Antonio Smith, who scolded his teammates during a timeout
to jolt them and helped limit Scott Padgett to four points for the
first 38 minutes. He saw A.J. Granger, who had 14 points in 18
minutes. He saw a team that wanted some respect against the
tradition-rich defending champions and snatched it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was a blessing that everyone did that,'' Johnson
said about classifying the third-seeded Wildcats as the favorites.
``Making us the underdog made us play harder. One thing about us is
we played hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats (28-9), who were trying to scoot into the Final
Four for the fourth straight season, found out just how hard the
Spartans (32-4) would play. Michigan State trailed by 17-4, 19-6
and 26-14 in the first half and Kentucky seemed to be one streak
away from making reservations for St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they did that, we would have been in trouble,'' Izzo said.
But it never transpired. Kentucky's senior threesome of Padgett,
Heshimu Evans and Wayne Turner did not score for more than 25
minutes, and the Spartans uncorked a 9-0 blitz to make the game
competitive again. Kentucky's lead never surged above five points
and Cleaves nailed a 3-pointer with two seconds left in the half to
bring Michigan State within 36-35.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they had turned it around when Mateen hit that three,''
Johnson said. ``I turned to my father and told him that was the
shot we needed. We hadn't played well in the first half and we were
only down one.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, whose team played the other three Final Four teams this
season and defeated only Ohio State, was sheepish about the shot,
saying: ``It could have been a little luck. I just thank God it
went in.''
</P>
<P>
   The second half was artistic, aggressive and awesome to watch.
Neither team had more than a four-point lead for the first 12
minutes, but, again, it was Cleaves who guided the Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   The former high school quarterback fired an 80-foot bomb to
Andre Hutson, who corralled it over his shoulder and made a tricky
layup to give Michigan State a 55-54 lead with 7 minutes 30 seconds
left. The Spartans never trailed again, erupting for 10 of the next
14 points for a 65-58 lead with 3:11 on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get back a few different times, a few different
situations,'' said Kentucky coach Tubby Smith. ``We were trying to
get the ball to the guards, but they made all the right moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Wildcats also made some wrong moves. They missed
three straight shots and two of four free throws after Michigan
State rolled to the seven-point lead, then had to rely on desperate
3-point shots. Peterson connected on six free throws in the last 29
seconds for Michigan State.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think they wanted it a lot more than us and they showed
it,'' Kentucky's Desmond Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   They will never win a contest for basketball beauty, they have
perhaps one player in Cleaves who is known nationally and they are
trying to do something that has not been achieved at their school
since Johnson was running the show 20 years ago, but the Spartans
looked gorgeous, gained a ton of national prominence and made their
former point guard howl like an undergraduate Sunday. Yes, it was a
magical day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get to the Final Four, anything can happen,'' Johnson
said. ``You have to go out there and make it happen. Now we have
the chance because we're there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
