<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLEY SHOWS THE KNICKS WHAT'S MISSING: HIM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Charles Oakley was surrounded by a bunch of dancing
and whirling kids bouncing on the purple-trimmed court as if it was
a box-spring mattress.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley is too old for such nonsense. He is too grizzled and too
hardened to gloat, too crotchety to act like his fresh-faced,
hardly legal-aged teammates in Raptors jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Typically Oak, he lumbered slump-shouldered away from the
celebration with his head of dreadlocks tilted down. As he exited
after a hard day's work, the Knicks could watch every personality
trait they used to embrace leave the court, too.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks used to dig around for victories like
scavengers and rope rebounds with intimidation tactics. They used
to have nerves as steady as a bomb technician's and an uncanny
knack for big plays. They used to have Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is a Toronto Raptor. And as he proved Sunday, the
clothes don't make the man. Oakley did everything he used to do as
a Knick while leading the Raptors to a franchise-high fifth
straight victory, 85-81, in a raucous overtime at Air Canada Center
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veteran teams would have found a way to pull that one out,''
Oakley said of the Knicks after grabbing 12 rebounds and scoring
all four of his points in overtime. ``We didn't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Knicks, though younger and more athletic with
Marcus Camby instead of Oakley, could not find a way to win. For at
least the sixth time this year, the Knicks came unglued at the
finish. In the last 10 minutes 21 seconds of the game _ including
the 5 minutes of overtime _ the Knicks lost a seven-point lead by
shooting 3 for 14 from the field, hitting 3 of 9 free throws and
turning the ball over three times.
</P>
<P>
   Just as mind-blowing, the Raptors (11-12) embarrassed the Knicks
(15-11) with a gaudy 65-44 gap in rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to get to where we want to be,'' said Patrick
Ewing, who was slow-footed Sunday but scored 21 and had the height
to grab 15 rebounds, ``we can't continue to make the unnecessary
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever fleeting chance the Knicks had was turned to dust when
Oakley's hustle got the best of them. After he grabbed two key
rebounds in overtime, he drifted open and coolly released his
familiar 18-foot jumper. Ewing, his defender, was nowhere near him
as Oakley gave the Raptors an 83-78 lead with 51.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   After Latrell Sprewell failed to box out the rookie who walks on
air, Vince Carter (23 points), for a rebound of Dee Brown's miss
with 12.9 seconds left, the ball found Oakley again. He was fouled
by Chris Childs, walked to the free-throw line and calmly made both
shots with 7.6 seconds left to provide the Raptors with an
unreachable 85-80 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oak, he played like Oak,'' said Ewing, who was often guarded
by Oakley. ``I'm not sure how many shots he took, but he hit the
ones he had to at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere beneath Oakley's gruff exterior was a smile after this
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have nothing against the guys on the court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley felt jilted by the Knicks' president, Ernie Grunfeld,
when he was traded in June for Camby. He felt betrayed by the
franchise that decided to reward him for a decade of service by
sending him to the outpost of Toronto, and he was embarrassed when
the organization decided to stage a tribute to him during the
halftime of his return to Madison Square Garden last month.
</P>
<P>
   Given the chance, Oakley refused to jab back at the Knicks. The
game had been enough of a reply. The Knicks missed him and that was
enough. They have not been the same since he left. In each failure
down the stretch, the Knicks have been hounded by the same
culprits: rebounds, free throws and turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to keep losing in the same way,'' coach Jeff
Van Gundy said. ``Just frustrating. We haven't made the significant
shots or rebounds to finish a game. That's the difference.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The difference was in the frontcourt. Carter, Oakley and another
former Knick, John Thomas, combined for 32 rebounds. And Tracy
McGrady came off the bench for nine rebounds. Meanwhile, a limping
Larry Johnson had one rebound, Kurt Thomas had five, and Ewing had
a team-high 15 while Camby, who fouled out with 3:50 left in
overtime, grabbed just four off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' weak rebounding could not be smoothed over with an
offensive effort. Sprewell, frustrated by chasing Carter all day,
was 3 for 11. Allan Houston, dogged by defensive blunders and four
turnovers, hit 7 of 15 shots, but none in the fourth quarter or
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got outworked,'' Childs said. ``We got outhustled, too.
They had 31 offensive boards. That's probably a record. The
question coming into the season after the moves the team made was
were we going to rebound. We have yet to prove we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have yet to prove they can make game-deciding,
Oak-like plays without Oakley on their side. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
