<HEADLINE>
BIG MOMENT FOR UCLA WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech was a big fish in the Bayou 20 years ago but a
sardine in the sea that was women's college basketball. Then it
made its first trip to the Pacific Ocean's edge and upset the food
chain.
</P>
<P>
   In January of 1979, the Lady Techsters put away Pepperdine, UCLA
and USC to establish itself as a whole lot more than a regional
power.
</P>
<P>
   Their 85-81 upset of UCLA was a whale of a win, not just because
Billie Moore's bunch was the defending AIAW champion but also
because the Bruins were riding a 36-game winning streak at Pauley
Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   The game, which swung on two free throws by Louisiana Tech's
Mary Mell Kendrick with 16 seconds left, effectively marked the end
of one era and the beginning of another.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, which hadn't finished lower than second in the nation in
the four seasons prior to 1979, hasn't finished higher than ninth
in the 18 years the women have been under the auspices of the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Techsters would go on to play (and lose to) Old
Dominion in the 1979 national championship game. They since have
won three NCAA titles and graced 10 Final Fours. Last year a
perfect Tennessee team was all that stood between the Lady
Techsters and a fourth national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight Louisiana Tech and UCLA will meet in the NCAA West
Regional title game at the Sports Arena. Once again, there's an
impressive winning streak on the line and one of the teams is
looking to make a name for itself at the other's expense.
</P>
<P>
   This time the winning streak belongs to the Lady Techsters, who
are unbeaten in 21 games, and the Bruins are the status seekers.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA advanced to the NCAA's Elite Eight for the first time in
school history Saturday with a 77-68 win over Colorado State. A
victory over the Lady Techsters would give the Bruins national
validation and maybe even some credibility in their own backyard.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy for the women, cavorting as the other
basketball team on a campus caught up in the aura of those 11 NCAA
men's championship banners. The men threw the women a beauty of an
outlet pass last week, bowing out in the first round of the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   So the ball's in the women's hands. If they can just finish with
a flourish, with a slam dunk on one of the premier teams, then
maybe people will stop asking center Janae Hubbard questions like,
``Do you practice in the men's gym?'' Or her personal favorite:
``Do you even get to step on Pauley Pavilion's court?''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4 Hubbard, a genteel giant, chuckled. She and the
rest of the Bruins' Fab Five junior class never doubted they'd one
day enjoy the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, Maylana Martin, Cathy Funicello, Melanie Pearson and
Marie Philman came to Westwood in the fall of 1996 from parts near
and nearer _ Fresno and Perris and North Hills and Huntington Beach
and Irvine. They came with a collective goal: to return UCLA to the
glory days it enjoyed when Ann Meyers and Denise Curry were running
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted to do was build a program,'' Pearson said.
``That's what makes getting to the Elite Eight so special. We built
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday morning, as Hubbard savored her biggest (but
hopefully not best) victory as a Bruin, she hardly knew what to
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to express how good it feels,'' Hubbard said. ``With
the men going out in the first round, I think a lot of people at
school are starting to come around to our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the men's players came around for one of the women's
postseason games. Rico Hines and Ryan Bailey were turned away at
the door, though. They thought they could get in free and didn't
have enough money between them for a soda, much less two tickets.
</P>
<P>
   As the door shut in their faces, Hines and Bailey knew exactly
how it once felt to be a member of the women's basketball team. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
