<SLUG> BC-BKC-HUSKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALENTED RESERVE MAKES CONNECTICUT EVEN MORE OF A FORCE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Connecticut, a 32-2 team, trucks to the Final Four
with this deployment:
</P>
<P>
   Center Jake Voskuhl. Tough. A mean game. Does not back down on
the offensive or defensive boards and gives the Huskies meaty
post-up defense. Forwards Richard Hamilton and Kevin Freeman.
Hamilton is the go-to guy. Silky smooth in the clutch. Freeman is a
warrior rebounder. Athletic and dangerous on put-back baskets.
Guards Ricky Moore and Khalid El-Amin. Moore is an unusual mixture
of dribbler, passer, shooter, defender and leader. El-Amin runs the
point. He is the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Connecticut, winner of the West Regional of the
National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament with a 67-62
victory over Gonzaga here on Saturday, will pack to St. Petersburg,
Fla., for its semifinal match with Ohio State. It is a lethal and
symmetric starting five. A group that plays a singular and
collective brand of defense that can be overwhelming. Three juniors
on the front line, one senior guard (Moore) and one sophomore
(El-Amin). Stars all around.
</P>
<P>
   And then, once the opponent gets a handle on the starters, here
comes, off the bench, Edmund Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders is the X factor for Connecticut. He takes an excellent
team and makes it superior. He is the sugar topping. Every team
wants a player like Saunders, who can push it over the top.
</P>
<P>
   He is a sophomore forward, a lanky 6 feet 8 inches and 220
pounds. He is a new ingredient for Connecticut. He did not play
last season because he was academically ineligible. This season he
was ready off and on the court. Against Gonzaga, he could not wait.
He played 23 minutes, plenty for a backup; in fact, it was four
more minutes than the starter Voskhul, who was in foul trouble,
played. Saunders scored 8 points and grabbed 7 rebounds (4
offensive). But it was the manner in which he did it: full of
emotion, inspiring his team, deflating Gonzaga. And his interior
defense was superb, sliding left and right against the Gonzaga big
men, denying post points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edmund is one of the most talented players on our team,'' said
Hamilton, the most talented of the Huskies. ``He can put the ball
on the floor and score on you or he can hit the jump shot. He is a
leader even though he's young. Edmund is the reason we have a team
at Connecticut that finally made it to the Final Four. If we had
him last year, we probably would have made it. We had him this year
and we made it. It's that one extra, special force. How good can he
be? As good as he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders has been hearing that for some time.
</P>
<P>
   He is from Waterbury, Conn., about an hour's drive from the
Connecticut campus in Storrs. Several coaches began recruiting him
when he was in eighth grade. Even then, they could sense his
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Before his big game against Gonzaga, he was in Connecticut's
bruising tournament tussle with Iowa, mixing it up easily with the
Hawkeyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried not to get caught up in the physical stuff,'' Saunders
said. ``It was definitely a game where they were bringing it and we
were, too. But we've got the kind of team when it's all said and
done, that can just play basketball. After the pushing and the
talking, can you play? We can.''
</P>
<P>
   He can.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the Big East schools wanted Edmund and North Carolina
wanted him early in the recruiting,'' said Dave Leitao,
Connecticut's associate head coach. ``We had some guys like Scott
Burrell who stayed home in the Connecticut area to play with us and
that set the tone. They showed you didn't have to go far to have
success, and that worked for us in getting Edmund. He has lots of
family and they live close enough so they can come to his games and
support him. He's a family guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edmund is very athletic, has a feel for the game and gives us
a high intensity on the defensive end. He is emotional and we try
to channel that in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about a young man who has special gifts, and if
he works hard there is no limit to what he can become.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut sees Saunders growing instantly, in his first
eligible season, right there in front of them. The Huskies see a
player who late against Gonzaga was tense and missed two free
throws but made up for that with hustle, determination and talent.
They see a player who all season has contributed in many ways,
always giving them something extra.
</P>
<P>
   The starting five for Connecticut snaps opponents to attention.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth man, Saunders, the X factor, makes Connecticut a Final
Four team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
