<SLUG> BC-BBA-VAUGHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO VAUGHN BRINGS BAT AND LEADERSHIP TO THE ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Before the Boston Red Sox, before the Anaheim
Angels, there was Haimish Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher and Mo Vaughn were classmates at the New Canaan (Conn.)
Country School, but athletic ability was not something they shared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had to play athletics, but he just wasn't an athlete,''
Vaughn recalled Sunday. ``We were blowing somebody out in a
basketball game, and I'm trying to get this kid to make a basket. I
wanted him to score one hoop before this season was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running down the floor on a fast break and I pitch him the
ball. Just me and him. He shoots and it banks off the iron. They're
running down. I give it to him again. I said, `You got to make
this.' He put a shot up and it went in and he felt good about it,
so I felt good about it. I just wanted him to make that shot. I
wanted him to experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a rare gesture the young Vaughn made that day, but it
foreshadowed the kind of leadership an older Vaughn would
demonstrate on a baseball field and in the clubhouse and dugout. He
has become known as much for his leadership as for his run
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to make people feel positive about
themselves,'' said Vaughn, dressing in the Angels clubhouse after
eight seasons in the Red Sox clubhouse. ``If I know that a guy who
has talent is not being aggressive enough, it upsets me because I
want everybody to feel they can do whatever they want if they
concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   When the burly first baseman speaks, his teammates listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only so many guys that when they yell at you in the
dugout and the clubhouse, you listen to,'' Mike Stanley said
earlier in spring training in the clubhouse that no longer houses
Vaughn. ``He's one of them. Other guys you kind of just say, `Sit
down and be quiet.'''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn adopted a paternal position with his Boston teammates.
``Those guys were my friends,'' he said. ``I lived and died with
the success of those individuals. I felt I needed to protect them
as players. I knew I could handle the adversity, the intensity of
it and take the weight of it. But the only thing I felt was
necessary was to work as hard as you possibly can to get ready so
that when you go into a situation, you have no fear of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox lost Vaughn as a free agent last November because
they undervalued him both as a player and as a leader. After they
spent a year insulting him, he accepted a six-year, $80 million
deal from the Angels and instantly enhanced both their playoff
chances and the spirit among their players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still getting to know guys, but you can tell looking in
his eyes, he has that fire,'' said Darin Erstad, who will move to
the outfield from first base to make room for Vaughn. ``He wants to
win; it's very obvious. I've never played with someone like that in
baseball who has that kind of presence about him, who has carried a
team, who has the reputation he has. I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, Erstad added, is the one who takes care of things if
they go wrong or if teammates bicker. ``That's very valuable,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Collins, the Angels' manager, wanted to make it clear that
the Angels signed Vaughn for his bat, the one that last year hit a
career-high .337, slugged 40 home runs and drove in 115 runs.
``That's why he's here; that's how he's earned his money,'' Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, the manager then said: ``What he brings to this team
besides a great player on the field is a guy who approaches the
game like every manager and coach thinks the game needs to be
approached _ with dedication, with preparation, with a desire to
win. He's not afraid to say something to somebody if their effort
is not as much as his. That's what I think every clubhouse needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for a manager or a coach to walk in there and say
you need to pick it up. It's a little different when one of your
fellow teammates says it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's presence should make the Angels a serious threat to the
Texas Rangers in the American League West Division. Only three
games separated the teams last season. Vaughn's absence from the
Red Sox is expected to render them a noncontender even for the
wild-card spot they won last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't focus on the past,'' Vaughn said, choosing not to talk
about the circumstances that sent him west. ``I played in Boston, I
left no stone unturned, I played hard. I have no regrets. Coming
here was a change, a nice change. They wanted me over here. That's
the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people thought Vaughn would never leave Boston because of
the work he did there with children, including his creation of the
Mo Vaughn Youth Center in Dorchester. But, he said, they did not
understand what drives him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main focus always was the job site and how my employers
perceived me,'' he said. ``When that changed, it was time to make a
change. Now I'm in a situation where these people want me here.
It's a nice, easy transition.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
