<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY SHARP FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Pitcher Chuck Finley made his second start of the
spring Sunday afternoon, going three innings and 51 pitches in the
Angels' 7-6 win over the Oakland A's at Phoenix Municipal Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Finley looked sharp, allowing one run and three hits while
striking out three and walking none. His next start will be Friday,
when he tries to get up to about 65 pitches and five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have went out there again (for the fourth inning), but
I didn't want to push my luck,'' said Finley, who was slowed by a
muscle strain in his upper back/neck for most of camp. ``I'm so
advanced from where I would normally be in my second start. The
good thing today is that I got to work out of a stretch. And I came
out of it all right, which is good the way guys have been dropping
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley added that he is ``surprised at my command of all three
pitches (fastball, splitter, curveball). It seems like everything
is working.''
</P>
<P>
   He was named the opening-day starter by manager Terry Collins
weeks ago, but where his turn falls in the rotation probably will
push him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to pitch opening day, but if they think I'd be better
off to go to the end of the line, that's fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't count on it,'' Collins said when asked about Finley's
opening-day start. ``Right now I don't think two more (spring)
starts is enough for him. Chuck's one of those guys who makes 115,
120 pitches a game. We need to get him up to 110 before he goes out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's normal turn would fall on the off-day Monday before
Tuesday's opening day (April 6). But if Finley needs another start
to be ready, he would pitch in minor-league camp in Mesa that
Monday and then make his season debut five days later.
</P>
<P>
   As it lines up now, Tim Belcher's turn in the rotation falls on
opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Big-play day: Tim Unroe's three-run homer in the ninth inning
capped the Angels' rally from a 6-4 deficit. Unroe, a non-roster
invitee, has three homers this spring to tie him with Tim Salmon
for the team lead. Anaheim improved to 9-9 in Cactus League play.
</P>
<P>
   Hot corner update: Dave Hollins is still bothered by a sore left
hamstring, but because the starting spot at third base is on the
line he was in the lineup Sunday for the second game in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins went 1 for 3 with a double and a run scored, raising his
spring average to .263 (5 for 19). Hollins knows there is no time
to waste, not with his competition, Troy Glaus, enjoying a
productive spring _ .438 (14 for 32), two homers and a team-leading
16 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting down to about 10 games left,'' Hollins said.
``If I woke up (Sunday) and it was hurting and I wasn't battling
for a job, then I might have sat out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollins obviously isn't close to 100 percent. On his double, he
slowed up going into second even though he might have had a chance
at a triple. He limped noticeably when scoring from second on Todd
Greene's single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to pop it out,'' he said. ``This thing is
(normally) a 10-day to two-week thing. And it's been only a week
since the pull.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave Hollins is well aware of what's going on,'' Collins said.
``It's why he's out there. He knows he needs to get at-bats and get
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Upset over Edmonds: Jim Edmonds missed his third game in a row
because of a tight groin and is listed as day-to-day, and Collins
isn't exactly pleased with his Gold Glove center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Edmonds is hurt that has irritated Collins, but
how Edmonds got that way. During outfield drills a few days ago,
Edmonds was a little too playful and hurt himself diving for balls.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Left fielder Darin Erstad was scratched from Sunday's game
because of the stomach flu. Collins will give him the day off again
today. . . . The Angels cut three pitchers Sunday, sending Joe
Jacobsen, Ryan Hawblitzel and Darrin Winston to minor-league camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
