<HEADER>
A8873 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARP-DRIVING24-COX     03-21 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braking technology keeps getting better
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology is an ongoing process, with one innovation often
leading to another. Nowhere is that more apparent than in the
automotive industry, specifically indriver-assisting safety
innovations.
</P>
<P>
   First there were anti-lock braking systems, or ABS, followed by
traction control systems. Now the industry is offering what may be
the best of the lot, stability control systems. But without ABS and
traction control systems, stability control systems could not
exist. All of the systems, regardless of automaker, work in concert
in one fashion or another.
</P>
<P>
   ABS is a system that uses wheel sensors, which measure wheel
rotation. An on-board computer determines if the wheels are locking
up and adjusts the hydraulic pressure accordingly to maintain
traction, allowing the driver to maintain steering control of the
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Many times, skid marks that lead to a crumpled spot on a
guardrail get darker as they get closer to the point of impact. The
marks tell you the driver kept pushing harder and harder on the
brake pedal trying to get the car to either stop or steer. To
regain control of the vehicle, the driver should have reduced brake
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   A locked wheel has lost traction, and to regain it, you have to
allow the wheel to rotate. The only way to do that is to back off
the brake.
</P>
<P>
   That's a tough call for any driver to make when he or she is
about to hit something. Computers, on the other hand, are not
distracted by outside events and go about their business quite
nicely. The only thing that is required of an ABS system is that
the driver push hard on the brake pedal and not release any
pressure until it has accomplished the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Next, add traction control. As the name indicates, these systems
are about maintaining a positive relationship between the tire and
the road surface. Typically, they work by measuring the difference
in wheel speeds. If one wheel is rotating faster than the others,
the system assumes it is spinning. Although systems differ from one
automaker to another, the ultimate goal is to make the spinning
wheel rotate at the same speed as the other wheels.
</P>
<P>
   These systems are particularly useful on slippery surfaces like
wet pavement, snowy roads, ice-covered bridges or sandy beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Many drivers think that when they have lost traction, applying
more gas will fix the problem. The real solution is less pedal
pressure. Basically, that is what a traction control system does.
It requires absolutely no input from the driver. It decreases the
amount of power to the wheel that is spinning so it can slow to the
point where is has the same rate of rotation as those wheels the
system assumes have traction.
</P>
<P>
   That assumption is an important one. For any traction control
system to work, there has to be the potential for traction present.
The fanciest computer-driven system in the world can't make a tire
grip a surface upon which there is no possibility of traction.
</P>
<P>
   Now come stability systems. They are the latest toys on the
automotive block. Through information gathered by yaw sensors,
which measure the sideways or lateral motion of a vehicle, and
working in concert with the ABS and traction control systems,
stability control systems help keep a car going in the direction
the driver wants.
</P>
<P>
   Remember your driving instructor's directions to steer in the
direction of a spin? If you have a stability control system, the
odds are that is a situation you will never have to address.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp, a consultant to the auto industry, writes for The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
