u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEST-DRIVE23-COX     03-21 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-DRIVE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Versatile Integra exudes flair
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Acura Integra GS-R front-drive coupe
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $22,654 (base: $22,100)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, side-impact beams and pads,
power anti-lock disc brakes
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 1.8-liter four-cylinder engine with 16 valves (170
horsepower), five-speed manual overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: floor mats, $99
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 25 mpg premium unleaded city, 31 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   The Integra is the lowest-priced model imported by Acura, the
upscale Honda division, but it's possible to make an argument that
it comes with the most potential for enjoyable driving.
</P>
<P>
   Various design and engineering features figure into that
characteristic, but the standout element is the Integra's
1.8-liter, four-cylinder engine. Available in 140- and
170-horsepower versions, it has good performance and decent fuel
economy, and gets good reliability ratings from the
consumer-concerned watchdog organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Integra line also offers the versatility of coupe
and sedan versions, with all three trim levels carrying impressive
lists of standard features. The LS, GS and GS-R models come with a
power moonroof, air conditioning, a six-speaker stereo with CD
player, power windows and mirrors, and tilt wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Base prices start at $19,200 for the LS coupe and slide up to
$22,400 for the GS-R four-door. The test GS-R totaled $22,654,
which includes a $455 delivery charge and one option, a $99 set of
floor mats.
</P>
<P>
   Although not a large car, the Integra, due for a makeover for
the 2001 model, has plenty of room and extremely good visibility
for its driver and front passenger. Height and tilt adjustment give
the driver's seat optimum flexibility for all but extremely large
folks, and both it and the passenger seat are firmly comfortable
and supportive. The best thing about the rear seats in the coupe is
that they fold down to expand the cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected of a Honda/Acura car, the interior is
neatly arranged and, for the most part, nicely fitted and
furnished, except for some varying types of plastic. The dash is
set low to aid visibility, and the white-on-black instrumentation
remains very visible.
</P>
<P>
   Glance at the GS-R's instrumentation, and what will immediately
strike most buyers drawn to a car in this class _ luxury/sporty
subcompact _ is the tachometer with its red line at 8,000 rpm.
Acura isn't putting you on, either. The 170-hp four-cylinder in the
GS-R willingly revs, wails and pulls right on up to the red line,
but its sophisticated innards have enough trickle-down technology
from Formula One Grand Prix racing and the $80,000 Acura NSX sports
car to still provide low-end torque.
</P>
<P>
   Little ride comfort is sacrificed for the sake of the GS-R's
strong handling ability. No traction control system is offered, but
the balance and stability of the 2,700-pound Integra, along with
straight-stopping power anti-lock brakes, make that a moot point.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles on city streets, expressways and two-lane roads will
explain why both the coupe and sedan can appeal to young buyers who
like the panache and older drivers who want some sports-car-like
performance but also need a family-friendly four-door.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the Integra can get near the upper end of the price
range for a class with strong offerings from Chevrolet, Ford,
Chrysler and other foreign manufacturers. But as last year's
American sales total of about 34,000 indicates, the Integra will
move buyers, and the GS-R version does it best.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
