A8876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NY     03-21 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI FAULTS GIULIANI'S RESPONSES TO `MORAL OUTRAGE' AT DIALLO
SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the grand jury investigation of the Amadou
Diallo case wrapping up and the daily protests over Diallo's
slaying in a hail of police gunfire gathering momentum, Gov. George
Pataki described the case Sunday as horrific and suggested that the
Giuliani administration was not ``responding appropriately to
criticism'' over the matter.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came as Ed Koch, a former New York City mayor,
state Comptroller Carl McCall and the Bronx borough president,
Fernando Ferrer, all said that they planned to be arrested outside
Police Headquarters Monday to protest the Diallo shooting and the
administration's response to it.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, a West African immigrant, was killed on Feb. 4 in the
vestibule of his apartment in the Bronx by four officers from the
Police Department's Street Crimes Unit. Diallo was unarmed and had
no criminal record. The incident has led to continuing protests,
including almost daily acts of civil disobedience outside Police
Headquarters in lower Manhattan, including the arrest of ex-Mayor
David Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Mayor Rudolph Giuliani denounced those protests as
``publicity stunts'' and said that they were getting ``silly.''
</P>
<P>
   In his most pointed comments on the Diallo case to date, Pataki
said on the ABC news program ``This Week With Sam Donaldson and
Cokie Roberts'' that the shooting had created an understandable
sense of moral outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor has done an excellent job on issues like crime,'' he
said, ``and the police have done an excellent job, but the Diallo
incident was so horrendous and so horrific that it has created a
sense of moral outrage, an understandable sense of moral outrage
where all of us have to take a look.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clear reference to the mayor's caustic response to the
protests, the governor added, ``I think the city is doing very
well, but part of governing is being tolerant and listening to
criticism and responding appropriately to criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the governor's comments, Giuliani, who was in
Phoenix for a speaking engagement, said: ``I haven't seen exactly
what the governor said. I think the New York City Police Department
conducts itself appropriately and has an excellent record of
restraint which, unfortunately, is not getting the attention that
it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth between the mayor and the governor is another
indication that their political relationship, never very warm, has
chilled even further in recent months as they have done battle over
issues ranging from school construction to which highway should be
named after Joe DiMaggio. It also comes as the two, both
Republicans, are seeking a higher profile nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's criticism capped a week in which the Police
Department and the Giuliani administration seemed increasingly
under fire. Dinkins and Rep. Charles Rangel were arrested to
protest the shooting; state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer
announced a civil-rights inquiry into the Police Department's
stop-and-frisk practices; federal prosecutors announced their own
civil rights investigation into the street crimes unit, where the
four officers who shot Diallo were assigned, and Public Advocate
Mark Green called on Police Commissioner Howard Safir to resign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC24-COX     03-21 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who'll fix 'Jetsonmobiles' of the future?
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I went, I saw, I marveled and I walked away from this
year's International Auto Show in Atlanta feeling a bit awed,
somewhat confused and deeply concerned. Lots of dazzling paint,
