realize what they are doing to their kids' air? I wonder if gas
masks come in team colors?
</P>
<P>
   the new ``Valdez'' There are, however, stylish alternatives that
show that cool doesn't have to be big.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler's PT Cruiser is a retro-looking small alternative to a
big SUV. It is based on the Neon car and has the potential to be
the next ``woody.''
</P>
<P>
   And high performance doesn't have to be high pollution.
DaimlerChrysler also showed the natural gas-powered Charger R/T
concept car. That's an attempt to deal with the environmental
problem and be the leader of the pack, not part of it. A little red
car caught my eye. The representative asked me if I wanted to sign
up for a test drive. We talked for a moment, and I told him I was
an automotive instructor. He asked me if I knew how to reprogram
the chips, the computer controls that regulate engine performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you mean other than the manufacturer's specs?'' I asked. He
nodded enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's illegal,'' I said and moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Reprogramming outside of specifications to enhance performance
can compromise emissions, fuel mileage and safety. That's why
making the changes is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   I ambled over to the luxury section of the show. All the
comforts of home from the driver's seat and an engine with power to
spare _ eight cylinders, 32 valves with variable valve timing.
Seats that sense and conform to your body weight and movement. Side
impact air bags. Night vision heads-up display using infrared
technology.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I shouldn't be surprised. I knew these options were on
the horizon. I guess it was the reality of finally seeing them in
real life that jolted me.
</P>
<P>
   What is going to happen when this stuff breaks?
</P>
<P>
   I was thinking about the current, sparse enrollment in our
automotive program at school. It's beyond the limits of most
mechanics to repair the vehicles we are driving today, let alone
``Jetsonmobiles.'' Who in the world is going to fix these things?
</P>
<P>
   When I first started teaching, I would tell my students, ``Just
imagine it, and someday cars will have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's here now, and I don't know if my imagination can take
much more. What's worse, I don't know where tomorrow's
rocket-scientist mechanics are going to come from.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor. Write her in care of Wheels,
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
