u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIALLO-CARDINAL-NYT &LR;      03-21 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-CARDINAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL URGES A DIALOGUE TO REBUILD TRUST IN POLICE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a Sunday Mass dedicated to officers of the New
York City Police Department, Cardinal John O'Connor entered the
emotional and political storm around the police shooting of Amadou
Diallo by expressing his gratitude for the officers' service and
urging an end to the hostile rhetoric between city officials and
leaders of the daily protests against the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming majority of people, anyone with any sense, in
my judgment, recognizes that the majority of police officers in New
York are people of integrity and decency,'' the cardinal said,
``that they are people struggling like all of us. You make
mistakes. Some have made grave mistakes, mistakes that have been
damaging, mistakes that have been damaging to people and damaging
to families.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking out over the packed sanctuary at St. Patrick's Cathedral
_ at least half of the crowd in pressed navy-blue uniforms _ he
said: ``You also make tremendous sacrifices. Many of you put your
lives on the line every day. It is a sacrifice for you and for your
families. And we are grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the cardinal said city officials must
not dismiss widespread perceptions that law enforcement officers
mistreat black and Hispanic suspects, nor blame the tensions on
media coverage. He said he had met with many community leaders and
advised them that the only way to rebuild trust between the police
and the community is through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the cardinal said he will lead an ecumenical prayer
service on April 8. Emphasizing that it would be for prayer, not
protest, he invited the police to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there has been discrimination against blacks and Latinos
and Asians,'' the cardinal said, ``then we do no good by denying
those injustices. As long as those perceptions are there, then they
must be dealt with. And it is rare that perceptions have no basis
in reality.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor also directed remarks at those who have staged daily
protests outside police headquarters. ``We cannot have
reconciliation,'' he said, ``if the talks begin with assumptions
that the police department is rotten to the core.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Mass was dedicated to the Holy Name Society, an
association of Roman Catholic officers within the police
department. The cardinal said he felt nervous about the sermon
because of the intense anxiety generated in the city by the slaying
of Diallo, an unarmed West African immigrant. To make matters
worse, the cardinal said, when he tried to print the sermon that he
had typed on his computer, he lost the computer file and could not
retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal said the glitch meant God must have wanted him to
speak from his heart as much as from his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have wanted me to say what I believe the overwhelming
majority of people in New York, whatever their race or religion,
want to say,'' the cardinal declared, ``and that is we deeply
believe in you. We trust you. We are grateful for you. We love
you.''
</P>
<P>
   He compared the police brutality crisis to the scandal that
plagued the archdiocese at the end of the 1980s, when several
priests were accused of sexually molesting youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church suffered severely,'' he said. ``Every priest felt a
cloud descend upon him. Here were men who had sacrificed their
families and other loved ones to serve the church, and all they got
from society was suspicion, some of it bordering on contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal said that while he grieves for Diallo and his
relatives, he also grieves for the four officers accused of firing
41 shots that killed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus weeps over all the suffering in the world,'' he said.
``Jesus weeps for Amadou Diallo. Jesus weeps for Mrs. Diallo. Jesus
weeps for all those who have been victims of tragedy. And Jesus
weeps for those who feel the cloud has fallen over them because of
a tragedy. Jesus weeps for those who are suspects in causing a
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the service, the officers gathered in front of the
cathedral, turning Fifth Avenue into a river of blue, and marched
together to a hotel for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Louis Richardson, a 38-year veteran who serves in the
Sixth Precinct, watched for a while before joining his colleagues.
He said most officers felt tainted by the Diallo shooting. And he
said he has heard concerns about the police from many relatives and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not know what happened in the vestibule of
Diallo's Bronx apartment building the night he was shot. But he
said only officers understand the difficulty of making
lightning-fast decisions about whether a suspect is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you act too fast, you might hurt someone who is innocent,''
he said, ``and if you don't act fast enough, then the suspect could
kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sgt. Rudy Hamilton, who is posted at police headquarters and
walks past Diallo protesters every day, O'Connor's sermon was a
source of inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that even though there's a cloud over us right now, we
still have to get up and go out there and show our faces,'' he
said. ``That crowd has a complaint, and I respect their right to
protest. But I will never duck when I walk by.''
</P>
<P>
   With his wife beaming beside him, Hamilton, who has been on the
force 15 years, said, ``I am proud to put on this uniform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
