<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8880 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MICHIGANST-KENTUC     03-21 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHIGANST-KENTUCKY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Michigan State storms back, ends Kentucky's hopes of repeat
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. LOUIS _ ``We're playing the men in the jerseys, not the
jerseys.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State players repeated that phrase so often over the
past two days you could almost hear their pep band providing
background music for the mantra.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first 10 minutes after the opening tip against
defending national champion Kentucky, it appeared the Spartans _
like frightened singers on stage for the first time _ had forgotten
the words to their own song.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for them, a demonstrative tongue-lashing by senior
forward Antonio Smith got the Spartans in rhythm before it was too
late.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State closed an early 13-point deficit to a single
point by halftime, then controlled the second half with defense and
rebounding to stop Kentucky 73-66 Sunday before a record crowd of
42,519 in the Midwest Regional final at the Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Top-seeded Michigan State (33-4), which is playing its 100th
season of basketball, advanced to the Final Four for just the third
time in school history and the first time in 20 years. For
third-seeded Kentucky (28-8), a run of three consecutive
appearances in the national championship game came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something you dream about as a kid _ getting to the
Final Four _ but most people only get to dream about it,'' Michigan
State guard Mateen Cleaves said. ``I'm floored by it, and it
probably hasn't hit me yet, but I'm excited. I wish we could fly to
Florida tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves will have to wait a few days before heading to St.
Petersburg, site of this year's Final Four, where Michigan State
will face No. 1-ranked Duke in the NCAA Tournament semifinals on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans found it hard to quell their enthusiasm for going
farther in the Tournament than any team at the school since Magic
Johnson, who was among the Spartans faithful in the
Kentucky-dominated crowd, led Michigan State to the national title
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of the opening period, it looked as if
Cleaves and the Spartans would only have to worry about a flight
home. Kentucky came out of the gate on the run and led 17-4 after
seven minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a 6-8, 250-pound bruiser who was the first recruit
Michigan State coach Tom Izzo signed when he took the job four
years ago, went face-to-face with every Spartan and challenged his
teammates to get back to the type of play that had gotten them to
the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew we weren't about to go down without a fight,''
Smith said. ``We were timid, and we weren't getting after it
defensively or on the boards, and that's not like us. I don't know
if we were scared or not, but we weren't playing like we normally
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause for the slow start, Smith's pep talk got the
job done.
</P>
<P>
   It also did not hurt matters that Morris Peterson, who led all
scorers with 19 points, and A.J. Granger came off the bench to
provide some instant offense for the struggling Spartans, who were
just 3-of-15 from the floor to start the game.
</P>
<P>
   Granger hit 3-pointers on consecutive possessions to ignite a
blitz during which Michigan State scored on 12 of 16 possessions
and hit 10 of 13 field-goal attempts to pull within 36-35 at the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Normally poised Kentucky, which had won nine straight Tournament
games, went from being oh-so-close to throwing a knockout punch to
being in a nip-and-tuck battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once, we were the team that got excited about the big
start,'' Wildcats forward Scott Padgett said. ``They kept their
poise and didn't try to get it all back right away. We still felt
like we were going to win the game, but they made the big plays
down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   After Cleaves hit a long 3-pointer at the first-half buzzer _
Kentucky coach Tubby Smith called it a ``momentum changer'' _
neither team led by more than four points until Michigan State
opened up some room with a late run.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans completely turned the halftime statistics around
with a spirited effort following the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   At the half, the Wildcats held a 19-11 rebounding margin and a
12-2 advantage in second-chance points, thanks to 10 offensive
rebounds. By the end of the game, Michigan State had won the
rebounding battle 33-29 and evened the second-chance points at 15.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Tayshaun Prince and senior Heshimu Evans led the
Wildcats with 12 points each, but Evans got in foul trouble and did
not score in the final 30 minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense in the second half was outstanding,'' said
Smith, who suffered his first Tournament loss as the Wildcats'
coach. ``Actually, it started midway through the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with my team, especially the seniors. It was
a great run. We can hold our heads up as we got beat by a very good
team today.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading 54-53 with 8:03 to play, Kentucky suffered through a
drought that lasted nearly four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Padgett, who was just 1-of-6 from the floor, including 0-for-4
from the 3-point line until hitting a pair of 3-pointers in the
final 30 seconds, misfired on a trey to start the five-possession
dry spell.
</P>
<P>
   Evans traveled, Wayne Turner turned the ball over, and Padgett
missed the front end of a one-and-one before Turner missed a layup
and Desmond Allison grabbed the rebound and missed an easy follow
attempt to keep the Wildcats stuck on 54.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Spartans got a couple of layups from Andre Hutson
and a 3-pointer from Cleaves to open a 60-54 lead with less than
five minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Things got interesting in the final minute with Padgett's 3s,
but Peterson, who also had a game-high 10 rebounds, went 6-for-6
from the foul line in the final 29 seconds to seal the win for the
Spartans.
</P>
</TEXT>
