<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK MAYOR TALKS PRESIDENTIAL POLITICS IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani spent the weekend
meeting with Arizona Republicans to discuss national politics, and
taking a rare break to play golf and relax before giving a speech
Sunday evening to an American Medical Association conference.
</P>
<P>
   The speech, the mayor's stated reason for being here, was
delivered at the association's National Leadership Development
Conference, which featured other prominent Republican speakers,
including former President George Bush and U.S. Sen. Jon Kyl of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani, who has expressed strong interest in running for
the U.S. Senate next year, has also been building a close
relationship with Arizona's other senator, John McCain, who has
expressed similarly strong interest in running for president, and a
visit to Arizona allows the mayor to strengthen his ties to the
McCain camp.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was in Washington this weekend, but Giuliani said he met
with several members of McCain's staff and other Republicans to
discuss presidential politics. The mayor said that his visit did
not involve any fund raising and that discussions did not focus on
his own political future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have discussions about the presidential race,'' the
mayor said after his speech. ``I had a meeting last night with a
number of Republicans in Arizona, but really it was more concerned
with national politics and various presidential bids, including
Senator McCain's.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Giuliani discussed the usual subjects that he
mentions in out-of-town talks, including New York's steep drop in
reports of crime and its booming economy and tourism. He opened
with his standard imitation of a mob gangster.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a nod to the broiling dispute back home, Giuliani was
careful to repeat his praise of New York City's police force,
saying that officers' use of firearms had been reduced more than
crime itself. It is a point the mayor has made consistently since
the shooting of Amadou Diallo by four police officers.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Giuliani answered several questions about the
continuing protests outside New York City Police Headquarters. Told
that Floyd Flake of Queens, a former representative who has been a
supporter of the mayor, planned to join the protests, Giuliani said
that the demonstrations had become redundant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any purpose in people getting
themselves arrested,'' he said. ``I think everyone understands the
point that's being made. Continuing to do this is merely piling
on.'' And, in what has become practically a daily exercise,
Giuliani praised the police force and its street crimes unit, which
he said has been under ``relentless attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who spent Friday afternoon in Ithaca, N.Y., has been
spending an increasing amount of time away from New York City. He
acknowledged that he worked in some time for golf in the desert
sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990321.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8883 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      03-21 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets retain focus in spite of distractions
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The Rockets officially moved past the feeling-out stages, past the
learning processes and lockout-season realities.
</P>
<P>
   But the change was not a matter of counting games in the 50-game
season and finding themselves at the midpoint of the season. It was
more intentional, less incidental than a date on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, finding themselves halfway through the regular
season and 25 games from the postseason, began a playoff push. And
they moved to that with a shove from coach Rudy Tomjanovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the guys about that (Saturday),'' Tomjanovich
said. ``I told them, `We have the same amount of losses as San
Antonio and the Lakers (nine). Well, why can't we be the third
seed?' That should be our focus right now, going after that deal.
If we don't get it, we don't get it. We'll play the hand that's
dealt. But I think that's a fair and reasonable goal to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the Jazz and Trail Blazers' fast starts with unchanged
teams have put them out of regular-season reach, the retooled
Rockets find themselves at midseason chasing nearly the same
regular-season accomplishments they might have considered within
reach when the season started full of hope and promise.
</P>
<P>
   At midseason, that might remain the Rockets' status, full of
possibilities made evident by a recent run. But that status also
reflects a sudden turnaround, covering far more ground than would
seem when comparing preseason plans to midseason accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks earlier the Rockets were whipped in Portland and
in line for a first-round playoff meeting with the Lakers and
likely no home-court advantage in the postseason. Even just a week
ago, they had lost to a Suns team not certain to make the playoffs
and were shaken by Scottie Pippen's complaints he had no clear role
in the offense.
</P>
<P>
   But at midseason, they are tied with the Spurs for fourth in the
Western Conference, one game behind the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the Rockets are on their best sustained run,
winning six of seven and eight of their past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the fourth-best record in the West and we haven't
played that long together,'' forward Charles Barkley said. ``We're
going to be good before the end of the season. We're playing well
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing better overall, in every area. The chemistry is
better. We won six of seven. I told you when I got hurt it would
take about two weeks to get everybody back on the same page. That's
been about right.''
</P>
<P>
   But a week ago they did not seem to be reading from the same
playbook. Pippen's comments stung, especially because the Rockets
knew they were a work in progress, trying to address the problems
that had frustrated him. But they also do not seem to have caused
any damage, and if anything might have increased a sense of urgency
to make the mix of talents work.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen would not say what effect his comments have had on the
team or his play. But there has been a marked difference in his
posture when pressed about the offense.
</P>
<P>
   He was more of a focal point in Tuesday's win over Portland. But
the offense was centered on Hakeem Olajuwon down the stretch in the
win over Denver and Barkley in Saturday's victory over Phoenix.
Pippen was often stationed at the 3-point line or on the opposite
baseline, often opening opportunities for other outside shooters by
bringing a defender out of range to double team or rotate.
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen described himself as more comfortable with and clear
about his role and the offense as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel I was fitting in in the offense,'' Pippen said.
``Right now, I'm more of an integral part of the offense. We're
starting to play better as a whole, as a team. When Charles and
Dream down in the low post don't have it going, they're able to
step out and set picks and help everybody else get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for me. When we have guys with the types of
offensive skills these guys have got, it makes us better as a team.
We're still trying to get familiar with each other. But we're
picking our spots. We're sort of sharing a lot more than when I
first got here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more games we play, the better we'll be. We'll jell more
as a team. And we're sharing the spotlight. Some nights Dream has
it going, or Charles or myself or one of our younger players.''
</P>
<P>
   Without addressing any role his public comments might have had
in shaping his role, Pippen even said he was happier with the way
he is being used, particularly as a playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much better,'' Pippen said. ``I feel like I'm being
utilized, and I'm able to be a big part of the team's offense. I
think it's made a difference to our team. It was probably my fault
more so than anything. But this has allowed me to have more
leadership and control of the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the standpoint of being able to control the tempo, make
the decisions and get the ball to the right person's hands, I can
hopefully get it to where we can execute. When you have the ball in
your hands you control the tempo of the game. It allows you to stay
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't put you in position to be down 15 points and having
to battle your way back into games. You control the tempo. That's
the most important thing. It's just a matter of you coming down and
executing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is more than Pippen's feeling about the offense that has
brightened the Rockets' perspective. In the past two weeks, Barkley
has improved rapidly from the effects of his knee surgery five
weeks ago. Antoine Carr, who was one of the additions that inspired
so much preseason confidence but has played in just one game, is
close to returning from the injured list. The addition of Sam Mack
has given the Rockets another 3-point shooting threat, taking
pressure off the Rockets' rookie backcourt of Michael Dickerson and
Cuttino Mobley and some of the playing-time burden from Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Rockets' streak of six wins in seven games, Olajuwon
has become increasingly effective inside, averaging 22.1 points per
game during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can always play much better,'' Olajuwon said. ``Where we
are now, we have much room for improvement. We should be peaking,
trying to come together going toward the playoffs. Everybody should
be at their peak collectively and individually for the playoffs. We
want to have at least some home-court advantage in the first round
or the first two rounds. Now is the time to position ourselves for
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets can think that way because after the past two weeks,
they can think again of doing damage in the postseason. They remain
among the league's most efficient offensive teams, have recently
begun to pick up their defense, and have begun to cut back on
turnovers, clearly their biggest weakness in the first half. And
the mood is nearly as hopeful as it was a half-season ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start winning, everybody is happy,'' guard Brent
Price said. ``That's the way it goes. When you're winning, you
start feeling good. When you're losing, you start to question. The
important thing is as a team, we have to stay together and battle
all the way through the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches would tell you we're doing great. I know the fans
had huge expectations. It just takes time. If you could just throw
a bunch of guys together and win, it wouldn't mean anything. We've
battled and had our share of controversy. I think it's starting to
come together. We're sitting in a good spot right now. The rest of
this month the schedule is in our favor. We feel good where we're
at right not.''
</P>
<P>
   Good enough to think of the playoffs and enjoy the thought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
