<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8884 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--NBAMIDTERM-HNS &LR;      03-21 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--NBA </SLUG>
 MIDTERM-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lockout causes NBA teams different kinds of woes
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Perhaps the most amazing thing about this NBA season is that it has
reached the midway point.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it just a few weeks ago we were embroiled in a lockout?
Wasn't it just a few weeks ago ``training camp,'' that one-week
period into which teams tried to cram a month's worth of work,
began?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, it was just a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   So, here we are, halfway through. Already.
</P>
<P>
   And what a ride it's been.
</P>
<P>
   When the season began, many questioned whether the abbreviated
post-lockout schedule of 50 games would produce a worthy NBA
champion. That such a brief season would put a dreaded asterisk
next to this year's champion.
</P>
<P>
   Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   With the crush of games and a hectic travel schedule, teams have
not only had to fight each other, but fight themselves as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's almost more legit,'' said Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich of the validity of this year's champion. ``I think it's
a bigger test. I think the mental and physical part you have to go
through is so much tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (normal) NBA season is a grind, but this is a 440(-yard
dash). A couple of 440s. I've already mentioned this _ the
irritability, fatigue and frustration level that people go through
is going to be a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   The team best able to avoid the above-mentioned distractions
will be standing at the end. Several teams have cracked under the
pressure, with the New Jersey Nets and the Minnesota Timberwolves
being the most obvious examples.
</P>
<P>
   But the one team that seems impervious to all outside forces,
the Utah Jazz, just keeps pick-and-rolling along.
</P>
<P>
   There have been enough injuries to keep the cast of ER working
for years to come, and enough bricks to build an arena for every
city in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is down all around the league, almost as low as the
shooting percentages.
</P>
<P>
   And heads have rolled. The Lakers' Del Harris, New Jersey's John
Calipari and Charlotte's Dave Cowens are out of work, and many
suspect New York's Jeff Van Gundy soon will join them.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long, crazy season. And it's only half over.
</P>
<P>
   Surprises
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves, if only because they have Kevin Garnett
playing with Joe Smith and over-the-hill Terrell Brandon instead of
Tom Gugliotta and Stephon Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Money, what else? Owner Glen Taylor wanted to
make Marbury and Garnett the John Stockton and Karl Malone of the
next millennium, so to keep the foundation in place, Taylor gave
Garnett the now-infamous six-year, $126 million extension.
</P>
<P>
   But Gugliotta left because he couldn't stand playing with
Marbury, and it turns out the high-strung point guard couldn't
stand playing in Garnett's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Or the shadow cast by his wallet, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is KG (Garnett),'' said Minnesota coach Flip
Saunders. ``(Marbury) said, `Right now, whether it's right or
wrong, I have a tough time playing with KG when he's making the
amount of money he's making and I'll be making only $71 million.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried, No. 1, to explain the idea of `only making $71
million' to him. And two, we shouldn't be penalized because of the
system. But if a guy doesn't have his heart in the right place,
then we have to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, if Gugliotta knew the way this situation was going
to play out, Tommy would still be here. His agent (Richard Howell)
told us, flat out, that Tommy had a problem playing with Stephon.
But we weren't willing to trade Steph to keep Googs.''
</P>
<P>
   With Allen Iverson leading the way, the Philadelphia 76ers have
come on like gangstabustas, playing .600 ball and doing it their
way. Iverson made the move to shooting guard (like he wasn't a
shooting guard before, right?) and the team took off.
</P>
<P>
   With non-demanding (the ball) types like Eric Snow, George
Lynch, Matt Geiger and Theo Ratliff on the court, Iverson is free
to create for himself. The difference is he's creating for his
teammates as well.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers are also probably the most fun to watch, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee Bucks, enthusiastically embracing George Karl's
system, have bolted out of the blocks with a 14-10 record.
</P>
<P>
   They have no center to speak of, but they have more shooters
than a firing squad. Glenn Robinson, Ray Allen, Dell Curry, Vinny
Del Negro, Armon Gilliam and Sam Cassell can fire it in with the
best of them. You can't leave anybody open on this team.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland Trail Blazers have shaken off their bad-boy image
to become one of the league's best, and certainly its deepest,
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's just a matter of time before Isaiah Rider explodes,
but with Damon Stoudamire, Brian Grant, Rasheed Wallace, Arvydas
Sabonis, Jim Jackson and Greg Anthony coming at you in waves, these
guys could have what it takes to go all the way. Except maturity,
that is.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Armstrong. While most view the Orlando Magic as Penny
Hardaway's team, this flea-like point guard has established himself
as the front-runner for Sixth Man of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   An incredibly quick, gifted athlete, Armstrong also has a rare
work ethic that has turned him from 10-day tryout to million-dollar
sixth man.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointments
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list in this department is the NBA, which put
together a schedule that has teams playing without the benefit of
training camp or practice time. Yeah, that makes for some pretty
good basketball. Shooting percentages have plummeted to ridiculous
lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have a lot of talent and you're playing more
games, it magnifies everything,'' Charles Barkley said. ``You have
to use those terrible players more.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play a lot of minutes now. Those guys that used to play
10 minutes a night are now playing 25 minutes a night.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nyets have taken underachieving to a new level
this season, so they fired the coach and the team, essentially.
</P>
<P>
   Calipari was canned soon after the blockbuster trade that
brought in Marbury from Minnesota and put Cassell on the road to
Milwaukee was completed. Still, any team that can put Marbury (or
Cassell), Keith Van Horn, Jayson Williams, Kerry Kittles and
Kendall Gill on the court has no business playing sub-.500 ball,
much less the sub-.200 ball the Nots are ``playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Hornets have shown a history of doing everything
possible to rid themselves of talent, so why should this year be
different?
</P>
<P>
   The team that has dumped Geiger, Alonzo Mourning, Larry Johnson,
Vlade Divac, Muggsy Bogues and Del Curry had another fire sale and
ridded itself of Glen Rice, who was dealt to the Los Angeles Lakers
for Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Jones will be a free agent after next season, so the clock is
ticking on his career in Charlotte-ry.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix entered the season with glowing visions of contending
for a championship in the Valley of the Sun after acquiring center
Luc Longley from Chicago and signing free-agent forward Gugliotta
to add to a roster that included Jason Kidd and Rex Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   But after their overtime loss to the Rockets on Saturday night,
the Suns slipped below the .500 horizon at 12-13. Make that the
Valley of the Stunned.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Vin Baker has been a study in frustration, starting
the season in a horrible free-throw slump and then losing his
confidence inside because he feared being fouled.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star and future Dream Teamer found himself on the bench
when Seattle coach Paul Westphal was forced to go with someone who
wanted to do something other than launch 20-foot jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   And now, our midseason awards: &QL; 
Most Valuable Player _ Alonzo Mourning, Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the Year _ Vince Carter, Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the Year _ George Karl, Milwaukee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-21-99 2255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
