<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, March 22.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ A consideration of what Milosevic
may be planning next. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels) _ News analysis on the choices now
facing NATO. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-NORTH (Northwest Territories) _ During the coldest part
of the tough winters in Canada's remote Northwest Territories, when
the crazy quilt of big lakes and small ponds freezes, a few brave
men take their trucks off the road and onto a blue-ice highway that
crosses 400 miles of bleached-out tundra. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT 8,9,10,11) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-MEET (Vienna) _ If all goes well here at an emergency
meeting set for Tuesday, the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries will take more than 2 million barrels of oil a day out of
world markets, starting in April. By Youssef M. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI-U.S. (Riyadh) _ Three months of American bombing of Iraq
are generating new tensions with Saudi Arabia. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Berlin) _ A look at the continuing disarray
inside the German government. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLERS (Orlando, Fla.) _ Jim Larson lost two women he
loved to random killers. First it was his sister, Sonja Larson. She
and a roommate were stabbed to death in 1990 by Danny Rolling, a
serial killer who said demons spoke to him from inside his head.
Then in 1997, his wife Carla Larson was abducted in a supermarket
parking lot by a man on vacation at Disney World. Later this month
his wife's killer, John Huggins, will join Rolling on Florida's
death row. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DWELLINGS-DISABLED _ A look at the progress being made on making
dwellings accessible to people with disabilities. By Stephen A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-TAXES _ John Kasich, the exuberant House Budget Committee
chairman and presidential candidate, started the year pushing a 10
percent across-the-board tax cut. But he has become a sign of his
party's dilemma: the budget won't allow it and the Republicans are
confused about how to proceed on what was once their unifying
issue. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT3) haa been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GRIDIRON _ The president attended the annual Gridiron
dinner, a white-tie affair, Saturday night. There was a lot of
material to work with. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   DINGELL-PROFILE _ Debbie Dingell, political spouse
extraordinaire, takes involvement with her mate's professional
institution to special levels, with the bipartisan civility retreat
for House members a prime example. Mrs. Dingell helped organize it.
Her husband, Rep. John Dingell, a Michigan Democrat who is the
House's most senior member, thinks the whole thing is bunk. But
that's only the beginning of their tensions: Mrs. Dingell wants to
take a position in the vanguard for gun control, while Dingell is a
former board member of the NRA. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT4) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-SUSTAIN (Des Moines) _ Improvements in workers'
productivity help to explain the central puzzle of today's economy.
Eight years into the current expansion, labor shortages and rising
wages should be raising the annual inflation rate, now only 1.7
percent. That happened in the 1980s, during the last growth cycle,
when the Consumer Price Index reached 4.6 percent. Nor are profits
suffering noticeably, despite somewhat slower gains recently. By
past standards, profits should be hurting, caught as they are
between rising pay and stagnant prices. But many corporations have
come up with numerous ways to dodge the bullet, and confound the
view, so widely shared, that inflation is an inevitable result of
sustained prosperity. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT13) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Protecting online privacy.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT12) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL-DESIGN (Undated) _ This has been the decade in which
software moved, big time, into the industrial designer's world. In
corporate offices across the country, engineers have been booting
up programs that let them tinker, in three dimensions, with every
permutation and combination of a product's design. It was just a
matter of time before engineers would aim their computers at
designing and refining the assembly lines on which those products
are made. And apparently, that time has come. By Claudia H.
Deutsch. (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-FOR-GIRLS (San Francisco) _ It is hard to be small and
unknown, particularly in the CD-ROM games market. Purple Moon,
which sought and failed to make a viable business out of computer
games for girls _ games that unlike current top-sellers in the
category, were not about eyeshadow selection or nail polish tricks
_ faced an unforgiving battle for shelf space with Mattel, which
claimed six of the top 10 girls' titles last year. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTRAGEOUS-CABLE-TV (Undated) _ The rambunctious next generation
of cable television shows owes a debt to two phenomena of recent
cable seasons: the rude and crude Comedy Central animated series
``South Park'' and the apparently bottomless popularity of
professional wrestling. Programmers are seeking to up the ante in
terms of, in their own words, the ``edginess'' and
``outrageousness'' of their new programming. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   POPCULTURE-ADCOL (Undated) _ When the Beatles came to America,
they were dubbed the Fab Four. Thirty-five years later,
Entertainment Weekly is undertaking an elaborate marketing and
promotional program centered on popular culture and called the Fab
400. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   GATES-BOOK-CHAMELEON (Washington) _ Which is the real Bill
Gates? Is it the author who insists, in his new book, ``Business
(at) the Speed of Thought,'' that all inter-office communications
should flow ``over e-mail so workers can act on news with
reflex-like speed''? Or is it the witness who testified in the
government's antitrust case against his company that he could not
remember dozens of e-mail messages he wrote or received over the
last several years? By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-REPUBLIC-MEDIA (Undated) _ The New Republic, a weekly
opinion magazine facing stagnant circulation, flat advertising
revenue, an editorial merry-go-round, and a scandal or two in the
ranks of its reporters, will unveil its redesign in the issue dated
April 12, courtesy of Roger Black, the designer who has jazzed up
magazines from Foreign Affairs and Reader's Digest to Harper's
Bazaar and Premiere. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT5) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MONICA-BOOK-MEDIA (Manchester, England) _ Although Monica
Lewinsky's tour of Britain has her publishers rubbing their hands
in glee, her American publishers, St. Martin's Press, do not have
as much cause for elation. After a huge initial burst of sales,
``Monica's Story'' has slipped to No. 3 from No. 1 on the New York
Times best-seller list, behind books by George Stephanopoulos and
Tom Brokaw. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire comments on
allegations of China's nuclear espionage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in `'e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DIVERSITY-POETS (Undated) _ The Academy of American Poets, a
65-year-old organization that is at the symbolic heart of the
American poetry establishment, is making what it calls significant
changes in its structure in response to criticism that it is an
elitist group, dominated by white male poets. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   KERSHAW-HITLER (New York) _ One way or another, Ian Kershaw,
professor of modern history at the University of Sheffield in
England, has spent the last decade in the shadow of Hitler, whom he
calls ``the most central figure of our century, possibly the most
central figure of all.'' By Ralph Blumenthal.
