A9000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-FASHIONS-COX     03-21 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-FASHIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fashion: Oscar night noteworthy, not surprising
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They just don't make 'em like they used to . . . the Oscar night
outfits, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Now that designers campaign as enthusiastically as congressional
candidates to get their clothes onto the right stars' backs, and
now that high-priced stylists _ not the stars themselves _ do the
actual shopping, the fun's gone out of watching the Oscars to gape
at who wore what.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone makes a see-through spectacle of herself the way
Cher used to do. No one shows up at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion
done up like an early Bette Midler bimbo.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there were still a number of noteworthy looks worth
recalling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beyond the Pale: Gwyneth Paltrow was the evening's
standard-bearer for style and grace. Though her pink satin gown by
Ralph Lauren could have been tailored a bit more seductively, it
was at least in the shade of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And Paltrow's hair, parted and pulled back into a flawless
chignon, typified the way stars strove for a look that couldn't be
poked fun at.
</P>
<P>
   _ Father knows best: Undoubtedly, actress Liv Tyler, who wore
Pamela Dennis, takes style pointers from her father, Steven, who
fronts the Oscar-nominated (``Armageddon'') band Aerosmith. Not
only has Liv shorn her hair to the length of her dad's; she also
wore a heavily jeweled choker that matched his as well.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heavy hitters: They may rule the box office and the record
charts, but neither best actor nominee Tom Hanks nor Mariah Carey _
who performed in a duet (``When You Believe'') with Whitney
Houston, who also wore Valentino _ looked as if they'd been
anywhere near a StairMaster lately. Hanks' boxy Valentino tuxedo
did nothing to conceal the paunch he's developed (presumably for a
new role) since ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   And, after appearing in so many music videos wearing the
skimpiest outfits imaginable, Carey looks as if she's put down Puff
Daddy and picked up puff pastry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Better (with time): Geena Davis has shown before on Oscar
night that she looks good in pale peach. So the sight of her in a
peachy gown during the pre-awards telecast was a bit of a letdown.
But when she took the stage to introduce a dance interpretation of
the Oscar-nominated film scores, she looked stunning in a
semi-sheer, jewel-encrusted gown that had Armani written all over
it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hair don'ts: A pair of actors showed off for the Oscars
sporting new, don't-try-this-at-home hairstyles. ``Austin Powers''
star Mike Myers had a brunet buzz cut that made him look like Dr.
Evil got hold of him.
</P>
<P>
   And ``A Simple Plan'' star Billy Bob Thornton had bleached blond
locks that threatened to make him prettier than girlfriend Laura
Dern.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
