<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDER RESTORED AS THREE TOP SEEDS MAKE FINAL FOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Now that we know who is packing for college
basketball's first Final Four spring break in Florida, it's
apparent that history will be a compelling theme next weekend at
Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   Our invited guests are Duke (36-1), Connecticut (32-2) and
Michigan State (33-4) _ all No. 1 seeds _ and No. 4 seed Ohio State
(27-8). This is the third time that three No. 1 seeds have reached
the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   And this is a glittering gathering. The combined winning
percentage of .895 bests the winning percentage of the two previous
Final Fours with three No. 1 seeds (1993 and 1997).
</P>
<P>
   All four teams are in position to make history. Here's the
rundown:
</P>
<P>
   Duke. The Blue Devils enter with a 31-game winning streak.
They'll be trying for their third title of this decade. Duke has
won four tournament games by the average margin of 30 points. The
biggest average winning margin by a national champion is 23.7
points by UCLA in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   With a national championship, the Blue Devils could cement their
claim to team of the 1990s. And for coach Mike Krzyzewski, it is a
return to the Final Four for the first time since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to be back in this spot, it's kind of dangerous,''
Duke junior forward Chris Carrawell said. ``He knows how to win.
He's got two national championships. We've got a great
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State. The Spartans return to their first Final Four
since 1979, when they won their national title behind Magic
Johnson. The Spartans are Big Ten Conference champions and have won
22 games in a row. The Duke-Michigan State semifinal is a rematch
of a Great Eight game that the Blue Devils won, 73-67.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut. The Huskies have erased nearly a decade of
frustration by reaching the school's first Final Four. Connecticut
is the only team other than Duke to spend time ranked No. 1 this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Three times this decade, Connecticut and coach Jim Calhoun
reached the regional final only to lose. The first disappointment
came in 1990 when the Huskies lost to Duke on a Christian Laettner
buzzer beater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Coach that we didn't want him to be known \Rany
longer\S as `the best coach who never got to the Final Four,' ''
said sophomore guard Khalid El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State. Other than Duke, the Buckeyes have the most Final
Four history in this field. This is Ohio State's ninth Final Four,
but its first since 1968. The Buckeyes will be trying to win their
first national championship since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   And Ohio State has authored one of the most amazing turnarounds
ever. Last season, the Buckeyes were 8-22 overall and 1-15 in the
Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were crying after every game, wondering when it would get
better,'' said Ohio State sophomore guard Michael Redd of last
season's struggles. ``This season has been a dream.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
