<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9003 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX     03-21 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERSON READY, BUT RANGERS KEEP FINGERS CROSSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ The Rangers need Danny Patterson back to have
any chance of a decent bullpen. That becomes even more dire if John
Wetteland isn't ready to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland has been troubled by back spasms and a bad ankle and
is questionable for Opening Day. Patterson is among the first line
of defense if the All-Star closer isn't ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want that opportunity, I just don't want it this way,''
Patterson said. ``I want to earn the job, I don't want to be forced
into it. But if they give me the ball, I'd be more than willing.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates hopes Wetteland will be ready. But Oates is
also formulating a backup plan that calls for Patterson,
right-hander Tim Crabtree and left-hander Eric Gunderson to share
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got three guys who can get me through the final two
innings,'' Oates said. ``If one of them gets hot, I could go with
him a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson could be that one because of his talent. Oates said he
compares favorably with Wetteland as far as ``stuff.' But questions
remain about Patterson's health and durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wetteland can pitch three days in a row and have the same
stuff,'' Oates said. ``With Patterson there can be a dropoff. You
just don't know. There's still a question of resiliency and
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were impressed with Patterson when he had a 1.68
earned-run average and 10 saves for Oklahoma City in 1996 and was
10-6 with a 3.42 ERA as a Rangers rookie in 1997. But he required
shoulder surgery after the season and was not as effective last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson relies on a sinking fastball _ similar to what Kevin
Brown throws and the ``Vulcan,'' a split-fingered fastball. Bullpen
coach Larry Hardy said Patterson needs both pitches to be
effective. Neither were effective last year as Patterson struggled
to come back from rotator-cuff surgery. By the end of the season he
had fallen into despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nothing; I didn't have anything left,'' Patterson said.
``I had no movement and no velocity. If I didn't put the pitch in a
perfect spot, it got hit. I felt like a monkey throwing the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers say Patterson is throwing the ball the way he did
before the surgery. But the results this spring have been mixed. He
followed two scoreless outings by allowing two runs in an inning
against the Reds yesterday. He has a 7.37 ERA after six outings and
opponents are hitting .324 off him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about resilient, but it wasn't consistent,''
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still night and day from last year,'' Hardy said. ``The
first thing is his strength is back and, with that, his mental
approach is better than it was last year in the fact that last year
he was always wondering how he was going to feel. I see him getting
better the whole year as he gets into it and sees he's healthy and
confident it's only going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson is a vital part of the Rangers' bullpen even with
Wetteland healthy. The Rangers were outscored 81-79 in the eighth
inning last season, the inning in which the setup relievers bridge
the gap between the starter and the closer.
</P>
<P>
   But come Opening Day, it could be Patterson facing down the
Detroit Tigers' Bobby Higginson, Tony Clark and Dean Palmer with a
one-run lead in the ninth inning.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
