<HEADER>
A9004 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-TEMPLE-HNS &LR;      03-21 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-TEMPLE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Blue Devils rip Temple 85-64
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There was a time when they took this sort
of thing for granted. It was simply part of the annual rites of
spring, a three-week romp through the bracket, twice ending with
smiles and high-fives and nets draped around necks.
</P>
<P>
   Final Four? Been there, done that, got a drawer full of
T-shirts, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at Continental Airlines Arena, the scene along the Duke
bench was a little different. It had been awhile _ at least by Blue
Devils standards, and there was nothing ho-hum about it.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there was genuine joy in the faces after an 85-64
victory over Temple in this East Regional final, none more than in
the one belonging to a coach who wondered if this sort of
experience would come his way again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting back to the Final Four, for me, is incredibly
fulfilling,'' Mike Krzyzewski said after his team advanced for the
first time in five seasons, earning a national semifinal date
Saturday with Michigan State in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '94-95, there was part of me that wasn't sure if we'd ever
do this again. It's not promised to anybody. For awhile there, it
seemed like it was. Seven out of nine years, it just seemed like
you just get it. Then a whole bunch of things were taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning a school-record 31st straight game, Duke (36-1) got
many of them back, earning its eighth Final Four trip of the
Krzyzewski era, the fifth by way of the New Jersey Meadowlands. In
returning to the game's biggest stage, the Blue Devils also quieted
the ghosts of last year's collapse against Kentucky in the South
Regional final, where they blew a 17-point lead and watched the
Wildcats go on to win the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we've had a lot of things happen,'' Duke guard
Trajan Langdon said. ``We got back to where we were last year, and
this time, we fought through.''
</P>
<P>
   Langdon, the fifth-year senior, made sure of it. With his team
struggling early, he assessed a shaky situation and decided it was
time to take charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a little bit nervous today at the beginning of the
game,'' Krzyzewski said. ``Trajan wasn't, but I sensed that they
were not afraid, but they were young.''
</P>
<P>
   Langdon was neither young nor afraid. With Temple off to an
early 9-5 lead, he scored on a runner, then drained a pair of
3-pointers. A spurt that eventually stretched out to 17-2 took much
of the starch out of an underdog that knew it would need a
near-perfect performance to pull off the upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Trajan went into that spree was bigger than the points,''
said Krzyzewski. ``It really settled everyone down. He amazed me,
knowing that he had to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Langdon got his team the lead, the rest of the Blue Devils
happily fell in line. They finished with 60 percent shooting from
the field, hitting 27-of-45. They made 10-of-17 from 3-point range,
with Langdon alone sinking five of six. And when they got tired of
nailing the long-range shots, they got the ball down low to Elton
Brand, who hit eight of 10 from the floor on his way to 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of all this, Temple was game, but Duke eventually
was too much to handle.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils led 43-31 at the half and extended the advantage
to 61-41 on another Langdon trey with 14:36 remaining, but Temple
wasn't quite done. A Mark Karcher 3-pointer capped a 13-3 run to
make it 64-54 with 10:23 still left, and memories of the collapse
against Kentucky were beginning to stir.
</P>
<P>
   But not for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get scared or anything like that,'' Duke point guard
William Avery said.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon again delivered, quelling the uprising with two free
throws. Brand provided the last five points in an 11-2 run that
settled the issue once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Karcher and Lamont Barnes finished with 19 points each for the
losers, but Temple made just 25 of 67 shots (37.3 percent).
Karcher's line typified the struggle, as he missed 18 of 25 shots,
including 12 of his 15 3-point tries.
</P>
<P>
   When it was done, Temple coach John Chaney had little trouble
identifying the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew someone was going to hit from the outside, we just
didn't know who or how well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon provided the answer, and the Blue Devils were headed off
to a rematch with Michigan State, a team they defeated 73-67 in the
Great Eight on Dec. 2 in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time coming, and it's a great feeling,''
Langdon said. ``I knew coming into the game that this was my last
chance to go to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Blue Devils are going. Being away for a while
may simply make the trip a little more fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
