<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DARLINGTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON TAMES DARLINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ His race car was too wrecked to run.
Fortunately for Jeff Burton, the race track ``Too Tough to Tame''
was too wet to race on yesterday afternoon _ a bizarre combination
that added up to a rain-shortened victory in the TranSouth
Financial 400.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when racing against threatening skies was as important
as racing the treacherous Darlington Raceway, Burton and his Roush
Racing crew transformed an early pit stop for track position and a
late stroke of luck into his second victory of the 1999 NASCAR
Winston Cup season.
</P>
<P>
   Burton also will be the Cup points-leader for the first time in
his career when he rolls into Texas Motor Speedway this week for
the Primestar 500 on Sunday. Burton scored the first of his seven
career victories at the 1.5-mile track in Fort Worth in April 1997,
and he will return after having won two of the past three races of
this season. Burton leads Gordon by seven points after five of 34
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus on Monday turns to Texas,'' said Burton, who will
have to break out a backup No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford Taurus for
the reconfigured and repaved TMS. ``We had this car slated to run
in Texas. We're disappointed we can't take it there. But the car
we're taking finished fourth at Atlanta. We think it's a car
capable of running up front.''
</P>
<P>
   That is where Burton was racing _ ahead of Gordon and Mayfield _
when the rain almost ruined his day. As it was, Burton got swept up
in a chain-reaction wreck down the frontstretch involving the
spinning cars of Ernie Irvan, Kenny Irwin, Kenny Wallace and Jerry
Nadeau. Burton tapped the rear of Nadeau's Ford, and slid hard into
the outside wall.
</P>
<P>
   It painted a serious ``Darlington Stripe'' on Burton's car, but
not enough to keep him from crossing the start/finish line ahead of
Mayfield and Gordon. The latter had dropped to third after running
into Irwin's disabled Taurus and damaging the right front section
of his Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   With the rain falling, NASCAR officials red-flagged the race to
a halt for the second time. The first stoppage came after only 45
of the 293 scheduled laps had been completed and consumed 2 hours,
46 minutes and 52 seconds. The race had become official after
reaching the halfway point, and with dusk settling in, NASCAR
declared the day over after 164 laps/224 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Burton already had exited his battered car, looked it over, and
performed a half-baked rain dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, yeah, I was waving for the rain to come on,'' said
Burton, who led three times for a race-high 59 laps. ``First of
all, I was mad because I knew it wasn't going to rain very long. I
just knew it wasn't, but it didn't have to rain very long. The
first thing that went through my mind was that we had the best car,
we had the best pit-stop decision, we did the right job _ and I
wrecked. So I was mad at myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The car was so whipped that crew chief Frankie Stoddard was
elected to direct it into Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every crew chief is a wannabe driver,'' Stoddard said. ``When
I saw my chance to drive into Victory Lane, I took it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was appropriate, because it was Stoddard's call to
``short-pit'' under green for track position that proved to be the
move of the race. Burton was running third to leader Mayfield and
Gordon when he and Dale Jarrett pitted under green on Lap 113.
Burton took on four tires and a full load of fuel in 16.5 seconds.
When that cycle of pit stops was completed, Burton assumed the lead
on Lap 120 and held it to the race's rowdy conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great pit stop _ a great call in the pits to come in
and pit early _ and then we got on and off pit road better than
anyone else,'' said Burton, one of eight drivers involved in 13
lead changes. ``It was a true team effort to win this race, and add
that with a dramatic wreck and all that stuff, it's hard to top
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Runnerup Mayfield, who finished a frustrating 36th at Atlanta
Motor Speedway last weekend, took pride in his second top-five
finish in five races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great car, an awesome car,'' said Mayfield, driver of
the No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford. ``But my hat's off to the 99 team. They
did a good job, pitting early and getting track position.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon _ like Burton a two-time winner this season _ posted his
fourth finish of third or better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could be leading the points right now, but we're
close and that's all right,'' said Gordon, driver of the No. 24
DuPont Automotive Finishes Monte Carlo. ``I'm frustrated because of
what happened to me on the last lap. But I'm the opposite of
Jeremy. I'm kind of glad it got called, because I would have never
ended up third.''
</P>
<P>
   And Burton never would have ended up the winner.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
