<HEADER>
A9007 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-INJURIES-HNS &LR;      03-21 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-INJURIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NL Central teams missing important components
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ORLANDO, Fla. _ The National League Central race might not be
decided on the field this season, but instead in the trainer's
room.
</P>
<P>
   A part of any sport, injuries have played an increasingly
important factor this spring _ and the regular season still is two
weeks away. Nowadays, a doctor is as valuable to a club as a
cleanup hitter or dominant pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Few teams around baseball have been lucky enough to avoid the
injury bug, with several key players suffering significant injuries
and others being diagnosed with severe illnesses. In the NL
Central, at least four teams currently have key players nursing
some kind of ailment, including the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Let's make the rounds:
</P>
<P>
   The Astros learned during the first week of camp they would be
without the services of Moises Alou at least until August and
possibly for the entire season because of a torn anterior cruciate
ligament in the All-Star outfielder's left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs, arguably the most banged-up club in the
division, will have to get use to life without pitcher Kerry Wood.
The 1998 NL Rookie of the Year is out for the season with a torn
right elbow ligament. To make matters worse, closer Rod Beck has
been slowed by a bulging disk in his lower back that threatens to
sideline him until the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle was expected to anchor the Cincinnati Reds'
pitching staff. But with his recovery from a weakened right
shoulder and strained left quadriceps (thigh) muscle slowed, the
club is anticipating Neagle's starting the season on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Edgar Renteria (knee bruise) and center fielder Ray
Lankford (knee surgery) have the Cardinals scrambling to find
alternatives in the likelihood neither is ready for the season
opener. Want more bad news, Cardinals fans? Righthander Matt
Morris' sprained right elbow may a lot worse than previously
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee and Pittsburgh, the remaining clubs in the six-team
division, have managed to dodge bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems right now that the team with nine healthy players
(opening day) might be the one to get out of the box the fastest,''
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``You're almost afraid
to put your team out there anymore (in exhibition games) with the
way players are going down. I can't remember a spring when there
have been so many significant injuries to so many different
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   And not just in the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit this spring? The Atlanta Braves lost slugging first
baseman Andres Galarraga for the season because of a cancerous
tumor in his lower back, and closer Kerry Ligtenberg is on the
shelf indefinitely with an elbow injury that threatens his season.
</P>
<P>
   Boston shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, the 1997 American League
Rookie of the Year and runner-up in last season's AL Most Valuable
Player voting, left the team this weekend and flew to California
for an MRI on his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The bad luck even extended to the manager's office when the
Yankees' Joe Torre was diagnosed with prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to control it,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The key is addressing the problem when it happens. Depending on
timing, most teams can evaluate talent within the system or
consider trades if an injury to a star player occurs early enough
during the spring. Otherwise, clubs are scrambling to fill gaps as
the season approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, well-stocked in the outfield and loaded with
All-Star players throughout the lineup, appear to be one of the
teams best equipped to handle injuries over the long haul, with
reliable replacement Richard Hidalgo already showing he can compete
on the major-league level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say depth is a problem when you can't find playing
time for all these people,'' Hunsicker said. ``I feel it's a nice
problem to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Until it is known how Alou responds to rehabilitation on his
knee, the Astros will make do with what they have. So will the
other teams in the division and around baseball. Just don't feel
sorry for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our division, for some reason, seems to be the hard-luck
division this year,'' said Cubs general manager Ed Lynch. ``There
is no sympathy asked for and none given. We are not going to feel
sorry for ourselves, because no one feels sorry for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
